{[%evp 0,24,30,19,56,53,53,42,42,77,95,31,45,18,51,9,16,1,-21,-38,2,9,65,28,63,32,27]} 1. e4 Nf6 {The Alekhine Defence is one of those opening having an appropriate name. True, the first recorded game with this opening was played in 1802 by Napoleon Bonaparte, against his favourite opponent, Madame de Remoussat, a countess. Probably a cavalry lover, Napoleon always started his games by moving both knights, regardless of colour. There were occasional games featuring the Alekhine Defence between 1880 and 1920, but the opening game into the limelight only during the Budapest 1921 tournament, where Alekhine used it twice. It is the kind of provocative opening that tends to pass through years or full decades of crisis. As a child, I remember reading that grandmaster Lev Alburt, a Soviet player at that time, complained that his main openings with black, the Volga (Benko) gambit and the Alekhine Defence are passing through a strong crisis, causing him to have worse results than usual. On the other hand, if we compare it with the Sicilian Dragon (or the Volga/Benko gambit), belonging to the same category, this is a bit surprising. The Alekhine Defence is by far more flexible, allowing Black to choose more than one setup in all the critical systems. This latter aspect made me adopt a different approach than in all my previous electronic books published by Modern Chess. Usually, I examine one line against all the opponent's systems. This time, I have analyzed two or more alternatives for Black, whenever the case was given (not in the minor lines, though). I had two main reasons for that. First of all, the way I built this database can offer a reliable repertoire for a long time. By alternating the lines, we can make the opponent's preparation harder. If one of them passes through a crisis, there always is a reserve. At the same time, I wanted to use the rich content of this opening to create some sort of multi-sided course on strategy, in tight connection with dynamics and tactics. The Alekhine Defence is mainly about structures, but the player with less space should always be aware of the dynamic elements, allowing him to disrupt the enemy (sometimes over extended) centre. Black's flexibility is obvious if we think that he can choose between playing on dark or light squares. A mixture of these is also possible. For instance, in Line 28, he eliminates the bishop on b3, getting some control on light squares, but his main plan is to advance his pawns on dark squares! Before he started his fulminant ascension toward the chess throne, Bobby Fischer was famous for his narrow repertoire. In the years preceding the historic 1972 match, something had changed, though. He started to occasionally open the game with 1.b3, while with black he adopted the Alekhine Defence as an alternative to his beloved Sicilian Najdorf. In his attempt to sidestep Spassky's preparation, he also played it twice in Reykjavik, winning one and drawing the other. Moreover, he did not choose the same system in the games. In the 13th game he answered 4.Nf3 with 4...g6, as he had always done before, while in the 19th he switched to the more static 4...Bg4, for the first time in his life. I have inserted Fischer's 6 games played in 1970 and 1972, leaving out that one played in 1965, which is less sound. Few words about how I have come to the idea of writing this electronic book. One evening dring our team championship, my colleague GM Lucian Miron complained to me that earlier that day, he could not get anything against an older player who had played 1...Nf6 against him. I opened my portable chess set and invited him to analyze a bit this opening, far from engines and books. I was pleasantly surprised that I could remember most of the critical ideas and move orders, even though I had played the Alekhine Defence only a few times two decades ago. Even though he started with the firm belief that engines are smashing Black's opening, Lucian gradually became interested in this opening, since he did not see obvious ways of refuting it. When I arrived in my room, I checked a few points of our joint analysis and discovered that engines had grown enough to understand that this was a sound opening. Twenty years ago, I had only used it as an experiment because engines were so skeptical about it. When choosing an opening against 1.e4, I am frequently concerned about having a weapon against 1.d4 leading to positions at least vaguely similar. I recommend the Gruenfeld as a good complement to the Alekhine Defence. In both openings, Black invites his opponent to build up a massive centre to start attacking it in the early middlegame.} 2. e5 {Obviously the principled continuation.} (2. d3 {and some minor alternatives are examined in Line 63.}) ({For} 2. Nc3 {, see Lines 64 and 65. None of these is challenging, but Black should choose his move order with care, if he does not wish to transpose to secondary lines of other openings.}) 2... Nd5 3. d4 {Clearly the main continuation.} ({The ultra resolute} 3. c4 Nb6 4. c5 (4. a4 {is Line 52.}) 4... Nd5 {gains a lot of space for White, but leaves his centre a bit vulnerable. This system is examined in detail in Lines 53 to 62.}) 3... d6 4. Nf3 {This is the classical continuation.} (4. c4 Nb6 {can introduce two important systems, but can also transpose back to the classical lines.} 5. f4 {The hyper-aggressive Four Pawn Attack. We could also call it the Euwe Attack, since the Dutch champion introduced it in 1921, shortly after Alekhine "inaugurated" his opening, and continued using it in later games. I have heard voices claiming that this system kills the Alekhine, but after thorough analysis, I have failed to see the point.} (5. exd6 cxd6 6. Nc3 g6 {features a fight of nerves. White tries to develop in such a way as to prevent ...Bg4, while Black needs to find ways of generating counterplay without it. True, if White plays an early Nf3, play transposes to the classical system.}) 5... dxe5 {This is the approved continuation, with many decades of history behind.} ({In his not very-known game with Ujtumen, Palma de Mallorca 1972 Interzonal, Fischer used a different move order:} 5... Bf5 6. Nc3 e6 7. Be3 Be7 8. Nf3 {. Ujtumen now took on d6 and spoiled the fun, but I wondered whether Fischer intended to transpose to the usual systems with ...dxe5 or had something different in mind. This remains a wild guess, but I discovered that Black can also play ...d6-d5 next, leading to positions that are similar to the classical 4.Nf3 Bg4. For this setup against the Four Pawn Attack, see Lines 38 to 41.}) 6. fxe5 Nc6 7. Be3 Bf5 8. Nc3 e6 9. Nf3 Be7 10. Be2 ({The ultra sharp} 10. d5 exd5 11. cxd5 Nb4 12. Nd4 Bd7 {tends to petter out inequality. See Lines 33 and 34.}) 10... O-O 11. O-O f6 12. exf6 Bxf6 {This is the main tabyia of the Four Pawn Attack. Black's well-coordinated minor pieces yield him certain pressure against d4, thus compensating for White's more compact structure. Play is mainly positional, but in Lines 35 to 37 I have highlighted the importance of concrete details when choosing the right move order.}) 4... g6 {Now is when the position may be similar to a Gruenfeld. This was Fischer's favourite, offering Black rich dynamic possibilities.} ({According to the database,} 4... Bg4 {is almost twice as popular, but a deeper analysis is required, involving the years when it was played, the level of the opponents and so on. Since there is so much material after 4...g6, I have examined 4...Bg4 in somewhat lesser detail. I only offered the guidelines in the sub-optimal lines for White and provided extensive analysis only to the critical lines. This move tends to lead to static play, involving patient manoeuvres. Despite their initial skepticism, engines tend to agree that Black's position is playable as the game advances.} 5. Be2 e6 6. O-O Be7 7. c4 Nb6 8. Nc3 O-O {For the introduction, see Line 28.} 9. h3 {This is one of the finesses I remembered during my analysis with my teammate. For short-term purposes, White needs to insert this move, but later, it will restrict his possibilities.} (9. Be3 {allows Black to play} Nc6 10. exd6 cxd6 11. d5 exd5 12. Nxd5 Nxd5 13. Qxd5 Be6 $11) 9... Bh5 10. Be3 d5 ({The difference after} 10... Nc6 11. exd6 cxd6 12. d5 exd5 13. Nxd5 Nxd5 14. Qxd5 {is that the bishop is not only attacked, but also far from e6.} Bg6 15. Rad1 $14) 11. c5 Bxf3 12. gxf3 (12. Bxf3 {allows} Nc4 {as in Line 29.}) 12... Nc8 (12... N6d7 {is also worth testing.}) 13. f4 {As an appetizer to the subtleties of this opening, let us see the moment when h2-h3 plays into Black's hands.} g6 14. Bd3 Bh4 15. Qg4 f5 16. exf6 Qxf6 {With the pawn on h2,} 17. Kg2 {followed by Kh3 would win, but here this is impossible.}) 5. Bc4 {The most active move.} ({In fact, the "purely classical" continuation, featuring harmonious developing moves, is} 5. Be2 Bg7 6. O-O O-O 7. c4 Nb6 8. Nc3 Nc6 9. exd6 cxd6 {The similarity with the Gruenfeld is clear now, due to the knights on c6 and b6. White did not seem to have any special ambitions in the opening, but retains a space advantage and has a harmonious development. These elements are typical for all classical systems in any opening. Play is strategically consistent, with Black trying to find a moment for breaking with ...d6-d5 and sometimes with ..e7-e5.} 10. h3 {Preventing ...Bg4.} ({The main alternative is} 10. Be3 Bg4 11. b3 d5 12. c5 Nc8 {Lines 2 to 5. White will gain space with b3-b4-b5 and Black will organize his counterplay with ...e7-e6 and ...N8e7-f5. When attacked, the other knight would go to a5, and sometimes further to c4.}) 10... Bf5 {A half-waiting game starts. Black needs to wait for Be3 before playing ...d6-d5. So far, Line 6.} 11. Be3 (11. Bg5 {[%emt 0:00:09] is Line} h6 12. Be3 d5 13. c5 Nc4) 11... d5 12. c5 (12. b3 {is Line 8.}) 12... Nc4 {Line 9. This is the point. The knight needs to reach c4 with gain of time.}) ({The relatively rare} 5. Ng5 {is examined in Line 1.}) 5... Nb6 6. Bb3 Bg7 {White has a choice now.} 7. Ng5 {An aggressive move, possible introduction to two different systems.} (7. a4 {is an attempt to induce ...a7-a5, thus restricting Black's possibilities at a later stage.} dxe5 (7... a5 {is possible, but deprives Black of the possibility of using certain setups. The insertion of these moves can also restrict White's possibilities in some others. Everything about it in Line 12.}) 8. a5 N6d7 {So far, Line 10.} 9. Bxf7+ $5 Kxf7 10. Ng5+ Kg8 11. Ne6 Qe8 12. Nxc7 Qd8 13. Nxa8 exd4 $44 {Line 11.}) ({The classical approach is} 7. O-O O-O 8. h3 {Preventing ...Bg4 in order to maintain the pawn on e5. I have examined none less than four different systems for Black.} (8. exd6 cxd6 {is examined in Line 24.}) 8... a5 ({If the players did not insert the a-pawns moves in the opening,} 8... Nc6 9. Qe2 Na5 {leads to interesting play. See Line 27.}) 9. a4 dxe5 (9... Nc6 10. Qe2 dxe5 11. dxe5 Nd4 12. Nxd4 Qxd4 {is examined in Line 25.}) 10. Nxe5 Nc6 (10... Bxe5 11. dxe5 Qxd1 12. Rxd1 Be6 {is a variation in Line 26.}) 11. Nxc6 bxc6 {see Line 26.}) 7... e6 8. Qf3 {The most aggressive continuation.} ({The other possible system is} 8. f4 dxe5 9. fxe5 O-O {So far, Lines 20 and 21.} 10. O-O c5 11. c3 cxd4 12. cxd4 Nc6 13. Nf3 f6 {With balanced play, as in Line 22.}) 8... O-O $5 {Traditionally considered unsound, this desirable move is completely playable in view of my analysis. For the introduction, see Line 17.} (8... Qe7 {is examined in Lines 14 to 16. The critical continuation is} 9. Ne4 h6 10. exd6 cxd6 11. Bf4 d5 12. Nd6+ Kf8 {Black is doing fine strategically but needs to find a plan to retrieve his coordination.}) 9. Qh3 h6 10. Nf3 ({After} 10. Ne4 {, White has made enough commitments to allow Black to block the centre.} d5 {Line 17.}) 10... dxe5 11. dxe5 Nc6 12. Bxh6 Nxe5 {Play is very sharp. White's attack looks dangerous, but his king is still in the centre. See Lines 18 and 19.} *

