{[%evp 0,50,30,26,62,70,66,52,30,51,94,32,13,17,17,-4,-27,-27,-24,1,1,20,21,5,14,57,20,9,30,10,5,7,57,38,30,25,16,11,51,48,72,17,6,22,24,-5,-1,-74,-3,-33,-80,-90,-86]} 1. e4 Nf6 2. e5 Nd5 3. d4 d6 4. Nf3 {This solid developing move can lead to different types of positions, depending on both players' choices during the next phase of the game.} g6 {This used to be Fischer's favourite move. Starting with this moment, there are several setups with at least some resemblance with the Gruenfeld Defence.} (4... Bg4 {is the other major branch, usually leading to static play and subtle manoeuvring.}) 5. Ng5 {A surprisingly early knight incursion, which cannot be dangerous, of course. Since it could cause some problems as a surprise weapon, it needs a bit of covering, though.} ({Moves such as} 5. exd6 {,}) (5. c4 {and}) (5. h3 {usually transpose to some of the main lines below.}) ({The main lines are} 5. Be2 {[%emt 0:00:09] examined in Lines 2 to}) ({and} 5. Bc4 {, which is the subject of Lines 10 to 27.}) 5... dxe5 {The simplest and probably best continuation.} (5... Bg7 $2 {runs into} 6. Qf3 Be6 7. Nxe6 fxe6 8. Qe4 $16) (5... c6 {allows} 6. e6 $5 $146 Bxe6 7. Nxe6 fxe6 8. c4 Nc7 9. h4 {with certain initiative for the pawn.}) 6. dxe5 (6. Bc4 Bg7 7. dxe5 c6 {transposes below.}) 6... Bg7 7. Bc4 {Unsurprisingly, this natural developing move is the most consistent.} ({The tempting} 7. c4 $2 {which may seem as one of the ideas behind 5.Ng5, weakens White's centre and queenside.} Nb4 8. Qxd8+ Kxd8 9. Nxf7+ {Otherwise, Black's previous play would not make any sense.} (9. Na3 {leaves White passive on the queenside.} Ke8 10. f4 f6 11. exf6 exf6 12. Nf3 Kf7 $17 {0-1 Shim Ng Min,F (1157)-Nowak,A (1458) OP-2020-0-04960}) 9... Ke8 10. Nxh8 Nc2+ 11. Kd1 Nxa1 12. Nxg6 hxg6 {White does not have clear ways of capturing the errant knight, which will likely return to play with decisive effects.} 13. Bd3 Kf7 14. f4 Na6 15. Na3 Bg4+ 16. Kd2 Rd8 (16... Nb4 $19 {may be even more convincing.} 17. Bb1 Bf5 18. Bxf5 gxf5 $19 {followed by ...Nxa2 if anything.}) 17. Kc3 Rxd3+ 18. Kxd3 Nb4+ {0-1 Nilsen,M (1826)-Thorstensen,E (2084) NOR-ch Class1 2013 (4) followed by ...Nxa2, thus freeing its colleague.}) (7. e6 {yields White only reasonable compensation for the pawn.} Bxe6 8. Nxe6 fxe6 9. Be2 Nc6 10. c3 Qd6 11. O-O O-O-O 12. Na3 Rhf8 13. Nc4 Qc5 14. Qb3 {½-½ Janosevic,D-Trifunovic,P YUG-ch09 Zagreb 1953 (2)} Nf4 15. Bxf4 Rxf4 $13) 7... c6 8. Nc3 {Trying to maintain the rhythm of the initiative, by using the indirect threat on f7.} (8. e6 {may be a bit more consistent than one move earlier, but not dangerous either.} Bxe6 9. Nxe6 fxe6 10. Nd2 Nd7 11. O-O b5 $5 $146 {Fighting for the light squares.} 12. Be2 (12. Bb3 Nc5 $11) 12... Ne5 13. Ne4 (13. c4 Nf4 $15) 13... O-O 14. c3 (14. Nc5 Qd6 $11) 14... Qb6 15. a4 a5 16. Ng5 Bh6 17. Nxe6 Bxc1 18. Qxc1 (18. Nxf8 Bxb2 $19 19. Rb1 bxa4) 18... Rf6 19. Ng5 (19. Nd4 b4 $132) 19... Raf8 $132) (8. f4 {offers Black good play after} f6 $146 9. exf6 exf6 10. Qe2+ Qe7 11. Qxe7+ Kxe7 12. Nf3 Be6 $11 {[%cal Gd5f4] Black gains a developing tempo due to the threat ...Nxf4.} 13. Kf2 (13. Na3 Nd7 $15) 13... Nxf4 14. Re1 Kf7 (14... Nd5 $2 15. Nd4 $18) 15. Nbd2 (15. Rxe6 $2 Nxe6 16. Nd4 Re8 $17) 15... Rd8 16. Ne4 Nh3+ 17. gxh3 Bxc4 18. Bf4 Kg8 19. Nd6 b5 20. Nxc4 bxc4 21. Rad1 Na6 $15) 8... h6 9. Nf3 (9. Bxd5 hxg5 10. Be4 Qxd1+ 11. Nxd1 {½-½ Kaniuth,E-Nadenau,O corr 1866} g4 $1 {Isolating the e5-pawn from its colleagues.} 12. Bf4 Be6 13. Ne3 Nd7 $19) (9. Nge4 Bxe5 10. Nxd5 cxd5 11. Bxd5 e6 (11... Qc7 {0-1 Revets,S-Hadley,G IECG TG.2004.0.15217 email (1)}) 12. Bc4 Qxd1+ 13. Kxd1 b6 14. Re1 Nc6 15. f4 Bg7 16. Nd6+ Ke7 17. Nxc8+ Raxc8 18. c3 Rhd8+ 19. Bd2 Na5 20. Bf1 Nc4 21. Bxc4 Rxc4 22. Kc2 b5 $11 {The position may be equal, but Black's play is more pleasant, due to his possible minority's attack.}) 9... Nxc3 10. Qxd8+ Kxd8 11. bxc3 Bg4 ({The untested} 11... Ke8 $5 {also looks fine. Black has the more compact structure, compensating for his slight problems of coordination.}) 12. Rb1 Bxf3 13. gxf3 Kc7 14. Bxf7 Bxe5 15. Bxg6 Bxc3+ 16. Ke2 Nd7 {Chances are about equal. White has two bishops, but his structure is weaker.} 17. Rb3 Be5 (17... Bf6 $5 18. Bf4+ e5 19. Bg3 Rhg8 20. Bf5 Nc5 21. Rc3 Na4 22. Ra3 b5 $11) 18. f4 Bf6 $11 19. Be3 b5 20. Bd2 {White starts chasing chimeras.} Nb6 21. Ba5 Rad8 22. Kf3 Rd4 23. Ra3 Rf8 24. Bc3 Rc4 (24... Rxf4+ 25. Kxf4 Bxc3+ 26. Kg4 Nd5 27. Rxa7+ Kb6 28. Ra3 b4 29. Rb3 Rg8 $19) 25. Bxf6 Rxf6 $19 {0-1 Capelan,G-O'Kelly de Galway,A Solingen 1973 (7)} *

