{[%evp 0,44,19,29,69,55,53,47,27,50,61,49,47,40,52,26,50,51,33,48,45,51,33,37,38,16,1,1,35,11,43,1,1,2,56,52,57,35,17,5,26,2,2,-98,-20,-20,-73]} 1. e4 Nf6 2. e5 Nd5 3. d4 d6 4. Nf3 g6 5. Be2 {This apparently modest move is in fact consistent. White does not intend to refute Black's opening, but aims for harmonious development, hoping that his superior space would offer him some long-term plus. The idea behind the last move is to keep the path clear for the c-pawn.} Bg7 6. O-O O-O 7. c4 {There is no other way to continue developing.} ({Hesitating for a moment with the generally use3ful} 7. h3 {allows Black to start effective counterplay.} c5 8. c4 (8. dxc5 dxe5 $132) 8... Nb4 9. exd6 cxd4 10. dxe7 Qxe7 11. Bg5 Qd7 12. a3 N4c6 13. Bd3 a5 14. Nbd2 Na6 $11 {[%cal Gb7b6] followed by ...b7-b6.}) 7... Nb6 8. exd6 {White has to release the tension now or on the next move. By doing it at this moment, he may try to confuse Black.} (8. h3 {is best answered with} dxe5 $1 (8... Nc6 9. exd6 cxd6 10. d5 {transposes to a line we avoid below.}) 9. dxe5 (9. Nxe5 {leaves White hanging a bit after} c5 $1 $146 10. dxc5 (10. Be3 Nc6 11. Nxc6 bxc6 12. dxc5 Qxd1 13. Rxd1 Na4 14. Bd4 Nxb2 15. Bxg7 Kxg7 16. Rd4 Na4 17. Bf3 Nxc5 18. Bxc6 Rb8 $11) 10... Bxe5 11. cxb6 Qxb6 12. Nc3 Be6 13. Nd5 Bxd5 14. cxd5 Nd7 $11) 9... Nc6 10. Bf4 {offers Black a pleasant choice.} Nd7 (10... Qxd1 11. Rxd1 Be6 {Planning ...Nd7.} 12. Na3 a6 {Preventing Nb5.} 13. Rd2 Nd7 {½-½ Leschinsky,P-Goralski,C Sueder Sommer op 1996 (5)} 14. Ng5 Ndxe5 15. Nxe6 fxe6 $11) (10... Be6 11. Na3 Nd7 {½-½ Jamrich,G (2294)-Farago,S (2314) Budapest FS02 IM 1999 (1)} 12. Ng5 Ndxe5 13. Nxe6 fxe6 14. Be3 $11) 11. e6 (11. Qc1 Ncxe5 12. Nxe5 Nxe5 13. Rd1 Nd7 14. Nc3 c6 $15) 11... fxe6 12. Bc1 {½-½ Saya,E (2293)-Mathieu,P (2208) Barcelona IM-B 5th 2021 (4)} Nc5 13. Nc3 e5 $15) ({I have taken} 8. Nc3 {as the main move order, as in the lines 3 to 9.}) 8... cxd6 9. h3 {Preventing ...Bg4 and delaying the knight's development for reasons revealed below.} (9. Nc3 Nc6 {transposes to the main lines 3 to 9.}) 9... e5 {Since White does not control e4, this is strong.} (9... Nc6 10. d5 $1 Ne5 ({The difference is made by} 10... Na5 11. Na3 $16) 11. Nxe5 Bxe5 12. a4 a5 13. Nc3 $14 {1-0 Tabatabaei,M (2629)-Tristan,L (2535) Titled Tuesday intern op 4th Aug 2pm blitz 2020 (2)}) 10. Nc3 ({With the knight on c3, the typical reaction would be} 10. Bg5 {½-½ Voekler,B (2369)-Lutz,K (2303) Oberliga Ost-B 0607 2006 (7.2) but here it allows} f6 11. Bh4 (11. Be3 e4 $1 {This is the difference.} 12. Ne1 f5 13. Qd2 Qf6 14. f4 d5 15. c5 Nc4 16. Bxc4 dxc4 17. Nc3 b6 $11) 11... e4 {Same issue.} 12. Nfd2 Nc6 13. Nxe4 g5 14. d5 Ne5 15. f4 Ng6 16. Bg3 gxf4 17. Bf2 (17. Bxf4 Nxf4 18. Rxf4 f5 19. Nec3 Qg5 20. Rf3 Nd7 $44) 17... f5 18. Nec3 f3 19. Bxf3 (19. gxf3 Qg5+ 20. Kh1 Qh6 $19) 19... Nxc4 $132) 10... exd4 {By releasing the tension, Black ensures himself active piece play, mainly because White has wasted a tempo on h2-h3, which is not useful under the given circumstances.} 11. Nxd4 ({Alternatively,} 11. Nb5 d5 12. Bg5 Qd7 13. c5 Nc4 14. Nbxd4 b6 {The simplest.} (14... Nxb2 {is a bit riskier.} 15. Qc1 Nc4 16. Bxc4 dxc4 17. Qxc4 Nc6 18. Rad1 Nxd4 19. Nxd4 h6 20. Bf4 Rd8 21. Bd6 {White has certain pressure and Black will need to sacrifice material in order to stay in the game.} b6 22. Rfe1 bxc5 23. Re7 Qxe7 24. Bxe7 Rxd4 25. Rxd4 cxd4 26. Qc6 Rb8 27. Qe8+ Kh7 28. Qxf7 Rb7 29. Qc4 Rxe7 30. Qxc8 Re1+ 31. Kh2 Re2 {Black should be able to draw this ending, for instance} 32. Qa6 Rxf2 33. Qxa7 Rf5 34. a4 d3 35. Qd7 Rf4 36. Qxd3 Rxa4 $11) 15. cxb6 Nxb2 16. Qc1 Nc4 17. bxa7 Qxa7 $11) 11... Nc6 12. Ndb5 {Trying to keep the control in the centre, but delaying the development even more.} (12. Be3 {allows} d5 13. Nxc6 bxc6 14. cxd5 Nxd5 15. Nxd5 cxd5 16. Bd4 Re8 17. Bf3 Be6 18. Qd2 (18. b4 Qh4) 18... Bxd4 19. Qxd4 Qb6 20. Rfd1 Qxd4 21. Rxd4 Rac8 $11) 12... Be6 13. Nxd6 Nd4 {Black has excellent compensation for the pawn, due to his pressure on White's undeveloped queenside.} 14. c5 (14. Bf4 Nxe2+ 15. Qxe2 Nxc4 16. Nxc4 Qd4 $11) 14... Nd7 15. Nxb7 (15. Be3 Nxc5 16. Bxd4 Qxd6 17. Nb5 Qb6 18. Bxg7 Kxg7 19. Qd4+ Kg8 20. Rac1 Rac8 $11) 15... Qc7 16. Nd6 Nxc5 17. Ndb5 Nxb5 18. Nxb5 Qe5 19. Be3 Rfd8 20. Qc2 Ne4 $44 21. Nxa7 Rxa7 22. Bxa7 Rd2 $13 *

