{[%evp 0,68,25,13,46,47,45,40,40,48,71,25,40,31,36,37,37,28,37,45,41,31,43,24,29,29,24,-3,-20,-17,-17,2,-6,-42,-34,-72,-63,-92,-77,-76,-90,-59,-130,-101,-98,-65,-60,-66,-43,-31,-30,-53,-25,-35,-17,-20,-10,-10,-2,-20,-29,-24,-28,-23,-29,-22,-28,-25,-25,-100,-91]} 1. e4 Nf6 2. e5 Nd5 3. d4 d6 4. Nf3 g6 5. Be2 Bg7 6. O-O O-O 7. c4 Nb6 8. Nc3 {With or without the intermediate exchange on d6, this developing move is the best.} Nc6 {Black continues his natural development, too.} ({Aimed at avoiding the systems with h2-h3,} 8... Bg4 {offers White some light initiative after} 9. h3 (9. exd6 cxd6 {is likely to transpose below, the same as}) (9. Be3 Nc6 10. exd6 cxd6) 9... Bxf3 10. Bxf3 Nc6 11. c5 $5 {Black is in no big danger, but has to struggle for a while.}) (8... dxe5 9. Nxe5 c5 {is less indicated than in the line with h2-h3 instead of Nc3, since White is better developed.} 10. dxc5 Bxe5 11. cxb6 Qxb6 12. Nd5 Qd6 13. Bh6 {with light initiative.}) 9. exd6 {Now is a good moment for releasing the tension.} (9. Bf4 {allows} Bg4 10. b3 ({After} 10. exd6 cxd6 {Both c4 and d4 are hanging in view of ...Bxf3.} 11. c5 dxc5 12. dxc5 Nd7 13. Be3 Qa5 $11 {with good counterplay.}) (10. c5 dxc5 11. dxc5 Nd7 $11) 10... Bxf3 11. Bxf3 dxe5 12. dxe5 Nxe5 13. Bxb7 Rb8 14. Ba6 Nexc4 15. Bxc4 Nxc4 16. Rc1 Ne5 $15 {0-1 Zimmerman,M (1600)-Piek,J (1400) FICGS class E 000059 email 2007 (1)}) 9... cxd6 {This is a classical tabyia of the Alekhine Defence. White has the centre, but Black's knights and the fianchetto bishop exert certain pressure on it. The situation is similar to that in several Gruenfeld variations. WHite's main traditional plan is to prepare ...d6-d5 (making the similarity with the Gruenfeld even stronger), but in certain cases ...e7-e5 is possible, too.} 10. Be3 {One of the two main continuations. White continues developing and consolidating the d4-pawn.} ({After} 10. b3 Bg4 {there is not anything better than} 11. Be3 {, transposing below.}) (10. d5 $2 {open the long diagonal, thus leaving the pawn on c4 vulnerable.} Na5 11. Nd2 Bd7 12. Bd3 Rc8 13. Qe2 Re8 14. Nce4 Qc7 $19 {0-1 Kryvoruchko,V (2200)-Sevostianov,P (2270) Lvov Tradition 02 2016 (6)}) (10. Bf4 {leaves the square on d4 vulnerable after} Bg4 11. d5 (11. b3 d5 12. c5 Bxf3 13. Bxf3 Bxd4 14. Rc1 Bxc5 15. Nxd5 Ba3 16. Bc7 Qe8 17. Bxb6 Bxc1 18. Nc7 Qc8 19. Nxa8 Bg5 $15) (11. c5 dxc5 12. dxc5 Nd7 13. Be3 Qa5 14. Qb3 Nxc5 $15 {½-½ Mery,R (1810)-Carpentier,G (1840) FRA-chT4 0405 2004 (7.5)}) 11... Na5 12. Nd2 (12. Rc1 Naxc4 13. b3 Bxf3 14. Bxf3 Ne5 15. Be2 Rc8 $15 {a few games were reaching this position, but White's compensation is not very convincing.}) 12... Bxe2 13. Qxe2 Rc8 $17) (10. Bg5 {has the same drawback as Bf4, but also the merit of putting pressure on e7.} Bg4 11. b3 d5 12. c5 Bxf3 13. Bxf3 Bxd4 14. Rc1 Bxc5 15. Nxd5 Ba3 16. Rc3 Nxd5 17. Qxd5 Qxd5 18. Bxd5 Rac8 $11) (10. c5 {is premature, due to White's incomplete development.} dxc5 11. dxc5 Qxd1 12. Rxd1 Bxc3 (12... Nd7 13. Be3 Nde5 $11) 13. cxb6 (13. bxc3 Na4 $15) 13... Bg7 14. bxa7 Rxa7 15. a4 Ra8 16. Bb5 Bg4 $11 {½-½ Santo Roman,M (2355)-Grunberg,S (2425) Maribor Pirc Memorial 3rd 1986 (8)}) (10. h3 {is the other important system, examined in Lines 6 to 9.}) 10... Bg4 {Black has developed all his minor pieces and is ready to start his counterplay. The immediate threat is ...Bxf3, since after Bxf3, the pawn on c4 would be hanging.} 11. b3 {The most solid continuation, maintaining the centre's integrity.} (11. d5 Bxf3 $1 {weakens White's kingside.} 12. gxf3 (12. Bxf3 {loses a pawn.} Ne5 13. b3 Nbxc4 14. bxc4 Nxf3+ 15. Qxf3 Bxc3 $15) 12... Na5 (12... Ne5 13. Bd4 Ned7 14. Bxg7 Kxg7 15. Qd4+ Nf6 16. f4 Nbd7 17. b3 $11 {0-1 Krapivin,V (2560)-Gipslis,A (2505) URS Club Cup 1st 1988 (10)}) 13. Bd4 e5 14. Bxb6 (14. dxe6 fxe6 15. Bxg7 Kxg7 $15) 14... Qxb6 15. Qd2 Rac8 16. b3 Qd8 17. Ne4 b6 $15) (11. c5 {helps Black to develop his counterplay.} Bxf3 12. Bxf3 (12. gxf3 dxc5 13. dxc5 Bxc3 14. bxc3 Nd5 15. Bd2 e5 $15 {[%cal Gd5f4] followed by ...Nf4 in the near future.}) 12... dxc5 13. dxc5 Nc4 14. Qe2 Nxe3 15. fxe3 (15. Qxe3 Bd4 16. Qg5 e6 17. Qxd8 Rfxd8 18. Na4 Rac8 $15 {1-0 Rosenkranz,C (1649)-Grimm,P (1855) GER-chT WK 3 U16 2007 (3.2)}) 15... Bxc3 16. bxc3 Rc8 $15 {0-1 Manish,A (2349)-Varga,Z (2436) Budapest Vezerkepzo GM Mix 2021 (1)}) 11... d5 {This is by far the most popular continuation. It has stood the scrutiny of practice over many decades.} (11... e5 {is also possible, though.}) 12. c5 {The most principled continuation. White creates a mobile queenside majority to get a crushing space advantage with b4-b5. In practice, things are not that easy, though. First of all, d4 needs permanent care and secondly, after b4-b5 the black knight could go to a5 and possibly further to c4.} (12. cxd5 {offers Black a pleasant position against the white Isolani. And of course, the Isolani with b2-b3 is anything but a dream.} Nxd5 13. Nxd5 Qxd5 14. Rc1 Rad8 15. h3 Bf5 16. Rc5 Qd6 17. Bc4 e6 $15 18. g4 Nxd4 $1 19. Bxd4 Be4 20. Qa1 Bxd4 21. Qxd4 Bxf3 22. Qxd6 Rxd6 23. Rc7 g5 $17 {0-1 Movsesian,J (2333)-Kashlinskaya,A (2441) EU-ch (Women) 15th 2014 (6)}) (12. a4 {deprives White of his structural mobility after} a5 13. c5 Nc8 14. Nb5 e6) 12... Nc8 {This passive retreat is not a concession needed in order to keep d5 defended. In fact, this is the best path for the knight, heading to e7-f5 after ...e7-e6. This plan puts the pawn on d4 in some danger.} 13. h3 {Statistics indicate this is the most frequently played move, but it yields Black a tempo for carrying out his plan. Besides, the exchange on f3 is part of Black's plan anyway.} (13. Rb1 {is likely to lead to a transposition to 13.b4. It could be the choice of those wishing to avoid 13.b4 Nxb4.} e6 (13... a5 14. a3 e6 15. b4 axb4 16. axb4 N8e7 17. b5 {also transposes.}) 14. b4 a6 {transposing.}) (13. b4 {is examined in Lines 4 to 5.}) 13... Bxf3 14. Bxf3 {The main achievement of 13.h3 is helping White to clear the e2-square for the knight, in order to consolidate d4. This fails to ensure absolute safety in the centre, since after ...Ne7-f5, the bishop on e3 will be exposed to an exchange, with the corresponding weakening of the dark squares. Moreover, the other bishop will also be exposed to ...Nh4, after the own knight cuts its retreat to e2.} e6 15. Qd2 {Preparing to consolidate d4.} (15. Rb1 {is too slow a way of starting the queenside attack.} N8e7 16. b4 Nf5 17. Ne2 Qf6 $1 {Just winning the central pawn.} (17... Nh4 18. b5 Nxf3+ 19. gxf3 Ne7 20. Ng3 h5 21. Qd2 h4 22. Ne2 Nf5 $11 {0-1 Sirosh,I (2402)-Nakamura,H (2766) Titled Tuesday intern op 24th May Late blitz 2022 (1)}) 18. b5 Ncxd4 19. Nxd4 Nxd4 20. Bxd4 Qxd4 21. Qxd4 Bxd4 22. Rfc1 Rfc8 $19 {0-1 Nitin,S (2381)-Hoang,C (2397) Titled Tuesday intern op 21st April blitz 2020 (4)}) (15. b4 {is quicker, but not threatening, either.} a6 (15... Nxb4 16. Rb1) 16. Rb1 N8e7 17. Qd2 (17. a4 Nf5 18. Ne2 Qf6 {leads to similar consequences as above, meaning that White loses d4.}) 17... Nf5 18. Ne2 Nh4 {Causing the typical kingside problems in this line.} 19. Bg4 h5 20. Bg5 Bf6 21. Bxh4 Bxh4 {This exchange favours Black, since d4 is even weaker than before and the black central pawns strongly restrict the white bishop.} 22. Bf3 Qf6 (22... b5 $5 {, stabilizing the queenside, is also good.}) 23. a4 Rfd8 24. Rb3 (24. b5 axb5 25. axb5 Na5 {opens new perspectives for the black knight, since the white bishop is not in time to prevent ...Nc4 with Be2.}) 24... Bg5 25. Qc3 e5 26. dxe5 Nxe5 27. Nd4 Bh6 28. Be2 Bg7 $11 {0-1 Sanchez,J (2461)-Dzhumaev,M (2529) Rochefort op 8th 2009 (6)}) 15... N8e7 16. Nb5 {Trying to change the course of the game.} (16. Rad1 {leads to similar play as above.} Nf5 17. Ne2 Nh4 18. Bg4 h5 19. Bg5 Bf6 20. Bxh4 Bxh4 21. Bf3 Bg5 22. Qc3 a5 23. a3 Bf6 24. b4 axb4 25. axb4 {0-1 Gvilava,M (2052)-Chestnov,D (2146) Vladimir op-B 2009 (5)} b5 $1 $15 {After stabilizing the queenside, Black has two comfortable targets on b4 and d4. This will help him in the fight for the a-file. With his knight stuck on e2, White cannot organize an attack against the b5-pawn.}) 16... Nf5 {Defending d6 and threatening ...a7-a6.} 17. Bg4 a6 18. Bxf5 axb5 19. Bc2 Ra3 {White has reached a normal regrouping, but Black cannot be unhappy about his position, either. The next phase of the game is interesting.} 20. b4 f5 {Obviously directed against the d4-pawn, but also weakening the central pawns a bit.} 21. Bb3 Qf6 22. Qd3 f4 23. Bc1 Ra6 {A surprisingly cautious move for Fischer.} (23... Rxb3 $1 24. axb3 Qxd4 $15 {leads to one-sided play, where White cannot undertake anything active.}) 24. Bb2 f3 25. g3 Qf5 26. Qxf5 gxf5 27. Rad1 Nxb4 28. Rfe1 Rfa8 (28... f4 $2 29. a3 Nc6 30. Rxe6 $16 {½-½ Browne,W-Fischer,R Rovinj/Zagreb 1970 (15)}) (28... Kf7 29. Re3 Nxa2 30. Rde1 $13) 29. a3 Rxa3 {Once again, an exchange sacrifice, aimed at maintaining Black's superb stability.} 30. Bxa3 Rxa3 31. Re3 Nc6 32. Bxd5 {White is forced to return the exchange and simplify to an equal ending. Otherwise, the weakness on d4 would doom him.} Rxe3 33. Bxc6 Rc3 34. Bxb7 b4 $11 *

