{[%evp 0,76,19,38,89,89,79,48,44,44,63,51,37,21,54,39,23,30,52,53,45,11,11,17,-3,-3,19,23,15,-20,-28,-12,-7,3,-5,-8,17,34,28,33,27,-25,28,22,36,36,24,33,33,32,32,0,0,-75,-75,-50,-17,1,-47,-37,-37,-5,0,4,4,0,0,0,0,0,0,-23,-38,-270,-295,-296,-312,-29997,-29998]} 1. e4 Nf6 2. e5 Nd5 3. d4 d6 4. Nf3 g6 5. Be2 Bg7 6. O-O O-O 7. c4 Nb6 8. Nc3 Nc6 9. exd6 cxd6 10. Be3 Bg4 11. b3 d5 12. c5 Nc8 13. b4 {The quickest way of starting the queenside attack. White intends to drive the knight away from c6 before the pressure on d4 becomes unbearable.} ({As mentioned before,} 13. Rb1 {may just transpose.}) 13... a6 ({Traditionally considered not recommendable and only rarely played,} 13... Nxb4 {deserves some attention.} 14. Qb3 {The most challenging move, leaving White with a choice between taking on d5 and b7 after the knight retreat.} (14. Rb1 Nc6 15. Rxb7 e6 $11 {fails to affect Black's stability and to cross his plans.}) 14... a5 $1 {As we will see below, this apparently weakening move is necessary. It clears the a7-square for the c8-knight and ensures Black some queenside space.} 15. a3 Nc6 16. Qxb7 (16. Qxd5 Qxd5 17. Nxd5 e6 (17... Bxf3 18. Bxf3 Nxd4 {is likely to yield White some pressure.} 19. Rab1 Nxf3+ 20. gxf3 e6 21. c6 bxc6 22. Nc7 Ne7 23. Nxa8 Rxa8 24. Rfc1 $14) 18. Nc7 Rb8 $13 {[%cal Gc8e7,Gf8d8] followed by ...N8e7 and ...Rfd8.}) (16. Nxd5 e6 17. Nc3 N8e7 18. Nb5 a4 19. Qc4 Nd5 $13) 16... N8a7 17. Rfd1 Rb8 18. Qa6 Bxf3 19. Bxf3 e6 20. Na4 Rb3 21. Be2 {0-1 Petr,J (2183)-Richterova,N (2186) CZE-chT1W 1617 2016 (8.6)} (21. Rd2 f5 22. Bd1 Rxe3 23. fxe3 f4 24. exf4 Bxd4+ 25. Rxd4 Nxd4 $15 {[%cal Ga7c6] Planning ...N7c6.} 26. Qxa7 $2 Qf6 $1 $19 {[%csl Gf4][%cal Gd4c6,Gd4e2] with a decisive attack. Black threatens both ...Ne2+ and ...Qxf4.}) 21... f5 $15 {The central pawn is in trouble. True, the knight on a7 seems to be hanging after capturing on d4, but so are the rook on a1 and the bishop on e2.} 22. Bf4 (22. g3 g5 $17 {only makes things worse for White, since his king is exposed now, too.}) (22. Ra2 f4 23. Bc1 Bxd4 24. Rxd4 Nxd4 25. Qxa7 Rb1 $19) 22... Nxd4 23. Bf1 Nac6 $15) 14. Rb1 {Before continuing the attack with a2-a4, White needs to defend the pawn on b4.} (14. a4 {allows} Nxb4 (14... b6 $5 15. b5 axb5 16. axb5 Rxa1 17. Qxa1 Bxf3 18. bxc6 Bxe2 19. Nxe2 bxc5 20. Rb1 Qd6 $13 {1-0 Ivarsson,J-Neckar,L Bad Pyrmont 1969 (8)}) 15. Qb3 a5 $15) (14. Qb3 {exposes the queen and weakens the defence on d4.} e6 15. Rad1 N8e7 16. h3 Bxf3 17. Bxf3 b6 (17... Nf5 $15) 18. Ne2 Rb8 19. Qa3 bxc5 20. bxc5 a5 21. g4 {Preventing ...Nf5.} Rb4 $15 {0-1 Jacek,M (2138)-Neckar,L (2302) CZE-chT2c 0607 2006 (11.5)}) (14. Qd2 e6 {does not change anything essentially.}) (14. b5 axb5 15. Nxb5 {ensures White some stability, but turns his structure less compact and fails to trouble the knight on c6.} e6 16. h3 (16. Qd2 N8e7 17. Rab1 Nf5 18. Rfd1 {0-1 Hallier,K-Zilberberg,A EU-ch corr ICCF corr 1973} Ra4 $15) 16... Bxf3 17. Bxf3 N8e7 18. Qd2 (18. Nd6 b6 {weakens the White structure even more.}) 18... Qa5 (18... Nf5 19. a4 Na5 $15) 19. Qb2 b6 (19... e5 20. Rfd1 e4 21. Be2 Nf5 $13 {0-1 Carlsen,M (2214)-Kopylov,M (2421) Kiel op 15th 2002 (5)}) 20. cxb6 Qxb6 21. Rfb1 Na5 $15) 14... e6 15. a4 {The most consistent continuation.} (15. Ne1 Bxe2 16. Nxe2 N8e7 17. Ng3 (17. a4 Nf5 18. b5 axb5 19. axb5 Nxe3 20. fxe3 Na5 $11 {[%cal Gg7h6,Ga5c4,Gf7f5] followed by ...Bg5, ...Nc4 and ...f7-f5, with good counterplay on dark squares.}) 17... b5 {The typical way of stabilizing the queenside.} 18. cxb6 Qxb6 19. Nf3 Rfc8 20. Qd2 Na7 21. Bh6 (21. a4 Rab8 $11) 21... Nb5 (21... Bh8 $11) 22. Bxg7 Kxg7 23. Qg5 Ng8 24. Nh5+ {½-½ Szilagyi,P-Kadrev,Z EU-chT 03th Group3 1964 (2.10)} Kf8 25. Nf6 Nxf6 26. Qxf6 Kg8 27. h4 Nd6 28. h5 Ne4 29. Qf4 Qd6 $11) (15. Qd2 N8e7 {mainly gives Black a free tempo.}) 15... N8e7 16. b5 axb5 17. axb5 Bxf3 {The fact that this line is viable for Black indicates that h2-h3 in the previous phase (as in Line 3) is premature. Black eliminates an important defender of the pawn on d4 and makes the square on c4 available for the knight, even though this is relative as we will see.} ({The neutral and possibly more consistent} 17... Na5 {is examined in Line 5.}) 18. Bxf3 Na5 19. Be2 (19. Bg5 {is an interesting way of preparing a later exchange sacrifice on c4.} h6 20. Bxe7 Qxe7 21. Qd3 Qg5 22. Rb4 Nc4 23. Rxc4 {Sooner or later, White would have to eliminate this knight anyway.} dxc4 24. Qxc4 Rad8 25. Rd1 Qf4 26. Ne2 Qb8 27. b6 Rd7 28. g3 Rfd8 {White has good compensation for the exchange, but the weakness on d4 restricts his active possibilities.} 29. h4 (29. d5 exd5 30. Rxd5 Bf6 31. Kg2 Kg7 32. Nf4 Be5 33. Rxd7 Rxd7 34. Nd5 h5 35. h4 Qe8 36. c6 bxc6 37. Qxc6 Rd8 $11) 29... Qa8 30. Kg2 Qa5 31. d5 {The only try, leading to double-edged play.} Bf8 $1 32. d6 $2 (32. Nc3 Qxc5 33. Qxc5 Bxc5 34. Ne4 Be7 35. d6 Rxd6 36. Nxd6 Rxd6 37. Rxd6 Bxd6 38. Bxb7 Bc5 $11) 32... Rc8 33. c6 (33. Rc1 Bxd6 $17) 33... Qxb6 34. Nf4 Rxc6 $17 {0-1 Janosevic,D-Gheorghiu,F Skopje/Ohrid Solidarnost-02 1968 (6)}) (19. Rb4 {has similar ideas.} Nc4 {Black threatens ...Nxe3 followed by ...Nf5 and ...Bh6, forcing White's hand.} (19... Nf5 20. Be2 {transposes below.}) 20. Bg5 (20. g4 Nxe3 21. fxe3 h5 $1 $132 22. gxh5 $6 Nf5 23. Qd2 Qg5+ 24. Kh1 Qxe3 $15) (20. Rxc4 dxc4 21. Bxb7 Ra3 22. Qc1 Rb3 23. b6 (23. Rd1 Qa5 $17) 23... Bxd4 24. Ne4 c3 $15) 20... Qa5 21. Rxc4 dxc4 {led to lively play in a correspondence game.} 22. Bxe7 (22. Bxb7 Rab8 23. Ba6 (23. Bf3 Nf5 24. Ne4 Qxb5 $17) 23... Nc6 $5 $13 {attacking d4 and threatening ...Nb4.}) 22... Rfe8 23. Bxb7 Rab8 24. Bd6 Rxb7 25. Qf3 Rd7 (25... Rxb5 26. Nxb5 Qxb5 $11 {is a simpler and more human way of reaching approximate equality.}) 26. Qc6 Red8 27. Ne4 Bxd4 28. b6 Qa8 (28... Rxd6 29. Nxd6 Qxc5 30. Qxc5 Bxc5 31. Nxc4 Rb8 32. Rb1 Rb7 $11) 29. Qxa8 Rxa8 30. Rc1 Rb7 31. g3 f5 32. Ng5 Ra1 33. Rxa1 Bxa1 34. Nxe6 Bf6 35. c6 {½-½ Bianchi,N (2100)-Valverde Toresano,A (2124) IECG CA.2003.0.00103 email} Rxb6 36. c7 Rc6 37. Nd8 Rxc7 38. Bxc7 c3 39. Nc6 c2 40. Bf4 Bb2 $11) 19... Nf5 20. Qd2 {Played in the vast majority of games, this naturally developing move does not seem to face Black with any special problems.} (20. g4 Nxe3 21. fxe3 {1-0 Barr,E-Sawyer,T APCT corr USA 1997} Qg5 22. Rf4 Rad8 $15 {[%cal Ge6e5]}) (20. Na4 Nc4 $5 {leads to dynamic play.} 21. Bxc4 dxc4 22. Nb6 Ra2 23. Nxc4 Nxd4 $11 (23... Qd5 24. Nb6 (24. Nd2 Bxd4 25. Bxd4 Nxd4 $15 {1-0 Hartmann,D-Vuillemot,M FRA corr France 1992}) (24. Rc1 Nxd4 $11) 24... Nxe3 25. Nxd5 Nxd1 26. Ne7+ Kh8 27. Rfxd1 Bf6 28. d5 Bxe7 29. d6 $11) 24. Nd6 {Allowing Black to fight for the initiative.} (24. Re1 {is more cautious.} Qd5 25. Nb6 Qe4 26. c6 $5 bxc6 27. Nd7 Rd8 28. b6 Rxd7 29. b7 Rxb7 30. Rxb7 h5 $11 {Black has entirely adequate compensation for the exchange.}) 24... Ne2+ 25. Kh1 Qh4 26. Qb3 Be5 $1 27. h3 (27. f4 Ng3+ 28. Kg1 Ne2+ 29. Kh1 Ng3+ 30. Kg1 {Black could continue delivering checks, with a draw, or else continue playing with} Nxf1 31. Qxa2 Nxe3 32. fxe5 Qd4 33. Qb2 Qxc5 34. Nxb7 Qd5 35. Nd6 Ng4 $13 {The e5-pawn is doomed, but the pawn on b5 is likely to ensure White adequate compensation.}) (27. g3 $2 Bxg3 28. fxg3 Nxg3+ 29. Kg1 Qxh2#) 27... Ng3+ 28. Kg1 (28. fxg3 Qxg3 $19) 28... Nxf1 (28... Ne2+ 29. Kh1 Rfa8 30. Rfe1 R8a3 31. Qc4 Nd4 32. Qf1 $13 {0-1 Kozlitin,O (2348)-Naumenko,O (2133) Chigorin Memorial 22nd 2014 (6)}) 29. Qxa2 Nxe3 30. fxe3 Qg3 $17) ({Even though rarely played,} 20. Rb4 {is consistent.} Nxe3 21. fxe3 Qg5 22. Rf3 e5 {Engines are skeptical about this natural continuation, but I find it playable.} 23. dxe5 (23. g3 {is the engines' favourite. White over-defends f4, preparing for Black's natural answer.} e4 24. Rf4 b6 {Stabilizing the knight.} (24... Bh6 25. Qc1 b6 26. c6 Qe7 27. Rb1 Bxf4 $2 28. Nxd5 $16) 25. c6 Qd8 26. Qd2 Qd6 27. Rb2 f5 28. Rf1 Bh6 29. Kh1 Kg7 {To my understanding, the position is statically balanced. The engines keep evaluating that White is a bit better, but suggest lines where the white rooks move along the first rank without any clear plan.}) (23. e4 exd4 24. Nxd5 Rfc8 25. Qc2 Bf8 $11) 23... Qxe5 24. Nxd5 {1-0 Messing,H (2355)-Begovac,F (2405) CRO-chT Pula 1993 (5)} Rac8 {White has problems keeping his extra pawn.} 25. Qd4 (25. Nb6 Qxc5 26. Nxc8 Qxb4 $11) 25... Rfe8 {Threatening ...Qxd4, when due to the hanging bishop on e2, White loses the pawn on c5.} 26. Kf2 (26. Qxe5 Bxe5 27. Ra4 Nb3 $11) (26. Bf1 f5 {[%cal Ge5e6]} 27. Qxe5 Bxe5 $11) 26... f5 $5 {Preparing ...Qe6 followed by ...Rxc5, without allowing Nf6+.} 27. Qxe5 Bxe5 $11) 20... h6 $1 {An accurate move, preparing ...e6-e5 under optimal circumstances. It is wrong to call such subtleties "computer ideas", since the line has been known since late '706.} ({In classical times, nobody played} 20... e5 {since it was known that} 21. Bg5 $1 {causes slight problems.} ({In modern times, people seem to have forgotten the old knowledge, though:} 21. Na4 $2 {1-0 Hou,Y (2578)-Le,K (2291) WMSG Rapid Pair KO 1st 2008 (2.2)} Nc4 $17) 21... f6 22. Be3 $14) 21. Rfd1 (21. Rb4 {can be answered with} e5 $146 22. dxe5 d4 23. Bxd4 Nb3 $3 {A nice tactical resource.} 24. Rxb3 Nxd4 25. Rb2 Bxe5 {Threatening ...Nxe2.} 26. Ne4 Qd5 27. Bf3 Kg7 {Black's dominating position in the centre ensures him adequate compensation for the pawn.} 28. Qb4 (28. Rd1 Ra3 29. Rb4 Rd8 $44) 28... Nxf3+ (28... f5 29. Nd6 Nxf3+ 30. gxf3 b6 31. Nc4 bxc5 32. Rd2 Bd4 $13) 29. gxf3 Bxb2 30. Qxb2+ f6 $13) 21... Qe7 $146 {Black needs to prepare the central break a bit more.} (21... Re8 22. Rb4 e5 23. dxe5 d4 24. Bxd4 Nxd4 25. Rxd4 Qc7 {1-0 Micklethwaite,M-Twitchell,N BFCC Open S105 corr 2001} 26. Rd5 $16) 22. Rb4 {Over defending d4 and c4.} (22. g4 Nxe3 23. Qxe3 Rfd8 $11) 22... Rfd8 23. Na4 (23. g4 Nxe3 24. Qxe3 b6 {is one of the moments proving that e7 is the best square for the queen.} 25. Na4 bxc5 26. dxc5 Nb7 27. Rdb1 {Unpinning the c5-pawn.} (27. Rc1 Rac8 {[%cal Gd5d4,Gg7f8] followed by either ...d5-d4 or ...Bf8.}) 27... Rxa4 $1 (27... d4 28. Qc1 Rxa4 {transposes.}) 28. Rxa4 Nxc5 29. Ra3 d4 $44) 23... e5 $1 24. Nb6 exd4 25. Bf4 {The position is complicated and offers chances to both sides.} d3 (25... Qxc5 26. Nxa8 Nc4 27. Bxc4 dxc4 28. Ra4 d3 $44) 26. Bf1 (26. Bxd3 Qxc5 27. Nxa8 Bc3 $15) 26... Qxc5 27. Nxa8 Nc4 28. Qe1 d2 (28... Rxa8 29. Bxd3 Nb2 30. Rxb2 Bxb2 31. Bxf5 gxf5 32. Bxh6 Qxb5 $13) 29. Bxd2 Nxd2 30. Qxd2 Bc3 31. Rc4 $1 Qxc4 32. Bxc4 Bxd2 33. Rxd2 Rxa8 34. Rxd5 Kf8 $11 {Black will not have the least problem after centralizing the king. True, the bishop is supposed to be more active than the knight, but the pawn on b5 is vulnerable.} 35. Rd7 $6 Ke8 36. Rxb7 $2 Nd6 37. Rc7 Nxc4 38. Rxc4 Ra1+ {mating next.} *

