{[%evp 0,49,28,25,79,79,64,46,46,35,75,45,45,15,27,30,37,38,45,45,41,17,17,15,15,18,15,26,26,-12,-5,-28,-28,-23,-32,-32,-32,-46,-59,-58,-49,-49,-50,-28,-29,-41,-57,-53,-66,-57,-66,-76]} 1. e4 Nf6 2. e5 Nd5 3. d4 d6 4. Nf3 g6 5. Be2 Bg7 6. O-O O-O 7. c4 Nb6 8. Nc3 Nc6 9. exd6 cxd6 10. Be3 Bg4 11. b3 d5 12. c5 Nc8 13. b4 a6 14. Rb1 e6 15. a4 N8e7 16. b5 axb5 17. axb5 Na5 {Things were sometimes on the edge for Black in the lines above, so the immediate knight jump to a5 is simpler. Black keeps the exchange on f3 in reserve, while any knight move on f3 would weaken White's control over c4.} 18. Ne5 {With ...Bxf3 in the air, in most of the games, White moves away with his knight.} (18. Nd2 {is passive.} Bxe2 19. Qxe2 (19. Nxe2 Nf5 20. Qc2 e5 {This is justified by the temporary and relative passivity of the white knights.} 21. Qc3 Re8 22. dxe5 Bxe5 23. Bd4 Bxh2+ $5 (23... Nxd4 24. Nxd4 Rc8 25. N2f3 Bf6 26. Rfe1 Re4 $11) 24. Kxh2 Rxe2 $11 {[%cal Gf5d4]} (24... Qh4+ 25. Kg1 Rxe2 26. Bf6 $14 {1-0 Baumann,K-Schwab,P EU-ch M corr 1996} d4 27. Qf3 $18) 25. Bf6 d4 26. Qd3 (26. Qf3 Qc7+ 27. Kg1 Rxd2 $19) 26... Rxd2 27. Qxd2 Qxf6 $17) 19... Nf5 20. Rb4 e5 {½-½ Manik,M (2345)-Konopka,M (2440) SVK-chT Slovakia 1995} 21. Na4 (21. dxe5 d4) (21. Nf3 exd4 22. Nxd4 Nxe3 23. Qxe3 Rc8 24. Na4 Nc4 25. Qd3 Re8 $15 {[%cal Gg7f8]}) 21... exd4 22. Bf4 Re8 23. Qd3 Bf8 24. g4 Ng7 25. Rxd4 Ne6 26. Rxd5 Nxf4 27. Rxd8 Raxd8 $15 28. Qc2 Re2 29. Rd1 $2 Nh3+ 30. Kg2 Nxf2 $19) (18. Bg5 {Exchanging this bishop weakens the central pawn.} h6 19. Bxe7 Qxe7 20. Re1 Bxf3 {Now is a good moment for this exchange.} 21. Bxf3 Qf6 22. Ne2 (22. Rb4 Nc4) 22... Nc4 23. Rb4 (23. Qd3 Ra3 24. Rb3 Rfa8 $17 {0-1 Pourkashiyan,A (2322)-Gozzoli,Y (2595) Titled Tuesday intern op 15th Feb Early blitz 2022 (5)}) 23... Rfb8 {[%csl Gb7][%cal Gb4c4] Defending b7 in anticipation of Rxc4.} 24. Be4 $5 Ra2 {[%cal Ga2d2]} 25. Bc2 (25. Bd3 Nb2 26. Qd2 Nxd3 27. Qxd3 e5 $15) 25... b6 26. c6 Rba8 $15) (18. Qd2 {Now is not a good moment for this move, since Black can invade c4 with gain of time.} Bxf3 19. Bxf3 Nc4 20. Qd3 Nf5 $15 {0-1 Pourramezanali,A (2525)-Maghsoodloo,P (2594) Fajr op 26th 2018 (7)}) (18. Rb4 {This idea remains interesting, even though it offers Black more freedom than in the similar line above.} Nf5 19. Qc1 {A consistent move, defending the knight and controlling a3.} (19. h3 {practically throws a tempo away.} Bxf3 20. Bxf3 Nc4 21. Rxc4 dxc4 22. Bxb7 Ra3 23. Ne2 Rxe3 24. fxe3 Nxe3 25. Qd2 Nxf1 26. Kxf1 Qf6+ 27. Bf3 e5 28. dxe5 Qxe5 29. Qd5 Qa1+ 30. Kf2 c3 31. c6 c2 32. Qc5 Bd4+ {0-1 Lehto,V-Konopka,M (2405) Espoo op 1989 (3)}) (19. Bd3 Nh4 $11) (19. Bg5 Qc7 $11 {leaves the pawn on d4 vulnerable.}) 19... Bxf3 (19... Qe7 20. Bg5 Qd7 21. Ne5 Bxe5 22. dxe5 Bxe2 23. Nxe2 $14 {1-0 Acor,C (2325)-Bodi,T (2274) Titled Tuesday intern op 30th Nov blitz 2021 (4)}) 20. Bxf3 Nc4 (20... Nxe3 21. fxe3 Bh6 $132) 21. Rxc4 {Otherwise ...Ncxe3 followed by ...Bh6.} dxc4 22. Bxb7 Ra7 23. Bf3 ({In the event of} 23. c6 {, if Black wishes to avoid unclear positions, he can simplify with} Rxb7 $5 24. cxb7 Qc7 $11) 23... Bxd4 24. b6 (24. Rd1 Rd7 25. Bxd4 Nxd4 26. c6 Rd6 $13) 24... Ra5 25. Rd1 Rxc5 (25... Bxe3 26. fxe3 Qg5 27. Ne4 Qxe3+ 28. Qxe3 Nxe3 29. Rb1 f5 30. Nc3 Rxc5 31. b7 Rb8 {[%cal Ge3d5]} 32. Ra1 Rc7 33. Ra8 Rcxb7 34. Bxb7 Rxa8 35. Bxa8 Kf7 $11 {Black has three pawns for the bishop and the square on h8 has a different colour than those the bishop is acting on. This would make the endgame with the bishop and the h-pawn versus nothing a clear draw. However, Black will probably not have to go to such extremes.}) 26. b7 e5 27. g4 Nxe3 28. fxe3 Qf6 29. exd4 exd4 30. Ne4 Qxf3 31. Nxc5 Qxg4+ {with a perpetual check.}) 18... Bxe2 19. Nxe2 (19. Qxe2 Bxe5 20. dxe5 Nf5 21. Rb4 Nc4 22. Ne4 {½-½ Broemme,S-Mueller Toepler,M GER OS-089 email 2008} Ncxe3 $5 23. Nf6+ Kg7 24. fxe3 Qe7 25. Rc1 Rfc8 26. g4 Rxc5 27. Rf1 Nh6 28. Rbf4 Qc7 $13) 19... Bxe5 20. dxe5 Nf5 21. Bd2 (21. Qc1 Nxe3 22. Qxe3 Nc4 23. Qd4 Qc7 $17 {[%cal Gf8c8]}) (21. Bd4 Qh4 $5 22. g3 Qh5 $132) (21. Bf4 Nc4 22. Ng3 Nxg3 23. hxg3 Qe7 $13) 21... Nc4 22. Bc3 Qg5 23. Ng3 Nxg3 24. hxg3 Rfc8 25. Ra1 $15 {½-½ Sukhov,N (2418)-Fedorko,A (2082) IECG CP.2001.F.00002 2005} Qe7 26. Rxa8 (26. Bd4 Rxa1 27. Qxa1 Nd2 28. Rd1 Nb3 $17) 26... Rxa8 27. Bd4 Qe8 28. b6 Na5 29. f4 Nc6 $15 *

