1. e4 Nf6 2. e5 Nd5 3. d4 d6 4. Nf3 g6 5. Be2 Bg7 6. O-O O-O 7. c4 Nb6 8. Nc3 Nc6 9. exd6 cxd6 10. h3 {This is the other main move, together with 10.Be3. Before continuing to develop, White prevents ...Bg4, thus securing his pawn on d4.} Bf5 {An active developing move. Black embarks on some sort of waiting game. He would usually play typical ...d6-d5 only after White develops his bishop to e3.} (10... e5 {is answered with the familiar} 11. Bg5 f6 12. Be3 $14) (10... d5 {is premature, since after} 11. c5 Nc4 {there is no white bishop on e3.} 12. b3 N4a5 13. Be3 b6 14. cxb6 axb6 15. Rc1 Bf5 16. Qd2 Nb7 17. Nb5 Rc8 18. Bf4 Qd7 19. Rfd1 $14 {1-0 Averbakh,Y-Kortschnoj,V URS-chT Republics 07th final A 1960 (7) The knight on b7 does not have perspectives.}) 11. b3 {The main alternative to the developing moves. White takes the control over c4, preventing the later knight's invasion. On the other hand, this move weakens the long diagonal, offering Black the possibility of deviating from the usual paths.} (11. Re1 {This relatively rare move is the most consequential way of continuing the half-waiting game. It is still too early for Black to play ...d6-d5.} Rc8 {Same policy.} 12. Bf1 {Still waiting.} (12. g4 Bd7 13. c5 dxc5 14. dxc5 Na8 {One of the ideas behind developing the rook to c8. The knight has comfortable access back to the centre via c7-e6 now.} 15. Be3 Nc7 (15... Be6 16. Qc1 b6 $5 $146 17. Ba6 Rc7 18. Rd1 Rd7 $11) 16. Qb3 {½-½ Langheld,W (1924)-Friend,R (1931) SB-2018-0-00540} e5 {planning ...Ne6 or immediately ...Nd4.} 17. Qxb7 $2 Rb8 $19 {In this simple trap, we can notice the knight's perfect coordination.}) 12... e5 {With his development complete, Black can undertake concrete actions already.} 13. Bg5 (13. Be3 {½-½ Marcinkowski,K-Bielavsky,J Warszawa Cup5-B op 1979 (6)} e4 14. Nd2 d5 15. c5 Na8 16. f3 exf3 17. Nxf3 Nc7 $11) 13... Qd7 {With the bishop on f5, this simple move maintains Black's coordination.} 14. dxe5 dxe5 15. c5 (15. Nb5 e4 16. Qxd7 Nxd7 17. Nd2 Bxb2 18. Rad1 e3 19. Rxe3 Bc2 20. Rde1 Nc5 21. Nb3 Bxb3 22. axb3 a5 $11 {½-½ Morozov,D (2376)-Pavlov,V (2417) RUS-ch14 sf-2 email 2014}) 15... Qxd1 16. Raxd1 Nd7 17. Nd5 (17. Nb5 Nxc5 18. Nd6 Rc7 19. Nxf5 gxf5 20. Nh4 Nd4 21. Be3 Nce6 $15 {0-1 Pacheco Lugo,A (2127)-Escalante Ramirez,B (2454) Titled Tuesday intern op 24th Aug blitz 2021 (5)}) 17... e4 (17... Rfe8 {[%cal Gh7h6]} 18. Bb5 f6 19. Be3 Be6 20. b4 h6 {[%cal Gf6f5] Planning ...f6-f5.} 21. Bc4 f5 22. b5 Ncb8 23. c6 bxc6 24. bxc6 Nxc6 25. Ba6 g5 26. Bxc8 Rxc8 27. Bxa7 e4 $44 {White's pieces are hanging and the pawn on a2 is vulnerable.}) 18. Bb5 Rfe8 (18... exf3 19. Bxc6 Rxc6 20. Ne7+ Kh8 21. Nxc6 bxc6 22. g4 Be6 23. Rxe6 fxe6 24. Rxd7 Bxb2 $11) 19. Bxc6 Rxc6 20. b4 (20. Ne7+ Rxe7 21. Bxe7 exf3 $17) 20... h6 21. Bh4 b6 22. g4 Be6 23. Rxe4 Kf8 $44 {½-½ Mishin,A (2330)-Pavlov,V (2417) RUS-ch14 sf-2 email 2014}) (11. Bf4 {runs into} e5 12. Bg5 (12. Be3 e4 (12... d5 $5) (12... Rc8 $5) 13. Nh2 d5 14. c5 {0-1 Tejkal,L (2135)-Michalek,F (2159) CZE-chT2c 0607 2006 (11.5)} Nd7 {[%cal Gd7f6]} 15. Nxd5 $6 Ndb8 16. Nf4 Nxd4 17. b4 Nbc6 $15) 12... Qd7 {A familiar reaction.} 13. d5 (13. dxe5 h6 $5 $146 14. Be3 dxe5 15. c5 Nc8 16. Qc1 g5 17. Rd1 Qe6 18. Nb5 Rb8 19. Nc7 {If Black intends to avoid the move repetition, he can try} Qg6 $5 $13) 13... Nd4 14. Nxd4 exd4 15. Nb5 Rfe8 (15... d3 16. Bxd3 {½-½ Maeder,K-Schiffer,K Bad Pyrmont International 1970 (7)} Rfc8 17. Rc1 Bxb2 18. Rc2 Bg7 $11) 16. g4 {The pawn on d4 is taboo due to the hanging bishop, so White needs to embark on concrete play.} d3 (16... Rxe2 $5 17. Qxe2 Re8 18. Qf3 Nxc4 19. gxf5 Qxb5 $44) 17. Bxd3 Bxd3 18. Qxd3 Bxb2 19. Rab1 Be5 20. Be3 Na4 21. Qa3 (21. Nxa7 h5 $15 22. f3 Nc5 23. Bxc5 dxc5 24. Nb5 Rxa2 $17) 21... a6 22. Qxa4 axb5 23. Qxb5 Qe7 24. c5 (24. Qxb7 Qh4 25. Kg2 Rxa2 $19 {[%cal Gh4g3] threatening ...Qg3+.}) 24... f5 $1 (24... Qh4 25. Kg2 Rxa2 26. Qxe8+ Kg7 27. Bf4 Bxf4 28. Rb3 $16) 25. Rb4 fxg4 26. Rxg4 Rxa2 27. Rb1 {½-½ Onem,C (1994)-Dlugolecki,G (2093) Afroasian-ch12 sf-D email 2010} Qf7 28. cxd6 Bxd6 29. Qxb7 Qf5 30. Bd4 Re7 $44) (11. g4 {gains a couple of tempi, but weakens the kingside.} Bc8 {Probably the best square for the bishop. Black keeps the d-file clear of minor pieces to enable ...d6-d5 and use the open file for other purposes later.} (11... Bd7 12. Be3 f5 13. c5 fxg4 14. Ng5 $36) 12. Be3 (12. c5 dxc5 13. dxc5 Qxd1 {One of the consequences of ...Bc8.} 14. Rxd1 Bxc3 15. bxc3 Na4) (12. Re1 f5 13. c5 (13. g5 e5 $15 {0-1 Kapitanchuk,T (2045)-Llanos,G (2368) ARG-ch sf Vicente Lopez 2016 (1)}) 13... fxg4 14. hxg4 (14. Ng5 $2 g3 15. fxg3 Bxd4+ $19) 14... dxc5 15. dxc5 Bxg4 $15) 12... f5 (12... d5 $5) 13. c5 dxc5 14. dxc5 fxg4 15. Ng5 (15. hxg4 Qxd1 16. Rfxd1 Bxg4 $11) 15... Bxc3 16. bxc3 Nd5 {Possible only with the bishop on c8.} 17. Bc4 e6 18. hxg4 Ne5 $11) (11. d5 {This pawn sacrifice yields White some compensation, but is not threatening.} Na5 12. Nd4 (12. Nd2 Rc8 $15) 12... Naxc4 13. a4 a5 14. Nxf5 gxf5 15. Re1 Re8 $5 $146 {Black prepares ...e7-e6, while maintaining the possibility of developing the queen to g6.} (15... Qd7 16. Bd3 e5 17. Qh5 e4 18. Bxc4 Nxc4 19. Bh6 Bxh6 20. Qxh6 f6 $13 {½-½ Roy,R (2020)-Senzacqua,F (2028) W-ch WS/H/769 email 2020}) 16. Bd3 e6 {[%cal Gd8f6] Engines evaluate the position as equal, but I feel that White still needs to prove his compensation for the pawn.}) (11. Be3 {is examined in Lines 7 and 8.}) (11. Bg5 {is the subject of Line 9.}) 11... d5 {Nevertheless!} 12. c5 (12. Be3 {transposes to Line 8.}) 12... Nd7 {fter b2-b3, this threatens ...Nxc5.} 13. Bb2 {Not the best square for the bishop, but there hardly is anything better.} (13. Nxd5 Nxc5 $15) (13. Be3 Nxc5 14. Nxd5 (14. g4 Ne4 $1 $17 {½-½ Lamorelle,Y (2171)-Gozzoli,Y (2222) FRA-chT2S 9899 1998 (7)}) 14... Ne6 15. Rc1 (15. Bc4 Be4 16. Nc3 Bxf3 17. Qxf3 Nexd4 18. Bxd4 Qxd4 19. Rac1 e6 $15 {0-1 Paoli,E (2210)-Landenbergue,C (2325) Reggio Emilia-B 8889 31st 1988 (10)}) 15... Qxd5 16. Bc4 Qa5 17. Bd2 (17. d5 Rad8 18. Bd2 Rxd5 $1 19. Bxa5 Rxd1 20. Rfxd1 Nxa5 $19) 17... Qxa2 18. b4 Qb2 19. Bc3 Qa3 20. g4 (20. Qd2 Rac8 21. Ra1 Qxc3 22. Qxc3 Ncxd4 23. Nxd4 Nxd4 $19) 20... Nexd4 $5 21. gxf5 Nxf5 $19 {0-1 Dubinsky,A-Grigorian,K URS Burevestnik CC-ch 1971}) 13... Be4 {Increasing the pressure on d4.} 14. Na4 {White needs to misplace another minor piece.} (14. Nxe4 dxe4 15. Ng5 Nxc5 16. dxc5 Bxb2 17. Rb1 Bg7 18. Qxd8 Rfxd8 19. Nxe4 {0-1 Dominguez,F (2141)-Escalante Ramirez,B (2422) American Continental 14th 2018 (3)} Rd4 20. Bf3 Rad8 $15) (14. Ng5 {is ineffective.} Bxd4 ({The less ambitious} 14... Bf5 {threatens both to take on d4 and to break with ...e7-e5, leaving the knight on g5 hanging. This forces} 15. Nf3 {, leading to a repetition.}) 15. b4 e5 16. Ngxe4 dxe4 $15) 14... Bxf3 15. Bxf3 e6 {We have reached a familiar structure. True, the knight on d7 does not have quick access to f5, but White's minor pieces are not especially active, either.} 16. Qd2 Qh4 17. Rfd1 $146 {For reasons revealed below, this is more constructive than placing the other rook on d1.} (17. Rad1 b5 $1 (17... Rfe8 18. Be2 a6 {½-½ Payen,A (2240)-Kahn,E (2245) Tapolca Budapest 1989 is playable, but does not show a clear plan.}) 18. cxb6 axb6 19. Be2 Nf6 $11 {The pawn on b6 is indirectly defended, since a2 is also hanging.}) 17... b5 {Even with the pawn on a2 defended, this works.} (17... Rad8 $5 {is another possible plan, using the fact that the white kingside is less well defended now.} 18. b4 e5 19. Bxd5 Nf6 20. Bxc6 bxc6 $36) 18. cxb6 axb6 19. Be2 Ne7 20. Bb5 Nf6 $132 {Black has the more compact structure and active play.} 21. Nxb6 $2 Ne4 $1 (21... Rab8 22. g3 (22. Qa5 Ne4 23. Rf1 Nxf2 24. Rxf2 Bxd4 25. Bxd4 Qxd4 26. Rc1 Rxb6) 22... Qxh3 23. Bf1 Qh5 24. Be2 $11) 22. Qe2 (22. g3 Qxh3 23. Bf1 Qh5 24. Qe2 Qxe2 25. Bxe2 Ra7 $15 {White's queenside majority is more of a weakness than strength. For instance:} 26. a4 Rb8 27. a5 Nc6 $17) 22... Rab8 23. Nd7 Rxb5 24. Nxf8 Bxf8 25. Qxb5 (25. g3 Qf6 $19) 25... Qxf2+ 26. Kh1 Nf5 $19 *

