1. e4 Nf6 2. e5 Nd5 3. d4 d6 4. Nf3 g6 5. Be2 Bg7 6. O-O O-O 7. c4 Nb6 8. Nc3 Nc6 9. exd6 cxd6 10. h3 Bf5 11. Be3 {The most natural and popular move, allowing Black to start his counterplay, though.} d5 12. c5 {The by far most popular move. Long decades of practice and recent engine checking coincide in evaluating Black's play as comfortable.} (12. b3 {is examined in Line 8.}) 12... Nc4 13. Bxc4 (13. Bc1 {is simplest met with} b6 $1 14. cxb6 {A necessary concession, making the d6-square available to the knight and clearing the a-file for the rook on a8.} (14. b3 {runs into} bxc5 $1 15. bxc4 cxd4 16. Nxd5 d3 17. Bxd3 Bxd3 18. Qxd3 Bxa1 $15 {as played in relatively many games.}) 14... axb6 15. b3 Na3 (15... Nd6 $11 {0-1 Nay,O (2595)-Yin,H (2496) Sufe Cup Shanghai 2000 (4)}) 16. Bxa3 Rxa3 17. Nb5 Ra8 18. Rc1 Qd7 19. Qd2 Rfc8 20. Rc3 Na7 $11 {1-0 Maric,R-Quinteros,M Vinkovci 1970 (11)}) 13... dxc4 14. Qa4 (14. d5 {exposes the white centre while sending the knight onto a favourable path.} Nb4 15. Bd4 (15. a3 Nc2 16. Rc1 Nxe3 17. fxe3 Bd3 18. Rf2 Bxc3 19. Rxc3 Qxd5 $15 {½-½ Nielsen,T-Brunner,L Nordic Team-ch 1983}) (15. Qd2 Bd3 $15 {0-1 Albert,K (2110)-Grunberg,M (2380) Timisoara op 1995 (3)}) 15... Bd3 16. Bxg7 Kxg7 17. Re1 Rc8 18. Re5 Rxc5 19. Qd2 Ra5 (19... Nxd5 20. b4 Nxc3 21. bxc5 Nd5 $44) 20. Rae1 {0-1 Weigend,J-Lemieux,Y EU-ch M1241 corr 2000} Nxd5 21. Nxd5 Rxd5 22. Rxe7 Rd7 23. Qc3+ Kg8 24. Rxd7 Qxd7 25. Ne5 Qd6 $11 26. Ng4 f6 $11) 14... Bd3 15. Rfd1 {Inderectly defending d4.} (15. Rfe1 {is long known to be inoffensive.} Nxd4 16. Nxd4 Bxd4 17. Bxd4 Qxd4 18. Rxe7 Qxc5 19. Rxb7 Rfb8 20. Qd7 Rxb7 21. Qxb7 Re8 {½-½ Payrhuber,K-Ogaard,L World U20-ch10 Final B 1969 (11) Black's active pieces at least compensate for White's more compact structure. In fact, White maintains equality only due to his stable knight.}) 15... Qe8 $5 {This relatively rare move, known for several decades but enjoying some increase in popularity lately, maybe the simplest. Black clears the d8-square for his rook, after which the queen opposition along the a4-e8 diagonal restricts White's possibilities.} (15... Qa5 {and}) (15... e5 {are more popular but by no means better.}) ({It is curious that many players, including grandmasters, have fallen into the trap} 15... Nxd4 $2 16. Nxd4 Bxd4 17. Rxd3 $1 $16 {1-0 Nepomniachtchi,I (2784)-Riazantsev,A (2638) Play for Russia Prelim blitz 2020 (3) one example being}) 16. Qb5 {Trying to put some pressure.} (16. b3 {weakens the queenside slightly.} e5 17. bxc4 exd4 18. Nxd4 (18. Rxd3 dxc3 $15 {0-1 Mueller Ludwig,K (2077)-Diaz Diaz,J (2120) Oberliga Ost-B 0607 2006 (11.8)}) 18... Nxd4 19. Qxe8 Rfxe8 20. Bxd4 Bxd4 21. Rxd3 Bxc5 $11) (16. Ne1 {leads to simplifications.} Nxd4 17. Qxe8 Rfxe8 18. Nxd3 cxd3 19. Rxd3 Nc2 (19... e5 20. Rad1 Rac8 21. b4 b6 22. Ne4 {½-½ Magar,T-Gross,S (2420) St Ingbert op 1987 (1)} bxc5 $11 23. Nd6 c4 24. Ra3 Nc2 25. Rxa7 Nxe3 26. fxe3 Red8 $15) 20. Rad1 Rac8 21. Na4 Nxe3 22. Rxe3 Rc7 $11 {½-½ Sankalp,G (2254)-Aravindh,C (2579) IND-ch Challengers 55th 2017 (8)}) (16. d5 {typically runs into} Bxc3 17. bxc3 Nd4 $1 18. Qxe8 Ne2+ (18... Nxf3+ 19. gxf3 Rfxe8 $11 {is only optically more pleasant for Black.}) 19. Kh2 Rfxe8 20. Bd4 Rad8 21. Ne5 Rxd5 22. Nxd3 cxd3 23. Rxd3 e5 24. Re3 Nxd4 25. cxd4 Rxd4 $15) (16. Kh1 $146 {avoids the tricks based on ...Nd4 or ...Ne5, but wastes a tempo.} Rd8 (16... e5 17. d5 e4 18. Ne1 Ne7 $13) 17. Ne1 Nxd4 18. Nxd3 Qxa4 19. Nxa4 cxd3 20. Rxd3 f5 21. Rad1 Nc6 $15) (16. Rac1 {Strangely, nobody has tried this developing move yet.} Rd8 17. Qb5 {transposes below.}) 16... e5 {This is how a modern game continued.} ({Unsurprisingly, in a classical one, Black preferred to develop.} 16... Rd8 17. Rac1 (17. Qxb7 Rb8 18. Qa6 Rxb2 $13) 17... Qd7 (17... f5 18. d5 f4 19. Bd2 Bxc3 20. Bxc3 Rxd5 21. Qxb7 Qc8 $11) (17... e5 18. d5 e4 $13) 18. b3 Nxd4 19. Bxd4 Bxd4 {½-½ Mikhalchishin,A (2520)-Pacl,V (2295) Karvina Hornicky Kahanec-10 1987 (12)}) 17. d5 e4 18. Ne1 Nd4 19. Qxe8 Rfxe8 20. d6 Rad8 (20... f5 $5 21. Rac1 Rec8 22. b4 Kf7 23. f3 a5 24. bxa5 (24. a3 $2 axb4 25. axb4 Nb3 $17) 24... Rxc5 25. fxe4 fxe4 26. Nxd3 exd3 27. Rb1 Ra7 {White has to struggle a bit in order to avoid getting the worse position.} 28. d7 Ke7 29. Rf1 Rf5 30. Rxf5 gxf5 31. Nd5+ Kxd7 32. Nb6+ Kc6 33. Nxc4 Kd5 34. Nb6+ Ke4 35. Bd2 {White seems to be able to defend his fortress, but not more than that.}) 21. Rac1 b6 22. Bxd4 Bxd4 23. c6 Bxc3 (23... Rxd6 $2 24. Nb5 Rdd8 25. c7 Rd7 26. Nxd3 exd3 27. Rxc4 $18) 24. d7 Bxe1 25. dxe8=Q+ Rxe8 26. Rxe1 Rc8 27. f3 f5 $44 {0-1 Milman,L (2428)-Shabalov,A (2605) World op 32nd 2004 (5)} *

