1. e4 Nf6 2. e5 Nd5 3. d4 d6 4. Nf3 g6 5. Be2 Bg7 6. O-O O-O 7. c4 Nb6 8. Nc3 Nc6 9. exd6 cxd6 10. h3 Bf5 11. Be3 d5 12. b3 {Even though by far less popular than 12.c5, this needs investigating. White maintains the central tension, aiming for a position with hanging pawns. Since Black has spent some time jumping around with his king's knight and also advanced his pawn to d5 in two moves, he needs some accuracy to reach equality.} dxc4 {The most natural answer. Black prepares to increase his pressure on the hanging pawns.} (12... e5 13. c5 {is not entirely satisfactory.}) (12... e6 {is playable, but cutting off the bishopțs retreat is a demanding plan.}) 13. bxc4 e5 {Before attacking c4, Black breaks in the centre. This leads to a sharp position, since the white pawns can advance to the fifth rank.} ({The natural} 13... Na5 {gains the control over the light squares, but leaves White with a stable space advantage.} 14. c5 (14. Ne5 Be6 $5 15. c5 Nd5 16. Nxd5 Bxd5 17. Bf3 Nc6 $11) 14... Nd5 15. Nxd5 Qxd5 16. Qa4 b6 17. Rac1 $14 {0-1 Andreev,E (2514)-Rozentalis,E (2613) Cappelle op 29th 2013 (9)} (17. Ne5 $5 $14 {N})) 14. d5 ({Aimed at keeping the d5-square for the knight,} 14. dxe5 {weakens the centre and offers Black easy play.} Nxe5 15. Nxe5 Bxe5 16. Qb3 Qh4 17. f4 Bg7 18. Rf3 Rad8 19. Rc1 Bd4 (19... Qe7 20. Bf1 Be6 21. Nb5 Nd7 22. Nxa7 {½-½ Niewold,J (1817)-Deneuville,C (2250) VW-Cup2 Gr16 email 2009} Nf6 23. Nb5 Ne4 $44) 20. Nb5 (20. Bxd4 Rxd4 21. Nb5 Rxf4 $15) 20... Bxe3+ 21. Qxe3 Rfe8 22. Qf2 Qxf2+ 23. Rxf2 a6 $11) ({Now is not a good moment for} 14. g4 $2 {due to} exd4 $1 $15) 14... Na5 {Black keeps the advance of the e-pawn in reserve.} (14... e4 $2 {hands in the control over d4 too soon.} 15. Nd4 Nxd4 (15... Na5 16. Nxf5 gxf5 17. c5 Nbc4 18. Bxc4 Nxc4 19. Rc1 Nxe3 20. fxe3 $16 {leaves Black with serious structural problems.}) 16. Bxd4 {White has a good control in the centre.} Rc8 17. Nb5 a6 (17... Nxc4 18. Bxg7 Kxg7 19. Nxa7 Rc7 20. Qd4+ Qf6 21. Qxf6+ Kxf6 22. Rfc1 Ra8 23. Nb5 $18) 18. Na7 Ra8 19. Rb1 Nc8 20. Bxg7 Kxg7 21. Nxc8 Bxc8 22. Qd4+ Kg8 23. c5 $18 {1-0 Goehring,D-Wichert,B RR-21385 freechess.de 2018}) 15. c5 ({The intermediate} 15. g4 {runs into another intermediate move:} e4 16. Nd2 (16. Nd4 Bd7 17. c5 Nbc4 $15 {White has weaknesses all over the board.}) 16... Bxc3 17. Rc1 Be5 18. gxf5 Qh4 19. Kg2 gxf5 (19... Rac8 {[%cal Ge5f4] is a subtle way of preventing} 20. f4 $6 {, which runs into} exf3+ {[%csl Gc4]} 21. Rxf3 Naxc4 $15) (19... Bf4 $5 $11) 20. f4 Kh8 21. Qe1 {1-0 Malyshev,V-Bortolin,B W-ch GT278 corr 1992} Rg8+ 22. Kh2 Qh6 {With the white king insecure, Black should keep the queen, of course.} 23. fxe5 Qxe3 24. Rxf5 Rae8 {[%cal Ge8e5,Ge3f4]} 25. Rxf7 Rxe5 $13) 15... e4 {Now is a good moment for this Zwischenzug.} (15... Nbc4 {allows the familiar} 16. Bg5 {, when White has dangerous initiative. True, this evaluation has more of a "human" character, since the engines indicate approximate equality.} f6 (16... Qc8 17. Na4 h6 18. Bh4 b5 19. Rc1 g5 20. Bg3 Rd8 {[%cal Ge5e4,Gf5e6] with such ideas as ...e5-e4 or ...Be6.}) 17. Bh4 g5 (17... Rc8 18. g4 Bd7 19. Ne4 $14) 18. d6 $1 (18. Bg3 Rc8 19. Na4 b5 20. cxb6 axb6 $15) 18... Be6 19. Nd5 gxh4 20. Rc1 Nb2 21. Ne7+ Kh8 22. Qc2 {1-0 Binas,J (2318)-Nepustil,F (2370) CZE-ch28 final email 2016 Despite his extra piece, Black is walking on a tight rope.}) 16. Nh2 $146 {A solid move, keeping the d-file clear for the queen.} (16. cxb6 exf3 $17) (16. Nd2 Nxd5 17. Nxd5 Qxd5 18. Nc4 Qxd1 19. Raxd1 Nc6 20. Nd6 Be6 $11) (16. Nd4 Nxd5 17. Nxd5 Qxd5 18. Nxf5 Qxf5 19. Rb1 Rab8 20. Rb5 Nc6 21. Qb1 Bd4 22. Bh6 Rfd8 23. Rxb7 Bxc5 $44 {1-0 Bjornsson,T (2224)-Einarsson,E (2111) Reykjavik op 19th 2000 (2) with just some compensation to White.}) (16. Bg5 f6 17. Nd4 fxg5 18. cxb6 Qxb6 19. Nxf5 gxf5 $15) 16... Nbc4 {In the next phase, White will face problems keeping his space advantage. The knight is attacked, and the bishop on e3 is exposed to an exchange, thus making c5 a vulnerability.} (16... Bxc3 {is also possible.} 17. cxb6 axb6 (17... Bxa1 {looks like pushing things a bit too far.} 18. Qxa1 axb6 19. Bh6 f6 20. Bxf8 Qxf8 21. Qd4 $44) 18. Rb1 h5 $13) 17. Rc1 (17. Qc1 Rc8 18. g4 Bd7 19. Bxc4 (19. Nxe4 Qe7 20. Bxc4 Qxe4 21. Be2 Qxd5 $15) 19... Nxc4 20. Nxe4 Bb5 21. Bh6 Qxd5 $11) (17. Bd4 Nb2 18. Qd2 Nac4 19. Bxc4 Nxc4 20. Qd1 Nb2 21. Qd2 Nc4 22. Qe2 {The only way of avoiding a draw by move repetition.} Bxd4 23. Qxc4 Qf6 {[%cal Ga8c8] Threatening ...Rac8.} 24. Nxe4 {Fortunately for him, White has this resource.} Bxe4 25. Ng4 Qg7 26. Rad1 Bc3 (26... Bxd5 27. Qxd5 Rad8 28. Qxb7 h5 29. Nh2 Bxc5 $11) 27. c6 (27. Qxe4 f5 28. Qe6+ Kh8 29. Ne3 Rae8 30. Qd6 Be5) (27. Rc1 Bb2 $17) 27... Bf5 28. c7 Bd7 29. d6 Rae8 $15 {The far advanced pawns restrict Black's activity, but White has only one pawn for a minor piece.}) 17... Nxe3 18. fxe3 Rc8 19. g4 (19. Na4 $2 {is too passive.} Qg5 20. Qd2 Bxh3 $17 21. Rf2 Rfd8 {[%cal Ga5c6] Planning to bring the knight back into play with ...Nc6.} 22. Qxa5 Bxg2 $1 $17 23. Rxg2 Qxe3+ 24. Kh1 Qxc1+) (19. Nb5 {is a bit more active. One of the ideas is to defend the d-file with Nd6.} Qg5 20. Qd2 Bxh3 21. Rf2 Be5 22. Nf1 f5 23. Nd6 Rc7 $132 24. Qxa5 $6 Bxd6) 19... Rxc5 20. gxf5 Rxc3 $11 {A safe continuation.} ({The more ambitious player may consider} 20... Bxc3 {, but this obviously runs into} 21. Rxc3 Rxc3 22. Qd4 Qc7 23. Ng4 {. Concrete analysis proves that Black can reach a bit more than a draw by perpetual:} Qg3+ 24. Kh1 Qxh3+ 25. Kg1 Qg3+ 26. Kh1 Qh4+ 27. Kg1 Rc2 28. Nf6+ Kh8 29. fxg6 (29. Rf2 Rc1+ 30. Bf1 gxf5 31. Nd7+ f6 32. Nxf8 Nc4 $19 {[%cal Gc4e5] followed by ...Ne5.}) 29... Qg3+ 30. Kh1 Qxg6 31. Rg1 Qh6+ 32. Bh5 Rd2 33. Ng8+ Rxd4 34. Nxh6 Rxd5 35. Nxf7+ Rxf7 36. Bxf7 Rd8 37. Rg5 Nc6 38. Bd5 h6 39. Rh5 Kg7 $15) 21. Rxc3 Bxc3 22. Qc2 Bg7 23. Qxe4 Re8 24. Qf4 (24. Qd3 b5 {[%cal Ga5c4]} 25. Qxb5 Rxe3 $15) 24... Qxd5 25. Ng4 Qxf5 26. Qxf5 gxf5 27. Rxf5 Nc6 $15 {Due to his activity and the opposite-coloured bishops, White should probably reach a draw, but for now, Black is a pawn up.} *

