{[%evp 0,49,25,25,54,49,49,31,31,31,52,38,23,27,34,34,34,19,33,38,28,29,30,0,0,10,21,0,0,-2,-2,-5,-5,3,-1,6,-11,-61,-69,-43,-39,-54,-52,-58,-58,-72,-63,-72,-72,-67,-55,-61]} 1. e4 Nf6 2. e5 Nd5 3. d4 d6 4. Nf3 g6 5. Be2 Bg7 6. O-O O-O 7. c4 Nb6 8. Nc3 Nc6 9. exd6 cxd6 10. h3 Bf5 11. Bg5 {An interesting move. Before playing Be3, White intends to provoke ...h7-h6. In certain lines, the weakness on h6 may count.} h6 ({As we know already,} 11... d5 {is not entirely convincing without a bishop on e3.} 12. c5 h6 13. Bf4 Nc4 14. b3 $14) 12. Be3 (12. Bh4 {allows Black to chyange plans.} g5 13. Bg3 e5 14. dxe5 dxe5 $11 {The bishop on g3 is relatively passive.}) 12... d5 13. c5 Nc4 14. Bc1 (14. Bxc4 dxc4 {does not change much concerning the similar position arising after 11.Be3. Here is an example showing that White's gain of time after a later Qd2 is irrelevant.} 15. d5 (15. Qa4 Bd3 16. Rfd1 Qe8 $1 $146) 15... Nb4 16. Qd2 (16. Bd4 Bd3 17. Bxg7 Kxg7 $11) 16... g5 {White has gained a tempo, but his queen is not optimally placed on d2, failing to question Black's central stability. Besides, Black's kingside expansion is useful, since the bishop got the g6-square for emergency cases.} 17. Bd4 f6 $1 {Continuing to consolidate the dark squares and avoiding the bishops' exchange.} 18. Be3 {The pawn on d5 was hanging.} Bd3 19. Nd4 Qd7 20. Ne6 Rfc8 21. Rfe1 Nxd5 22. Nxd5 Qxe6 23. Nb4 Qd7 24. Rac1 Rd8 25. Red1 Qb5 26. b3 f5 $15 {½-½ Faibisovich,V-Bagirov,V URS-ch Semifinal 1970}) 14... Be4 $5 {One of the possible reactions.} ({White's main idea is to meet} 14... b6 {with} 15. b3 bxc5 16. bxc4 cxd4 17. Nxd5 e6 $1 {With his pawn on h6 hanging, Black needs to deviate from the similar line examined after 11.Be3.} (17... d3 18. Bxd3 Bxd3 19. Qxd3 Bxa1 20. Bxh6 $14) 18. Ba3 Re8 19. Nf4 e5 20. Nd5 d3 21. Bxd3 e4 $1 $146 {It appears that in order to retain adequate compensation for the pawn, Black needs to refrain from the exchange, since the white bishop will be exposed.} (21... Bxd3 22. Qxd3 e4 23. Qe3 exf3 24. Qxf3 $14 {as played in a series of games.}) 22. Be2 (22. Bc2 exf3 23. Bxf5 fxg2 24. Kxg2 gxf5 $13) (22. Bxe4 Bxe4 23. Rc1 Qa5 24. Bd6 Re6 25. Bf4 Qxa2 $11) 22... exf3 23. Bxf3 Rc8 {[%cal Gd8a5]} 24. Qd2 Nd4 $44 {Now is a moment when the light-squared bishop causes White some worries.}) 15. Bxc4 (15. Ne1 Bf5 16. g4 {The only way of avoiding a move repetition.} Bc8 17. Nc2 b6 18. b3 N4a5 19. cxb6 axb6 20. Be3 Nb7 {[%cal Gb7d6] followed by ...Nd6.}) (15. Nxe4 dxe4 16. Ne1 (16. Nh2 Qd5 17. Qa4 b5 18. Qxb5 N4a5 19. Rd1 Rfb8 20. Qa4 Rb4 $132) 16... Qd5 {may lead to fascinating tactical play, based on the fact that with his knight on e1, White's development is suffering..} 17. Qa4 b5 $1 18. Qxb5 Nxb2 $3 (18... N4a5 19. Nc2 $16) 19. Bxb2 (19. Qxb2 Nxd4 $19 20. Bd1 Nf3+) 19... Rab8 20. Bc4 $1 {WHite is not without resources, either.} Qd7 21. Qa4 (21. Bxf7+ Rxf7 22. Qe2 Qd5 $15) 21... Rxb2 22. Bb5 Qxd4 23. Bxc6 Qxa4 24. Bxa4 Rb4 25. Bc6 Bxa1 26. Nc2 Bc3 27. Nxb4 Bxb4 $15) 15... Bxf3 16. Qxf3 dxc4 $11 {Black is well developed and ready to fight against White's centre.} 17. d5 (17. Rd1 Nxd4 18. Qxb7 {0-1 Bykovskiy,O (2349)-Bogdanovich,S (2593) UKR-ch sf Omelnyk 2017 (2)} Qa5 19. Qxe7 (19. Bxh6 Qxc5 20. Bxg7 Kxg7 21. Qd5 Qxd5 22. Nxd5 e5 23. Ne3 Rfc8 {[%cal Ga8b8]} 24. Rd2 Rc5 25. Rc1 Rac8 $11) 19... Rae8 20. Qh4 g5 21. Qg4 (21. Qg3 Nf5 22. Qg4 Qxc5 $11) 21... Qxc5 22. Be3 $2 Rxe3 23. fxe3 Nc2 $11) 17... Ne5 18. Qg3 Nd3 19. Qh4 Bxc3 20. bxc3 Qxd5 21. Bxh6 Rfe8 (21... Qxc5 22. Bxf8 Rxf8 23. a4 b6 $44 {yields Black a dominating position for the exchange.}) 22. Be3 Rac8 $11 *

