{[%evp 0,45,38,41,57,40,43,43,21,41,75,21,30,29,43,14,20,20,47,24,27,18,26,31,31,24,23,20,8,-20,8,3,8,8,34,-7,-1,28,18,28,26,19,3,2,2,-15,-11,-21]} 1. e4 Nf6 2. e5 Nd5 3. d4 d6 4. Nf3 g6 5. Bc4 {This active move can introduce a few different systems. Some of them are tactically sharp, others are only strategically ambitious.} Nb6 ({The seemingly solid} 5... c6 {, keeping the a2-f7 diagonal defended, is too passive. Black gives up the possibility of attacking the white centre with ...Nc6 and exposes himself to} 6. exd6 Qxd6 (6... exd6 $6 7. O-O Bg7 8. Re1+ {1-0 Bujdak,P (1753)-Buchaillot,L (1808) SC-2014-0-00248 faces Black with early problems.}) 7. O-O Bg7 8. Re1 O-O 9. Bg5 Re8 10. Nbd2 $14 {Black has reached some sort of passive Scandinavian or Caro Kann version.}) 6. Bb3 Bg7 {This is the initial tabyia of this variation. Before moving on, let us observe the position a bit. The bishop on b3 is active, at the cost of consuming two developing tempi. We could say something similar about the black knight on b6, but let us not forget that this is its usual location in most variations! At the same time, if the white bishop does not produce any concrete damage to Black's position, it will most likely be either passive, or exposed to an exchange. White has two main approaches. One of them is fighting for the initiative at an early stage. The alternative is consolidating the pawn on e5, in order to maintain his space advantage.} 7. a4 {Played at this stage, this is likely to induce some differences concerning the main lines below.} ({Consolidating the central pawn with} 7. Bf4 {is not promising. It deviates from the natural course of development and exposes the bishop.} O-O 8. O-O (8. h3 $5) 8... Nc6 (8... Bg4 $5) 9. h3 (9. Qe2 Bg4 $11) (9. Nc3 Bg4 10. Re1 dxe5 $146 11. dxe5 Qxd1 12. Raxd1 e6 13. Rd3 h6 $11 {[%cal Gf8d8]}) 9... a5 {Forcing White to lower the stability of his bishop.} 10. a4 {This is not one of those rare cases White can do without this move. If allowed to push his pawn to a4, Black will have the possibility of developing his rook to a5, increasing the pressure on e5.} (10. a3 a4 11. Ba2 dxe5 12. dxe5 Qxd1 13. Rxd1 Bf5 14. c3 e6 15. Nbd2 Ra5 16. Re1 h6 17. g4 Bd3 18. Kg2 g5 19. Bg3 Rb5 $15) (10. c3 a4 11. Bc2 dxe5 12. dxe5 Qxd1 13. Rxd1 Ra5 14. Re1 Nc4 $15) 10... dxe5 11. dxe5 Qxd1 12. Rxd1 Be6 13. Nc3 (13. Bxe6 fxe6 {forces White to delay his development for one more move.} 14. Bg3 Nc4 15. Nc3 Rad8 $5 $11 {Black does not need to hurry to take on e5, which would also lead to equality, of course.}) 13... Bxb3 14. cxb3 e6 15. Ne4 Nd5 16. Bg3 h6 17. Rac1 Nce7 (17... Rfd8) 18. Bh2 (18. Nf6+ Nxf6 19. exf6 Bxf6 20. Rxc7 Nd5 21. Rxb7 Bxb2 $11) 18... Rfd8 19. g4 Nc6 20. Nc5 Rab8 21. Bg3 Bf8 22. Ne4 Be7 $11 {0-1 Orlov,A (2365)-Solozhenkin,E (2565) RUS-Cup01 Chigorin Memorial 1996 (2) Black is well regrouped and solid, having nothing to fear.}) (7. Nbd2 O-O 8. h3 {is another way of maintaining the centre intact, played in a famous game. By developing his knight on d2, White obviously intended to avoid the queen exchange, but this plan has a hidden drawback.} a5 {A familiar plan.} 9. a4 (9. a3 a4 10. Ba2 Nc6 11. Qe2 Ra5 $15) (9. c3 a4 10. Bc2 Nc6 11. Qe2 dxe5 12. Nxe5 a3 13. b3 (13. Nxc6 axb2 14. Bxb2 bxc6 15. O-O Ba6 16. Bd3 Bxd3 17. Qxd3 c5 $15) 13... Nxd4 $1 $17) 9... dxe5 10. dxe5 Na6 $5 {With the knight on d2, the a4-pawn is a comfortable target now.} (10... Nc6 $5 11. Qe2 Bf5 12. e6 (12. O-O Qc8 {[%cal Gf5e6] followed by ...Be6.}) 12... Bxe6 13. Bxe6 fxe6 14. Qxe6+ Kh8 15. O-O Qd5 $11 {Black's activity compensates for the minor structural defect.}) 11. O-O Nc5 12. Qe2 (12. c3 Nxb3 13. Qxb3 Be6 $11) (12. Re1 Nxb3 13. Nxb3 Qxd1 14. Rxd1 Bd7 15. Nc5 Bc6 $11) 12... Qe8 13. Ne4 Nbxa4 14. Bxa4 Nxa4 15. Re1 Nb6 16. Bd2 a4 {0-1 Spassky,B (2660)-Fischer,R (2785) World-ch27 Fischer-Spassky +7-3=11 1972 (13) White has just some compensation for the pawn, due to his space advantage, but Black cannot complain about the outcome of the opening. The game eventually turned out to be one of the most complicated and fascinating in history.}) (7. Qe2 O-O 8. h3 Nc6 9. O-O {transposes to Lines 25 to 27.}) (7. Ng5 {is examined in Lines 14 to 22.}) (7. O-O {is the subject of Lines 23 to 27.}) 7... dxe5 {This is the approved variation. Black uses the fact that White has spent a tempo on a pawn move in order to start active play in the centre. This continuation tends to lead to forced play with drawish tendencies.} ({Those preferring a positional fight may be glad to find out that} 7... a5 {is playable, too. True, this implies changing the plans against a few main setups, usually carried out without inserting the pawn moves.}) 8. a5 {Having said "A"...} (8. dxe5 Qxd1+ 9. Kxd1 Bg4 $11) (8. Nxe5 Bxe5 9. dxe5 Qxd1+ 10. Kxd1 Be6 $1 $146 11. Bxe6 fxe6 12. a5 Nd5 13. Bh6 Nc6 14. Re1 O-O-O 15. Kc1 g5 $5 $11 {Planing ...Rdg8.} 16. Bxg5 Rdg8 17. Bh4 Rxg2 {White cannot trap the daring rook.} 18. Bg3 Nd4 19. Ra4 Ne2+ 20. Rxe2 Rg1+ 21. Kd2 Rxb1 22. b3 Rd8 $15) 8... N6d7 9. dxe5 (9. Bxf7+ {is examined in Line 11.}) 9... Nxe5 10. Qxd8+ Kxd8 11. Nxe5 Bxe5 12. Bxf7 {The simplifying phase has led to an ending where White has a more compact structure and some problems in completing his queenside development. Besides, his bishop may face some dangers.} Bf5 {This is my favourite continuation. Black develops and maintains the threat of isolating the bishop with ...e7-e6 in reserve.} (12... e6 {, with the obvious intention of trapping the bishop, is also playable, but I feel that Black is a bit on the edge on his way to equality.} 13. Bg5+ Kd7 14. Ra3 Nc6 15. f4 Bxb2 16. Rd3+ Bd4 17. Nd2 (17. c3 Rf8 18. Bxg6 hxg6 19. cxd4 Nxa5 20. d5 b6 $13) 17... Rf8 18. Bxg6 hxg6 19. Nf3 Rf5 20. Nxd4 Nxd4 21. Rxd4+ Kc6 {Black is better on the queenside, but vulnerable on the other wing. Besides, his king is exposed a bit. Objectively, the position is equal and a correspondence game should end in a draw, but the situation may be a bit uncomfortable for over-the-board players.} 22. Rc4+ (22. Rd8 Rxa5 23. O-O Rc5 24. Rg8 b5 25. Rxg6 Kb7 26. Rg7 Rxc2 {A thrilling pawn race starts now.} 27. h4 b4 28. h5 a5 29. Bf6 e5 30. Bxe5 Bf5 31. Rg5 Bh7 32. f5 b3 33. f6 Rc5 34. f7 b2 {½-½ Reis,C (2399)-Dos Santos,M (2403) BRA-ch23 final email 2012} 35. h6 a4 36. Bxb2 Rxg5 37. f8=Q Rxf8 38. Rxf8 Rg6 39. Bc1 a3 $11) 22... Kd6 23. h4 Rxa5 24. Bf6 c5 25. Kd2 {1-0 Cardoso Garcia,S (2192)-Rain,R (2238) BRA-ESP email 2013 [16]} b5 {As an over-the-board player, this is my first candidate.} 26. Rc3 Bb7 27. Re1 (27. Rg3 Be4 $17) 27... Bxg2 28. Rg3 Bd5 29. Rxg6 b4 30. h5 (30. f5 Ra2 31. fxe6 Bxe6 32. Be7+ Kxe7 33. Rexe6+ $11) 30... Ra2 31. h6 b3 32. h7 (32. Rc1 Be4) 32... Rxc2+ 33. Ke3 b2 34. Rb1 Rh2 35. Be5+ (35. h8=Q Raxh8 36. Bxh8 Rxh8 37. Rxb2 Rh3+ 38. Kd2 c4 $15) 35... Kc6 36. Rg8 Rh3+ 37. Kd2 Rh2+ 38. Kc3 Rh3+ 39. Kxb2 Rh2+ {Even after eliminating the pawn on b2, the white king cannot avoid the perpetual check, since going to a1 or a3 would run into ...Ra2 mate!!}) 13. Bb3 {White evacuates the bishop, while also defending c2. The threat of ...e7-e6 was more realistic after the bishop's development.} (13. Na3 e6 14. Bg5+ Kd7 15. O-O-O+ Bd6 {White needs to hurry to create counterplay before the bishop gets trapped.} 16. Nc4 Nc6 17. Bf4 Ke7 18. Bxd6+ cxd6 19. Nxd6 h5 $1 {Preventing a later Bh5.} (19... Rhd8 20. Nxf5+ gxf5 21. Bh5 Nxa5 $11) 20. Nxf5+ gxf5 21. Bxe6 Kxe6 22. Rhe1+ Kf6 $15 {White has certain compensation for the knight, but Black is no worse.}) 13... Na6 14. Na3 Nc5 15. Ba2 Bf6 {A typical situation, not only for the Alekhine defence, but also for the Pirc and Modern. Black's activity compensates for the minor structural defect.} 16. O-O Kc8 (16... c6 17. Be3 Na4 18. Nc4 Bxc2 19. Rac1 Bf5 20. a6 b6 21. Rfd1+ Ke8 22. Bb3 b5 $13 {½-½ Khan,V (2164)-Ilyin,I (1762) BI-2012-F-00012 2013}) 17. Bd5 (17. Rb1 Rd8 18. Be3 Na4 $132) 17... Rd8 18. Bf3 Be4 19. Bxe4 Nxe4 20. Re1 Rd4 21. c3 Ra4 22. Bf4 Nd6 23. Bxd6 {½-½ Mourato,M (2329)-Grego,L (2316) POR Cup18 email 2012} *

