1. e4 Nf6 2. e5 Nd5 3. d4 d6 4. Nf3 g6 5. Bc4 Nb6 6. Bb3 Bg7 7. a4 dxe5 8. a5 N6d7 9. Bxf7+ $5 {A sound sacrifice, leading to approximate equality, though.} Kxf7 10. Ng5+ Kg8 11. Ne6 {The best continuation of the attack.} (11. Qf3 Nf6 12. dxe5 Bg4 13. Qb3+ (13. exf6 Bxf3 14. f7+ Kf8 15. Ne6+ Kxf7 16. Nxd8+ Rxd8 17. gxf3 Nc6 $17 {0-1 Sakelsek,T (2202)-Santo Roman,M (2426) Mitropa Cup Saint Vincent 2001 (7)}) 13... Qd5 14. exf6 Qxb3 15. cxb3 exf6 16. Ne4 Nc6 $15 {1-0 Dudek,R (2330)-Rudolph,J (2260) Verbandsliga Nord Baden 1997 (2.1)}) 11... Qe8 12. Nxc7 Qd8 $1 {The queen is best placed on this square, since it controls the knight's escape square on c7 and can attack it along the eighth rank after developing the queenside.} (12... Qf7 13. d5 Na6 14. Nxa8 Nf6 15. Nc3 Bf5 16. O-O Qe8 17. d6 $16) 13. Nxa8 ({White can force a draw by repetition with} 13. Ne6 $11 {, of course.}) 13... exd4 {There is a good chance that the knight will perish, leaving Black with two minor pieces for a rook. Due to Black's imperfect coordination, with his king on g8 immobilizing the rook, White can generate enough compensation, though.} 14. c3 (14. O-O Nc6 15. c3 Nc5 16. b4 dxc3 17. Qxd8+ Nxd8 18. bxc5 c2 19. Nc3 Bxc3 20. Ra2 Bf5 21. Nc7 Be5 22. g4 Bxg4 23. Nb5 Nc6 24. Rxc2 Bf5 25. Rd2 a6 26. Na3 Bc3 27. Ra2 Nxa5 $11 {½-½ Cleto,F (2545)-Rain,R (2477) BRA jub35-A email 2004}) (14. Qd3 Ne5 (14... h6 $5 $146 {Preparing ...Kh7 and aiming at distracting the queen.} 15. Qxg6 Ne5 16. Qe4 Be6 17. Ra3 Bd5 18. Qf5 e6 19. Qh5 Nbc6 20. Rg3 Qxa8 21. Bxh6 Qf8 $13 {The pin along the h-file keeps Black's position together.}) 15. Qb3+ Kf8 16. Nd2 d3 17. c3 Bh6 18. O-O Kg7 19. Re1 Nbc6 20. Qb5 Qd6 21. Ne4 Qb8 22. Bxh6+ Kxh6 23. f4 Nf7 24. Qxd3 Qxa8 25. b4 a6 $11 {1-0 Ahrens,G (2210)-Mangold,W (2265) Remote Superturnier 17 email 2012}) (14. Qe2 Ne5 15. O-O Nbc6 16. f4 Nf7 17. Qb5 Nd6 18. Qb3+ Kf8 19. f5 gxf5 20. Bf4 e5 $17 {1-0 Krogh,C (2280)-Oliwa,M (2235) DEN-ch int U18 1992 (5)}) 14... h6 {I find this move the safest. Black prepares to restore his coordination with ...Kh7.} (14... Nc5 15. cxd4 Bxd4 16. O-O Nc6 17. Be3 e5 18. Na3 Kg7 19. Nb5 {has been played in a few correspondence games, with variable results.}) 15. cxd4 Nf6 16. Nc3 Kh7 17. O-O Bf5 18. Bf4 Na6 19. Re1 Qd7 (19... g5 {is also possible, but I believe Black should not hurry to drive the bishop onto a better square at this height.} 20. Be5 Qd7 21. Ra3 Rxa8 (21... g4 22. Rb3 Rxa8 23. Rb5 Rf8 {½-½ Roeckendorf,P (2139)-Warzecha,H (2009) GER-ch 2014-D-V7 serv}) 22. Rb3 Nb8 $6 {Black starts to play passively.} (22... g4) (22... Be6 23. d5 Bf7) 23. d5 $1 {Preventing ...Nc6.} Na6 24. Qd4 Qc8 $6 (24... g4 25. Ne2 Rc8 $13 {looks very much playable.}) 25. Ne2 Qd7 26. d6 $14 {½-½ Feldblioum,V (1912)-Lagergren,H (1921) W-ch WS/H/599 email 2017}) 20. Qa4 Rxa8 21. Qxd7 Nxd7 22. Rxe7 Nb4 23. Be5 Nxe5 24. dxe5 Rb8 {The endgame is complicated, with approximately equal chances. There were two correspondence games from this position.} 25. Ra4 Nc6 26. Rc7 a6 27. f4 g5 28. g3 Kg6 29. Ne4 gxf4 30. gxf4 Bf8 31. Kf2 Nd8 32. Rc2 (32. Ke3 Ne6 33. Rc1 Be7 34. Rac4 Rd8 35. b3 h5 $11 {½-½ Rimkus,B (2154)-Byrne,M (2276) VW-Cup11 Gr09 email 2018}) 32... Ne6 33. Ke3 Bc5+ 34. Kf3 (34. Rxc5 Bxe4 35. Rc1 Bc6 $15 {[%cal Gg6f5]}) (34. Nxc5 Bxc2) 34... Be7 35. Rg2+ Kf7 36. Rd2 b5 37. Ra2 Bxe4+ $5 38. Kxe4 Rc8 39. b3 Nc5+ 40. Kf5 Nxb3 41. Rd7 Rc6 42. Rb2 Nc5 43. Rc2 b4 44. e6+ Kf8 45. Rb7 b3 {½-½ Schueppel,R (2446)-Bonfissuto,G (2293) W-Cup18 sf02 email 2013} 46. Rb8+ Kg7 47. Rg2+ Kh7 48. Re2 $13 *

