{[%evp 0,36,23,17,61,61,61,61,61,61,78,30,30,30,30,36,41,41,40,-19,21,17,13,18,18,22,22,-6,-9,-2,26,31,33,43,37,37,41,17,55]} 1. e4 Nf6 2. e5 Nd5 3. d4 d6 4. Nf3 g6 5. Bc4 Nb6 6. Bb3 Bg7 7. a4 a5 {In principle, this is the move White intends to induce with 7.a4, hoping that it would restrict Black's possibilities in certain lines. In fact, all Black has to do in the critical positions of the lines below is... to change plans concerning the systems without a2-a4 and ...a7-a5. This is useful information for those wishing to keep the game positional and avoid the forced lines examined above, including a forced draw in the opening.} 8. Ng5 {As we will find out later, one of the main moves without inserting the pawn moves.} (8. O-O O-O {is likely to transpose to Lines 23 to 27, for instance} 9. h3 Nc6 10. Qe2 {transposing.}) (8. exd6 {is examined in Line 13.}) 8... e6 9. Qf3 (9. f4 {is the main alternative.} dxe5 10. fxe5 O-O 11. O-O c5 12. c3 cxd4 13. cxd4 Nc6 14. Nf3 {Without the rook pawn moves, this is an important tabyia, examined in Line 22. With the actual queenside structure, switching to static play makes sense.} Nd5 (14... f6 {The same plan as in the usual lines.} 15. Nc3 {With the actual queenside structure, this is the critical continuation. The point is that the knight on b6 may be hanging if the centre opens.} (15. exf6 Qxf6 {does not make much of a difference concerning Line 22, to which I kindly invite you to refer. Here is just one of the rare examples.} 16. Bg5 Qf5 17. Be3 Nd5 18. Bf2 Nf4 19. Nc3 Nh3+ 20. gxh3 Qxf3 21. d5 Qxd1 22. Raxd1 exd5 23. Bxd5+ Kh8 24. Kg2 Bf5 $11 {½-½ Simmelink,J-Weyerstrass,R NED-ch27 corr9698 1996}) 15... fxe5 16. Bg5 Qd7 17. dxe5 Nxe5 18. Nxe5 Qxd1 (18... Rxf1+ $2 {is fine with the pawns on a2 and a7, but here it more or less loses.} 19. Qxf1 Qd4+ 20. Kh1 Qxe5 21. Bd8 $1 {This is the difference.} Qc5 22. Ne4 Qb4 $6 23. Ng5 $18 {1-0 Grischuk,A (2606)-Ponomariov,R (2630) Torshavn op 3rd 2000 (5)}) 19. Raxd1 Rxf1+ 20. Kxf1 Bxe5 21. Be3 (21. Bd8 Bxc3 22. bxc3 Nd5 $11) (21. Rd8+ Kf7 22. Be3 Nd7 23. Ne4 b6 $11) 21... Nd5 $1 $146 (21... Bxc3 22. Rd8+ Kf7 23. bxc3 Nd5 24. Bd4 Ke7 25. Rh8 $14 {1-0 Sonnet,J (2243)-Krzyzanowski,A (2352) EU-ch M/009 email 2003}) 22. Nxd5 exd5 23. Rxd5 Be6 $1 24. Rb5 (24. Rxe5 Bxb3 25. Re7 Rf8+ 26. Ke2 Rf7 $11) 24... Bxb3 25. Rxb3 {If allowed to play h2-h3, White would retain long-term queenside pressure, precisely because of the insertion of the rook pawn moves. But Black can exchange one pawn with} Bxh2 26. Rxb7 Be5 $11 {, when White's advantage is rather symbolic.}) 15. Nc3 h6 16. Ne4 (16. Qd3 Ncb4 17. Qe2 b6 18. Bc4 Ba6 {Clearly a consequence of the rook pawn moves.} 19. Bxa6 Rxa6 20. Bd2 Ra8 $11 {1-0 MacKintosh,I (2240)-Krecak,Z (2394) EU-ch65 sf11 email 2003}) 16... Nce7 17. Qe2 Bd7 18. Bxd5 Nxd5 19. b3 Bc6 20. Ba3 Nb4 {Once again, the moves a2-a4 and ...a7-a5 help Black.} 21. Rac1 Qd5 22. Ned2 g5 23. Rc5 Qd8 24. Bxb4 axb4 25. Ne4 Rc8 26. Nd6 Rc7 27. Rfc1 Rd7 28. Kh1 g4 (28... Rxd6 $5 29. exd6 Qxd6 $44) 29. Nd2 f5 30. a5 Qh4 31. Qe1 Qg5 32. a6 h5 $13 {½-½ Wiesinger,J (2072)-Salati,P (2265) VW-Cup11 Gr42 email 2018}) 9... Qe7 ({Under the given circumstances,} 9... O-O $6 {is less good than in the similar Lines 17 to 19.} 10. Qh3 h6 11. Nf3 dxe5 12. dxe5 Nc6 13. Bxh6 Nxe5 14. Nxe5 Bxe5 15. Bxf8 {The capture on b2 loses, since the rook has the square on a2 available.} Qxf8 $14) 10. Ne4 dxe5 {This is possible only in the actual configuration.} ({It is worth mentioning that} 10... h6 {, which is the main continuation without the pawn moves, runs into} 11. exd6 cxd6 12. Bf4 d5 13. Nd6+ Kf8 14. Nb5 $14 {This is the difference! The errant knight does not need to exchange the passive bishop on c8, but can use this weak square.}) ({Curiously,} 10... d5 {is also good.} 11. Nf6+ (11. Bg5 $2 dxe4 $19) (11. Nc5 Nc6 12. Qe3 f6 $15 13. f4 fxe5 14. fxe5 Qh4+ 15. g3 Qxd4 $17) 11... Bxf6 12. exf6 (12. Qxf6 Qxf6 13. exf6 Nc6 14. c3 e5 15. O-O Be6 16. dxe5 Nxe5 17. Bf4 Nbd7 $11 18. Re1 $2 Nd3 $19) 12... Qb4+ 13. Qc3 ({The point is that White cannot play} 13. c3 $2 {due to} Qxb3 $19) 13... Nc6 14. Be3 Nd7 15. O-O Qxc3 16. Nxc3 Nxf6 {White should have compensation for the pawn, due to the relative weakness of the dark squares, but Black is not worse for sure.}) 11. Bg5 (11. dxe5 Nc6 12. Bg5 Nxe5 13. Qf4 Qb4+ {Once again, c2-c3 is not available.} 14. Nbc3 Nbd7 $13) 11... Qb4+ {Same issue.} 12. Nbd2 (12. c3 $2 Qxb3 13. Nf6+ Kf8 $19) 12... N8d7 {Play remains complicated.} 13. c3 (13. Nf6+ Nxf6 14. Bxf6 Bxf6 15. Qxf6 O-O 16. c3 Nd7 17. Qxe6 fxe6 18. Bxe6+ Kg7 19. cxb4 exd4 20. O-O axb4 21. Rfc1 c6 $11 {½-½ Root,D (2460)-Beelby,M (2260) American op Los Angeles 1989 (5)}) 13... Qf8 14. dxe5 h6 15. Nf6+ Nxf6 16. Bxf6 Bxf6 17. exf6 (17. Qxf6 Bd7 18. O-O Bc6 $11 {followed by ...Nd7.}) 17... Qd6 18. O-O-O Bd7 $11 *

