{[%evp 0,68,37,27,59,51,46,39,39,32,78,47,47,45,40,34,34,53,42,32,40,0,27,23,50,58,45,45,43,-15,-15,-15,-34,-16,-11,-4,26,3,-1,-1,10,35,82,82,58,61,61,61,73,62,62,49,49,66,70,64,65,55,59,57,43,43,52,45,42,59,66,41,39,30,47]} 1. e4 Nf6 2. e5 Nd5 3. d4 d6 4. Nf3 g6 5. Bc4 Nb6 6. Bb3 Bg7 7. a4 a5 8. exd6 {This exchange also induces differences concerning Line 16.} exd6 $1 {The correct reaction.} ({The usual} 8... cxd6 {is less adequate now, since the square on b5 remains weak.} 9. O-O O-O 10. h3 (10. Na3 Bg4 11. c3 Na6 12. Re1 $14 {½-½ Brent,M-Noseda,J USA-BEL corr 1990}) 10... Nc6 11. Re1 Bf5 12. Na3 $14) 9. Bg5 {The most direct try of using the changed circumstances.} (9. Qe2+ Qe7 10. Qxe7+ {½-½ Illescas Cordoba,M (2620)-Granda Zuniga,J (2605) Pamplona 9596 6th 1995} Kxe7 11. Bg5+ Ke8 12. O-O Be6 13. Re1 Kd7 14. Nc3 h6 15. Bxe6+ fxe6 16. Be3 Nc4 $11) (9. O-O O-O {leads to static play.} 10. Re1 (10. Bg5 {is best met with} Bf6 11. Qd2 Nc6 (11... Bg4 12. Qf4 $14 {½-½ Oratovsky,M (2411)-Polaczek,R (2363) POR-chT Penafiel 2020 (7.5)}) (11... Bxg5 12. Nxg5 Nc6 $11 {transposes to the main line.}) 12. c3 (12. Bh6 Bg4 $5 13. Bxf8 Bxf3 14. c3 Kxf8 15. gxf3 Bg5 16. f4 Bh6 17. Qe3 Qf6 $44) 12... Bxg5 13. Nxg5 Bf5 14. Na3 d5 15. Rfe1 Qd7 $11 {Black \is well developed and has little to fear. For instance:} 16. Nb5 Nd8 17. Re2 c6 18. Na3 f6 19. Nf3 Bg4 $11) 10... d5 (10... h6 $5 $146 {Black does not need to weaken the square on e5 so soon. Instead, he can prevent Bg5 and then keep developing.} 11. Nc3 Nc6 12. h3 Bf5 $11) 11. Bf4 Be6 12. Be5 Bh6 $5 13. Nc3 Re8 14. h3 f6 (14... Nc6 15. Bh2 Nb4 16. Ne2 Nc4 $11) 15. Bh2 Qd7 16. Qd3 c6 17. Re2 Na6 18. Rae1 Nb4 19. Qd1 Bf7 $11 {1-0 Ivanov,A (2470)-Alburt,L (2520) New York exh 1989 (2) This is one of the situations when the insertion of the rook pawn moves yield Black certain queenside stability.}) 9... f6 {With the king on e8 still, this is legal and best!} (9... Bf6 {is less indicated here, due to} 10. Qe2+ $1 Kf8 11. Bh6+ Bg7 12. Qe3 $14) 10. Bf4 g5 $1 $146 {Now is a good moment for forcing White to make up his mind with respect to the bishop.} ({But} 10... d5 {is not wrong, either.} 11. O-O O-O 12. Na3 g5 {Better late than never.} (12... c6 {offers White certain initiative.} 13. c4 Re8 (13... g5 14. Bd2 $5 $14) (13... Na6 $5) 14. c5 N6d7 15. Nb5 $1 Na6 (15... cxb5 16. Bxd5+ Kh8 17. axb5 $14 {with a crushing space advantage, overcompensating the sacrificed knight.}) 16. Nd6 Re6 17. Bg3 $14 {1-0 Brzezinski,B (2163)-Shishkov,V (2077) W-Cup21 WS09 email 2015}) 13. Bg3 (13. Bd2 Nc6 {inhibits c3-c4 in view of the potential threat ...g5-g4.} 14. c3 Bf5 $11) 13... c6 (13... f5 {is interesting, but maybe not entirely sound.} 14. Be5 Nc6 15. Bxg7 Kxg7 16. Re1 (16. c4 dxc4 17. Nxc4 g4 18. Nxb6 cxb6 19. d5 gxf3 20. dxc6 fxg2 $11) 16... f4 17. c4 (17. Ne5 Bf5 $11) 17... g4 (17... dxc4 18. Nxc4 g4 19. Nxb6 cxb6 20. d5 gxf3 21. dxc6 $14 {The difference with respect to the similar line above is made by the rook's presence on e1. Black has certain problems in view of the potential threat Re7+.}) 18. Ne5 Qh4 {with chances for counterplay based on ...g4-g3.}) 14. c4 Na6 $11 {/ is the most solid option, now that the bishop is far from d2.}) 11. Bg3 (11. Nxg5 {is interesting but not especially threatening.} fxg5 12. Qh5+ Kd7 13. O-O (13. Qh3+ Ke8 14. Qh5+ Kd7 {is only a move repetition.}) 13... d5 14. Bxg5 (14. Qh3+ Kc6 15. Qc3+ Kd7 $11) 14... Qe8 15. Qh3+ Qe6 16. Qg3 Bf6 17. f4 (17. Bf4 Rg8 18. Qd3 Nc6 19. c3 h5 20. Qh7+ Ne7 21. Qxh5 Qf5 $15) 17... h6 18. Bxf6 Qxf6 19. Nc3 c6 $13) 11... Qe7+ $1 {This leads to unusual play, with both kings in the centre.} 12. Kd2 {The most challenging move, threatening Re1.} (12. Kf1 Be6 (12... h5 13. h4 g4 14. Ne1 Be6 $11) 13. d5 (13. Bxe6 Qxe6 14. Na3 O-O $11) 13... Bd7 $11) 12... Kd8 $1 13. Re1 Qf8 {Black's structure is very compact.} 14. Na3 {White should hurry to develop and this is the most flexible way of doing it.} (14. Nc3 Bd7 15. Kc1 Kc8 16. Kb1 h6 $13 {[%cal Gf6f5] followed by ...f6-f5.}) (14. c3 h5 15. h3 Bh6 16. Ke2 g4 $132 17. Ne5 $2 fxe5 18. Bh4+ Ke8 19. dxe5 d5 $17) 14... h5 (14... Bd7 $5) 15. h3 (15. h4 g4 16. Ng1 Bh6+ 17. Ke2 f5 18. f4 N8d7 19. Kf1 Nf6 $11) 15... h4 (15... Bh6 {works less well with Na3 instead of the neutral c2-c3.} 16. Ke2 g4 17. Ne5 $1 fxe5 18. Bh4+ Ke8 19. dxe5 d5 20. Nb5 {A big difference with respect to the similar line above.} Na6 21. Bxd5 $36) 16. Bh2 g4 17. hxg4 Bh6+ (17... Nc6 $5 18. Kc1 Bxg4 $13) 18. Ke2 Bxg4 19. Kf1 {White has regrouped properly, but Black can keep play dynamic.} h3 $1 20. Ng5 $1 hxg2+ 21. Kxg2 Bxd1 22. Ne6+ Kc8 23. Nxf8 Bh5 24. Ne6 Na6 25. Rh1 Kd7 {The structure remains symmetrical and Black has normal development. White can still try:} 26. Bxd6 Bf7 27. Bf4 Bxe6 28. Bxe6+ Kxe6 29. Rxh6 Rxh6 30. Bxh6 Nxa4 31. b3 Nb6 32. Bd2 Rd8 33. Re1+ Kf5 34. c3 c5 $11 *

