{[%evp 0,40,37,27,59,39,39,48,48,48,78,43,43,32,47,22,39,-23,41,38,80,-13,-11,-35,-18,3,-15,-15,19,-2,-2,-32,-9,-8,-8,-32,-21,-24,-24,-18,-29,-29,0]} 1. e4 Nf6 2. e5 Nd5 3. d4 d6 4. Nf3 g6 5. Bc4 Nb6 6. Bb3 Bg7 7. Ng5 {A very direct attempt at grabbing the initiative.} e6 $1 {The best answer.} (7... O-O {allows} 8. e6 (8. h4 {is also interesting, for instance} h6 9. h5 hxg5 10. hxg6 d5 11. gxf7+ Rxf7 12. Bxg5 {with huge compensation for the piece.}) 8... f6 9. Nf7 Qe8 10. Nh6+ Kh8 11. d5 $14) (7... d5 {is the kind of move Black should play only after White has made some important commitments (like in Line 17 for instance). Otherwise, he will be left with a passive bishop on g7.}) 8. Qf3 {Trying to maintain the rhythm of the attack.} (8. f4 {is examined in Lines 20 to 22.}) 8... Qe7 {The approved continuation.} (8... O-O {is better than its reputation and will be examined in Lines 17 to 19.}) 9. Ne4 {Threatening Bg5.} (9. exd6 {is premature.} cxd6 10. c3 O-O 11. O-O h6 12. Nh3 e5 13. dxe5 dxe5 14. Re1 Nc6 $17 15. Nf4 {1-0 Nepomniachtchi,I (2492)-Polaczek,R (2426) Champions Challenge 97th blitz 2005 (1.3)} Qf6 16. Nd5 Qxf3 17. gxf3 Nxd5 18. Bxd5 Ne7 $17) 9... h6 (9... dxe5 {is also frequently played, but I believe that it helps White in view of} 10. dxe5 h6 11. Nf6+ Kf8 12. Qc3 {Without the exchange on e5, White would not have this resource. In order to dislocate the knight on f6, Black will need to sacrifice a pawn. There are several ways of doing it, but I feel that his compensation is on edgeusually on the edge. Here is a variation enjoying some correspondence games practice.} Nd5 13. Bxd5 exd5 14. Be3 Na6 15. O-O c5 16. Nxd5 Qxe5 17. Bxc5+ Nxc5 18. Qxc5+ Kg8 19. Nbc3 Kh7 20. Rfe1 Qf5 {Engines claim equality and several correspondence games ended in draws. I would not feel comfortable with black in an over-the-board game, though.}) 10. Nf6+ (10. Bf4 {is the subject of Line 15.}) (10. exd6 cxd6 11. Bf4 {is examined in Line 16.}) 10... Kf8 {White seems to be active, but due to his incomplete development, he lacks stability. The queen is tied up to the knight's defense, the centre is a bit vulnerable and the bishop on b3 is passive and unable to create tactical threats.} 11. Bf4 {Consolidating e5.} (11. c3 dxe5 12. dxe5 N8d7 13. Nxd7+ Nxd7 $15) (11. Be3 Nc6 12. Ne4 dxe5 13. dxe5 (13. d5 Nd4 14. Bxd4 exd4 15. dxe6 Bxe6 $17 {0-1 Uehara,S (1987)-Janev,E (2497) Cappelle op 27th 2011 (3)}) 13... Nxe5 14. Qg3 {1-0 Baselmans,L (2233)-Jansen,B (2174) Eindhoven WLC op 12th 2022 (6)} Ned7 $17 {[%cal Gb6d5,Gg7b2]}) 11... Nc6 12. c3 {Defending d4 and freeing the bishop.} dxe5 13. dxe5 Nd5 $1 $146 {Provoking mass simplifications and leading to equality.} (13... Nd7 14. Nxd7+ Bxd7 15. Qe3 $14) 14. Nxd5 (14. Bxd5 Nxe5 15. Bxe5 exd5 16. O-O (16. Qf4 g5) 16... Qxe5 17. Nxd5 Bf5 $15 18. Ne3 (18. Na3 Be4 $19) (18. Nd2 $2 Rd8 $19) 18... Be4 19. Qe2 Bc6 $5 $15) 14... exd5 15. Qxd5 (15. O-O g5 16. Be3 Be6 $15) 15... Bxe5 16. Bxe5 Nxe5 17. O-O Kg7 18. Na3 (18. Re1 $2 Nf3+ $1 $19) 18... c6 19. Qd4 Rd8 20. Qe3 Qf6 $11 {The position is symmetrical and Black does not have problems.} *

