1. e4 Nf6 2. e5 Nd5 3. d4 d6 4. Nf3 g6 5. Bc4 Nb6 6. Bb3 Bg7 7. Ng5 e6 8. Qf3 Qe7 9. Ne4 h6 10. exd6 cxd6 11. Bf4 {This is White's main hope for an advantage in this system. Black will soon lose the right to castle.} d5 12. Nd6+ Kf8 {Of course, Black is in no immediate danger, but he will need some effrot to get coordinated. On the other hand, the knight on d6 is hanging a bit and in most cases it has to take on c8, thus helping Black to develop his queenside. White's main hopes are connected with the structure, which resembles the Fischer setup in the Caro Kann (3.exd5 cxd5 4.Bd3). If Black does not free himself quickly, White may have chances to start a slow but consistent kingside attack, using the e-file and the e5-square.} 13. c3 (13. Nxc8 {looks a bit premature.} Nxc8 14. c3 Nc6 15. Nd2 (15. O-O {1-0 Grischuk,A (2759)-Babazada,K (2408) Titled Tuesday intern op 1st Oct blitz 2019 (4)} Qf6 $5 $146 {White cannot get rid of the half pin without exposing his queen.} 16. Nd2 (16. Qe3 N8e7 $11) (16. Qg3 N8e7 17. Nd2 Kg8 $11) 16... g5 17. Bg3 Qxf3 18. Nxf3 Bf6 19. Ne1 Be7 20. Nd3 Nd6 $11 {Whenever a knight reaches d6 in this structure, Black should be happy with his position. True, the white knight is also optimally placed on d3, which maintains the position equal.}) 15... Bf6 {Preparing the king's advance.} (15... Qf6 16. Qe3 N8e7 $11) 16. Bg3 (16. Qe2 Kg7 17. Nf3 Nd6 $11) 16... Kg7 17. O-O b5 18. Qd3 b4 19. Qb5 {½-½ Artamonov,R (2003)-Eigenmann,W (2011) EU-ch SC-OR/375 email 2020} Qe8 $11) 13... Nc6 {before inducing White to take on c8, Black creates the additional possibility of ...Rxc8.} (13... h5 {1-0 Grischuk,A (2777)-Dubov,D (2699) FIDE Steinitz Memorial blitz 2020 (14) is the actual move order in}) 14. O-O {After this natural move, evacuating the king from the centre, Black faces the task of inducing the exchange on c8.} (14. Nxc8 Rxc8 15. O-O Bf6 $11) (14. a4 {is premature with the king in the centre.} e5 (14... Na5 15. Bc2 e5 $11) (14... Bd7 15. O-O e5 16. dxe5 Nxe5 17. Bxe5 Bxe5 18. Nxb7 Kg7 $44) 15. Nxc8 Rxc8 16. dxe5 Nxe5 17. Bxe5 Qxe5+ 18. Kf1 Bf6 (18... Nc4) 19. Na3 Kg7 20. g3 h5 21. h4 Rhe8 $11) 14... h5 $5 {Dubov's idea, carried out in a slightly different move order, as mentioned above. Black threatens with a massive pawn expansion.} (14... Bf6 {runs into} 15. a4 $14 {, questioning Black's queenside stability. The central break is less effective after White's castle.}) (14... g5 {is the main alternative to the main move. Both continuations have equal merits, leading to an approximate equality.} 15. Nxc8 {White finally takes on c8, thus allowing his bishop to retreat to a safe square.} (15. Bg3 h5 {offers Black active counterplay.} 16. Re1 (16. h3 g4 17. hxg4 hxg4 18. Qxg4 f5 19. Qf4 Bf6 20. Re1 Bg5 21. Qf3 Bd7 $15 {with excellent attacking chances.}) (16. h4 gxh4 17. Bf4 e5 18. Nxc8 (18. dxe5 Bg4 19. Qe3 Bxe5 $15) 18... Rxc8 19. Re1 e4 20. Qh3 Re8 21. Nd2 Bh6 $132) 16... h4 17. Nf5 Qd8 18. Bd6+ Kg8 19. Nxg7 Qxd6 20. Ne8 (20. Nh5 f5 $17) 20... Qf4 $11) 15... Nxc8 (15... Rxc8 16. Bd2 f5 {is also interesting, of course.}) 16. Be3 f5 {An ambitious plan. White does not have enough resources to take advantage of the relative weakness on e5. The point is that the light-squared bishop can hardly contribute to that.} (16... Nd6 $11) 17. Nd2 Nd6 18. Rae1 Bf6 19. Qd1 {This position was reached in two correspondence games. Black has a harmonious development and for White it is not easy to prove a constructive plan.} Na5 (19... Kg7 20. Bc2 Qf7 21. Nb3 Nc4 22. Bc1 b6 23. Nd2 Nd6 24. Nf3 Rac8 25. Ne5 Bxe5 26. dxe5 Ne4 27. f3 Nc5 28. b4 Nd7 29. f4 g4 30. Be3 h5 31. Bd3 h4 {½-½ Sorcinelli,A (2290)-Koch,C (2339) SM-2020-0-00429}) (19... f4 $6 {Black should think twice before allowing White to sacrifice.} 20. Bxf4 gxf4 21. Bxd5 Nd8 22. Bxe6 Nxe6 23. d5 Rd8 24. Rxe6 Qf7 25. Qf3 $14) 20. Re2 (20. Bc2 f4 $13 21. Qf3 Qf7 22. g3 fxe3 23. fxe3 Kg7 24. e4 dxe4 25. Nxe4 Nxe4 26. Qxe4 Raf8 27. Rf2 (27. Qxe6 Qxe6 28. Rxe6 Nc4 $15) 27... Nc4 28. Ref1 Nd6 29. Qd3 Qh5 $13) 20... Nxb3 21. Nxb3 b6 22. Rfe1 Qf7 23. f3 Re8 24. Nc1 Kg7 25. Nd3 f4 26. Bc1 Nf5 27. Ne5 Qc7 28. Qd3 (28. Ng4 h5 29. Nxf6 Kxf6 30. Re5 h4 {stabilizing the kingside.} 31. Qe2 Qc6 $11) 28... h5 $11 {½-½ Roesch M,H (2410)-Pavlov,V (2415) RUS-ROW email 2018 [23] The position is rather static and for both players it is far from easy to make progress.}) 15. Nd2 {This yields Black good counterplay.} (15. Na3 {is not more effective, either.} Bh6 16. Nxc8 Rxc8 17. Bg3 h4 $11) (15. h3 {is an open invitation to kingside trouble.} g5 16. Bh2 g4 {Black has certain initiative.} 17. hxg4 $6 hxg4 18. Qxg4 $6 Bd7 $1 $17 {[%cal Ge6e5] Threatening not only ...e6-e5, but also to double rooks along the h-file.} 19. Nxb7 e5 20. Qf3 (20. Qg3 Bf5 21. Nc5 Rd8 $19 {[%cal Gd8d6,Gd6h6]}) 20... Rxh2 21. Kxh2 exd4 $17) (15. h4 {looks like the critical continuation.} e5 $1 {ith the g4-square available to the knight, switching to the Isolani structure is a good idea.} 16. Nxc8 (16. dxe5 Nxe5 17. Bxe5 Bxe5 18. Nxc8 Rxc8 19. g3 g5 $5 $132) 16... Rxc8 17. Re1 (17. dxe5 Nxe5 18. Qh3 Ng4 19. Nd2 Bf6 20. Rae1 Qd8 $11) 17... Re8 18. Bxd5 {The critical continuation.} (18. Bg5 Qd7 19. dxe5 Nxe5 20. Qd1 Kg8 21. Nd2 Kh7 22. Nf3 Nec4 $11) 18... Nxd5 19. Qxd5 Qxh4 20. Bh2 (20. Bxe5 Bxe5 21. dxe5 Qg5 $11 {followed by ...Rxe5.}) 20... Qd8 21. Qc5+ (21. Qxd8 Rxd8 22. dxe5 Rd5 23. f4 g5 24. c4 Ra5 $11) 21... Kg8 22. dxe5 h4 23. Na3 h3 $44 {With obvious compensation for the pawn, partly due to the bishop's unfortunate placement on h2.}) 15... g5 (15... Bh6 16. Bxh6+ Rxh6 17. Nb5 Kg7 $11) 16. Nxc8 Nxc8 (16... Rxc8 17. Be3 f5 18. Rae1 Bf6 19. g3 Re8 $11) 17. Be3 Nd6 18. Rfe1 g4 19. Qe2 {Black has achieved an active regrouping. He lost the thread only a bit later.} Bh6 20. Nf1 Qf6 21. Bc2 Ne7 {Harmonious regrouping} 22. Bd3 Nef5 23. Bxh6+ Rxh6 24. Qd2 Rc8 $5 $146 {Probably the safest plan. Before continuing the kingside plan, Black prepares the king's transfer to b8.} (24... h4 25. Re5 b5 $11) ({The game went} 24... Kg7 {The king is unsafe in this area, but the last move is not a mistake yet.} 25. Re5 Rg8 (25... h4 $1 $11) 26. Rae1 (26. Ng3 $1 Nxg3 27. fxg3 $14) 26... Kh8 (26... h4 $1) 27. a4 Qg7 (27... h4 28. Qf4 Qg5 29. Qxg5 Rxg5 30. Ne3 Kg7 $11) 28. Qf4 h4 (28... Qg5 29. Qxg5 Rxg5 30. Ne3 Kg7 31. g3 $14) 29. Ne3 g3 30. fxg3 hxg3 31. h3 $16 {1-0 Grischuk,A (2777)-Dubov,D (2699) FIDE Steinitz Memorial blitz 2020 (14)}) 25. Re5 Rh8 26. Ng3 Nxg3 27. fxg3 Ke7 $11 {[%cal Ge7d7,Gd7c7,Gc7b8] Followed by ...Kd7-c7-b8.} *

