{[%evp 0,40,25,46,65,53,53,53,28,42,72,23,18,29,29,16,12,5,5,9,-6,-74,24,15,76,0,36,8,7,-4,-16,-22,-23,-8,-11,-9,-15,-19,30,-4,-3,-1,-1]} 1. e4 Nf6 2. e5 Nd5 3. d4 d6 4. Nf3 g6 5. Bc4 Nb6 6. Bb3 Bg7 7. Ng5 e6 8. Qf3 O-O $5 {From an an abstract point of view, this is the most desirable move. However, Black needs to know precisely what he is doing, since his king is exposed to direct threats now.} 9. Qh3 {The obvious continuation of the attack.} (9. Ne4 dxe5 10. dxe5 N8d7 (10... Bxe5 11. Bg5 f6 $17 {0-1 Barzen,P (2321)-Holtel,J (2305) GER-ch Blitz 2020 (9)}) 11. Bg5 Nxe5 12. Qg3 f6 13. Bf4 (13. Qxe5 fxg5 $19 14. Bxe6+ Kh8 $19) 13... Nd5 14. Bxe5 fxe5 15. O-O Qe7 16. Na3 b6 17. Nc4 Bb7 18. Rfe1 Nf4 19. f3 Rad8 $17 {0-1 Anka,E (2355)-Schroll,G (2330) Kecskemet III-A 1991}) 9... h6 10. Ne4 (10. Nf3 {is examined in Lines 18 and 19.}) 10... d5 $1 {Now is one of those moments when Black can and should block the centre. He should not tolerate the knight on the optimal e4-square. White's commitments that justify the last move are the queen's unusual placement and the time wasted by the knight (including the next move). In may of the lines below, the bishop on b3 will be passive with respect to the normal French structures.} (10... Kh7 11. Bg5 $18) (10... dxe5 11. dxe5 Qd4 12. Nf6+ Bxf6 13. exf6 h5 14. O-O Qxf6 15. Nc3 $36 {1-0 Greig,S (2223)-Stock,G (2120) NAPZ/WS/M/20 email 2015}) 11. Nc5 {The most active knight jump.} (11. Nf6+ $146 {leads to a pawn exchange, yielding Black a space advantage in the centre, fully compensating for the absence of the g7-bishop.} Bxf6 12. exf6 Qxf6 13. Bxh6 Re8 14. c3 e5 15. Qe3 Nc6 16. O-O Bf5 $11) (11. Ng3 {places the knight on a relatively passive square.} Kh7 12. Nd2 c5 13. c3 Nc6 14. Nf3 {1-0 Nemeth Junior,H (2045)-Cordeiro,M (2197) Rio Negrinho Froebel op 2021 (6)} (14. Ne2 cxd4 15. cxd4 f6 {The capture on f6 leaves the queen exposed to ...e6-e5.} 16. f4 Nc4 17. O-O {The exchanges on c4 are followed by ...Nxd4.} Nxd2 18. Bxd2 Qb6 19. Bc3 Bd7 $11) 14... cxd4 15. cxd4 f6 16. Bc2 fxe5 17. Nh5 {White has lost ground in the centre, so he needs to start his attack.} Qc7 18. Ng5+ Kg8 19. Bxg6 Nxd4 20. Nh7 e4 21. Nxf8 Qc4 22. Qg4 Nc2+ 23. Kd1 Qd4+ 24. Bd2 Nxa1 $13) 11... Kh7 12. f4 (12. Nd2 N6d7 13. Nxd7 Bxd7 14. O-O c5 15. c3 cxd4 16. cxd4 Bb5 ({In a classical game, a renowned Alekhine Defence expert played a bit too artificially, but not necessarily badly.} 16... Rh8 $5 17. Nf3 Kg8 18. Bd2 Bf8 19. Rfe1 Nc6 20. Qg4 Rc8 21. Rac1 {1-0 Dzindzichashvili,R (2485)-Alburt,L (2515) New York International 1984 (5)} Kg7 22. h4 Be7 $11 {followed by ...Na5.}) 17. Re1 Nc6 18. Nf3 Qb6 19. Be3 Rac8 20. Rac1 Nb4 21. Rc3 a5 22. Rec1 Rc6 $11) (12. Be3 N8d7 13. Nd3 (13. Nxd7 Bxd7 14. Nd2 f5 15. f4 a5 16. c3 Ba4 $11) 13... c5 14. Nxc5 (14. dxc5 Nc4 15. f4 Nxe3 16. Qxe3 f6 17. exf6 Qxf6 18. Nd2 a5 19. a4 b6 20. cxb6 Ba6 21. O-O Qd4 22. Qxd4 Bxd4+ 23. Kh1 Rab8 $44 {with strong queenside pressure, fully compensating for the pawn.}) 14... Nxc5 15. dxc5 Nd7 16. f4 f6 17. exf6 Qxf6 18. Nc3 Qe7 $15 19. Na4 $6 e5 20. f5 Rxf5 21. g4 Rf8 22. Bxd5 Nf6 $19 {0-1 Bueno,T (2095)-Arnold,G (2236) EM/M/A073 corr 1999}) 12... N6d7 $1 $146 13. Nxd7 (13. Nd3 b6 14. O-O c5 {forces White to play resolutely, due to the threat of ...c5-c4.} 15. f5 (15. c4 Nc6 16. dxc5 Nxc5 17. Nxc5 bxc5 18. Be3 d4 19. Bf2 f5 $11) 15... exf5 $1 (15... gxf5 16. Bxd5 exd5 17. Qxf5+ Kh8 18. Qh5 Kh7 19. Rf3 $40) 16. Bxd5 Nxe5 17. Bxa8 f4 18. g4 Bxg4 19. Qg2 Qxd4+ {Black has overwhelming compensation for the rook.} 20. Kh1 (20. Nf2 Be2 21. Re1 f3 22. Qh3 Nbd7 23. Bb7 Rb8 $15) 20... f3 21. Bxf3 Bxf3 22. Rxf3 Nxf3 23. Qxf3 c4 24. Nf4 Re8 25. Ng2 Nd7 $44) 13... Nxd7 14. Be3 c5 15. c3 (15. dxc5 f6 16. exf6 Nxf6 $15) 15... cxd4 16. cxd4 (16. Bxd4 f6 17. exf6 Nxf6 18. Qh4 b6 19. Nd2 (19. O-O Ba6 20. Re1 Ne4 21. Qxd8 Raxd8 $15) 19... Ba6 20. O-O-O Nh5 21. Qxd8 Raxd8 22. Bxg7 (22. g3 Bxd4 23. cxd4 Rc8+ 24. Kb1 Bd3+ 25. Ka1 g5 $15) 22... Kxg7 23. g3 Bd3 $11 {followed by ...Bf5 and ...Nf6.}) 16... Nb6 17. O-O Bd7 18. Nd2 (18. g4 Nc4 $132) 18... f5 {Securing the kingside and freeing Black's hands for his queenside play.} 19. g4 fxg4 20. Qxg4 Rc8 $11 *

