{[%evp 0,11,23,30,55,44,44,44,44,44,73,30,24,32]} 1. e4 Nf6 2. e5 Nd5 3. d4 d6 4. Nf3 g6 5. Bc4 Nb6 6. Bb3 Bg7 7. Ng5 e6 8. Qf3 O-O 9. Qh3 h6 10. Nf3 dxe5 11. dxe5 Nc6 12. Bxh6 Nxe5 13. Nxe5 {The simplest continuation, aiming for rapid development.} Bxe5 14. Nc3 (14. Bxf8 {runs into} Bxb2 {, when White has to work a bit to prove his compensation for the pawn.} 15. Bh6 Bxa1 16. c3 Nd5 17. O-O Qf6 18. Bd2 e5 19. Qd3 Nf4 20. Bxf4 exf4 21. Qc4 c6 22. Nd2 Be6 23. Qb4 Bxc3 24. Qxb7 Re8 25. Ne4 Qe5 26. Nxc3 Qxc3 27. Bxe6 Rxe6 28. Qxa7 Kg7 $5 $11) 14... c5 $1 $146 {Black should not offer his opponent the tempo he needs for continuing his development. The bishop on b3 starts facing problems.} (14... Re8 {is too slow, allowing White to retain some advantage.} 15. Ne4 (15. O-O Qf6 16. Ne4 Qh8 17. c3 Nd5 18. Rae1 Bg7 $11 {½-½ Vicioso Sanchez,M (1958)-Sienkiewicz,W (2205) ESP AEAC XV W/P/22 email 2016}) 15... f5 16. Rd1 (16. f4 Qd4 17. fxe5 Qxe4+ 18. Kf2 Qxe5 19. Rhe1 Qh8 20. Rad1 c5 21. c3 c4 22. Bc2 Bd7 $13) 16... Qe7 17. f4 Bxb2 18. O-O Bg7 (18... fxe4 19. f5 $18) 19. Ng5 c5 20. Bxg7 Qxg7 21. Qd3 Qc7 22. Rf3 c4 23. Qc3 $14) (14... Bg7 15. O-O (15. Rd1 {1-0 Dabetic,R (2325)-Hasecic,S (2335) YUG-ch sf Pula 1988 (4)} Qf6 $11) 15... c5 16. Rad1 Qe7 17. a4 c4 18. Ba2 a5 19. Bxg7 Kxg7 20. Qe3 Ra6 21. Rd4 $14) 15. Bxf8 (15. Rd1 {does not induce positive situation changes.} Bd7 16. Qe3 Qc7 17. Ne4 c4 (17... Bc6 $5 18. Bxf8 Rxf8 19. Nxc5 a5 20. a4 Bxg2 21. Rg1 Nd5 22. Bxd5 Bxd5 $44 {The bishops are very strong and the white king is insecure.}) 18. Qg5 Nd5 19. Bxc4 (19. Bxf8 Kxf8 $19 20. Bxc4 Bf4 21. Qh4 Qxc4 $19) 19... Bxb2 20. Bxd5 (20. Bd3 Bg7 $11) (20. Bxf8 $2 Qxc4 $19) 20... exd5 21. Bxf8 Rxf8 22. Rxd5 Re8 23. f3 Bc6 24. O-O Bxd5 25. Qxd5 Qxc2 $11 26. Qxb7 Rd8 27. h4 Bd4+ 28. Kh2 Qxa2 $11) 15... Qxf8 16. Qe3 (16. a3 c4 17. Ba2 Bd7 18. O-O Bc6 {does not make much of a difference.}) 16... Bg7 {After isolating the bishop from the rest of its army, Black will have excellent compensation for the exchange. His bishop on g7 is a monster.} 17. a3 {The best defence.} (17. Na4 c4 18. Nxb6 axb6 $17 19. Bxc4 Qb4+) (17. a4 {weakens the a-pawn and the square on b4.} c4 18. Ba2 Qb4 19. Rb1 Bd7 $5 $15) 17... c4 18. Ba2 Bd7 19. O-O ({It does not make much sense to castle under the fire:} 19. O-O-O Re8 20. h4 Nd5 21. Nxd5 exd5 22. Qxa7 Qe7 $44 23. Rxd5 Qf6 24. Qd4 Qxd4 25. Rxd4 Bxd4 26. Rd1 Bxf2 27. Rxd7 b5 $11 {[%csl Gh4]} 28. Rd5 $2 Re1+ 29. Kd2 Ra1 $17) 19... Re8 20. Rad1 {Completing the development of the available pieces.} (20. b4 Nd5 21. Nxd5 exd5 $17) (20. b3 Qxa3 $17) (20. Qe2 Bxc3 21. bxc3 Rc8 22. Rfe1 Rc5 23. Rad1 Bc6 $15 {The bishop will stay out of play forever.}) (20. Rab1 Bc6 21. Ne4 Nd5 22. Qg3 b5 23. c3 e5 24. Rbe1 Nf4 25. f3 f5 26. Nf2 Qf6 $44 27. Nh3 (27. Bb1 Nh5 28. Qh3 Nf4 29. Qg3 Bh6 {[%cal Gh6g5,Gg5h4]} 30. Nh3 Nd3 31. Bxd3 cxd3 $17) 27... Nd3 28. Re2 Bh6 $15) 20... Bc6 21. Rfe1 (21. Qg3 Qc5 22. Rfe1 Qf5 23. Bb1 Qa5 $44) 21... Nd5 $5 22. Nxd5 exd5 23. Qc1 Rxe1+ 24. Rxe1 b5 25. c3 d4 26. cxd4 Bxd4 27. Bb1 Qd6 28. Re2 Qf6 29. a4 a6 30. axb5 axb5 $44 {White is tied up to the defence of the pawns on f2 and b2. The bishop cannot step into freedom without giving up the pawn on b2. The position looks like what study composers call "a positional draw". Black can restrict himself to making neutral moves, such as ...Kg7 and ...Bb7.} *

