{[%evp 0,48,28,28,48,49,49,49,49,49,69,28,22,22,47,16,29,22,35,-1,-9,-8,14,18,22,-7,15,15,50,65,57,-2,10,57,57,40,40,34,97,45,45,7,7,7,5,5,-2,-1,9,-15,23]} 1. e4 Nf6 2. e5 Nd5 3. d4 d6 4. Nf3 g6 5. Bc4 Nb6 6. Bb3 Bg7 7. Ng5 e6 8. f4 {White consolidates his centre, delaying his attacking plans until reaching a satisfactory developing stage. The drawback of this system is that White will have to return with his knight to f3, resulting in the waste of two tempi.} dxe5 9. dxe5 {A modest continuation.} (9. fxe5 {is the main continuation, examined in Lines 21 and 22.}) 9... Qxd1+ 10. Kxd1 Bd7 11. Nc3 Bc6 12. Nge4 N8d7 {Black has displayed his minor pieces very harmoniously.} 13. Be3 (13. Ke2 Nd5 14. Nxd5 exd5 15. Ng5 O-O $11) 13... O-O-O {The most natural.} (13... O-O $5) 14. Ke2 Nd5 15. Nxd5 exd5 16. Ng5 Rde8 {[%cal Gf7f6] Threatening ...f7-f6.} 17. Nxf7 {There is no way back for White.} Rhf8 18. Ng5 Nxe5 $5 {One of the good continuations. Black opens the centre in order to start the attack against White's king and vulnerable minor pieces. Black can also prepare the sacrifice on e5 with one or more preliminary moves.} (18... d4 $5 19. Bd2 (19. Bxd4 $2 Rxf4 20. Be3 Rg4 21. Rhg1 Rxg5 22. Bxg5 Rxe5+ 23. Be3 Bh6 $19) 19... Nxe5 20. fxe5 Rxe5+ 21. Kd1 Rf2 22. Rg1 Ree2 23. Bf4 Bf6 24. Nxh7 Be7 $44) (18... h6 19. Nf3 g5 20. g3 gxf4 21. gxf4 Bxe5 $1 22. Nxe5 (22. fxe5 Bb5+ 23. c4 dxc4 24. Nd4 Nxe5 25. Nxb5 Ng4 26. Kd2 (26. Bxc4 Rf2+ $19) 26... Nxe3 27. Ba4 Rf2+ 28. Kc1 (28. Kc3 Rd8 $19) 28... Rg8 $44) 22... d4 23. Bd2 Nxe5 24. fxe5 Rxe5+ 25. Kd3 Rf3+ 26. Kc4 Rh5 27. Rhg1 Bd5+ 28. Kxd4 (28. Kb4 c5+ 29. Ka3 c4 $11) 28... c5+ 29. Kxc5 Bxb3+ 30. Kd4 Bxc2 31. Rg3 $11 (31. Rac1 $2 Rd3+ 32. Ke4 Rxd2+ $19)) 19. fxe5 Bxe5 20. Kd1 (20. Rhf1 $2 {runs into} Bb5+ $1 21. c4 dxc4 22. Bc2 c3+ 23. Bd3 cxb2 24. Rad1 Rxf1 25. Rxf1 Bf4 26. Bxb5 Rxe3+ 27. Kd2 Re1+ $5 28. Rxf4 Rd1+ ({Only not} 28... b1=Q $2 29. Rf8+) 29. Kxd1 (29. Ke2 b1=Q 30. Rf8+ Rd8 $19) 29... b1=Q+ 30. Kd2 Qxb5 $19) (20. Raf1 Bf4 (20... Bb5+ 21. c4 dxc4 22. Bc2 Bf4) 21. Nxh7 (21. Rxf4 Rxf4 22. Kd2 Rg4 $17 {attacking g2 and threatening ...d5-d4.}) 21... Rxe3+ 22. Kd1 Rf7 23. Ng5 Rf5 24. g4 Rxg5 25. Rxf4 Rh3 $11) 20... Bxb2 21. Rb1 Bc3 22. Bd2 {0-1 Rubinetti,J (2440)-Toth,C (2377) Najdorf Memorial Great fin 2000 (1.1)} Bxd2 23. Kxd2 Rf2+ 24. Kc3 Rxg2 $44 *

