{[%evp 0,57,19,38,89,89,79,48,44,44,63,40,34,25,19,6,7,10,30,47,13,20,44,-13,-6,25,11,-4,-4,-6,-14,-15,-7,-15,-24,-59,-24,-7,64,64,33,1,-17,-17,-48,-42,-11,-30,-6,0,-4,-4,32,14,-8,2,-15,-32,-26,-35]} 1. e4 Nf6 2. e5 Nd5 3. d4 d6 4. Nf3 g6 5. Bc4 Nb6 6. Bb3 Bg7 7. Ng5 e6 8. f4 dxe5 9. fxe5 {The main continuation, keeping the queens on board and opening the f-file.} O-O {The most restrictive move order.} ({By far more popular,} 9... c5 {offers White the chance to deviate from the main line with} 10. Qf3 (10. c3 O-O {transposes to the main line.}) 10... O-O 11. dxc5 {maintaining chances for some advantage.}) 10. Qg4 {The only way of deviating from the usual paths.} ({The main continuation,} 10. O-O {is examined in Line 22.}) 10... a5 {As so many other times, it is useful to molest the bishop before starting the central counterattack.} ({In the event of} 10... c5 {White may consider} 11. dxc5 {, when the queenside structure slightly favours him with respect to a similar line below.}) 11. c3 {Trying to recycle the bishop, but weakening the pressure along its actual diagonal.} (11. a4 {is best met with} h5 12. Qh4 c5 13. c3 (13. dxc5 N6d7 {leaves the white queenside weakened a bit.} 14. Be3 (14. g4 {runs into} Nxe5 {, parrying all the threats by tactical means.} 15. gxh5 Qxg5 $1 16. Qxg5 Nf3+ 17. Ke2 Nxg5 18. Bxg5 Na6 19. hxg6 fxg6 20. c3 Nxc5 21. Bc2 b6 $11 22. Bxg6 Ba6+ 23. Ke1 Bf6 24. Bxf6 Rxf6 25. Rg1 Kf8 $44) 14... Nxe5 15. Nc3 Ng4 16. Bf4 Qd4 17. Qg3 Nc6 $11) 13... Nc6 14. O-O (14. g4 {is once again answered resolutely.} Nxd4 $1 15. cxd4 Qxd4 16. Nc3 Nd5 17. Nf3 Qxg4 18. Qg3 Nb4 19. O-O b6 $44 {Three pawns and the superior activity guarantee Black enough compensation for the knight.}) 14... cxd4 15. g4 dxc3 16. bxc3 (16. gxh5 Qd4+ $19) 16... f6 17. Nxe6 Bxe6 18. Bxe6+ Kh8 19. gxh5 fxe5 20. Rxf8+ Bxf8 21. Bg5 Qd1+ 22. Kg2 Qe2+ 23. Kg3 Qe1+ 24. Kh3 Qf1+ {½-½ Emelyanov,M (2536)-Pavlov,V (2423) Borzenko Memorial email 2015}) (11. a3 a4 12. Ba2 c5 13. dxc5 Nd5 14. Qh3 h5 15. Nc3 Qc7 16. O-O Qxc5+ 17. Kh1 Nxc3 18. Qxc3 Qxc3 19. bxc3 Ra5 $17) 11... a4 12. Bc2 f5 {Immediately using the latter circumstance.} 13. Qh3 (13. exf6 Qxf6 14. Qh4 h6 {leads to balanced play.} 15. Nf3 Qxh4+ 16. Nxh4 g5 17. Ng6 Rf7 18. h4 Nc6 19. hxg5 hxg5 20. Na3 (20. Bxg5 Ra5 21. Bd2 e5 $44) 20... e5 21. d5 Nxd5 22. Bxg5 Bf5 $13 {½-½ Parshin,V (2330)-Pavlov,V (2420) EU-ch 2014 sf17 email}) 13... h6 14. Nf3 g5 {Black has made a lot of progress on both wings. White needs to start resolute play.} 15. g4 c5 16. Qh5 (16. gxf5 exf5 17. Bxg5 hxg5 18. Rg1 g4 19. Rxg4 fxg4 20. Qh7+ Kf7 21. Qg6+ Kg8 22. Qh7+ (22. Ng5 Rf4 $19) 22... Kf7 $11 23. Bg6+ $2 Ke6 24. Qxg7 gxf3 $19) 16... cxd4 17. Bxg5 Qe8 18. Qxe8 Rxe8 19. Bf6 Bxf6 20. exf6 Nc6 $13 {½-½ Havumaki,A (2416)-Pavlov,V (2431) W-ch40 sf04 email 2016} *

