1. e4 Nf6 2. e5 Nd5 3. d4 d6 4. Nf3 g6 5. Bc4 Nb6 6. Bb3 Bg7 7. Ng5 e6 8. f4 dxe5 9. fxe5 O-O 10. O-O {As mentioned before, the main continuation.} c5 11. c3 (11. dxc5 {is inoffensive since it allows the exchange of queens.} Qxd1 12. Rxd1 N6d7 13. Ne4 (13. Be3 Nxe5 14. h3 Bd7 $11) 13... Nxe5 14. h3 Bd7 15. Nbc3 Bc6 16. Be3 Nbd7 17. Rd2 b6 18. cxb6 axb6 19. Re1 Ra5 20. Bd4 b5 21. a3 Rb8 $132 {0-1 Nechaev,A (2277)-Lopes,M (2123) ESP AEAC XV W/P/26 email 2016}) 11... cxd4 12. cxd4 {The most consistent move, strengthening e5 and preparing Nc3.} (12. Qxd4 Nd5 $5 $146 (12... Nc6 13. Qxd8 Nxd8 14. Nf3 Bd7 15. Be3 Na4 16. Rf2 b6 17. Na3 {0-1 Soellig,M-Schulze,U corr 1998} Bc6 18. Rd1 Nc5 $13) (12... Qxd4+ 13. cxd4 Nc6 14. Be3 Na5 15. Ne4 Bd7 16. Nbc3 Bc6 $11 {½-½ Roth,R-Giese,G GER jub50 qJVH28 corr 1996}) 13. Nf3 (13. c4 Qb6 $1 14. c5 Qd8 $1 15. Nc3 Nc6 $15) 13... Nc6 14. Qe4 Qc7 15. Re1 b6 16. Na3 a6 17. Bxd5 exd5 18. Qxd5 Be6 19. Qe4 Bf5 20. Qe2 Bg4 21. Bf4 Rae8 $11) 12... Nc6 {From structural point of view, Black is doing better, but he faces some at least abstract kingside dangers. Moreover, developing his queen's bishop will still require some time.} 13. Nf3 (13. Be3 {runs into} Nd5 (13... Na5 $5 14. Nc3 {½-½ Gorodetzky,D (2342)-Tukhaev,A (2564) EU-ch blitz Minsk 2015 (18.44)} Nxb3 15. Qxb3 Nd5 $11) 14. Bxd5 exd5 (14... Qxd5 15. Nc3 Qd8 16. Nge4 $16) 15. Nc3 {The position is about equal and Black even has some choices.} f6 (15... h6 16. Nf3 Be6 17. Rc1 Qd7 18. Qd2 Kh7 19. Bf4 Rac8 20. h3 Ne7 $11 {½-½ Kholmov,R (2495)-Iordachescu,V (2440) Moscow GM3 1996}) 16. exf6 Bxf6 (16... Rxf6 17. Qd2 Bf5 18. Nf3 Qd7 19. Ne5 Nxe5 20. dxe5 Re6 $11 {0-1 Marques,A-Rain,R (2214) WZ-ch sf08 email 2018}) 17. Qd2 Qd6 $1 $146 (17... Bf5 $6 18. Rxf5 gxf5 19. Ne6 $14 {as played in three games.}) 18. Rae1 (18. Nb5 Qe7 19. Rae1 Bf5 $11) (18. Bf4 Qb4 $11) 18... Bf5 $11) 13... f6 {Black is a bit better developed at this stage, justifying this typical pawn break. The idea is to eliminate the danger of an attack based on the outpost on e5. True, the last move weakens the a2-g8 diagonal, offering White some ideas for fighting for the initiative.} 14. exf6 (14. Nc3 fxe5 {yields White just normal compensation for the pawn.} 15. Bg5 (15. dxe5 Nxe5 $11) 15... Qd7 16. dxe5 (16. d5 exd5 17. Nxd5 Nxd5 18. Bxd5+ Kh8 19. Re1 Nd4 $15 20. Nxd4 Qxd5 $17 {0-1 Cote,J (1947)-Saleh,M (2224) Aylmer op 1993 (5)}) 16... Nxe5 17. Nxe5 Rxf1+ 18. Qxf1 (18. Kxf1 Qxd1+ 19. Rxd1 Bxe5 20. a4 Kg7 21. a5 Nd7 22. Ne4 b6 23. Bxe6 Ba6+ 24. Kg1 Nf8 25. Bd5 Rc8 26. axb6 axb6 27. Ra1 Bb5 28. Ra7+ Nd7 29. Be3 Rc7 $11 {1-0 Radulski,J (2502)-Laketic,G (2467) SCG-chT1 Vrnjacka Banja 2005 (6)}) 18... Qd4+ 19. Kh1 Qxe5 {White's compensation for the pawn, based on his better development, suffices only for ensuring chances for maintaining approximately equal chances in a complicated though simplified position. From practical point of view, Black's play seems to be easier, though, at least of we consider the practical results.} 20. Bf4 (20. Be7 Bd7 21. Re1 Qf5 22. Qe2 Re8 23. Bd6 Qf6 24. Ne4 Qxb2 25. Qf3 Bc6 $15 {0-1 Pupols,V (2343)-Alburt,L (2575) US Open-88 Portland 1987 (10)}) (20. Bd8 Bd7 21. Re1 Qh5 22. Bxb6 axb6 23. Qd3 Bc6 24. Bxe6+ Kh8 $15 {0-1 Dueckstein,A (2345)-Fauland,A (2450) AUT-ch Bad Schallerbach 1989 (3)}) (20. Bh4 Bd7 21. Re1 Rf8 22. Qd3 Qd4 23. Qxd4 Bxd4 24. h3 {½-½ Morozov,D (2310)-Sabaev,S RUS-ch sf Pskov 1998 (1)} Bf2 25. Bxf2 Rxf2 26. Bxe6+ Bxe6 27. Rxe6 Kf7 28. Re2 Rxe2 29. Nxe2 Kf6 30. Kh2 Ke5 31. Kg3 Ke4 $15) 20... Qf5 {½-½ Mukhametov,E (2515)-Golubovic,B (2365) Bern op 1995 (3)} 21. Bd2 Bd7 22. Qe2 Rf8 23. h3 Kh8 24. Re1 Bc6 $15 25. Bxe6 Qf2 $17 {½-½ Arzumanyan,S-Polaczek,R EU-ch41 corr 1986}) (14. Bf4 fxe5 15. Bxe5 Nxe5 16. dxe5 Nd5 17. Re1 Qb6+ 18. Qd4 Qxd4+ (18... Bd7) (18... Qa5 $2 19. Nc3 Rf4 20. Qd2 Rf8 21. Bxd5 exd5 22. Qxd5+ Qxd5 23. Nxd5 Bg4 24. e6 {1-0 Juhnke,J-Ligterink,G World U20-ch10 Preliminaries E 1969 (4)}) 19. Nxd4 Nf4 20. Nc3 Nd3 21. Re3 Nxe5 $11) 14... Qxf6 15. Bg5 (15. Be3 Nd5 16. Bf2 (16. Bxd5 exd5 17. Nc3 Bg4 $11) 16... Nf4 17. Nc3 Nh3+ {is similar and could transpose after} 18. gxh3 Qxf3) 15... Qf5 16. Be3 Nd5 17. Bf2 (17. Bxd5 exd5 (17... Qxd5 18. Nc3 Qd6 $11) 18. Nc3 Bd7 (18... b6 $5) 19. Qd2 Rae8 $11) 17... Nf4 {Black has good counterplay, despite not having developed his queenside yet.} 18. Nc3 (18. Bg3 $2 Nxd4 19. Nxd4 Nh3+ 20. gxh3 Bxd4+ 21. Kg2 Qxf1+ 22. Qxf1 Rxf1 23. Kxf1 Bxb2 $19) 18... Nh3+ 19. gxh3 (19. Kh1 Nxf2+ 20. Rxf2 Nxd4 $17) 19... Qxf3 20. Qxf3 (20. d5 {does not promise much, either.} Qxd1 21. Raxd1 exd5 22. Bxd5+ Kh8 23. Kg2 Bf5 $11 24. Rfe1 $2 Bxh3+ $1 25. Kxh3 Rxf2 $17 {0-1 Zapata,A (2510)-Timman,J (2630) OHRA Amsterdam 1987}) 20... Rxf3 21. Nb5 (21. d5 {may be answered with} Na5 (21... Nd4 $146 {is also possible.}) 22. Nb5 Nxb3 23. axb3 {White's initiative is temporary and he has many weak pawns.} exd5 (23... Bd7 {leads to less interesting play, but equalizes in a simpler way.} 24. Nc7 Rc8 25. Nxe6 Bxb2 26. Rxa7 Rd3 $11) 24. Nc7 {Black has a choice between two exchange sacrifices.} Rxf2 (24... Bxh3 $5 25. Nxa8 Bxf1 26. Rxf1 Rxb3 27. Bxa7 Rxb2 28. Nc7 Be5 29. Nxd5 Bxh2+ $44) 25. Rxf2 Rb8 26. Rd1 d4 (26... Bxh3 27. Nxd5 Kh8 $44 {is a bit simpler.}) 27. Ne8 {If he manages to stabilize the position, Black will have fantastic compensation for the exchange, due to his strong bishops. The problem is that he needs to display some accuracy to neutralize the white knight's activity.} Bf8 $1 $146 (27... Be5 28. Re1 Bh8 29. Nf6+ $14 {was played in three games.}) 28. Rxd4 Bc5 29. Rd8 Be7 30. Rfd2 Kf8 $1 (30... Bxd8 $2 31. Rxd8 Kf8 {runs into} 32. Nd6+ $18) 31. Nc7+ {The discovered check on d6 does not work now.} Bxd8 32. Rxd8+ Ke7 33. Rh8 b5 34. Nd5+ (34. Rxh7+ Kd6 $11) 34... Kd6 35. Nf4 a5 36. Rxh7 Bf5 $11) 21... Bd7 22. d5 {A familiar pawn break.} (22. Nc7 $2 {runs into the unexpected} Nxd4 $1 $19 23. Nxa8 Ne2+ 24. Kg2 Rxb3 $1 {The white king is in bog danger.} 25. Bxa7 (25. Rac1 Nf4+ 26. Kh1 Rxb2 27. Rc7 Bc6+ 28. Rxc6 bxc6 $19 {0-1 Jensen,V (2250)-Brautsch,S Aarhus-D 1988 (6)}) (25. axb3 Bc6#) 25... Rxb2 26. a4 Bc6+ 27. Kf2 Nd4+ 28. Kg3 Be5+ {0-1 Schwaegli,B (2265)-Hirt,M Wohlen op 1993 (7)}) (22. Kg2 Raf8 $19) 22... Rxb3 (22... Na5 {may transpose to a line examined above.} 23. Nc7 Nxb3 24. axb3 Rc8 25. Nxe6 Bxb2 26. Rxa7 Rd3 $11) 23. axb3 exd5 24. Nc7 Rc8 25. Nxd5 Bxb2 26. Ra2 Bg7 {Black has normal compensation for the exchange.} 27. Kg2 Re8 28. Nc7 Re7 29. Re1 {1-0 Wesche,T (1926)-Barhorst,A (1897) Webchess op2 Gr66 email 2006} Ne5 $5 $11 30. Rxa7 $2 Bc6+ $19 *

