{[%evp 0,60,19,31,57,55,71,60,39,62,78,39,32,27,31,10,30,13,28,-11,3,23,12,21,30,40,35,35,41,24,29,34,23,23,26,29,34,36,40,45,77,19,31,15,37,21,42,18,37,47,43,39,55,51,70,33,19,17,24,18,6,0,44]} 1. e4 Nf6 2. e5 Nd5 3. d4 d6 4. Nf3 g6 5. Bc4 Nb6 6. Bb3 Bg7 7. O-O {Unlike the continuations examined above, this is a positional plan. White intends to complete his development before taking important decisions.} O-O (7... Bg4 $2 {is premature due to} 8. Bxf7+ Kxf7 9. Ng5+ {wins.}) 8. Re1 {Not the most effective way of consolidating e5.} ({In the event of} 8. Qe2 {, apart from 8...Nc6, transposing to Line 27 after 9.h3, Black can immediately play} Bg4 $11 {followed by ...Nc6.}) (8. exd6 {is examined in Line 24.}) (8. h3 {is investigated in Lines 25 to 27.}) 8... Nc6 {Maintaining the flexibility from the point of view of our repertoire.} (8... Bg4 {is playable, of course, but I see a minor problem after} 9. exd6 cxd6 10. c3 {In Line 24, examining this structure, we do not play ...Bg4.}) 9. Nbd2 {Solid but not especially active.} (9. e6 {is not dangerous, since White does not have enough development.} fxe6 10. c3 (10. Bxe6+ Bxe6 11. Rxe6 {runs into the resolute} Rxf3 $1 12. gxf3 {Otherwise, Black wins a pawn with the double attack ...Nxd4.} Nxd4 13. Re4 e5 $15 {with more than enough compensation for the exchange, due to White's shattered kingside structure, Black's strong centre and advance in development.}) (10. Ng5 Nxd4 $17) 10... d5 $15 {It is not easy for White to prove his compensation for the pawn.}) (9. Qe2 Bg4 $15 {[%cal Gc6d4,Gd6e5] threatening both ...Nxd4 and ...dxe5.}) (9. c3 {wastes another developing tempo, yielding Black comfortable equality.} dxe5 10. Nxe5 Nxe5 11. dxe5 Qxd1 12. Bxd1 Bf5 13. Nd2 Nd7 14. Nf3 Nc5 15. Bg5 Rfe8 16. Nd4 Nd3 17. Re2 (17. Re3 {0-1 Wenzel,B (2079)-Dumjahn,C (2032) Hamburg-ch MA 2018 (9)} Nxe5 {is similar.}) 17... h6 18. Nxf5 gxf5 19. Bc1 Nxe5 20. Bf4 Ng6 21. Bxc7 Rec8 22. Ba5 e6 $11 {Black's minor pieces are active and he can think of starting the minority's attack. These compensate for White's bishops' pair.}) (9. exd6 cxd6 {transposes to Line 24.}) 9... dxe5 10. dxe5 Bg4 11. e6 {The only way to maintain the material equality.} (11. h3 Bxf3 12. Qxf3 Bxe5 {simply wins a pawn.}) 11... f5 {With his queen's bishop developed, Black can avoid the exchange on e6.} 12. h3 {1-0 Mayorga,N (2242)-Bernard,I (2282) LNA Puma Cup 2006 (4)} Bh5 $1 $146 {There is no need to exchange the bishop yet. Black will gladly do it if this supposes spoiling the kingside structure with gxf3.} 13. a4 {It appears that White does not have useful developing moves.} (13. c3 Na5 14. Bc2 Qd5 15. Qe2 Rad8 $11 {Black is better developed and the pawn on e6 is not entirely secure.}) (13. Qe2 a5 ({The immediate} 13... Nd4 {is also good, but not the strongest.} 14. Qf1 $5) 14. a4 (14. c3 a4 15. Bc2 Ne5 $15) 14... Nd4 15. Qe3 (15. Qd3 Nxf3+ 16. Nxf3 Qxd3 17. cxd3 Bxf3 18. gxf3 Rfd8 $17) (15. Qf1 Nxb3 16. Nxb3 Bxf3 17. gxf3 Qd6 $15) 15... Nd5 16. Qd3 Nf4 17. Qe3 Qd6 $15 18. Nc4 Bxf3 $1 19. Nxd6 Nxg2 20. Qd2 cxd6 21. Rf1 Ne2+ 22. Kh2 Be5+ $19) (13. Nf1 Qxd1 14. Rxd1 Bxf3 15. gxf3 Nd4 $15) 13... Na5 (13... a5 $5 $11) 14. Ba2 {An interesting pawn sacrifice, aiming at keeping the dangerous bishop.} Nxa4 15. Bb1 b5 16. c3 {Black's knights are hanging a bit, but being better developed, he can deal with this small problem.} Nb7 (16... c5 $5 17. Bc2 Bxc3 $5 18. Bxa4 (18. bxc3 Nxc3 $19 {traps the queen.}) 18... Bxd2 19. Bxd2 Bxf3 20. gxf3 bxa4 21. Rxa4 Nc6 $11) 17. Qb3 a6 18. Rxa4 Bxf3 $1 (18... Nc5 19. Rd4 $1 $14) 19. gxf3 {White needs to keep his queen defended.} (19. Nxf3 $2 {runs into} Nc5 $17) 19... Nc5 20. Rd4 $1 {This is the difference! This intermediate move keeps White in the game.} Qxd4 (20... Bxd4 21. Qb4 Bxf2+ 22. Kxf2 Qd6 $13 {[%cal Gf8f6]}) 21. cxd4 Nxb3 22. Nxb3 a5 23. Bd3 c6 $13 *

