{[%evp 0,56,24,11,47,54,46,26,24,21,61,39,30,30,30,24,32,24,30,24,25,10,14,-18,-18,8,14,12,32,36,37,28,35,28,25,17,18,-2,-2,-23,-14,-23,-24,-24,-22,-24,-24,-24,-24,-24,0,5,0,-11,0,-16,28,36,27]} 1. e4 Nf6 2. e5 Nd5 3. d4 d6 4. Nf3 g6 5. Bc4 Nb6 6. Bb3 Bg7 7. O-O O-O 8. exd6 {Abstractly speaking, this looks like an early concession, since it throws away part of White's space advantage. It is not a bad practical decision, though; strong players have occasionally used this system. White's idea is to rid himself of the potential weakness on e5 and his dream is to build up a slow but consistent kingside attack, using the e-file among other elements, in the spirit of the Torre Attack, for instance. Black has two main plans. He can prepare a central break with ...e7-e5, or set up queenside pressure, by occupying the c4-square and maybe advancing his b-pawn.} cxd6 {The most natural answer.} (8... exd6 {is also playable, even though the omission of the moves a2-a4 and ...a7-a5 may slightly favour White concerning Line 13.}) 9. Re1 {The most popular and natural move.} (9. h3 {does not make too much sense at this stage, since in the absence of any central tension, ...Bg4 is not such a big threat. Since it was played in an online game between top players, it deserves mentioning, though.} Nc6 10. a4 {I do not see the point behind this move, either. White weakens his queenside with his development incomplete.} Na5 (10... e5 $6 11. Bg5 $1 $14 (11. a5 $6 Nd7 $11 12. d5 $6 Nxa5 13. Ba2 b5 $15 {1-0 Firouzja,A (2749)-Carlsen,M (2862) Magnus-Alireza Blitz 2021 (5)}) 11... Qc7 12. a5 Nd7 13. Nc3 $14) 11. Ba2 d5 {With the bishop on a2, a natural move.} ({The provocative} 11... Bf5 {, planning ...Rc8, is also possible.} 12. b4 Nc6 13. a5 Nc8 14. c3 d5 $11 {followed by ...Nd6.}) 12. Nc3 e6 (12... Bf5 13. Ne2 Rc8 14. c3 Nac4 15. Ng3 Bd7 16. Bb1 Nd6 17. Re1 Nbc4 $11) 13. Ne5 Bd7 14. b4 Nc6 (14... Nac4 $11) 15. Nxc6 Bxc6 16. Bb3 {0-1 Ovcharov,T (2009)-Orev,P (2135) WchT Silent Opatija 2014 (7.2)} Nc8 $5 {[%cal Gc8d6] followed by ...Nd6.}) (9. c3 Nc6 10. Re1 {transposes to the main line.}) 9... Nc6 10. c3 ({Alternatively,} 10. h3 {We will see that this can make sense in a line below.} Bf5 11. Nc3 {In this system, White frequently develops his knight this way. The knight is not supposed to stay on c3, but to use this square on its way to the kingside. Under these circumstances, h2-h3 makes sense, of course, since ...Bg4 could create problems on d4 in the absence of c2-c3.} (11. c3 {is not consequent after h2-h3. White just wastes time by advancing his pawns.} e5 12. Be3 (12. dxe5 dxe5 13. Nbd2 h6 $5 $11 {securing f7 and inviting White to display a developing plan.}) 12... Qc7 (12... Na5 $11) (12... e4 $5 13. Nh2 Na5 14. Bc2 d5 $15) 13. Na3 a6 (13... Rad8 14. Bg5 $14) 14. dxe5 Nxe5 15. Nd4 Bd7 16. Qd2 Rfe8 17. Bh6 Nbc4 18. Nxc4 Nxc4 19. Bxc4 Qxc4 20. Bxg7 Kxg7 21. a3 Qd5 $11 {The position is approximately equal. Things would be different with the black Isolani on d5, but the way it is, he has the long diagonal at his disposal.} 22. Qf4 Bc6 23. Qg3 Rxe1+ 24. Rxe1 Re8 25. Rxe8 Bxe8 26. Qf3 Qg5 (26... Qxf3 27. Nxf3 Kf6) 27. Kh2 Qe5+ 28. g3 Qf6 29. Qe3 Bc6 30. f4 Bd5 $11 {1-0 Grischuk,A (2747)-Bortnyk,O (2579) ICC op final blitz 2016 (1)}) 11... Rc8 12. Bg5 {The point behind provoking the weakening of g6 will be revealed a bit later.} h6 13. Be3 d5 (13... Na5 {is supposed to run into} 14. Nh4 {, when the bishop's retreat would leave g6 undefended. However, Black can try} e6 $5 $146 15. Nxf5 exf5 16. Qf3 Qd7 17. Rad1 Rfe8 {with interesting play and approximate equality.}) 14. Ne2 {An important part of White's plan. He gradually concentrates his forces on the kingside.} Na5 (14... Nb4 15. Rc1 Nc4 $11) 15. c3 Nbc4 16. Bc1 Qb6 17. Nf4 Be4 18. Nd2 {The start of an interesting sequence.} Nxb3 19. Nxc4 Qa6 20. Qxb3 dxc4 21. Qd1 Bc6 22. Rxe7 {White has won a pawn, but his development is incomplete. The main question remains whether Black can maintain a blockade on d5, or in other words, keep his light-squared bishop active.} Rfe8 (22... Qa5 23. Re1 Rfe8 $44) 23. Rxe8+ Rxe8 24. Be3 {1-0 Anand,V (2670)-Timman,J (2620) Linares 10th 1992 (9)} g5 25. Nh5 Qb5 26. Qd2 Qd5 27. f3 f5 {Black has enough compensation for the pawn.} 28. Bxg5 (28. Bf2 Qf7 29. Nxg7 Kxg7 $11) 28... hxg5 29. Qxg5 Qf7 $13 30. Nxg7 $2 Qxg7 31. Qxf5 Re2 32. Qc8+ Kh7 33. Qf5+ Kh6 34. Qf4+ Qg5 35. Qf8+ Kg6 36. Qg8+ Kf6 37. Qd8+ Kf5 38. g4+ Kf4 39. Qd6+ Kxf3 40. Rf1+ Ke4 41. Qe6+ Kd3 42. Rd1+ Rd2 $17) (10. Bg5 {bears familiar ideas.} h6 11. Be3 (11. Bh4 g5 12. Bg3 g4 13. Nh4 (13. d5 Nxd5 14. Qxd5 gxf3 {[%csl Gb2]} 15. c3 fxg2 16. Nd2 Ne5 $15 {[%cal Gg8h8,Gf8g8]}) 13... Nxd4 14. Ng6 Re8 15. Bh4 Nf5 16. Qxg4 Nxh4 17. Qxh4 e6 18. Qxd8 Rxd8 19. Ne7+ Kf8 20. Nxc8 Raxc8 21. c3 d5 $15 {½-½ Aubert,L (2285)-Hauchard,A (2490) FRA-chT France 1994 (4)}) 11... Na5 12. c3 Nxb3 13. axb3 Nd5 14. c4 (14. Bd2 e6 15. c4 Nc7 16. Bc3 b6 $11 {[%cal Gc8b7]}) 14... Nxe3 15. Rxe3 {1-0 Rausch,S (2315)-Babinetz,R (1725) Seefeld op 04th 1993 (8)} e6 16. Nc3 a6 17. Qd2 Qc7 $11 {Black's structure is very flexible and his bishops may become dangerous later. Black's most natural plan is to prepare ...b7-b5 with ...Bd7.}) 10... Bf5 {Black keeps developing, delaying a bit his counterplay in the centre.} (10... e5 {is also playable, but requires certain accuracy from Black..} 11. Bg5 (11. dxe5 dxe5 12. Qxd8 Rxd8 13. Ng5 Rf8 14. Be3 h6 15. Ne4 Rd8 16. Na3 Bf5 17. f3 Na5 18. Bxb6 axb6 19. Nc4 Nxc4 {½-½ Varberg,K (2245)-Ottesen,S (2404) DEN-ch email 2007} 20. Bxc4 Kf8 $11) 11... Qc7 12. Na3 a6 13. dxe5 {Trying to maintain the initiative.} (13. h3 Na5 $11) 13... dxe5 14. Be3 Rd8 15. Bxb6 {Trying to create threats on light squares, with f7 as a main target.} (15. Qc2 Nd5 16. Bxd5 Rxd5 17. Nc4 Bf5) (15. Qe2 Nd5 16. Bxd5 Rxd5 17. Nc4 Rb8 18. Nb6 Rd8 19. Rad1 Be6 $11) 15... Qxb6 16. Nc4 Qc7 17. Qe2 Be6 18. Ng5 (18. Nfxe5 Nxe5 19. Nxe5 Bxb3 20. axb3 Re8 21. f4 Qb6+ 22. Qf2 Qxb3 $11) 18... Bd5 19. Rad1 Ne7 20. Rxd5 {The critical idea.} ({The insertion of the moves} 20. g3 h6 {½-½ Raidaru,M (2387)-Debevec,B (2324) WS MN/063 email 2010 followed by a draw agreement, just when things were about to become interesting is typical for correspondence chess.} 21. Rxd5 {leads to similar play as in the main line.} Nxd5 22. Nxf7 Qxf7 23. Nb6 Rab8 24. Nxd5 Kh8 25. Nf4 Qf6 26. Ne6 Re8 27. Nc5 Qc6 28. Ne4 b5 $11) 20... Nxd5 21. Nxf7 Qxf7 22. Nb6 Rab8 {Is removing the rook from the attacked square and defending b7.} 23. Nxd5 ({The point of the latter part of my previous comment is that after} 23. Rd1 {Black can play} Nxb6 24. Bxf7+ Kxf7 25. Qf3+ Ke8 {with some material advantage, since b7 is defended. True, the activity of White's queen should maintain the balance even.}) 23... Kh8 $1 (23... Rxd5 24. Rd1 Rbd8 25. Rxd5 Rxd5 26. Qe4 $16) 24. Ne3 (24. Nb6 Qf4 $5) 24... Qe7 25. Bd5 b5 $11 {White has full compensation for the echange but hardly more.}) 11. Bg5 (11. Na3 e5 $5 $146 12. Bg5 Qd7 {Black always has this comfortable reaction after developing the bishop. to the bishop's incursion to g5.} 13. dxe5 dxe5 14. Qxd7 Nxd7 {[%cal Gd7c5] Planning ...Nc5.} 15. Be3 e4 (15... Na5 16. Bc2 Bxc2 17. Nxc2 Nc4 $36) 16. Nd4 Nde5 17. Nxf5 gxf5 $11) 11... h6 12. Bh4 Re8 13. Nbd2 Na5 14. Bc2 Bxc2 15. Qxc2 Rc8 16. h3 Qd7 17. a4 e6 {Black is very flexible and has a good game. Here are a couple of examples.} 18. Bg3 f5 (18... a6 19. Ne4 Rc6 20. Bh2 Nd5 21. Qe2 Rec8 22. Nfd2 Bf8 23. h4 Qd8 24. h5 g5 25. Rac1 Qb6 26. Rb1 Qd8 27. Rf1 Kh8 28. Rbe1 f5 29. Ng3 Nf4 30. Qe3 d5 31. Ne2 Nxh5 {½-½ Kurgansky,V (2366)-Grego,L (2305) EU-ch 2015 sf13 email Not a typical drawn position, of course. But Black has a good game.} 32. b4 Nc4 33. Nxc4 Rxc4 34. Qxe6 f4 $13) 19. Re2 Nd5 20. Qd3 a6 21. Qc2 Nc6 22. Qb3 Na5 23. Qc2 Nc6 24. Qb3 b5 $5 {Avoiding the move repetition.} 25. axb5 axb5 26. Nf1 (26. Qxb5 Rb8 $11) 26... Rb8 27. Ree1 Nc7 28. Ne3 b4 $11 {0-1 Chapado,R (2118)-Rudolf,M (2229) LSS WC-2014-P-00012 2010} *

