{[%evp 0,60,38,22,68,67,67,61,53,35,92,33,33,27,32,23,37,0,15,15,26,24,32,32,20,33,28,28,28,27,27,30,30,30,30,24,24,33,33,28,39,36,35,19,31,42,42,42,53,53,53,53,65,73,70,23,15,36,37,4,8,5,20]} 1. e4 Nf6 2. e5 Nd5 3. d4 d6 4. Nf3 g6 5. Bc4 Nb6 6. Bb3 Bg7 7. O-O O-O 8. h3 {This leads to one of the most important Alekhine defence tabyias. White declares his intentions of keeping his pawn on e5. Black has several ways of fighting for either counterplay or simplifying to interesting endgames. Since this is such an important system, I have examined none less than four alternatives for Black in some detail. At times, Black seemed to be on edge in all of them, but modern engines consider them all as entirely satisfactory.} a5 {This move order is important for players who intend to meet 7.a4 with 7...a5 as in Line 12.} ({For} 8... Nc6 {see Line 27.}) 9. a4 {The only reasonable answer. White should not allow Black to gain too much queenside space.} (9. a3 a4 10. Ba2 dxe5 11. dxe5 Qxd1 12. Rxd1 Nc6 $1 (12... Bf5 {0-1 Gesyan,S (1945)-Rakhimzhan,A (2273) FIDE World Uni Rapid-C 1st 2021 (3) allows White to solve his problems with} 13. e6 Bxe6 14. Bxe6 fxe6 15. Ng5 e5 $11) 13. Re1 (13. Bf4 Bf5 $15 14. e6 Bxb2 $17) (13. e6 Bxe6 14. Bxe6 fxe6 15. Ng5 Rad8 16. Rf1 Nd4 $17) 13... Bf5 14. e6 Bxe6 15. Bxe6 fxe6 $15 16. Nc3 (16. Rxe6 Nd4 17. Nxd4 Bxd4 18. Re2 Rxf2 19. Rxf2 Rf8 $17) (16. Ng5 Nd4 $17) 16... Nd4 17. Nxd4 Bxd4 18. Nd1 Kf7 $15) (9. c3 a4 {is also comfortable for Black.} 10. Bc2 dxe5 11. Nxe5 N8d7 12. Nxd7 (12. Nf3 c5 $11) 12... Bxd7 13. Re1 Ra5 14. Nd2 c5 $11) 9... Nc6 (9... dxe5 {is examined in Line 26.}) 10. Qe2 {Almost unanimously played.} (10. exd6 Qxd6 (10... cxd6 $6 11. Nc3 Bf5 12. Nb5 $14) (10... exd6 $5) 11. c3 e5 $1 $11) (10. Bf4 dxe5 11. dxe5 Be6 12. Bxe6 Qxd1 13. Rxd1 fxe6 14. Bg3 Nc4 $11) 10... dxe5 {Black does not have any other constructive moves. He prepares to activate his queen by releasing the tension.} 11. dxe5 Nd4 12. Nxd4 Qxd4 13. Re1 {White defends his central pawn and is ready to question the queen's stability in the centre.} (13. e6 {leads to simplifications.} Bxe6 14. Bxe6 fxe6 15. Qxe6+ Rf7 16. Nd2 Qd5 $146 (16... Qd6 $5 $146) 17. Qxd5 Nxd5 18. c3 Nf4 19. Ne4 Ne2+ 20. Kh2 Nxc1 21. Raxc1 Rf5 22. Rfd1 b5 $5 $11 {Black has good counterplay.}) 13... Bd7 {Continuing to develop.} ({Practice has shown that White retains the better chances after} 13... Be6 14. Bxe6 fxe6 15. Nd2 Rf5 16. Nf3 Qc4 17. b3 Qxe2 18. Rxe2 $14 {Usually, Black should go for this structure only after Bf4, when the exchange on e6 more or less forces the bishop's retreat to g3 or h2. In this position, it will go to either b2 or a3.}) (13... e6 {planning the same manoeuvre as in the game, without fearing a later e5-e6, is a bit too slow, allowing the white knight to reach f3 with stronger effects than in the main line. It remains a solid, but somewhat passive alternative.} 14. Nd2 Bd7 15. Nf3 (15. c3 {only spends a tempo on a pawn move.} Qc5 16. Nf3 Bc6 17. Be3 Qe7 18. Nd4 Bd7 19. f4 Nd5 20. Bd2 c5 21. Nb5 Bc6 $11) 15... Qc5 16. Be3 Qb4 17. Red1 Bc6 18. Nd4 Nd5 (18... Rfd8 {1-0 Glek,I (2590)-Timmer,R (2300) Haarlem AKN op 03rd 1994 (3)} 19. h4 $14) 19. c3 {Forcing the queen to abandon the b-file.} (19. Nxc6 bxc6 20. Rd4 Qb7 $132 {The constant pressure along the b-file and the strong centralized knight compensate for Black's structural defect and White's space advantage.}) 19... Qe7 20. Nxc6 bxc6 21. Bc1 Rab8 22. Bc2 Rfd8 23. f4 c5 24. Kh2 Qe8 {Planning ...Qc6.} 25. Be4 {It is not clear how White is going to make progress if Black restricts himself to neutral moves, but the position is a bit one-sided.}) 14. c3 (14. Nc3 {places the knight on a square that does not offer other perspectives than provoking an exchange on b5.} e6 $5 {Preventing ...e5-e6.} (14... Rad8 $6 15. Bg5 Rde8 $6 16. Rad1 Qc5 17. Be3 Qc6 {0-1 Kollars,D (2598)-Mamedyarov,S (2770) Titled Arena Mar 6th blitz 2021} 18. Nb5 $18) (14... Bc6 15. Nb5 Bxb5 16. Qxb5 c6 17. Qe2 Nd5 18. c3 $14 {½-½ Leko,P (2625)-Timman,J (2620) Hoogovens Wijk aan Zee 1996 (7)}) 15. Nb5 Bxb5 16. Qxb5 Qb4 (16... c6 $11) 17. Qe2 {1-0 Hedrera,M-Terblanche,D Afroatin-ch prel-5 corr 1997} Rfd8 {Preventing Bd2.} (17... c5 18. Bd2 $14) 18. Ra3 (18. Bg5 Rd7 $11) 18... Qf8 19. h4 Bh6 20. f4 Rd7 $11 {Black is solid, well regrouped and controls the d-file.}) (14. Nd2 {is less effective than in the similar line above, since the bishop reaches c6 in time.} Bc6 15. Nf3 Qb4 {Threatening to spoil White's kingside structure with ...Bxf3, due to the hanging rook on e1.} 16. Bd2 (16. e6 f5 $132) 16... Bxf3 17. Qd3 $1 (17. gxf3 Qh4 18. Kg2 e6 {is comfortable for Black.}) 17... Qc5 18. Qxf3 e6 $1 {This seems to be the best move order. Black consolidates his position, neutralizing the bishop on b3 and does not hurry to expose his bishop.} (18... Bxe5 {is a bit premature and likely to hand in the initiative to White.} 19. Be3 $1 (19. Qxb7 Bd4 20. Be3 Rad8 $11) 19... Qd6 {In view of the threat Bxb6, Black has to keep his bishop defended.} 20. Rad1 (20. Bh6 Bxb2 21. Bxf8 Rxf8 $44) 20... Qf6 21. Qxb7 Rfd8 22. c3 Bd6 23. Qe4 $14 {0-1 Velez,R (2000)-Pena Gomez,E (2250) CADAP MLP-02/2003 email 2005 with light pressure.}) 19. Qxb7 (19. Rad1 Nd7 $5 20. Qxb7 Nxe5 21. Be3 Qc6 22. Qb5 Rfb8 23. Qe2 Nd7 $11) 19... Bxe5 20. Be3 Qb4 $11 {Black is better regrouped than in the game above. One important nuance is that} 21. Bxb6 {pins the white bishop, allowing} Bxb2 22. Rab1 cxb6 $15) 14... Qh4 15. Nd2 {Now is a better moment for developing the knight.} (15. e6 {once again deserves mentioning.} Bxe6 16. Bxe6 fxe6 17. Nd2 (17. Qxe6+ Rf7 18. Be3 Rd8 19. Nd2 {1-0 Pritchard,O (2208)-Gibbons,R (2361) NZL-ch78 email 2011} Qf6 20. Qxf6 exf6 $11) 17... Qf6 $5 (17... e5 18. Ne4 $44) 18. Nf3 (18. Ne4 Qf5 $11) 18... e5 $5 19. Nxe5 Qe6 20. Nf3 Qxe2 21. Rxe2 Rad8 {Black's control over the d-file and the latent queenside pressure yield him good play, even though White can win a pawn.} 22. Bg5 Rfe8 23. Rxe7 Rxe7 24. Bxe7 Rd3 {With his a4-pawn hanging and facing a threat...Nc4, there is not much White can do to activate his position.} (24... Rd5 $5 25. Bg5 Nc4 26. Rb1 b5 27. b3 Nb6 $44 {with good queenside counterplay.}) 25. Kf1 {This natural move has a hidden drawback.} (25. Bg5 Nc4 26. Rb1 Nb6 $11) (25. Bc5 Nc4 26. Rb1 b6 27. Bd4 Bxd4 28. Nxd4 Kf7 $11) 25... Nc4 26. Ra2 ({The point is that} 26. Rb1 $2 {runs into} Rxf3 $1 27. gxf3 Nd2+ 28. Ke2 Nxb1 $19) 26... Kf7 27. Bg5 Rd1+ 28. Ke2 Rb1 $11) 15... Bc6 16. Nf3 Qh5 {Both sides are close to completing the development and a direct conflict is imminent.} 17. e6 {There seems to be nothing more constructive, since Black was threatening ...Bxf3.} (17. Bd1 $146 {leads to drawish simplifications.} Bxf3 18. Qxf3 Qxf3 19. Bxf3 c6 20. e6 (20. h4 e6 21. Bd1 Rfd8 22. Bc2 Nc4 23. f4 h5 $11) 20... f5 21. Ra3 Bf6 22. Rb3 Nxa4 23. Rxb7 Nc5 24. Rc7 Nd3 25. Rd1 Nxc1 26. Rxc1 Rab8 27. Rc2 Rb3 28. Ra7 Rfb8 29. Rxa5 Rxb2 30. Rxb2 Rxb2 31. Rc5 Rb1+ 32. Kh2 Rf1 $11) 17... f5 18. Ne5 (18. Bf4 Bxf3 19. Qxf3 Qxf3 20. gxf3 {yields White an active position, but the current structure allows Black to build up a fortress.} c5 $1 ({The hesitating} 20... Rac8 {allows White to retain some pressure.} 21. Red1 c5 22. Bd5 Nxd5 23. Rxd5 b6 24. Rd7 Rc6 25. Re1 Bf6 {1-0 Adam,C (2179)-Almarza Mato,C (1977) W-ch WS/M/257 email 2010 Black should still hold, but his position is slightly unpleasant.}) 21. Red1 c4 22. Be3 Ra6 23. Bc2 Be5 24. f4 Bd6 $11) (18. Bd1 {offers Black a tempo for retrieving his coordination.} f4 19. Qc2 Qc5 $11) 18... Qxe2 19. Rxe2 Bd5 20. Bxd5 Nxd5 21. Nd7 Rfd8 {[%cal Gd5f6] In order to maintain chances for an advantage, White should find a way of consolidating his knight. Black intends to exchange it with ...Nf6.} 22. Bg5 (22. Be3 $5 $146 Ra6 $1 (22... Nxe3 {is abstractly a bit premature, but might work, too.} 23. Rxe3 Ra6 {The start of a fluent way of activating the rooks.} 24. Rd1 Rda8 25. g4 {The most constructive plan.} fxg4 26. hxg4 Rc6 27. Re4 Raa6 28. Rde1 Rd6 29. f4 c6 30. f5 Ra8 $1 {Parrying f5-f6.} 31. Kg2 b5 $132) 23. Rd2 ({After} 23. Rd1 Rd6 {White has to spend a tempo on parrying the threat ...Nxc3!} 24. Ree1 Nxe3 25. Rxd6 exd6 26. Rxe3 Re8 27. f4 d5 $11) 23... Nxe3 {Now is the moment to take the bishop.} (23... Rd6 $2 24. Bc5 $16) 24. Nf6+ $1 Bxf6 25. Rxd8+ Kg7 26. fxe3 Rb6 27. Rd2 Rxe6 28. Kf2 h5 29. Rd7 Be5 30. Rad1 Bd6 31. Rd3 b6 $44 {Black has the better structure and a pawn for the exchange. I do not see a way for White to make progress.}) 22... h6 $146 (22... Bf6 {is more passive, but playable anyway.} 23. Be3 (23. Rd2 $5) 23... h5 ({With the bishop hanging, Black cannot play} 23... Ra6 24. Rd2 $16 Nxe3 $2 25. Nxf6+) 24. Rd1 Nxe3 25. Rxe3 Kg7 $11 {½-½ Vanttaja,I (2247)-Aho,J (2397) Nordic Club-chT 2nd email 2007 [4] Black takes advantage of his extra move ...Bf6 with respect to the line above. His position remains very solid.}) 23. c4 (23. Be3 {practically transposes above.}) (23. Rd1 {runs into} Nxc3 24. bxc3 hxg5 {, when White has just reasonable compensation for the pawn.}) 23... Nc3 $5 (23... hxg5 {also works.} 24. cxd5 Ra6 25. Rc1 c6 26. dxc6 Rxc6 27. Rxc6 bxc6 $11) 24. bxc3 hxg5 25. Rb1 b6 26. Re3 Bf6 27. Rb5 Kg7 28. c5 bxc5 29. Rxc5 Rh8 $5 {Planning ...Rh4.} 30. Rxc7 (30. g4 Rh4 31. Rc4 Ra6) 30... Rhc8 $11 {Black retrieves the pawn with a normal position.} *

