{[%evp 0,46,22,9,46,40,40,21,50,21,64,30,30,28,28,30,30,14,-7,-8,10,-3,48,53,45,34,37,24,38,10,8,-3,-36,-46,-37,-23,17,21,21,23,3,8,24,29,1,1,9,-27,-31]} 1. e4 Nf6 2. e5 Nd5 3. d4 d6 4. Nf3 g6 5. Bc4 Nb6 6. Bb3 Bg7 7. O-O O-O 8. h3 a5 9. a4 dxe5 {For those feeling that Black's strive for activity was too "elaborated" in the previous line, this surely is a simpler way of freeing his play.} 10. Nxe5 (10. dxe5 {faces Black with less problems.} Qxd1 11. Rxd1 Nc6 12. Bf4 Be6 {As mentioned in a previous commentary, this is a good moment for provoking this exchange.} 13. Bxe6 fxe6 14. Bg3 Nb4 $11) 10... Nc6 {A direct way of fighting against White's space advantage.} ({In this line, we actually examine two systems, the second one being} 10... Bxe5 $5 11. dxe5 Qxd1 12. Rxd1 Nc6 $146 (12... Be6 {may be premature since after} 13. Bxe6 fxe6 14. Bh6 {the rook cannot go to d8 yet.} Rc8 15. Nd2 Nc6 16. Nf3 $14 {1-0 Seaman,R-Barreras Garcia,A corr 1990 White has reached an optimal regrouping and maintains some pressure.}) 13. Nc3 (13. Bh6 {is answered with} Rd8 14. Rxd8+ Nxd8 15. Nc3 Be6 $11) 13... Be6 14. Bxe6 fxe6 {This is a different situation when provoking the exchange on e6 is justified. Black has exchanged his other bishop for a knight, reaching a position with the thematical fight between a knight and the somewhat restricted dark-squared bishop. In an optimal scenario, this could be a good knight versus a bad bishop, but we are far from it yet.} 15. b3 {The most solid continuation.} (15. Bh6 Rf5 $11) (15. f4 {exposes this pawn.} Nb4 16. Rd2 Rxf4 {wins a pawn at no obvious compensation.}) (15. Ne4 {leaves a4 insufficiently well defended.} Rfd8 16. Bh6 Rxd1+ 17. Rxd1 Nxa4 18. b3 Nb6 19. Nc5 Kf7 20. Nxb7 a4 $11) 15... Nd5 $5 {A sound, though not absolutely necessary pawn sacrifice.} (15... Nxe5 16. Ne4 $14) (15... Rad8 16. Bh6 $14) (15... Rfd8 $5 16. Bb2 Nd5 17. Ne4 Ndb4 $11 {is fine, but abstractly it is a bit disturbing that Black does not have the rooks placed on f8 and d8.}) 16. Nxd5 (16. Ne4 Rf5 17. Bb2 b6 18. Rd2 h6 19. Rad1 g5 20. Nc3 Nxc3 21. Bxc3 Rc8 22. f3 Kg7 23. Kf2 Kg6 $11 {followed by ...h6-h5.}) 16... exd5 17. Rxd5 Rfd8 18. Rd2 Kf7 19. f4 Rxd2 20. Bxd2 Rd8 21. Bc3 Rd5 22. Rc1 Nb4 $44 {The king is ready to control and maybe undermine the enemy centre with the help of the pawns, while the other pieces keep White under pressure on the queenside. Black has entirely adequate compensation for the pawn. By the way, the immediate threat is ...Na2.} 23. Bxb4 (23. Bb2 Rd2 24. Bc3 Rd5 $11) (23. Be1 Rc5 24. c4 Nd3 $11) 23... axb4 24. c3 Rd3 25. cxb4 c6 26. Rc5 (26. Rb1 Rd4 $11) 26... Rxb3 27. b5 cxb5 28. Rxb5 Ra3 29. a5 h5 30. Kf2 Ke6 $11) 11. Nxc6 bxc6 12. c3 (12. Be3 {exposes the bishop to} Nd5 13. Qf3 {1-0 Mussanti,D (2279)-Darcyl,T (2386) ARG-chT Villa Martelli 2018 (7.1)} Nxe3 $1 {Weakening White's dark squares in a moment when he is underdeveloped is more important than clearing the light diagonals.} 14. fxe3 e5 $36 15. Qxc6 (15. Bxf7+ Kh8 {threatening ...Be6} 16. Qxc6 Ra6 17. Qd5 Rd6 18. Qxa5 Qg5 19. Kh2 Bb7 $17) (15. dxe5 Bxe5 16. Nc3 Qe8 $15) 15... Ra6 16. Qc4 exd4 17. Rxf7 Rxf7 18. Qxf7+ Kh8 19. Nd2 Rf6 20. Qd5 Qxd5 21. Bxd5 dxe3 22. Nc4 Rf5 $15) 12... Rb8 {Still preparing one of the central breaks by putting some pressure along the b-file.} (12... e5 {is entirely possible, too.} 13. dxe5 Bxe5 14. Bh6 Qxd1 15. Rxd1 Re8 {White's structure is more compact but Black is a bit more active and the weakness on b2 also counts a bit..} 16. Nd2 Be6 (16... Ba6 $5) 17. Re1 Bxb3 18. Nxb3 Nc4 19. Rab1 Bd6 {Not really necessary at this stage.} (19... Rab8 $5 20. Nd4 Rb6 21. b3 Nd6 $11) (19... f5 20. Nd2 Nb6 21. Ra1 Kf7 22. Kf1 Rab8 $11) 20. Rxe8+ Rxe8 21. Nd2 Nb6 22. Ra1 f6 23. Be3 Kf7 24. Kf1 {½-½ Nielsen,M-Bortolin,B olm13 qual GP3 B5 corr 1998}) 13. Bg5 (13. Nd2 $146 {leaves the bishop on c1 temporarily passive.} c5 14. dxc5 Nd7 15. Ne4 Ne5 (15... Bb7 16. Bc2 Bxe4 17. Bxe4 Nxc5 18. Bc2 Qd6) 16. Bc2 Ba6 17. Re1 Qe8 $44 {Black is very active and has several threats: ...Qc6, ...Rd8 followed by the invasion on d3, ...Nc4.}) 13... c5 $1 $146 {This is the most direct way of achieving counterplay.} (13... Nd5 {embarks a slow positional game, allowing White to consolidate his space advantage.} 14. Nd2 Be6 (14... h6 15. Bh4 c5 16. dxc5 Nf4 $44) 15. Re1 h6 16. Bh4 Nf4 17. Bg3 (17. Bxe6 $14) 17... Bxb3 18. Nxb3 Nxg2 19. Kxg2 (19. Re2 Qd5 20. Nc1 $14 {[%cal Gc3c4]}) 19... Qd5+ 20. Qf3 Qxf3+ 21. Kxf3 Rxb3 $11 {0-1 Rodriguez Vargas,O-Torre,E Olympiad-20 Final B 1972 (13)}) 14. dxc5 Nd7 15. Bc4 (15. Bc2 Nxc5 16. Qxd8 Rxd8 17. Bxe7 Rd5 $44) 15... Ne5 $1 (15... Rxb2 16. Qc1 Rb8 17. Rd1 $14) (15... Nxc5 16. Qxd8 Rxd8 17. Bxe7 $16) 16. Bb5 c6 17. Qxd8 Rxd8 18. Bxe7 Rd7 19. Bd6 Rxd6 20. cxd6 cxb5 21. axb5 Rxb5 22. b4 Nc6 23. bxa5 Nxa5 $13 *

