{[%evp 0,38,26,21,65,65,79,32,32,32,69,26,26,35,35,33,33,1,24,-13,58,45,60,57,37,8,35,28,20,15,56,-2,36,29,37,28,18,14,14,-42,-16]} 1. e4 Nf6 2. e5 Nd5 3. d4 d6 4. Nf3 g6 5. Bc4 Nb6 6. Bb3 Bg7 7. O-O O-O 8. h3 Nc6 9. Qe2 Na5 {For those ready to meet 7.a4 with 7...dxe5 as in Lines 10 and 11, this is a very interesting system. Black does not try to free himself by an early action in the centre. He prefers to exchange the light-squared bishop and rely on his solid structure to create counterplay on the wings. I remember that many years ago, when I experimented a bit with the Alekhine Defence, I had this line in my repertoire even though engines were simply outraged by Black's position. Engines grow smarter and seem to have caught up with the merits of a viable plan since the '80s.} 10. Nc3 (10. Bg5 {runs into} Nxb3 11. axb3 f6 12. Bh4 (12. exf6 exf6 13. Bf4 (13. Be3 {1-0 Pieper,T (2210)-Kindl,P (2335) Oberliga Wuerttemberg 9192 1991} Nd5 $11) 13... Re8 14. Qd2 g5 15. Bg3 {0-1 Firnhaber,I (2303)-Haag,F GER-ch28 V07 corr 1998} h6 16. h4 Bg4 $36) 12... g5 {The typical kingside expansion.} 13. Bg3 Bf5 (13... g4 14. hxg4 Bxg4 15. Nbd2 Qd7 $132) 14. Rd1 Qe8 15. c4 fxe5 16. dxe5 Qh5 17. Nbd2 Nd7 18. Re1 a5 19. Ne4 h6 $11 {0-1 Kramer,J (2387)-Bortnyk,O (2552) Staufer op-A 28th 2016 (6)}) (10. Re1 {does not make much of a difference with respect to the main line.} Nxb3 (10... dxe5 11. dxe5 c5 {is also possible, forcing White to spend a tempo on inducing the exchange on b3.} 12. Bd2 Nxb3 13. axb3 Nd5 14. Na3 Nc7 {Here are the merits of ...c7-c5. The knight will soon reach the perfect blocking square on e6.} 15. Rad1 Ne6 $11 {Possibly followed by ...b7-b6 and ...Bb7, with a harmonious position.}) 11. axb3 Nd5 12. c4 (12. Bd2 c6 13. c4 Nc7 14. Nc3 dxe5 15. dxe5 Ne6 16. Rad1 Qc7 $11 {[%cal Gb7b6,Gc8b7] followed by ...b7-b6.}) 12... Nb4 13. Na3 (13. Nc3 Bf5 $132) 13... dxe5 14. dxe5 Qd3 15. Bd2 Qxe2 16. Rxe2 Na6 17. b4 Rd8 18. Bc3 c6 19. Rae1 Nc7 20. Kh2 Ne6 21. g3 b6 22. Rd2 Bb7 $11 {½-½ Bores,R (2270)-Reznicek,T (2285) CZE-chT2 9697 1996}) 10... Nxb3 11. axb3 {Almost developing the rook on a1. In the future, Black might have to spend a tempo on ...a7-a6 or ...a7-a5.} Bf5 {Black keeps developing and invites White to show his cards.} 12. Bf4 (12. Rd1 {is meant to inhibit ...dxe5, but does not make part of a global plan..} a6 (12... a5 $5) 13. Ne4 Bxe4 14. Qxe4 dxe5 {Suddenly, the d-pawn is pinned.} 15. Nxe5 Qd5 16. Qe1 Nd7 17. Bf4 (17. Ra5 Qe6 $11 18. Bf4 b6) 17... Nxe5 18. dxe5 Qe6 19. Rd2 Rfd8 20. Rad1 Rxd2 21. Rxd2 f6 22. Rd3 a5 23. Re3 f5 24. Bg3 (24. Qd2 a4 25. b4 c6 26. h4 Qa2 $132) 24... Qb6 25. f4 c6 26. Kh2 Rd8 27. Re2 Qb4 28. Qxb4 {½-½ Boehnke,H (2325)-Rain,R (2251) W-Cup21 WS24 email 2015}) (12. Re1 {looks more natural, of course} a5 13. Bf4 (13. Ne4 dxe5 14. dxe5 a4 $11) 13... h6 {Preparing the kingside expansion.} (13... c6 {is a bit passive} 14. g4 Bc8 15. Qe3 $14 {1-0 Hameister,R (2407)-Rain,R (2251) W-Cup21 WS24 email 2015}) 14. d5 (14. Bh2 {is likely to cause some problems along the back rank if the position opens.} g5 15. Ra3 c6 16. Rea1 dxe5 17. dxe5 Nd5 18. Nxd5 Qxd5 19. b4 a4 20. Rxa4 Rxa4 21. Rxa4 Qb5 $5 22. Qxb5 cxb5 23. Ra7 Rd8 $44) (14. Bg3 {avoids the problem mentioned above, but exposes the bishop in the long run.} g5 15. Ra3 Bg6 16. Rea1 f5 $1 17. exf6 exf6 18. Rxa5 Rxa5 19. Rxa5 Re8 20. Qd2 f5 $15) (14. g4 Bd7 15. Qe3 {runs into} g5 16. Bg3 f5 $36) (14. h4 Bg4 $11) 14... g5 15. Bg3 Nd7 16. h4 Bg4 $11) 12... h6 13. Rfe1 (13. g4 Bd7 {does not improve White's position.}) 13... g5 14. Bg3 Bg6 15. h4 (15. d5 Bh5 16. Qe3 dxe5 17. Bxe5 f6 18. Bg3 Nxd5 19. Nxd5 Qxd5 20. Qxe7 Rf7 $11) 15... g4 16. Nd2 Qd7 17. Nc4 h5 18. exd6 exd6 19. Nxb6 axb6 $11 {½-½ Daanen,A (2154)-Wernikiewicz,Z (2289) RA-2018-0-00567} *

