1. e4 Nf6 2. e5 Nd5 3. d4 d6 4. Nf3 Bg4 {This is the other classical main line apart from 4...g6. It suits players with static style well, or those who wish to slow down the impetu of a dynamic or aggressive opponent. Even though there is nothing wrong with 4...g6, there are a few reasons why I could not ignore 4...Bg4. As mentioned in the introduction, this is aimed to be more than just an opening database. I wanted to develop a whole strategy course, with all the needed dynamic and tactical nuances. Such a discourse could not be complete without this solid system. Secondly, Fischer used it once in his match with Spassky, which speaks about the merits of the line. Finally, during the evening analysis mentioned in the introduction, this was one of the systems in which I could remember several important nuances and prove it playable to my wife and friends. As a general evaluation, Black's position in the critical Lines 29 to 32 looks cramped and difficult. However, if Black knows what he is doing, he can hold his own. As said, it is a matter of taste. And even if you will only play 4...g6 in tournament games, studying 4...Bg4 will enrich you strategically. For space reasons, I have examined only the critical lines in detail, offering an orinettaive coverage in the variations where everything has been fine for Black for decades, according to the official opinion.} 5. Be2 (5. h3 {is premature.} Bxf3 (5... Bh5 {may transpose to the main lines below if White normally develops, while} 6. g4 Bg6 7. e6 fxe6 8. Ng5 {yields him only some compensation for the pawn.} Qd7 9. Qe2 Nc6 10. Nxe6 Bf7 $15 {½-½ Crisan,I-Kertesz,A ROM-ch Semifinal 1982 (5)}) 6. Qxf3 dxe5 7. dxe5 e6 {Black has reached a comfortable position.} 8. Bc4 (8. c4 $2 Nb4 9. Qxb7 $2 N8c6 10. Qb5 Nc2+ 11. Ke2 N2d4+ {0-1 St Martin,S-Bacon,J APCT corr USA 1992}) (8. a3 Nd7 9. c4 Ne7 10. Qxb7 Rb8 11. Qxa7 {0-1 Alvarez Castillo,H (2216)-Llanos,G (2398) American Continental 02nd 2003 (3)} Nf5 $36 {[%cal Gd8h4,Gf8c5] Planning ...Qh4, ...Bc5 with a dangerous attack.} 12. b4 $2 Bc5 13. bxc5 Nd4 14. Qa4 Nb3 $17) 8... Nc6 9. Qe4 Qd7 $146 10. O-O O-O-O 11. Re1 (11. Nd2 f5 $1 12. exf6 gxf6 13. Re1 e5 $11) 11... h5 12. Nd2 g5 13. Nf3 g4 14. hxg4 hxg4 15. Qxg4 Be7 16. Bd2 Rdg8 17. Qe4 Bc5 18. Rad1 Rh5 $44 {with a promising attack for the pawn.}) (5. Bc4 {is a blow in the wind.} e6 ({Only not} 5... Nb6 $2 6. Bxf7+ Kxf7 7. Ng5+ {wins.}) 6. O-O Nb6 7. Bb3 (7. Be2 Nc6 8. exd6 cxd6 $11) 7... dxe5 8. h3 $5 $146 (8. dxe5 Qxd1 9. Rxd1 Nc6 $15 10. Bf4 Bxf3 11. gxf3 g5 12. Bg3 Bg7 13. Re1 O-O-O 14. Nc3 h5 15. h3 {½-½ Hegedus,R (2108)-Pereszlenyi,G (2055) SVK-chT2B 0809 2008 (4.4)} h4 16. Bh2 Nd7 $17) 8... Bxf3 9. Qxf3 exd4 10. Qxb7 c5 11. a4 (11. Ba4+ N8d7) 11... Qd7 12. Qxd7+ Kxd7 13. a5 Nd5 14. Nd2 Nc6 $15) 5... e6 6. O-O {The move order at this stage is not so important.} (6. c4 Nb6 7. O-O {is another possible way of reaching the main tabyia.}) 6... Be7 7. c4 Nb6 8. Nc3 O-O {A first important moment.} 9. h3 $1 {Only this move allows White to maintain some pressure. But in chess (as in life) there rarely is such a thing as "the perfect move order". As we will see, at a later stage, this move will restrict White's possibilities.} ({The immediate} 9. Be3 {allows} Nc6 $1 ({In fact, Black is forced to use this nuance. Here is what can happen if he follows the same pattern as in the main line:} 9... d5 10. c5 Bxf3 11. gxf3 Nc8 ({It is worth mentioning that the first game featuring the plan based on ...d6-d5, went} 11... N6d7 {I will mention this idea with a few more details in the comments to Line 30. In this setup, the omission of h2-h3 is not relevant, as far as I can understand.} 12. b4 f6 $6 13. f4 f5 $6 {0-1 Gaprindashvili,N-Kushnir,A World Women-ch 1969 (4) with a solid, but passive position for Black.}) 12. f4 g6 13. Bd3 Bh4 14. Qg4 f5 15. exf6 Qxf6 16. Kg2 $3 {The threat Kh3 is decisive. In the main line, the white pawn is on h3, preventing this plan.} Qe7 17. Kh3 Bf6 18. f5 exf5 19. Bxf5 $18) 10. exd6 (10. b3 dxe5 11. Nxe5 Bxe2 12. Nxe2 Nxe5 13. dxe5 Nd7 14. f4 Bc5 $11) 10... cxd6 11. d5 (11. b3 d5 {leads to similar play as in the classical line of the 4...g6 system.} 12. c5 Nc8 13. b4 a6 14. Rb1 Bf6 15. a4 N8e7 $13 {Instead of ...g7-g6 and ...Bg7, Black has played ...Be7-f6. The tempi are even and the positions are similar.}) 11... exd5 12. Nxd5 Nxd5 13. Qxd5 {A first aspect is that the bishop is not hanging (as it would do on h5). Secondly, it can return to e6 to unblock the centre.} Be6 (13... Bf6 $11) 14. Qd2 (14. Qb5 Bf6 {[%cal Gd8e7]} 15. Qxb7 Bd7 $11 {followed by ...Rb8.}) 14... d5 15. c5 a5 $5 $11) 9... Bh5 (9... Bxf3 {can be answered with} 10. Bxf3 {The pawn on c4 is not really hanging, because of the threat Bxb7.}) 10. Be3 {The most consistent continuation. Unlike i the 4...g6 classical system, WHite usually maintains the central tension.} (10. exd6 cxd6 {frees Black's play a bit.} 11. Bf4 (11. Be3 d5 12. c5 Bxf3 13. Bxf3 Nc4 14. Bf4 Nc6 15. b3 N4a5 16. Rc1 b6 $11) 11... Nc6 (11... a6 $5 12. b3 d5 13. c5 N6d7 14. b4 Nc6) 12. d5 exd5 13. Nxd5 Bf6 $5 $11 {with active play.}) 10... d5 {This is the most reliable continuation. It was introduced by Alburt in his game against Katalymov in 1972 and has been considered Black's main chance for reaching a viable position ever since.} (10... Nc6 {runs into} 11. exd6 cxd6 12. d5 exd5 ({The oldest game ever with this line went} 12... Bxf3 13. Bxf3 Ne5 {Exchanging on e6 followed by Bg4 is probably simplest now, but the game continuation is not bad, either.} 14. b3 Nxf3+ 15. Qxf3 e5 16. Qe2 f5 17. f4 $14 {0-1 Grodner,C-Plante,J Paris-ch 1953 (6)}) 13. Nxd5 Nxd5 14. Qxd5 {The bishop is not only hanging, but also far from e6, allowing White to retain a stable plus.} Bg6 15. Rad1 $14) (10... dxe5 {is answered with} 11. Nxe5 Bxe2 12. Qxe2 N8d7 13. Rad1 $14 {With better development and more space to White.}) 11. cxd5 {White tries to use the relative weakness of the black queenside, a direct consequence of the bishop's early departure to the opposite wing.} ({The main continuation} 11. c5 {is examined in Lines 29 to 32.}) 11... Nxd5 12. Qb3 {The only consequenc continuation.} Nc6 $5 {Black continues his development, ingoring the threat on b7.} (12... Nxe3 13. fxe3 Nd7 {is also playable.} 14. Qxb7 Rb8 15. Qxa7 Rxb2 {White's centre is vulnerable and his queen is misplaced. This ensures Black reasonable compensation for the pawn.} 16. Qa6 (16. Rab1 Rc2 17. Rfc1 Rxc1+ 18. Rxc1 {1-0 Gurevich,D (2425)-Tomaszewski,R (2385) WchT U26 03rd 1981 (8)} Nb6 19. Qb7 Bg6 20. e4 Qa8 $44) 16... Bg6 17. e4 Qa8 (17... Rb6 18. Qd3 Qb8 $44) (17... Nb6 18. Rab1 Rb4 {Planning ...c7-c5.} 19. Rfd1 Qa8 20. Qxa8 Rxa8 $44) 18. Qxa8 Rxa8 19. Bb5 Nb8 $1 {After the king's rook has reached the queenside, this apparently passive retreat does not spoil Black's coordination. Its idea is depriving the white bishop of its stability on the queenside, by controllingc6.} (19... Nb6 20. a4 Bb4 21. Nd1 Rb3 {1-0 Salai,L (2440)-Smejkal,L (2125) CZE-chT 9798 1997 (9)} 22. Bc6 Ra5 23. Nf2 $14) 20. a4 c6 {The point.} 21. Bc4 {Trying to defend the important light squares against the rook's intrusion.} (21. Bd3 Rb3 22. Rfc1 Bb4 23. Na2 Ba5 24. Bc4 Re3 25. d5 Bxe4 26. dxe6 fxe6 27. Bxe6+ Kf8 $13) 21... Rb4 22. Ba2 (22. Be2 Rb3 23. Rfc1 Bb4 $11) 22... Nd7 $44 23. d5 cxd5 24. exd5 exd5 25. Nxd5 Bc5+ 26. Kh1 Rbxa4 $11) 13. Qxb7 {The critical continuation.} (13. Nxd5 Qxd5 14. Qxd5 (14. Qxb7 $2 Nxd4 $1 $17 15. Qxd5 $2 Nxe2+ 16. Kh2 exd5 $19) (14. Bc4 Qd7 {½-½ Golubev,M (2492)-Reshetkov,K (2146) Odessa Geller-85 Clock sim 2010 (1)} 15. Qxb7 Rab8 16. Qa6 Bxf3 17. gxf3 Rb6 18. Qa4 Rb4 19. Qc2 Nxd4 $17) 14... exd5 15. Rac1 a6 (15... f6 16. Ba6 $5) 16. Rfd1 {1-0 Jacobs,R (2373)-De Meye,J (2138) RCCA-ch 20 sf13 email 2014} f5 $11 {Black does not have any special problems.}) 13... Nxe3 14. fxe3 Nb4 {[%cal Gc7c6,Ga8b8,Gb8a8] We have reached a familiar picture. White's centre is exposed and the queen vulnerable, while Black has made important progresses with his development. One of the threats is ...c7-c6 followed by the perpetual attack against the queen with ...Rb8-a8.} 15. Qe4 c6 {Preparing ...Nd5.} (15... Rb8 $5 16. Rad1 Bg6 17. Qf4 c5 {This break usually yields Black ample compensation for the pawn.} 18. Rd2 cxd4 19. Nxd4 (19. exd4 Nc2 20. Rb1 Rb4 $44) 19... Bg5 20. Qg3 Bh6 21. Rfd1 Qb6 22. Bc4 Rbd8 23. Kh2 Bh5 24. Be2 Bg6 25. a3 Nd5 26. Nxd5 Rxd5 $44 {½-½ De Homont,R (2062)-Petrigin,O W-ch WS/H/365 email 2012}) 16. Rad1 Bg6 17. Qf4 Nd5 18. Nxd5 Qxd5 $146 {The most logical. Black not only keeps the possibility of breaking with ...c6-c5, but also creates immediate queenside threats.} (18... cxd5 {is less principled, but also playable. Because the white queen is isolated on the kingside, Black can set up pressure against the queenside.} 19. Bd3 Bxd3 20. Rxd3 Qa5 21. a3 Qb5 22. Rd2 Rac8 23. Ne1 a5 $44 {½-½ Bernal Varela,N (2127)-Wosch,A (2205) FICGS rapid silver 000038 email 2011 (2)}) 19. b3 (19. a3 Qa2 20. Rd2 Rab8 $15) (19. Ra1 c5 $44) 19... Qa5 20. Rd2 (20. Ra1 c5 $44) (20. a4 Rab8 21. Nd2 Bc2 $11) 20... Bb4 {Black retrieves the pawn with excellent play.} *

