{[%evp 0,48,20,9,63,63,63,46,46,46,64,63,56,55,56,55,53,24,54,35,65,47,47,49,49,35,40,48,48,41,41,48,50,30,77,52,81,50,27,22,88,57,13,9,9,-23,2,-30,16,32,24]} 1. e4 Nf6 2. e5 Nd5 3. d4 d6 4. Nf3 Bg4 5. Be2 e6 6. O-O Be7 7. c4 Nb6 8. Nc3 O-O 9. h3 Bh5 10. Be3 d5 11. c5 {The by far most popular continuation and rightly considered to be the main line. White simply gains a lot of space, leaving it up to Black to devise a regrouping plan.} Bxf3 {Now is a good moment for this exchange. White must choose between keeping his structure intact and maintaining the control on c4.} 12. Bxf3 {While this is natural, it allows Black to start his usual queenside counterplay.} (12. gxf3 {is examined in Lines 30 to 32.}) 12... Nc4 13. Bf4 {The most active.} (13. b3 {was famously played during the Fischer-Spassky 1972 match. I would like to highlight a curious fact. As mentioned in the previous line, the first game where Black played 10...d5 was Katalymov-Alburt, 1972 (I will insert it in the next line). I checked the dates and discovered that Alburt's game took place 17 days before the Spassky-Fischer game! I cannot know whether Fischer continued to receive and read the Soviet chess magazines during the match, but for a game to be published and the magazine sent, 17 days look a bit tight for those times. It is more probable that he knew the 1969 Gaprindashvili-Kushnir game mentioned in Line 28. Whether he spotted the differences between the positions with and without h2-h3, remains a pure speculation. We can only guess where he would have retreated with the knight to after 12.gxf3.} Nxe3 14. fxe3 {White has parted with the bishops' pair, but strengthened his centre. He will soon break with e3-e4. Quite typical for Spassky's style.} b6 {Also typical for Fischer's straightforward style!} (14... Nc6 {is more restrained, but equally good.} 15. Rb1 Bg5 16. Qe2 Ne7 17. Bg4 Ng6 18. b4 b6 $11 {1-0 (34) Mustonen,I-Nikkarinen,J Finland 1993}) 15. e4 c6 16. b4 {I would prefer} a5 $1 (16... bxc5 17. bxc5 Qa5 $6 (17... Nd7 $5 18. exd5 exd5 19. Bg4 Bg5 20. Qd3 g6 $11 {with just a symbolic advantage to White.}) 18. Nxd5 $5 (18. Qe1 $5 Qc7 19. Kh1 $14) 18... Bg5 $1 19. Bh5 cxd5 20. Bxf7+ Rxf7 21. Rxf7 Qd2 22. Qxd2 Bxd2 23. Raf1 Nc6 $11 {½-½ Spassky,B-Fischer,R (2785) World-ch27 Fischer-Spassky +7-3=11 1972 (19)}) 17. a3 b5 $5 {Black plans ...Na6-c7, bringing the knight closer to the important d5- and e6-squares.} 18. exd5 exd5 $11 {makes the latter square more relevant.}) (13. Bc1 {is unnecessarily passive, since the pawn on b2 was not really hanging.} b6 14. b3 Na5 15. b4 Nc4 16. Rb1 a5 17. a3 axb4 18. axb4 bxc5 19. bxc5 Nc6 20. Re1 Qd7 21. Bg4 Rfb8 $11 {0-1 Petrushin,A (2355)-Alburt,L (2510) URS-ch46 Semifinal 1978}) 13... b6 (13... Nxb2 14. Qb3 Nc4 15. Qxb7 $16) 14. b3 Na5 15. b4 {This usually looks like a concession, but with the actual pieces placement, White has some concrete ideas.} (15. Rc1 bxc5 16. dxc5 Nac6 17. Re1 a5 18. Nb5 Na6 19. Be2 Bg5 20. Bxg5 Qxg5 21. Nd4 {1-0 (41) Tseitlin,M (2200)-Fainberg,M (2200) Tbilisi 1973 MCD [ChessBase II]} Nxd4 22. Qxd4 Nb4 $11) (15. Na4 bxc5 16. Nxc5 Nd7 (16... Bxc5 17. dxc5 Nac6 18. Re1 Nd7 19. Rc1 a5 20. Qd2 Rb8 $11 {1-0 Gufeld,E-Gurgenidze,B Goglidze Memorial 1974 (12)}) 17. Nxd7 Qxd7 18. Be3 Nb7 19. Qc2 Rfc8 $11) 15... Nc4 16. Rc1 {Suddenly, Black needs to count with the threat Nxd5 followed by Rxc4.} (16. Be2 Nc6 17. b5 N6a5 18. c6 Ba3 $11 {[%cal Ga7a6]}) 16... c6 $1 {An important consolidating move.} (16... a5 17. Nxd5 exd5 18. Rxc4 dxc4 19. Bxa8 axb4 20. cxb6 {[%cal Gd4d5]} c6 21. d5 Qxb6 22. d6 $14) 17. Be2 (17. a4 Na6 18. Rb1 bxc5 19. dxc5 (19. bxc5 Qa5 $11) 19... Rb8 20. Na2 Bg5 $132) 17... b5 {Black seems to have consolidated, but White can still fight for the initiative.} (17... a5 {runs into} 18. b5 $1 (18. bxa5 b5 19. a4 {was also played, but it transposes to our main line.}) 18... bxc5 19. dxc5 Bxc5 20. Bxc4 dxc4 21. Qg4 $14) 18. a4 (18. Bxc4 dxc4 19. Qf3 ({The game quoted below went} 19. a4 a5 {transposing.}) 19... a5 $5 20. Nxb5 axb4 21. Nd6 c3 22. Rb1 Qa5 $13 {The knight on d6 looks impressive, but it does not create any threats. AT the same time, Black has an advantage on the queenside.}) 18... a5 $1 $146 {In this position, a novelty, even though we will transpose to the game mentioned above.} (18... a6 19. Ra1 $14 {yields White some pressure 1-0 (45) Kozlov,V (2460)-Marantz,M Moscow 1974}) 19. bxa5 $146 {The most consistent.} (19. Bxc4 dxc4 {takes us back to the game we have been talking about.} 20. bxa5 b4 (20... Qxa5 $5 21. axb5 cxb5 22. Ne4 Nc6 23. Nd6 Qa4 24. Qg4 h5 25. Qxh5 Nxd4 $13) 21. Na2 (21. Ne2 c3 $17) 21... b3 22. Nb4 Qxa5 23. Rxc4 Qxa4 24. Qd3 Qb5 25. Rb1 Ra4 26. Qxb3 Na6 {White has won a pawn, but will not be able to free himself from the double pin until the end of the game.} 27. Bd2 (27. Nxc6 $5 {was a possible try, not yielding White an advantage, though.} Qxb3 28. Nxe7+ Kh8 29. Rxb3 Rxc4 30. Be3 Nb4 $11) 27... Rd8 28. Qc2 h6 29. Be1 Ra8 30. Qe2 Rd8 31. Kf1 Bf8 32. h4 h5 33. Rb3 g6 34. g3 Ra1 35. Qd3 Ra4 36. Kg2 Bh6 {½-½ Kratochvil,J (2201)-Greig,S (2099) WS TT/4/15/fin email 2017 White cannot free himself from the pins and the position can be described as a positinal draw.}) 19... b4 $1 $146 {The third novelty in this line, apparently a paradox. The explanation is that the whole variation is highly transpositional.} (19... Rxa5 {was played in the game mentioned in the comments to Black's 17th move.} 20. axb5 cxb5 21. Rb1 Qd7 22. Bd3 $14 b4 23. Rxb4 Nc6 24. Ra4 Rxa4 (24... Nb2 25. Bxh7+ Kxh7 26. Qb1+ $18) 25. Qxa4 Nb2 26. Qc2 Nxd3 27. Qxd3 Rb8 28. Be3 Rb4 29. Rb1 Rc4 30. Ne2 $14 {½-½ Kaunonen,K-Jensen,I FIN-DEN corr 1985 White could not break Black's fortress, but going for this position with a pawn down does not make much sense.}) 20. Nb1 (20. Na2 Qxa5 21. Bxc4 dxc4 22. Rxc4 Qxa4 23. Nxb4 (23. Qxa4 Rxa4 24. Nxb4 Na6 25. Rb1 Rb8 26. Bd2 f6 $5 {with a similar situation as below.}) 23... Qb5 24. Qc2 Ra4 25. Rb1 Na6 26. Bd2 Rb8 $11 {We have reached a familiar situation, in which White cannot free himself from the double pin.}) 20... Qxa5 21. Nd2 Na3 22. Bd3 Nd7 {Just dveeloping, since the pawn on a4 can wait..} (22... Qxa4 23. Qg4 {yields White certain initiative, but seems to be playable nevertheless. Objectively, it may be less good than the main line, but I have analyzed it in some detail to highlight typical aspects of the fight against White's centre.} g6 24. Bh6 Nd7 $1 {Better late than never!} (24... Re8 25. f4 $16 {with a very strong attack.}) 25. Bxf8 (25. f4 {does not work so well now.} b3 26. f5 exf5 27. Bxf5 Nxe5 $1 {This is the difference!} 28. dxe5 Qxg4 29. Bxg4 b2 {White's attack has ended right after starting and his structure is in ruins. True, he has an extra piece, but this suffices only for maintaining approximate equality.} 30. Rcd1 (30. Rc3 Rfb8 31. e6 f6 $15) 30... Bxc5+ 31. Kh1 Nc2 $5 $13) 25... Rxf8 {The rook prepares for the later break with ...f7-f6. White must do something about the threat ...b4-b3 now.} 26. Qd1 (26. Ra1 b3 27. Nb1 {Black will soon be a rook down, but all White's central pawns are vulnerable now.} h5 28. Qf4 (28. Qg3 Qxd4 29. Rxa3 Nxc5 {Black's three connected pawns, White's lack of coordination and weak pawn on e5 ensure Black enough compensation for the rook.} 30. Bxg6 $5 h4 $1 31. Qe3 Qxe3 32. Bxf7+ Rxf7 33. fxe3 Bg5 $13) 28... Bxc5 29. Qh6 Qxd4 30. Bxg6 fxg6 31. Qxg6+ Kh8 $11 {with a draw by perpetual.}) 26... Qxd1 27. Rcxd1 (27. Rfxd1 f6 $44 28. f4 fxe5 29. fxe5 Bg5 $15) 27... Bxc5 28. dxc5 Nxc5 29. Be2 Na4) 23. Qg4 Kh8 24. Ra1 Rfb8 $13 *

