{[%evp 0,46,17,15,43,57,37,43,39,65,59,61,57,34,57,61,61,60,61,51,65,32,41,62,59,40,102,53,81,51,45,22,31,33,25,32,35,15,21,11,16,20,14,-21,0,-6,67,0,0]} 1. e4 Nf6 2. e5 Nd5 3. d4 d6 4. Nf3 Bg4 5. Be2 e6 6. O-O Be7 7. c4 Nb6 8. Nc3 O-O 9. h3 Bh5 10. Be3 d5 11. c5 Bxf3 12. gxf3 Nc8 {This may seem to be the most passive move. In fact, Black has a clear trajectory for his knight in mind. If allowed, he will play ...Bh4 followed by ...Ne7-f5, solving all the problems. In this position, engines tend to be over optimistic from White's point of view. The consider White's bishops' pair and space advantage to be slightly more important than they really are and change their mind only in the later phase of the fight.} (12... Nc4 $2 {loses a pawn without any compensation.} 13. Bxc4 dxc4 14. Qa4 f6 15. Qxc4 fxe5 16. Qxe6+ Kh8 17. dxe5 Rxf3 18. Kg2 Qf8 19. b4 Nc6 20. b5 Nd8 21. Qd5 $16 {1-0 Kovalev,V (2648)-Markzon,G (2069) PNWCC Online Masters WOO rapid 2020 (1.14)}) (12... N6d7 {is known for a long time. Kushnir was the first to play like this with the pawn on h2. With the insertion of h2-h3, the line was played for the first time a bit later. However, this move never seems to be popular. My explanation is that, the same as Kushnir, all the players with black blocked the kingside quickly with ...f7-f5, leaving Black in a passive, though solid, position. In more recent years, there has been some activity in correspondence chess, making the line look playable. Here are a few possibilities.} 13. f4 (13. b4 a6 14. f4 Nc6 {does not make much of a difference.} 15. Kh2 Kh8 {The start of an effective global regrouping.} 16. Rg1 Rg8 17. Rb1 g6 18. a4 Bf8 {Clearing the e7-square just in time.} 19. b5 axb5 20. axb5 Ne7 21. Ra1 Rxa1 22. Qxa1 Nf5 23. Bg4 Bh6 $11 {½-½ Novosad,M (1924)-Arnold,G (2226) W-Cup18 WS36 email 2011 Black has completed his regrouping and has little to fear. Now is the first moment we notice that White's optically impressive queenside attack is ineffective.}) 13... Nc6 ({As mentioned,} 13... f5 {1-0 Arias,R-Colombo Berra,F CADAP zt5 sf corr 1976 is passive. This is how most over-the-board games continued, the first of them being}) 14. Bb5 (14. b4 a6 {transposes above.}) (14. f5 $6 {runs into} Ndxe5 15. dxe5 d4 $15 16. f6 {1-0 Adoue,C-Fragola,H LADAC corr Argentina 1992} gxf6 17. Bh6 dxc3 18. Bxf8 Qxf8 $15) 14... Ndb8 (14... Bh4 15. Bxc6 bxc6 16. Qa4 Nb8 17. b4 f5 18. Kh2 Qc8 $11) 15. Qa4 f6 16. Be2 Qe8 17. Kh2 Kh8 18. b4 fxe5 19. fxe5 Bh4 20. f4 Nd7 21. Qd1 Ne7 22. Bg4 Nf5 $11 {0-1 Szalay Ocsak,B (2092)-Kahn,E (2193) Budapest FS12 Nadassy 2020 (4.5) The line looks entirely playable, but since there is not enough practice yet, I have examined in more detail the classical main variation with ...Nc8.}) 13. f4 {The by far most popular continuation. White creates the positional threat f4-f5.} ({As we know, the queenside pawn attack is not threatening, at least not immediately.} 13. b4 Bh4 14. b5 ({A recent online blitz game ilustrates Black's regrouping possibilities:} 14. f4 Ne7 15. Bd3 Nf5 16. Bxf5 exf5 17. b5 c6 18. a4 Nd7 19. Rb1 Re8 20. Qd3 g6 21. Na2 Nf8 22. bxc6 bxc6 23. Qa6 Qc8 24. Qxc8 Rexc8 25. Rb7 Ne6 26. Nc3 Bd8 27. Rfb1 Kf8 28. Kf1 Ke8 29. Ke2 Bc7 30. Kd3 Rcb8 $11 {0-1 Galkin,A (2600)-Socko,B (2630) ACP Blitz Playchess.com INT 2006 (4)}) 14... Ne7 15. Bd3 {1-0 Devocelle,L-Houillon,B FRA corr France 1985} a6 (15... g6 {is a bit more passive.} 16. Bh6 Re8 17. a4 Kh8 18. Qd2 Nf5 19. Bxf5 gxf5 20. Kh2 Rg8 21. Ne2 a6 22. Rg1 Rg6 {with a solid position.}) 16. a4 axb5 17. axb5 Rxa1 18. Qxa1 Nd7 19. Ne2 {Anticipating ...f7-f6 and preventing a typical psueod-sacrifice.} (19. Qa7 $2 {allows} Nxe5 20. dxe5 d4 $15) 19... Re8 {Clearing the f8-square for the knight.} 20. Qa7 Qc8 21. Ra1 Nf8 22. f4 Nfg6 23. Kh2 Rf8 $11 {preparing ...f7-f6.}) ({The first game in which Black played this system went} 13. Kh2 Bh4 (13... Nc6 $5) 14. f4 Ne7 {Black successfully completed the first part of his regrouping.} 15. Bd3 g6 16. Rg1 Kh8 17. Qf3 Nbc6 18. Rac1 f6 19. Qe2 fxe5 20. fxe5 Nf5 21. Bxf5 Rxf5 22. Rg4 Qe7 23. f4 Raf8 24. Qd3 Nd8 25. Ne2 c6 26. Ng1 Nf7 27. Nf3 Rh5 28. Rcg1 Nh6 29. Kg2 Qd8 30. Kf1 Nf5 $15 {0-1 Katalymov,B-Alburt,L URS-ch40 Semifinal 1972}) 13... Bh4 14. f5 (14. Bd3 {is examined in Lines 31 and 32.}) 14... Ne7 15. Bd3 {A positional pawn sacrifice.} (15. fxe6 fxe6 16. Bd3 Nf5 17. Qg4 Nc6 18. Kh1 Nce7 $11 {0-1 Toth,G-Fekete,A HUN-ch07 B01 corr 1998}) 15... Nxf5 16. Bxf5 exf5 {White has managed to weaken the defence of the d5-pawn.} 17. Qf3 (17. Qb3 Nc6 {[%cal Gc6e7,Rf5f4] Threatening ...f5-f4 and getting ready for defending the pawn with ...Ne7.} 18. f4 (18. Qxd5 f4 19. Bxf4 Qxd5 20. Nxd5 Nxd4 21. Rad1 Ne6 $11) (18. Qxb7 Qd7 19. Qb3 f4 20. Bxf4 Qxh3 $15) 18... Ne7 19. Qxb7 Rb8 $11) 17... Nc6 $5 $146 {The most active defence, based on hidden dynamic nuances.} (17... c6 {is only apparently passive.} 18. Qxf5 Na6 19. Ne2 Nc7 {The knight is on a good path, ready to control the light squares.} 20. Kh2 f6 21. Qg4 (21. e6 g6 22. Rg1 Kh8 23. Rxg6 hxg6 24. Qxg6 Qe7 25. Bh6 Qh7 26. Nf4 Rg8 27. Rg1 Rxg6 28. Nxg6+ Qxg6 29. Rxg6 Rg8 $19 {0-1 (29) Folk,P (2295)-Smejkal,L Czech Republic 1995}) 21... f5 22. Qh5 Qe7 23. Rg1 (23. Nf4 Bg5 24. Nxd5 Nxd5 25. Bxg5 Qf7 $11) (23. Rad1 Rae8 24. Rd2 Ne6 25. Nf4 Qg5 26. Qf3 Qh6 27. Nxe6 Qxe6 28. Bf4 g5 $11 29. Bxg5 $2 Bxg5 30. Rg1 Qg6 31. h4 Bxd2 32. Rxg6+ hxg6 $19) 23... f4 $1 24. Nxf4 Bxf2 $1 $11) 18. Nxd5 (18. Qxf5 {allows Black to organize a blockade on light squares.} g6 19. Qf3 (19. Qg4 {prevents ...Ne7 but runs into} f5 20. exf6 Bxf6 $11) 19... Ne7 $11) 18... Qd7 19. Rad1 Rad8 {White's position is by far less stable in the centre than it looks.} 20. Nf4 (20. Nf6+ {does not yield more than equality.} gxf6 21. Qh5 Bg5 (21... fxe5 22. Qxh4 f6 23. dxe5 Qxd1 24. Rxd1 Rxd1+ 25. Kg2 Nxe5 $13) 22. Bxg5 fxg5 23. Qxg5+ Kh8 24. Qf6+ Kg8 25. Kh2 Ne7 26. h4 Qe6 $11 27. Rg1+ Ng6 28. Qxe6 fxe6 29. h5 Kf7 $11) (20. Nc3 g5 $1 {followed by ...f5-f4 offers Black good counterplay.}) 20... Bg5 {Threatening to exchange the knight and organize a perfect blockade.} 21. Nh5 (21. Kh2 Bxf4+ 22. Qxf4 (22. Bxf4 Nxd4 $15) 22... Ne7 $11) 21... f4 $1 22. Bxf4 (22. Nxf4 Bxf4 23. Qxf4 Qxh3 24. d5 Ne7 25. d6 Nf5 $15) 22... Bxf4 23. Qxf4 Nxd4 $11 *

