{[%evp 0,54,17,23,43,37,65,65,65,36,61,52,61,49,61,61,61,61,51,26,70,41,46,57,47,46,81,95,107,85,90,59,51,78,69,61,125,62,136,133,125,127,132,125,144,132,131,126,124,107,136,136,84,39,6,32,16]} 1. e4 Nf6 2. e5 Nd5 3. d4 d6 4. Nf3 Bg4 5. Be2 e6 6. O-O Be7 7. c4 Nb6 8. Nc3 O-O 9. h3 Bh5 10. Be3 d5 11. c5 Bxf3 12. gxf3 Nc8 13. f4 Bh4 14. Bd3 {The most consistent continuation. White maintains all his potential threats.} g6 (14... f5 {is solid, but as usual, a bit passive, depriving Black of an important square for his knight.} 15. b4) (14... Ne7 $2 {is premature due to} 15. Qg4 Nf5 16. Bxf5 exf5 17. Qxf5 $18) 15. f5 $5 {An ambitious continuation. I vaguely remember that I had it in my repertoire with white about 40-45 years ago.} (15. b4 {allows Black to continue his regrouping.} Ne7 16. Qg4 Nf5 17. Bxf5 {The only challenging continuation, weakening the defence on d5.} exf5 18. Qf3 c6 19. b5 Qa5 $5 $146 (19... Nd7 $6 {0-1 Brustman,A (2325)-Lados,P (2250) Warsaw Legion op 1990} 20. Nxd5 $1 cxd5 21. Qxd5 $16 {yields White overwhelming compensation for the piece.}) 20. Bd2 (20. Nxd5 {is less efefctive ow.} cxd5 21. Qxd5 Qxb5 $17) (20. Rac1 Nd7 21. bxc6 bxc6 22. Nxd5 cxd5 23. Qxd5 Rfd8 $13) 20... Rd8 21. a4 Qc7 22. Kg2 (22. a5 {is best met with} a6 $1 {Blocking the queenside with b5-b6 would leave White without a plan, while} 23. bxc6 Nxc6 $11 {is fine for Black.} 24. Nxd5 $2 Nxd4 $19) 22... a5 $1 {Preventing a4-a5-a6 before developing the knight.} (22... Nd7 23. a5 a6 24. bxc6 bxc6 25. Rfb1 {followed by Rb6 is a bit molesting.}) 23. Ne2 Nd7 24. b6 {The only constructive plan. White tries to win the pawn on a5.} Qc8 25. Nc1 Nf8 26. Nb3 Ne6 {Things are not that simple, because d4 and f4 are also hanging.} 27. Bc3 (27. Qd3 f6 $11) 27... Qd7 28. Rfd1 Ra6 $11 {White has defended the hanging pawns but should not take the one on a5.} 29. Nxa5 Rda8 $15) (15. Qg4 {is examined in Line 32.}) 15... exf5 16. Qf3 (16. Qb3 Ne7 17. Qxb7 Nbc6 {[%cal Gf5f4] Threatening ...f5-f4.} 18. Ne2 Rb8 19. Qa6 Nb4 20. Qa3 Nxd3 21. Qxd3 Rxb2 $15) 16... Ne7 $1 $146 (16... Nc6 17. Qf4 {[%cal Gc3d5] Threatening Nxd5 under improved circumstances.} (17. Nxd5 N8e7 {is reasonable for Black.}) 17... Be7 18. Rad1 $14) 17. Bh6 (17. Qf4 g5 $15) (17. b4 a6 $11 {does not change much.}) 17... Nbc6 $1 (17... Re8 18. Qf4 $16 {causes Black serious coordination problems.}) 18. Ne2 (18. Qf4 {is parried with} g5 19. Bxg5 Bxg5 20. Qxg5+ Ng6 21. Qxf5 Nxd4 $11) (18. Bxf8 {is a bit premature.} Qxf8 19. Qe3 (19. Ne2 Qh6 $44) 19... Nd8 20. Kh1 Ne6 21. Ne2 Kh8 22. Rg1 g5 $44 {with a slightly improved version of the main line.}) 18... Kh8 19. Bxf8 {Now this is more or less forced.} (19. Kh1 Rg8 $15) 19... Qxf8 $44 {Black has a pawn for the exchange and a solid structure, restricting the white bishop. Besides, d4 is a permanent weakness. In the next phase, he will transfer his queen's knight to e6.} 20. Qe3 {Preventing ...Qh6.} ({The attempt to prevent ...Nd8-e6 with} 20. Bb5 Nd8 21. Bd7 {endangers the bishop after} c6 $13) (20. Qf4 {runs into} g5 21. Qf3 (21. Qe3 Qh6 $44) 21... f6 $44) (20. Rad1 Qh6 21. Qe3 Bg5 22. f4 Bh4 23. Kh2 Nd8 24. b4 Ne6 25. b5 Rf8 (25... g5 26. Qf3 gxf4 27. Nxf4 Rg8 28. Ne2 Rg5 $44) 26. Qf3 f6 27. exf6 Bxf6 28. Qe3 Ng7 $44) 20... Qg7 (20... Nd8 21. Qf4 g5 22. Qf3 f6 23. exf6 Qxf6 $13) (20... g5 21. f4 f6 22. exf6 Qxf6 23. Kh1 (23. Kh2 Rf8 {[%cal Ge7g6]}) 23... Rg8 24. Rg1 g4 $13) 21. Kh1 (21. Bb5 Nd8 22. Bd7 g5 23. Kh1 f4 24. Qf3 Ne6 $11) 21... Rf8 $5 {This move prepares ...f7-f6 and keeps the rook away from the g-file, thus preventing an undesired exchange.} (21... Rg8 {looks more natural, but at a later stage the rook may have to avoid the exchange along the g-file.}) 22. Rg1 Nd8 23. b4 Ne6 24. Raf1 g5 25. f4 Qh6 26. fxg5 Bxg5 27. Qf3 Be3 $11 {Now is the moment when the rook is better placed on f8.} *

