1. e4 Nf6 2. e5 Nd5 3. d4 d6 4. Nf3 Bg4 5. Be2 e6 6. O-O Be7 7. c4 Nb6 8. Nc3 O-O 9. h3 Bh5 10. Be3 d5 11. c5 Bxf3 12. gxf3 Nc8 13. f4 Bh4 14. Bd3 g6 15. Qg4 {This move implies "losing" two tempi, but it is for a good cause. White induces Black to block the kingside. White renews the threat of f4-f5.} f5 {As mentioned before, this would not be possible with the white pawn on h2 instead of h3.} (15... Kh8 {may run into} 16. Nxd5 $5 $146 exd5 17. f5 {with a very powerful attack, taking advantage of the hanging bishop on h4 and the knight's presence on the opposite wing.} Ne7 {This seems to be the best chance.} (17... Nc6 18. Bh6 Re8 (18... Rg8 19. f6 Bxf6 20. exf6 Qxf6 21. Bg5 Qe6 22. Qh4 $5 $18 {followed by Bf6 and Rae1. This is even stronger than the exchange on e6 followed by winning the exchange with Bf6+.}) 19. Kh1 $16) 18. Qxh4 Nxf5 19. Qxd8 Rxd8 20. Bg5 Rg8 (20... Re8 21. Bxf5 gxf5 22. Bf6+ Kg8 23. Kh2 $18) 21. Bf6+ Ng7 22. f4 Nd7 23. Bxg7+ Rxg7 24. f5 gxf5+ 25. Kh2 $14) 16. Qd1 $5 {This ensures the queen the highest mobility. It was White's choice in the only grandmaster game with this line.} (16. exf6 Qxf6 $11 {yields Black a comfortable position, as White does not have the plan Kg2-h3.}) (16. Qg2 {This is not the best square for the queen, since it is isolated from the other board sectors.} Kh8 17. Kh1 Rg8 18. Rg1 Nc6 19. a3 Qf8 20. Qf3 Nd8 21. Rg2 Nf7 22. Nb5 Qe7 23. Rag1 a6 24. Nc3 Na7 25. Bc2 Nc6 26. b4 Na7 27. Bd3 Nc6 {½-½ Bellin,R (2403)-Tymrakiewicz,R (2252) BCF-chT2 0708 (4NCL) 2007 (1)}) (16. Qe2 {has some minor drawbacks if compared to the main line.} Nc6 17. a3 (17. Rab1 {runs into} Nb4 {when the bishop does not have the square on e2.} 18. Bb5 c6 19. Ba4 b5 20. Bd1 a5 $11 {Black is safe on the queenside and could come up with a kingside plan.}) 17... b6 $132 18. b4 bxc5 19. bxc5 N8e7 20. Rab1 Na5 $132) 16... Nc6 17. Kh2 {Preparing the knight's transfer to f3, while also taking measures against ...g6-g5. Ignoring this pawn break is likely to yield Black counterplay, as shown below.} (17. a3 N8e7 ({With the queen on d1,} 17... b6 18. Qa4 {may cause some micro problems.}) 18. b4 g5 $5 $146 {White's center suddenly appears to be not that solid.} 19. fxg5 (19. Qh5 Ng6 20. fxg5 Ncxe5 21. dxe5 d4 $11) 19... Nxe5 $1 20. f4 (20. dxe5 d4 21. Qe2 dxe3 22. Qxe3 Kh8 23. f4 h6 $44) 20... Nxd3 21. Qxd3 h6 22. Ra2 Ng6 23. Rg2 c6 24. Ne2 Qe7 25. Kh1 Kf7 26. Ng1 Rh8 27. Nf3 hxg5 28. fxg5 Rh5 $13) 17... Kh8 (17... Qd7 18. Ne2 b6 {looks like a reasonable alternative.}) 18. Ne2 {Continuing the plan.} ({Once again, neglecting the positional threat ...g6-g5 would yield Black active play.} 18. Rb1 Rg8 19. b4 a6 20. a4 N8e7 21. Ne2 Qf8 22. Ng1 g5 $1 23. Nf3 g4 $1 24. Nxh4 Qh6 25. Rg1 $1 {The only move.} (25. Ng2 Qxh3+ 26. Kg1 g3 27. fxg3 Rxg3 28. Rb2 Rag8 29. Rff2 Rxe3 $19) (25. Kg3 gxh3+ 26. Kxh3 Ng6 $19) 25... Qxh4 26. Rg3 Ng6 $13) 18... Nb4 $5 $146 ({The game went} 18... N8e7 19. Ng1 Ng8 20. Nf3 Nh6 21. a3 Nf7 22. b4 a6 {Black does not have any counterplay and engines consider that his position is critical. Moreover, White eventually won. Despite all these, I believe White has difficulty proving a concrete advantage.} 23. Rg1 Rg8 24. Rg2 h6 {This weakening is unnecessary, but Black was dreaming of starting a kingside attack later.} 25. Qc2 Kh7 26. Rag1 Nh8 27. Bd2 Qe7 28. Bc3 Nd8 29. Bd2 Ndf7 30. c6 b6 31. a4 Qd8 32. Qd1 Be7 33. Qe2 Qc8 34. Rc1 (34. b5 a5 {blocks the queenside with an obvious draw.}) 34... Ra7 35. Rgg1 Qf8 36. Rb1 (36. Bxa6 Bxb4 $132) 36... Qa8 37. Rgc1 {If Black maintained his neutral policy, the game would probably end in a draw. But suddenly, he became ambitious.} g5 $6 38. fxg5 Bxg5 $6 (38... Nxg5 39. Rg1 Nxf3+ 40. Qxf3 Qf8 41. Rxg8 Qxg8 42. Rg1 Qf7 43. Qe2 {With the black queen needing to secure the kingside, this move forces the weakening of the queenside.} a5 44. bxa5 bxa5 45. Bb5 $16) 39. Nxg5+ Nxg5 40. Rg1 $18 Qd8 41. Rg3 Ne4 42. Bxe4 Rxg3 43. Bxf5+ Rg6 44. Bxg6+ Nxg6 45. Rg1 {1-0 Vasiukov,E-Alburt,L Zonal Vilnius 1975 (2) and White won.}) 19. Bb1 a5 20. a3 Na6 {Changing the initial path.} 21. Bd3 c6 22. Ng1 Qd7 23. Nf3 Bd8 24. b4 axb4 25. axb4 Na7 {Black sacrifices a pawn to reach perfect regrouping and stability on light squares.} 26. Bxa6 bxa6 27. Rxa6 Rb8 28. Qd2 Nb5 29. Ng1 Rg8 30. Ne2 Nc7 31. Ra7 Qc8 32. Ra4 Bh4 33. Rfa1 Rb7 34. Nc3 Qb8 35. Rb1 h6 $11 {Black is very solid and ...g6-g5 is a more realistic plan than in the game.} *

