{[%evp 0,44,25,25,43,37,45,45,45,21,21,2,9,23,20,20,36,31,31,46,51,31,101,66,84,73,73,28,33,31,63,44,26,55,9,19,87,-38,-70,-74,-88,-89,-87,-95,-85,-78,-100]} 1. e4 Nf6 2. e5 Nd5 3. d4 d6 4. c4 {Optically, the most natural move, since the exposed knight on d5 is really "inviting". We should mention, though, that if White plays Nf3 at an early stage, the play could transpose to the classical system, examined in Lines 2 to 9.} ({Before moving on, I would just mention that} 4. f4 {is an inaccurate move order if White intends to play the Four Pawns Attack:} dxe5 5. fxe5 c5 $1 6. c4 Nb4 7. a3 (7. d5 Bf5 8. Na3 e6 $15 9. d6 $2 Qh4+ $1 $19) 7... N4c6 $132) 4... Nb6 5. f4 {The aggressive Four Pawns Attack is practically as "old" as the Alekhine Defence itself. It was first played by Euwe in 1921, a bit more than one month after Alekhine himself introduced "his" opening in top tournament practice. It is a natural reaction to Black's provocative opening. White takes all the given space, but in doing so he spends many tempi on pawn moves and creates some potential weaknesses in his own camp. Traditionally considered an adventurous system, it nowadays enjoys the engines' blessing. However, not much has changed with respect to classical knowledge. Black can achieve normal play with a bit of accuracy.} (5. exd6 {is examined in Lines 42 to 52.}) (5. Nf3 g6 6. Be2 Bg7 7. O-O O-O 8. Nc3 {is one of the possible transpositions to the classical system, analyzed in Lines 2 to 9.}) 5... dxe5 {Black releases the tension in the center, in order to start to set up piece pressure.} ({In many games,} 5... Bf5 {only leads to a transposition after ...dxe5 on one of the next move. It can have independent value, offering Black a viable alternative to the main variation. Please refer to Lines 38 to 41.}) 6. fxe5 (6. dxe5 $2 {is inconsequent. Instead of a massive centre, White gets only weaknesses.} Qxd1+ {And he loses the right to castle, too.} 7. Kxd1 Nc6 8. Be3 Bf5 9. Nf3 O-O-O+ 10. Nbd2 f6 $17 {AFter the opening of the centre, the white king will face serious problems.}) (6. c5 $6 {is a premature display of activity.} Nd5 7. fxe5 (7. dxe5 e6 8. Qc2 Qe7 $17 {0-1 (35) Kruk, S (1740)-Yeung, C (1717) ICCF email 2017}) 7... Bf5 8. Nf3 e6 9. Nc3 Be7 10. Bc4 O-O 11. O-O Nc6 $11) 6... Nc6 {This system is maybe one of the most transpositional in the Alekhine Defence. I would like to highlight an important aspect, though. Black does not need to develop his queen's knight so early, but should not delay it for too long, either.} ({Here is an illustration of what could happen if he neglects the latter:} 6... Bf5 7. Nc3 e6 8. Nf3 Be7 9. Be3 O-O $6 ({Now was the last moment for} 9... Nc6 {True, this allows} 10. d5 {examined later, but avoids simpler and more signigicant problems.}) 10. Bd3 $1 {This is strong only because Black has refrained from putting d4 under pressure.} Bg4 (10... Bxd3 11. Qxd3 {yields White the control over the e4-square, yielding him a consistent positional advantage, for instance} Nc6 12. O-O f6 13. exf6 Bxf6 14. Ne4 $16) 11. O-O Nc6 {Too late to be effective.} 12. h3 Bxf3 13. Qxf3 Nxe5 {This natural move leads to trouble.} (13... Nxd4 $2 14. Qe4 Nf5 15. g4 $18) (13... Nb4 14. Qe4 Nxd3 15. Qxd3 $14) 14. Bxh7+ $1 Kxh7 15. dxe5 {[%cal Gc3e4] The black king is in serious danger. White intends to play Rad1 followed by Ne4.} Qd3 16. Rad1 Qg6 (16... Qf5 17. Qxf5+ exf5 18. b3 g6 19. c5 Nc8 20. Rd7 $16) 17. Rd4 (17. b3 $5 c6 18. Ne4 $16 {is simpler.}) 17... Rad8 18. Rg4 Qd3 19. Ne4 Nxc4 20. Bg5 $1 {Surprisingly winning material.} (20. Rxg7+ Kxg7 21. Qg4+ Kh8 {1-0 Velimirovic, D-Marovic, D YUG-ch27 Umag 1972 (19) should have led only to a draw.}) 20... Qxf3 21. Rxf3 Rde8 (21... Bxg5 22. Nxg5+ {does not change much.}) 22. Bxe7 Rxe7 23. Ng5+ Kh6 {Otherwise ...Rxc4 wins a knight.} 24. Rfg3 Nxe5 25. Rh4+ Kg6 26. Ne4+ Kf5 27. Rg5#) 7. Be3 {White should not hurry with developing his king's knight.} (7. Nf3 {allows} Bg4 $1 {It is worth mentioning that in many games, Black was happy to place the bishop on this square even after he had played ...Bf5 first!} 8. Be3 e6 9. Nc3 (9. Be2 Bxf3 10. gxf3 {Forced, since the pawn on c4 needs defending.} Qh4+ 11. Bf2 Qf4 $17) 9... Be7 10. Be2 Bxf3 11. gxf3 Bh4+ 12. Kf1 O-O 13. Kg2 f6 14. f4 fxe5 15. dxe5 (15. fxe5 Bg5 16. Bg1 Rf4 $17) 15... Qe8 $11 {followed by ...Ne7, with pleasant play.}) 7... Bf5 8. Nc3 {The best move order again.} (8. Nf3 $6 {was Euwe's choice in the first game featuring the Four Pawns Attack.} e6 (8... Nb4 {is the simplest way of punishing White's move order.} 9. Na3 e6 10. Be2 Be7 11. O-O O-O 12. Qd2 c5 $132) 9. Bd3 $6 {Inaccurate for more than one reason.} (9. Be2 Be7 10. Nc3 {transposes to our main lines.}) 9... Bxd3 (9... Nxd4 10. Nxd4 Bxd3 11. Qxd3 c5 $11) (9... Bg4 $1 {White can transpose above by losing a tempo in his turn with 10.Be2, or else try} 10. Nbd2 Nxe5 $1 11. Be4 Bxf3 12. gxf3 Nc6 13. Bxc6+ bxc6 $15) 10. Qxd3 Qd7 11. Nbd2 {Â½-Â½ Euwe, M-Kostic, B Den Haag International The Hague 1921 (1)} (11. Nc3 {does not change much.} O-O-O 12. Rd1 f6 13. exf6 gxf6 $11) 11... O-O-O 12. O-O f6 13. exf6 gxf6 $11 {The difference with respect to the similar lines where Black played ...Be7 and ...0-0 instead of ...Qd7 and ...0-0-0 is that White does not have the absolute control over e4 and Black is doing fine.}) 8... e6 (8... Nb4 $6 9. Rc1 $14 {leads to nothing.}) 9. Nf3 ({Many players prefer to delay the knight's development for one more move.} 9. Be2 Be7 10. Nf3 {Black should now castle, transposing to our main lines, since} Bg4 $2 {arrives much too late.} 11. O-O Bxf3 (11... O-O 12. b3 $5 {consolidates c4, preparing for h2-h3 and Bxf3.}) 12. Rxf3 $16) 9... Be7 ({After wasting a tempo on the way, the benefist of} 9... Bg4 {are less clear.} 10. Be2 Bxf3 11. gxf3 {There is a lot of theory here, too, but since White could play 9.Be2, I prefer to stick to the natural classical move order.}) 10. d5 {This is White's only way of deviating from the classical main line. The resolute advance of the d-pawn leads to sharp play, but if Black knows what he is doing, chances are about equal.} (10. Bd3 {allows} Bg4 (10... Nb4 11. Bxf5 Nxc4 12. Bc1 exf5 {0-1 Mrosla,E-Algra,J IECG TG.2002.0.14380 IECG email (2)} 13. a3 {forcing the knight to retreat to c6, in order to parry Qa4+} Nc6 14. O-O O-O 15. b3 Nb6 {0-1 Mrosla,E-Algra,J IECG TG.2002.0.14380 IECG email (2) We have transposed back to} 16. d5 Nxe5 $5 17. Nxe5 Bc5+ 18. Kh1 Qf6 19. Bf4 Bd6 20. Qe2 Rae8 21. Rae1 Re7 22. Bg3 g6 23. Qb2 Bxe5 24. Bxe5 Rxe5 25. Ne4 Qg7 26. Nf6+ Qxf6 27. Qxe5 Qxe5 28. Rxe5 Rc8 29. Rfe1 Kf8 $11) 11. Rf1 (11. O-O Nxd4 12. Bxd4 Bxf3 13. Qxf3 Qxd4+ 14. Kh1 O-O $17) 11... O-O 12. h3 Bh4+ (12... Bxf3 13. Rxf3 f6 $11) 13. Kd2 Bxf3 14. Qxf3 Bg5 15. Bxg5 Qxg5+ 16. Qe3 Qxe3+ 17. Kxe3 Rad8 18. c5 Nc8 19. Rad1 N8e7 $11 {Â½- (56) Â½ (56) Costa, M (2012)-Morcillo Holgado, M (1939) ICCF email 2020}) (10. Be2 {is examined in Line 35 to 37.}) 10... exd5 11. cxd5 Nb4 12. Nd4 (12. Bb5+ {is comfortably met with} c6 13. dxc6 (13. Nd4 N6xd5 $1 14. Nxf5 Nxe3 15. Nxe3 cxb5 $15 16. Qg4 {1-0 (37) Vollbrecht,J-Geerlings,H (1950) corr 1986} Qd3 $19) 13... bxc6 14. Nd4 {Â½- (24) Â½ (24) Collazo Gibanel,S (1690)-Barea Serra,J (1638) Santa Eulalia de Roncana 2019} Nc2+ 15. Nxc2 Qxd1+ 16. Rxd1 cxb5 17. Nd4 Bg4 18. Ndxb5 (18. Rc1 a6) 18... Bxd1 19. Nc7+ Kd7 20. Nxa8 Rxa8 21. Kxd1 Nc4 $11 {Retrieving the pawn with comfortable play.}) 12... Bd7 {Preventing Bb5+. With the pawn on d5 hanging, White is at crossroads.} 13. Qf3 (13. Qb3 $6 {misplaces the queen.} O-O 14. d6 (14. e6 fxe6 15. Nxe6 Bxe6 16. dxe6 Qd6 17. a3 Bh4+ 18. g3 Bxg3+ 19. hxg3 Qxg3+ 20. Ke2 Qf3+ 21. Kd2 Rad8+ {0-1 Caputo, F-Eigenmann,W (1927) EU-ch SC-OR/353 email ICCF email 2020}) (14. Be2 Bc8 15. Bf3 $2 Nd3+) 14... cxd6 15. e6 $1 (15. Qxb4 $2 dxe5 $19) 15... fxe6 16. Qxb4 d5 17. Qb3 Bh4+ 18. g3 Bg5 {Black has more than enough compensation for the piece. The situation is similar to the French with blocked centre where Black sacrifices a knight for two pawns with ...Nxe5.} 19. Bxg5 Qxg5 20. Be2 Qe3 21. Nc2 Qf2+ 22. Kd2 Nc4+ 23. Kc1 Rac8 24. Qxb7 Ba4 25. Qa6 Nxb2 26. Kxb2 Qf6 27. Qxa4 Qxc3+ 28. Kb1 Rb8+ 29. Bb5 Rf2 30. Rc1 a6 31. Qxa6 Qd3 32. Qxe6+ Kh8 $19 {0-1 Soto Palomo,C (1967)-Padilla Lopez,D (2089) ESP AEAC W/P/089 email ICCF email 2016} 33. a4 Qb3#) (13. Nf3 Bg4 $5 {Playing for more than a draw.} (13... Bf5 $11 {leads to a move repetition.}) 14. Bxb6 axb6 15. a3 (15. Be2 Bc5 (15... Ra5 16. O-O Nxd5 17. Bb5+ Bd7 18. Qxd5 Bxb5 19. Nxb5 Qxd5 20. Nxc7+ Kd7 21. Nxd5 Rxd5 $11) 16. a3 Bxf3 17. Bxf3 Qh4+ 18. g3 Qd4 19. Qxd4 Nc2+ 20. Kd2 Nxd4 21. Bd1 {Â½-Â½ Geller,E (2490)-Vaganian,R (2600) Sochi Chigorin Memorial 1986 (11)} b5 $13) 15... Bxf3 16. gxf3 Bh4+ 17. Ke2 Na6 18. Qd4 (18. b4 O-O 19. f4 f6 20. e6 f5 21. Bg2 Qf6 22. Qd3 c6 $11) 18... O-O 19. Rd1 Nc5 20. Rg1 Kh8 21. Bh3 f5 22. f4 Qe8 23. Bg2 Be7 24. Bf3 Na4 25. b4 {White has an impressive centre, but Black can generate strong counterplay, partly because the white king stays in the centre.} c5 26. Qd2 (26. dxc6 bxc6 $11) 26... Nxc3+ 27. Qxc3 cxb4 28. axb4 Ra2+ 29. Kf1 Qb5+ 30. Qd3 Qxb4 31. d6 Bh4 32. Rg3 Qxf4 33. Rh3 Rfa8 {[%cal Ga2f2,Ga8a2]} 34. d7 Bd8 $5 $13) (13. Nb3 c6 $5 {Again an ambitious approach.} ({If Black is happy with a draw,} 13... Bf5 {more or less forces} 14. Nd4 $11 {with a repetition.}) 14. d6 Bg5 15. Bc5 (15. Bxg5 Qxg5 16. Qe2 O-O 17. Kf2 Rae8 18. Re1 f6 $17) (15. Bd4 {[%cal Rb3d4] deprives White of Nd4 after} Bf5 $36) 15... N4d5 16. Nxd5 Nxd5 17. Bc4 Bf4 (17... Be6 18. O-O $16 {Â½-Â½ Prundeanu,H-Kertesz,A Arad 1975}) 18. Qh5 (18. O-O Qh4 19. h3 O-O 20. Bxd5 cxd5 21. Qd4 g5 22. Rf3 Rae8 $13) 18... Qg5 19. Qxg5 Bxg5 20. O-O b6 21. Bf2 O-O 22. Rae1 Rae8 $13 {/î€¯}) ({For} 13. e6 {see Line 34.}) 13... c5 {A necessary reaction. In view of the possible check on c2, White is more or less forced to part with his strong centre.} 14. dxc6 (14. Nf5 Nc2+ 15. Kd2 {1-0 (23) Morozevich, A (2659)-Manea, A (2338) Chess.com INT 2020} Nxe3 16. Nxe3 (16. Kxe3 O-O 17. Kf2 Bxf5 18. Qxf5 f6 19. e6 Nc8 20. g3 Nd6 21. Qf4 c4 $15) 16... c4 17. a4 O-O 18. a5 Bg5 19. axb6 Qxb6 20. Ncd1 Rae8 $15 {with strong initiative for the piece.}) (14. e6 O-O $19 {0-1 (29) Ruiz Font,E (1899)-Romero Calduch,S (1734) Linares 2010}) 14... Bxc6 15. Nxc6 (15. Qg4 N6d5 16. Bd2 (16. Qxg7 Nxe3 17. Qxh8+ Bf8 $19) 16... Qb6 $146 {=.}) 15... bxc6 {The most ambitious. Black maintains the threat on c2.} ({There is nothing wrong with} 15... Nxc6 {, as played in two games, of course.}) 16. Qe4 N6d5 $11 17. Bf2 $2 {Â½- (35) Â½ (35) Kulaots, K (2578)-Yuffa, D (2502) Moscow 2016} (17. Bd4 O-O $11 18. Bc4 (18. Rd1 f5 19. Qb1 f4 $132) 18... Nc2+ 19. Qxc2 Nb4 20. Qf2 Qxd4 21. Qxd4 Nc2+ 22. Kf2 Nxd4 $11) (17. Nxd5 Qxd5 18. Qxd5 Nxd5 19. Bd4 Nb4 $11) 17... f5 $1 {A clear hint about how relative White's space advantage is.} 18. Qb1 (18. exf6 Nxf6 $17) (18. Qxf5 Rf8 19. Qe4 Rf4 20. Qxh7 Rxf2 21. Kxf2 Qb6+ $19) 18... Nf4 19. Be3 Nfd3+ 20. Bxd3 Qxd3 21. Qxd3 Nxd3+ 22. Ke2 Nxe5 $17 {0-1 (59) Rattinger,T (2350)-Arnold,G (2428) ICCF email 2006} *

