{[%evp 0,60,28,8,77,62,55,55,44,39,43,30,48,48,48,48,48,48,48,48,27,61,90,82,82,82,39,0,55,50,30,-70,-42,-42,-42,-68,-73,-42,-42,-76,-76,-76,-42,-54,-53,-53,-71,-71,-71,-68,-62,-28,-22,-21,-21,-21,-21,-16,-20,-20,0,-38,-46]} 1. e4 Nf6 2. e5 Nd5 3. d4 d6 4. c4 Nb6 5. f4 dxe5 6. fxe5 Nc6 7. Be3 Bf5 8. Nc3 e6 9. Nf3 Be7 10. d5 exd5 11. cxd5 Nb4 12. Nd4 Bd7 13. e6 {The most consistent continuation of the attack.} fxe6 14. dxe6 {The only way of maintaining the rhythm of White's initiative.} (14. Nxe6 Bxe6 15. dxe6 Qxd1+ 16. Rxd1 Nc2+ 17. Ke2 Nxe3 18. Kxe3 {Â½- (27) Â½ (27) Torres Herrero,J-Arias Velasco,J (1946) Barcelona 2003} c6 $5 $15) 14... Bc6 15. Qg4 {The by far most popular move.} (15. Nxc6 {This makes Black's play simpler.} Qxd1+ 16. Rxd1 (16. Kxd1 Nxc6 17. Kc2 O-O-O 18. Bb5 Rd6 $11) 16... Nc2+ 17. Kd2 Nxe3 18. Kxe3 bxc6 19. Be2 O-O 20. Rhf1 Bg5+ 21. Ke4 Bf6 22. Bg4 Rab8 $11 {0-1 Videnova,I (2301)-Cmilyte, V (2497) EU-ch (Women) 13th Gaziantep 2012 (1) With opposite-coloured bishops on board, the e-pawn is not dangerous, while the white queenside is vulnerable.}) (15. a3 {runs into} Bh4+ $1 16. g3 Bxh1 17. axb4 Bf6 {With just normal white compensation for the exchange.} 18. Qg4 O-O 19. O-O-O Qe8 20. Bd3 Bg2 21. Nf5 h5 22. Nh6+ Kh8 23. Qf5 g6 24. Qxg6 Qxg6 25. Bxg6 Bh3 26. Bf7 Rfd8 {Â½-Â½ (26) Modestino,M (2251)-Fluit,J (2201) ICCF email 2019}) (15. Qh5+ {is a different way of activating the queen than in the main line.} g6 16. Qh6 {The most principled continuation. White prevents Black from castling.} (16. Nxc6 bxc6 {forces White to step back in order to parry ...Nc2+.} 17. Qf3 Rf8 18. Qe4 Qd6 19. a3 N4d5 $15 {0-1 Bohak, J (2273)-Ter Veen, K (2176) W-ch WS/M/103 email ICCF email 2007}) ({In the event of} 16. Qg4 Bh4+ {, Black's extra tempo ...g7-g6 with respect to the main line looks rather useful. For instance, after} 17. g3 Bxh1 18. O-O-O $2 Bf6 $1 {The knight jump} 19. Nf5 {does not attack g7.} N4d5 $17) 16... Bh4+ (16... Bf6 {is also playable.} 17. O-O-O Qe7 18. a3 N4d5 19. Nxc6 bxc6 20. Nxd5 Nxd5 21. Rxd5 cxd5 22. Bb5+ Kd8 23. Rf1 {Â½-Â½ Filipenko,A (2380)-Gleizerov,E (2410) URS Soviet Union 1987} Rb8 24. Bd7 Rxb2 $5 25. Rxf6 Rxg2 {Attacking the rook on f6 by controlling g5.} 26. Rf2 Qxa3+ $11) 17. g3 Bxh1 18. gxh4 Qd6 $1 $146 {On this square, the queen has the highest mobility. It maintains the central knight under pressure and keeps an eye on... h2!} (18... Qf6 $2 19. O-O-O O-O-O 20. Bh3 $16 Kb8 21. Rxh1 Nc4 22. Rd1 $18) 19. Qg5 {Preventing Black's long castle.} (19. O-O-O $2 {does not work with the queen on d6.} O-O-O 20. Bh3 Kb8 21. Rxh1 Nc4 $17 22. Rd1 $2 Qxh2 $19 {This is the difference! Black attacks the bishop and threatens mate on c2.}) 19... O-O 20. O-O-O N4d5 21. Bd3 Nxe3 22. Bxg6 $11 {There is nothing better than forcing a draw.} hxg6 23. Qxg6+ Kh8 24. Rxh1 (24. Rg1 Bg2) 24... Qxd4 25. Qh5+ (25. Rg1 Rf1+ 26. Rxf1 Nxf1 27. Qh5+ Kg8 28. Qf7+ Kh8 29. Qh5+ Kg7 30. Qg5+ $11) (25. Qh6+ $2 Kg8 26. Rg1+ Ng4) 25... Kg7 26. Qg5+ (26. Rg1+ Kf6 $19) 26... Kh7 $11) 15... Bh4+ {A familiar check. White seems to have all the space he needs for proving a big advantage, but Black's minor pieces are active and the white king is exposed still.} 16. g3 {White must sacrifice the exchange.} (16. Kd1 O-O $1 $17) (16. Kd2 O-O 17. a3 N4d5 18. Nxc6 bxc6 19. Nxd5 Nxd5 $19 {Â½- (50) Â½ (50) Moston, M-Parkes, N CServe email 1997}) 16... Bxh1 17. O-O-O (17. Qxg7 Qf6 $19) (17. gxh4 O-O 18. O-O-O Qf6 {transposes to the main line.}) 17... Qf6 ({With the pawn on g7,} 17... Bf6 $2 {loses to} 18. Nf5 $18) 18. gxh4 (18. Nf5 O-O 19. Nxh4 Bf3 20. Nxf3 Qxf3 21. Qxf3 Rxf3 22. Bxb6 cxb6 $15) (18. Bb5+ c6 19. gxh4 O-O {transposes below.}) 18... O-O 19. Bb5 {The most popular move, threatening Bg5 followed by e6-e7. White has tried other bishop moves, too, with the idea of gaining a tempo by attacking the bishop on h1.} (19. Be2 Bd5 20. Bg5 Qe5 21. e7 Rf7 {Keeping the f-file defended against, for instance, Nf5 or Rf1.} ({Without entering further details,} 21... Rfe8 {is also playable.}) 22. a3 {Questioning Black's stability.} (22. Nf3 $2 Nxa2+ $1 23. Nxa2 Qxe2 24. Re1 Bxf3 25. Rxe2 Bxg4 26. e8=Q+ Rxe8 27. Rxe8+ Rf8 $17 {0-1 Bol, J-Diepstraten, L NED corr Netherlands 1979}) 22... Na2+ (22... Nc6 {is also good.} 23. Nxd5 Nxd5 24. Bc4 Ncxe7 25. Nf3 Rxf3 26. Qxf3 c6 27. Rf1 h6 28. Qf7+ Kh8 29. Bd3 Qd6 $13 {Â½-Â½ Huebener, J-Sprenger corr 1984 White has just normal compensation for the pawn.}) (22... h6 $5 $146 23. Bxh6 {Black can now choose between ...Na2+, transposing below and} Nc6 24. Nxc6 bxc6 25. Bg5 Re8 $11) 23. Nxa2 h6 $1 $146 (23... Bxa2 $2 24. Nc6 bxc6 25. Rd8+ {wins}) 24. Bxh6 Bxa2 25. Bg5 Re8 $13 {Possibly followed by ...R8xe7.}) (19. Bg5 {runs into} Qxf1 $1 20. Rxf1 Rxf1+ 21. Nd1 (21. Kd2 Nc4+ 22. Ke2 Raf8 23. Nd1 Nc2 $19) 21... Nd3+ 22. Kc2 Ne1+ 23. Kc1 Nd3+ 24. Kc2 Ne1+ 25. Kc3 $2 {In vain avoiding the perpetual check.} c5 $17 26. Nf5 Nd5+ 27. Kc4 {1-0 Den Broeder,G-De Veij,A NED-ch09 corr7981 Netherlands 1979} h5 $1 28. Qe2 b5+ $1 29. Kxb5 (29. Kxc5 Rxf5 30. Qxe1 Ne3+ 31. Kd6 {The only wy of avoiding the fork with ...Nc2+.} Nc4+ $19 {with a decisive attack.}) 29... Rxf5 30. Qxe1 Nc7+ 31. Ka4 Bc6+ 32. Kb3 Bd5+ 33. Kc3 Bxe6 $17) (19. Bh3 Bf3 $5 20. Nxf3 Qxf3 21. Qg3 Qxg3 22. hxg3 Rfe8 23. a3 Nc6 $13 {with just reasonable compensation for the exchange.}) 19... c6 {I have taken this as the main move since White could reach this position by checking on b5 on move 18.} ({It is worth noticing, though,. that Black had other ways of parrying the threat, for instance even} 19... a6 $5 $146 20. Bg5 Qf2 21. e7 (21. Rxh1 axb5 $17 {leaves a2 hanging. If we compare this position with the similar one after ...cxb5 in a line we avoid,} 22. Nd1 {allows} Rxa2 23. Nxf2 Rxf2 $19 {for instance} 24. Kd1 Nc4) 21... axb5 22. exf8=Q+ Rxf8 $13 23. Rxh1 $2 Nd3+ $19) 20. Bg5 (20. Rxh1 cxb5 $17) 20... Qe5 (20... Qf2 $2 21. Rxh1 cxb5 22. Nd1 Rfc8+ 23. Kb1 Qf8 24. Ne3 $16 {Â½-Â½ Gypser,A (2075)-Braun,P (2268) Bayern-chI Bank Hofmann 3rd Bad Wiessee 1999 (2)}) 21. e7 Rf2 $1 {[%csl Gf5] Keeping f5 defended and preparing Black's counterplay.} (21... Rfe8 $2 {0-1 (34) Grischuk, A (2748)-Svidler, P (2726) Odessa 2009} 22. Nf5 $16 h5 $2 23. Qxb4 $18 {Â½- (34) Â½ (34) Dimitrov, V (2455)-Videki, S (2405) Wiesbaden 1990}) 22. Qe6+ (22. Rxh1 cxb5 $17 {Â½- (55) Â½ (55) Penafiel Lopez, J-Machuca Palacios, E Spain 1987}) (22. Bf1 Re8 $17) 22... Qxe6 23. Nxe6 N4d5 24. Nxd5 Nxd5 25. Nc7 (25. Bc4 Be4 26. Bb3 Re8 27. Nc7 Kf7 $11 {[%cal Gh7h6] followed by ...h7-h6.}) (25. Rxh1 cxb5 $17 26. Re1 Re8 27. Re5 h6 $19) 25... Nxc7 26. Rd8+ Kf7 27. Bd3 g6 28. e8=Q+ Nxe8 29. Rxa8 Nd6 30. Rxa7 Ke6 $11 {0-1 (61) Chrobak, G-Paroczai, A Hungary 1998 Even though the lines with 10.d5 do not offer White an advantage objectively, they may seem a bit too violent for an Alekhine Defence player. This is one of the reasons I have offered an alternative in Lines 38 to 41.} *

