{[%evp 0,54,27,21,53,59,59,48,58,48,48,48,44,44,44,44,44,44,44,43,74,30,30,45,45,35,37,33,33,24,23,30,24,22,57,57,11,11,33,55,47,46,80,3,24,3,18,17,9,-44,-38,-27,-27,-27,-16,-51,-46]} 1. e4 Nf6 2. e5 Nd5 3. d4 d6 4. c4 Nb6 5. f4 dxe5 6. fxe5 Nc6 7. Be3 Bf5 8. Nc3 e6 9. Nf3 Be7 10. Be2 {The main continuation, leading to subtle positional play.} O-O 11. O-O f6 {Black needs to undermine the white center before the threat d4-d5 becomes real.} 12. exf6 {White does not gain anything by refraining from this exchange.} (12. Qe1 fxe5 13. dxe5 a6 14. Rd1 Qe8 15. Qg3 Rd8 16. Rxd8 Qxd8 17. Rd1 Qe8 18. a3 Na5 19. Bxb6 cxb6 20. b4 Nc6 21. Kh1 Qb8 $11 {Â½-Â½ (21) Perevozchikov, V (2031)-Parmet, D (1983) FICGS email 2010}) (12. Nh4 fxe5 13. Nxf5 Rxf5 {[%cal Gd8f8]} 14. d5 (14. Rxf5 exf5 15. d5 Nd4 16. Bxd4 exd4 17. Qxd4 Qf8 $15 18. Qf4 Bd6 19. Qf3 Nd7 20. Rf1 g6 21. Nb5 Be5 $17 {Â½- (46) Â½ (46) Selianinov,P-Chestnov,D Smolensk 2001}) 14... Rxf1+ 15. Qxf1 exd5 16. cxd5 Nd4 $13 17. Bd3 (17. Rc1 Bg5 $15 {Â½- (26) Â½ (26) Kukla,M (1969)-Muheim,S (2064) Belfort 2005}) 17... Bd6 18. Kh1 Qe7 $13) (12. Qb3 fxe5 13. d5 (13. dxe5 Qe8 14. Nb5 Qg6 $132 {Â½- (39) Â½ (39) Reynes Gonzalez,M (2070)-Cabanna,D (2125) Budapest 2006}) 13... Nb4 14. d6 (14. Rac1 Nd3 15. Rcd1 Nc5 16. Bxc5 Bxc5+ 17. Kh1 exd5 18. Nxd5 c6 $15 {Â½- (28) Â½ (28) Valcrose,T (1787)-Metras,D (1965) Salon de Provence 2014}) 14... Bxd6 15. c5 Nc2 16. Bf2 Nxa1 17. Rxa1 e4 18. Ne1 (18. Nxe4 {Â½- (59) Â½ (59) Nowak,D (2204)-Gwozdzik,Z (1927) Tarnowskie Gory 2008} Nd5 $19) 18... Be5 19. cxb6 Qd2 20. Rd1 (20. Bf1 Bxh2+ 21. Kxh2 Qxf2 $19 {[%cal Gf8f6,Gf6h6]}) 20... Qh6 21. h3 (21. Bg3 Bxg3 22. hxg3 Qe3+ 23. Kh2 Rf6 $19) 21... e3 $19) 12... Bxf6 {The main tabiya of the Four Pawns Attack. White maintains part of his centre and the more compact structure in general. However, all Black's minor pieces are active and wel coordinated. True, the knight on b6 may turn into a passive piece if White has the time to consolidate his c4-pawn with b2-b3, but then he can relocate it with ..Nc8-d6, for instance. Black's main source of counterplay is the relative weakness on d4. He can attack it, sometimes grab it by tactical means, or else break in the centre with ...e6-e5. All these sound logical, but it is worth knowing that White can prevent the position from becoming plain equal in the next phase, by means of a precise move order. Even so, Black will not have much to complain in the middlegame.} 13. Qd2 {Such a natural developing move, connecting the rooks, would not require any special comments. But since a top player refrained from it and got punished for that, it is worth mentioning that one of the concrete merits of the last move is creating the potential possibility of Bg5, thus weakening the pressure on d4.} ({The aforementioned game went} 13. Kh1 $6 Qe8 $1 {For tactical reasons, the queen is better placed here than on e7. This move works out well because the threat Bg5 is not real now.} 14. Qd2 (14. Bg5 Bxg5 15. Nxg5 Rd8 16. d5 exd5 17. cxd5 Qe3 18. Nf3 Nb4 19. Nd4 Bc8 $13) 14... Rd8 15. Rad1 Nxd4 $1 {With the queen on e7, this does not work.} 16. Nxd4 $2 (16. Bxd4 {is better.} c5 {With the queen on e7, this would lose to Bxf6.} 17. Qe3 cxd4 18. Nxd4 Na4 19. Nxa4 Rxd4 20. Rxd4 Bxd4 21. Qxd4 Qxa4 22. a3 Qc2 $11) 16... c5 {With the queen on e7, White could play Nxf5.} 17. Ncb5 cxd4 18. Bf4 d3 $19 {0-1 (32) Giri,A (2764)-Avila Pavas,S (2393) Chess.com INT 2020}) (13. d5 {is not too threatening.} Ne5 14. Bc5 (14. Qb3 Nxf3+ 15. Bxf3 Be5 16. g3 Bd3 17. Be2 Rxf1+ 18. Rxf1 Bxe2 19. Nxe2 exd5 20. Bxb6 axb6 21. cxd5 Qd6 $11 {0-1 (28) Szentgyorgyi,S (1862)-Mester,A (2119) Budapest 2011}) (14. Nxe5 Bxe5 15. Bd4 Qf6 16. Bxe5 Qxe5 $11) 14... Re8 15. Qb3 Nbd7 16. Ba3 Ng4 17. Rac1 c5 18. dxc6 {Â½-Â½ (18) Rozentalis, E (2631)-Vaganian, R (2577) Belgium 2011} bxc6 19. Bd6 Qb6+ 20. Qxb6 axb6 $11) 13... Qe7 ({It is worth mentioning that the idea of} 13... Qe8 {is anything but new. Kortschnoy played it in this position twice, seven decades ago.} 14. Bg5 $1 {is the critical move. However, it would be exaggerated to say that it refutes Black's last move.} (14. Rad1 Rd8 15. Qc1 (15. Kh1 Nxd4 16. Bxd4 c5 $11 {[%csl Ge8][%cal Rd4f6]}) (15. Bg5 $2 Nxd4 $17) 15... Rd7 (15... Qg6 16. Kh1 Bg4 17. Bd3 {1-0 Suetin, A-Kortschnoj, V URS-ch20 Final Moscow 1952 (10) Kortschnoj played his queen to h5, running into Ne2, but} Qe8 $11 {was fine for Black.}) 16. Rd2 Qg6 17. d5 exd5 18. Bxb6 axb6 19. Nxd5 Rdf7 20. Nxf6+ Rxf6 21. Nh4 Qg5 22. Nxf5 Rxf5 23. Rdd1 Nd4 $1 24. Bd3 (24. Rxd4 Rxf1+) (24. Qxg5 Nxe2+) 24... Rxf1+ 25. Rxf1 Nf3+ 26. Kh1 Qxc1 27. Rxc1 Ne5 28. Be4 c6 $11 {0-1 (49) Feldman,N-Kortschnoj,V Leningrad 1953 EXT 2000 [ChessBase II]}) 14... Rd8 (14... Bxg5 15. Qxg5 h6 16. Qe3 Rd8 17. Rad1 Qe7 18. h3 a6 19. Kh1 {White is somewhat better, at least theoretically, but Black can harass him, with good practical chances to confuse him.} Nb4 20. Ne1 Rde8 21. b3 Nd7 {preparing either ...e6-e5 or ...c7-c5.} 22. Bh5 Rb8 23. Qg3 Qd6 $11 24. Qe3 $2 Bg4 $1 {Oops!} 25. Rxf8+ Rxf8 26. Bxg4 Rf1+ 27. Qg1 Rxg1+ 28. Kxg1 Nf6 $19 {0-1 Poulin,M-Zugic,I (2406) Quebec op Montreal 1999 (5)}) 15. Bxf6 Rxf6 16. h3 {It is important to prevent ...Bg4.} (16. Qe3 Bg4 17. Ne4 Rf8 18. Rad1 Bxf3 19. Rxf3 Rxf3 20. gxf3 e5 21. Qg5 Kh8 22. c5 {Â½-Â½ Matinian, N (2495)-Levin, E (2505) RUS-ch rapid Sochi 2016 (4)} h6 $5 23. Qg3 Nd5 24. dxe5 Nxe5 $15) 16... Bg6 17. Qe3 $14 {Once again, the same evaluation as above. Black may be a bit worse but in the Hedgehog way.} Nb4 18. Rad1 Nc2 19. Qc1 Qe7 20. Rf2 Rdf8 21. Bf1 Nb4 22. a3 Nc6 23. Qe3 R6f7 $1 (23... Bh5 24. Ne4 Rf4 25. Neg5 $14) 24. Re1 (24. Ne4 Nd5 $1 25. Qe1 Nf4 $11) 24... Bh5 25. g4 Bg6 26. Be2 Na5 27. b3 Qxa3 $132 {As almost anything played by Kortschnoj, this line does not deserve discarding.}) 14. Rad1 Rad8 {Both sides are fully developed and White is at crossroads. He needs to find proper regroupings and distinguish between real threats and illusory ones. In this line, we will examine the less important continuations.} 15. h3 {In principle, it is useful to prevent ...Bg4, but as we will see in later lines, this is not a threat yet. At this stage, the last move is some sort of a waste of time.} (15. Qe1 {is not the best way of avoiding the opposition between the black rook and the white queen along the d-file.} Nb4 16. Qg3 Nc2 17. Bf2 Qb4 {Black has excellent counterplay.} 18. Ne5 (18. Qxc7 Qxb2 19. Nb5 Qxa2 20. Ne5 {Â½- (25) Â½ (25) Moraza,M-Cobo Arteaga,E Havana 1970} Ne3 21. Nc3 Qa5 22. Bxe3 Qxc3 $17) 18... Qxb2 19. c5 Nd5 20. Nxd5 exd5 21. Rb1 Qxa2 22. Rxb7 Nxd4 23. Bxd4 Qxe2 24. Rxc7 (24. Rxf5 Qd1+ 25. Rf1 Qxd4+ $19) 24... Rde8 $15) (15. c5 {is inoffensive since it solves the problem of the b6-knight.} Nd5 16. Bf2 (16. Nxd5 exd5 $11) 16... Kh8 (16... g5 $5) 17. Rfe1 Qf7 $11 {0-1 Kantane,A (2310)-Kantans,T (2496) Stockholm Challenge 2016 (1)}) (15. b3 {is a way of anticipating ...Bg4, but once again looks like a small loss of time.} h6 {The most popular move, but not the only good one. It is some sort of waiting move, which also prepares the bishop's retreat to h7 and prevents Bg5 forever.} (15... Bg4 $2 {is precisely what White had prepared for.} 16. Ne4 $1 Bxf3 17. Nxf6+ Rxf6 18. Bxf3 $16 {With the pawn on c4 defended, this is possible.}) (15... Nb4 16. Qc1 Nd7 $146 {[%cal Gc7c5,Gb4c2] planning ...c7-c5.} 17. c5 Nb8 $11 {followed by ...N8c6 and ...Nd5.}) 16. Qe1 (16. Kh1 Nb4 $5) 16... e5 (16... g5 {is another idea behind ...h7-h6.} 17. Qg3 Qg7 $132 18. Nb5 {1-0 (58) Legenia, A (2144)-San, T (2242) Chess.com INT 2021} g4 19. Nh4 Nxd4 $13) 17. d5 Nd4 18. Qf2 (18. Nxd4 exd4 19. Bxd4 Bxd4+ 20. Rxd4 Qe3+ 21. Qf2 Qxc3 22. Rf4 Qd2 23. Rxf5 Rxf5 24. Qxf5 Qxe2 25. Qf7+ Kh7 26. Qxc7 Qe3+ 27. Kh1 Rf8 $17) 18... Nxe2+ (18... Bg4 $13) 19. Qxe2 {0-1 (38) Aydincelebi,K (1975)-Bashirli,N (2352) Konya 2017} Nd7 20. Nd2 e4 $11) (15. Rfe1 $6 {releases the control over the f-file.} Bg4 $1 $146 16. Ne4 (16. b3 Bxf3 17. Bxf3 Nxd4 $17) 16... Bxf3 17. Nxf6+ Qxf6 $1 {With the rook away from f1, this is strong.} 18. gxf3 Nxd4 19. Bxd4 e5 $17) ({The by far most popular move,} 15. Qc1 {is examined in Line 36.}) ({In my opinion, the critical move is} 15. Kh1 {and we will deal with it in Line 37.}) 15... Bg6 $1 {By retreating with the bishop from the relatively exposed square on f5, Black makes the threat ...Nxd4 real. Besides, he could consider ...Bh5 at some stage.} 16. Qc1 (16. c5 Nd5 17. Bf2 Ndb4 18. Bc4 Na5 19. Qe2 Nxc4 20. Qxc4 Nd5 21. Rde1 Nf4 $11 {0-1 Egelstaff,R (2233)-Fichaud,A (2364) ICCF izt 09 email ICCF email 2017 [6]}) (16. Qe1 $146 e5 17. d5 e4 18. dxc6 exf3 19. Bxf3 bxc6 20. Rxd8 Rxd8 21. Bxc6 Nxc4 22. Nd5 Qd6 23. Nxf6+ gxf6 24. Bh6 Ne5 {[%csl Gc6]} (24... Qxc6 25. Qe7 Qd7 26. Qxf6 $18) 25. Bf3 $8 Nxf3+ 26. Rxf3 Qd1 $11) (16. Kh1 Nxd4 $1 17. Bxd4 (17. Nxd4 c5 $15 {and there is no hanging bishop on f5.}) 17... e5 $11 18. Nxe5 Bxe5 19. Rxf8+ Qxf8 20. Qe3 Bxd4 21. Rxd4 Re8 22. Qd2 Qe7 $11) 16... e5 {The same idea as in the next line with 15.Qc1.} 17. d5 Nd4 18. Nxd4 (18. Bxd4 exd4 19. Nxd4 Bg5 20. Qa1 Qe5 $44 21. Ne6 Be7 $1 {with the brutal threat ...Bd6.}) 18... exd4 19. Bxd4 Bg5 20. Qa1 {With such a passive white queen, Black obviously has full compensation for the pawn.} c5 {The start of promising play on dark squares.} (20... Na4 21. Bf3 Nxc3 22. bxc3 Bf4 $44) 21. Bf2 (21. dxc6 Rxd4 $19) 21... Rxf2 $1 {The simplest way of developing Black's initiative.} 22. Rxf2 (22. Kxf2 Qe3+ 23. Ke1 Bh4+ $19) 22... Be3 23. Rdf1 Rf8 $1 $146 (23... Qh4 $2 24. Qe1 Rf8 25. b3 $18 {1-0 De Vries,E-Odendahl,R Dieren op 1990 (7)}) 24. Nd1 (24. b3 Rxf2 25. Rxf2 Qf6 26. Bf3 Qd4 27. Qe1 Bxf2+ 28. Qxf2 Qxc3 29. Qxc5 Qe1+ 30. Kh2 Qe5+ 31. Kg1 h5 $5 $17) (24. Qe1 Nxc4 $1 25. Bxc4 Bxf2+ 26. Qxf2 Rxf2 27. d6+ Qf7 28. Bxf7+ Rxf7 $11) (24. Qd1 Qh4 25. Qe1 Qd4 {[%csl Gc4]} 26. Nb5 Rxf2 27. Rxf2 Qxb2 $13) 24... Bxf2+ 25. Rxf2 Rxf2 26. Kxf2 Nxc4 $11 {with the idea} 27. Bxc4 Qh4+ *

