{[%evp 0,52,24,17,61,61,61,61,61,31,31,31,37,37,46,46,37,37,37,44,37,37,46,32,44,33,33,26,39,19,19,24,29,-3,24,16,11,-15,9,-9,-3,0,13,14,55,0,25,6,0,32,20,4,4,20,6]} 1. e4 Nf6 2. e5 Nd5 3. d4 d6 4. c4 Nb6 5. f4 dxe5 6. fxe5 Nc6 7. Be3 Bf5 8. Nc3 e6 9. Nf3 Be7 10. Be2 O-O 11. O-O f6 12. exf6 Bxf6 13. Qd2 Qe7 14. Rad1 Rad8 15. Kh1 {Even though by ten times less popular than 15.Qc1, this is the critical continuation. Before anything, White takes measures against the break with ...e6-e5, after which the threats on dark squares are Black's main trumps.} h6 {Controlling g5 is important for several reasons. First of all, White can forget about Bg5, but soon we will notice another subtle aspect.} ({With the bishop on f5,} 15... Nxd4 $2 {is unsound.} 16. Bxd4 {[%cal Bc7c5,Bd4f6]} e5 17. Bxb6 Rxd2 18. Nxd2 $1 axb6 19. Rxf5 $16) ({In the event of} 15... Bg4 {White plays} 16. Ne4 {True, things are not entirely clear.} Bxf3 17. Nxf6+ Rxf6 18. gxf3 $1 {The player enjoying more space should avoid unnecessary exchanges!} (18. Rxf3 $6 Rxf3 19. gxf3 Qf7 20. Qc3 Qf6 21. b4 Nc8 {The start of complex knights regrouping.} 22. b5 N6e7 23. Qc1 h6 24. Rg1 Nf5 $132 {0-1 Matinian,N (2470)-Gabrielian,A (2458) Titled Tuesday intern op 27th Oct Chess.com INT blitz 2020 (10)}) 18... Qf7 19. b3 Rf5 $5 {This rook will cause Black some light trouble in the next phase. In the game above, Black did not have this problem and could maneuver with his knights freely.} (19... Ne7 $2 20. Bg5 Rf5 21. Bd3 Rxd4 22. Qe3 $16) 20. f4 (20. Bd3 Rh5 $1 (20... Rxf3 $6 21. Rg1 {[%cal Gd3e4] followeed by Be4 yields White strong initiative.}) 21. Be4 Ne7 {[%cal Gc7c6] Planning ...c7-c6 followed by ...Nf5.} 22. Bxb7 Nf5 $44 {with such threats as ...c7-c5, ...c7-c6 or the brutal ...Ng3.}) 20... Ne7 21. Bg4 Rf6 {Back to origins!} 22. d5 $5 (22. Qg2 Nf5) 22... exd5 23. Bd4 dxc4 24. Qe2 Rfd6 25. Bxb6 axb6 26. Be6 $1 Qxe6 27. Qxe6+ Rxe6 28. Rxd8+ Kf7 29. Rd7 (29. bxc4 Rc6 30. Re1 Nf5 $11 {with absolute stability for Black.}) 29... cxb3 30. axb3 c6 31. Rxb7 b5 $44 {/î€¯ It does not seem that White has any winning chance.}) (15... Kh8 {may lead to a transposition.} 16. Qc1 (16. Bg5 Bxg5 17. Qxg5 Qxg5 18. Nxg5 h6 19. Nf3 Bg4 $11) 16... h6 $1 {We are back in the main line.} (16... Bg4 {is insufficient for two reasons.} 17. Ng5 {Oh, the g5-square...} (17. Ne4 Bxf3 18. Bxf3 {The pawn on c4 is defended.} Bxd4 19. Bg5 {The same square...} Bf6 20. Rxd8 Qxd8 21. Nxf6 gxf6 22. Bh4 $14 {with dangerous pressure for the pawn.}) 17... Bxe2 18. Nxe2 $14) (16... Rd7 17. Bg5 {No comment already.} Bxg5 18. Qxg5 Qxg5 19. Nxg5 {After ...Rd7, the rook on f8 is undefended, so the bishop is in danger in view of g2-g4 or Nxe6. Only this justifies Bg5, as Black does not have the time to take on d4..} Rf6 {0-1 Konings, F (2132)-Bezemer, A (2283) Hoogeveen op 24th 2021 (3)} (19... Rxd4 20. g4) (19... h6 20. Nxe6 $16) 20. Nf3 $14)) (15... Rd7 {This plan is less effective than it may seem.} 16. Qc1 Rfd8 $6 17. d5 $1 $146 (17. c5 {1-0 Boulet,B-Van Eeckhout,G O'Kelly mem-C corr8490 Belgium 1984} Nd5 $11) 17... exd5 18. cxd5 Nb4 19. Bxb6 axb6 20. Nd4 $16 Bxd4 21. Rxd4) 16. Qc1 {Now is a good moment to take the queen out of the opposition with the black rook.} (16. h3 Kh8 17. Qc1 {is another possible move order.}) 16... Kh8 {Finally threatening ...Bg4, since Ne4 followed by Nxc6 will come without check. However, after the king move, Black needs to be aware of another possible reaction by White.} 17. h3 (17. b3 $5 {is a subtle way of preventing ...Bg4, but it weakens the long diagonal, while also wasting a tempo. In a line below, Black will be ready to spend two tempi (...Nc6-a5-c6) in order to provoke b2-b3.} Rd7 {Using the given tempo for starting an active plan, based on increasing the pressure on d4.} (17... Bg4 $6 {runs into the unexpected} 18. Nh4 $1 {threatening Ng6+.} Bxh4 19. Rxf8+ Rxf8 20. Bxg4 $14 {Unfortunately for Black, the pawn on c4 is defended, which is the idea behind b2-b3.}) 18. Rd2 (18. h3 Rfd8 19. d5 exd5 20. cxd5 Nxd5 21. Nxd5 Rxd5 22. Rxd5 Rxd5 23. Bc4 Rd8 24. Re1 Qf8 25. Bf4 Re8 $11 26. Rxe8 Qxe8 27. Bxc7 Be6 {Â½-Â½ Hvenekilde, J (2320)-Jorgensen, J DEN-chT 9394 Denmark 1993 (3)}) (18. Bg1 Rfd8 19. c5 Nd5 20. Bb5 Nxc3 21. Qxc3 Be4 $11) (18. d5 exd5 19. cxd5 Ne5 20. Nd4 Bg4 21. Bxg4 Nxg4 22. Ne6 Rf7 23. Bc5 Qe8 $13 {In view of ...Bxc3, White's space advantage is by far less stable than it may seem.}) 18... Rfd8 19. Rfd1 {Â½-Â½ Grobler, D (1982)-Perrin, R (1865) GBR-ch Res-A 0607 email ICCF email 2006} Bg4 (19... g5 $5 $11 {followed by either ...Bg7 or ...Qg7 and later maybe ...g5-g4, is also interesting.}) (19... Qf7 $5 {[%cal Gb6c8] Planning ...Nc8-d6.}) 20. h3 ({After the rook's departure from the f-file} 20. Nh4 {leads nowhere due to} Bf5 $1 $11) 20... Bxf3 21. Bxf3 Nxd4 22. Bxb7 c5 23. Be4 Nc8 {Planning ...Nd6.} 24. Na4 Nb6 25. Nb2 Nf5 26. Bf2 Rxd2 27. Rxd2 Nd7 $11 {Black has a good game, due to his control on dark squares.}) (17. Bg1 Bg4 $5 $146 18. Nh4 (18. Ne4 Bxf3 $15 19. Nxf6 $2 Bxe2 $19) 18... Bxh4 19. Rxf8+ Rxf8 20. Bxg4 Bg5 21. Qc2 Nxc4 22. Qe2 Nd6 23. Bxe6 Re8 24. Re1 Nd8 25. d5 Bh4 26. g3 Bf6 $11) (17. d5 Ne5 {The simplest. By keeping the pawns on board, Black aims at gaining a tempo by attacking c4.} 18. Bxb6 (18. Nd4 Nexc4 $15) (18. b3 exd5 19. Bxb6 Nxf3 20. Bxf3 Bxc3 21. Qxc3 axb6 22. cxd5 Qd6 $11) 18... axb6 19. Nd4 Bg5 20. Nxf5 (20. Qa1 Ng4) 20... Rxf5 21. Qc2 Rxf1+ 22. Rxf1 c6 23. dxc6 bxc6 24. Qe4 Bf6 25. Qe3 Qb4 26. b3 Nxc4 27. Bxc4 Bxc3 28. Qxe6 Qd6 {Â½-Â½ Capone, N (2127)-Lenaerts, L (2036) BEL-ch U20 Elite Bruges 2012 (3)}) {We have reached another stage of both sides' regrouping. We have seen that the previous sequence had its inner logic from both sides' points of view. The situation will not change during the next phase.} 17... Rd7 {Black starts increasing the pressure on d4, but since this implies a major regrouping of strong pieces, he should choose his later move order with care.} (17... Bh7 {removing the bishop from the f-file, in order to make ...e6-e5 an issue, is also playable.} 18. Bg1 Qe8 $5 $146 {Trying to improve Black's overall harmony.} 19. Nb5 (19. Rfe1 Qf7 20. Bf1 Nc8 21. c5 N8e7 22. Bc4 Nd5 23. a3 g5 24. b4 a6 $11) (19. b3 Nc8 20. Nb5 Rf7 $11) 19... Rd7 20. b3 a6 21. Nc3 Nc8 22. Bd3 (22. c5 N8e7 $11) 22... Bxd3 23. Rxd3 Nd6 24. Re1 Nf5 25. Qd1 (25. d5 Qg6 $132) 25... Qd8 {Already a perfect regrouping.} 26. Rxe6 (26. Ne4 Be7 $11) 26... Nb4 27. Rd2 Bg5 28. Nxg5 (28. Rf2 Ng3+ 29. Kh2 Bf4 $11) 28... Ng3+ 29. Kh2 Nf1+ 30. Kh1 Ng3+ $11 {with a draw by perpetual.}) 18. Bg1 {A good prophylactical move, removing the bishop from a vulnerable square. More about it is below.} (18. c5 {is premature.} Nd5 19. Bb5 Qd8 $1 $146 20. Bg1 Rdf7 $11 {We can notice that Black;'s regrouping is by far more harmonious than in the old correspondence game below.}) (18. d5 {runs into the familiar.} Ne5 $1 19. b3 (19. Nd4 Nexc4 $11) 19... Nxf3 20. Bxf3 exd5 21. Rde1 Qd8 22. Nxd5 Bh4 23. Bc5 Bxe1 24. Bxf8 Qxf8 25. Qxe1 c6 26. Nxb6 axb6 $11 {Â½-Â½ Glaser, K (2242)-Pavlov, V (2427) VW-Cup8 sf07 email ICCF email 2017}) 18... a6 $1 $146 {Defending b5 before continuing the main plan.} ({The correspondence game continued with the premature} 18... Rfd8 {As mentioned before, this is a committal regrouping and needs to be handled with care.} 19. c5 Nd5 20. Bb5 {Black is solid, but a bit passive. With his rook immobile on d7, he will not find it easy to free himself from the pin.} Ndb4 21. a3 Nc2 22. Ne2 $1 (22. Bxc6 {This is an unnecessary concession.} bxc6 23. Ne2 Be4 $11 {Â½-Â½ Zaitsev, A-Zilberberg, A Lenin mem corr7073 USSR 1970}) 22... Be4 23. Nf4 {Black is hanging a bit and g6 is vulnerable.} e5 24. dxe5 Rxd1 25. exf6 Qxf6 26. Rxd1 $14) 19. Rd2 {Preparing to defend d4.} (19. b3 Rfd8 20. Qf4 Qb4 (20... g5 $5 21. Qg3 Qg7 $13) 21. Rc1 Nxd4 22. Nxd4 Bxd4 23. Bxd4 Rxd4 24. Qxc7 R4d7 25. Qe5 Nc8 $11 {followed by ...Ne7 and then either ...Ng6 or ...Nc6.}) 19... Qd8 20. Qd1 {The most harmonious regrouping.} (20. Rfd1 {leaves the queen out of play.} Nc8 $5 {Heading for d6 and then either e4 or f5.} 21. d5 (21. b3 Nd6 22. Bd3 Bxd3 23. Rxd3 e5 24. d5 Nb4 25. R3d2 Qe8 $11 {followed by ...e5-e4, for instance} 26. a3 $6 e4 $1 $15) 21... exd5 22. Nxd5 Nd6 {Black has not lost his coordination any single bit.} 23. Nxf6 (23. Bh2 Ne4 24. Nxf6 Rxd2 25. Nxd2 Nf2+ {Taking advantage of the rook's departure from f1.} 26. Kg1 Qd4 27. Nf3 Nxh3+ 28. Kh1 Nf2+ 29. Kg1 $11) 23... Qxf6 24. c5 Ne4 25. Rxd7 Ng3+ 26. Kh2 Nxe2 27. Qe3 Nxg1 28. Kxg1 Bxd7 29. Rxd7 Qxb2 $11) {Another critical moment in the mutual regrouping plan.} 20... Na5 $5 {Hitting onto the hidden drawback of White's regrouping. By forcing b2-b3, Black will leave the knight on c3 hanging a bit. For achieving that, he does not hesitate to spend two tempi.} ({With the actual white regrouping,} 20... Nc8 $6 {is likely to face Black with serious problems after} 21. d5 exd5 22. Nxd5 Nd6 23. Bh2 Ne4 24. Nxf6 Rxd2 25. Nxd2 Rxf6 26. Nxe4 Qxd1 27. Bxd1 Bxe4 28. Rxf6 gxf6 29. Bxc7 $16) (20... g5 21. d5 $14) 21. b3 (21. c5 Nbc4 22. Bxc4 Nxc4 23. Re2 b6 $11) 21... Nc6 {After this simple move, White will face serious problems undertaking anything concrete. Part of his pieces are tied up to the defense of the d4-pawn, while d4-d5 is impossible now.} (21... c5 {is also possible.} 22. Nb1 (22. Bd3 Bxd3 23. Rxd3 Nc6 24. d5 Nb4 25. Bxc5 Nxd3 26. Bxf8 Nf4 $13) 22... Nc6 (22... cxd4 23. Nxd4 Bg5 24. Rxf5 Rxf5 25. Rd3 Rf6 26. Nc3 $14) 23. dxc5 Rxd2 24. Qxd2 Qxd2 25. Nbxd2 Nd7 $44 {Due to his active minor pieces, Black has certain compensation for the pawn. Proving that in a game might be uneasy, so I clearly prefer the main line.}) 22. a3 $5 {White maintains his existing setup and starts gaining some space.At this stage, it is clear that he does not have obvious constructive plans. The position is statically (or is it dynamically?!) balanced, and each player has to be careful not to disturb this balance to his disfavor.} (22. Bf2 g5 $5) (22. Re1 {releases the latent pressure along the f-file, allowing} e5 23. d5 e4 $11) 22... Kg8 $5 {The same as in the case of ...Nc6-a5-c6, this is not a tacit draw offer. We have to get used to the idea that after both sides have completed their development, each move should serve a small purpose in the given concrete situation. The last move over defends the rook on f8, preparing to retreat with the f5-bishop without freeing White from the task of defending d4.} ({Concretely,} 22... Bg6 {allows} 23. Qc1 {True, this is not such a problem, since Black can continue his apparently waiting game.} Na5 $5 ({The point is that} 23... Nxd4 $2 {loses to} 24. Nxd4 Bxd4 25. Rxf8+ Qxf8 26. Rxd4 $18) (23... Bf5 {is also possible, renewing the threat on d4 and inviting White to allow a move repetition. The natural way of avoiding that is} 24. Rfd1 {but then} Nc8 $11 {is fine for Black, for similar reasons as above.}) 24. Qb2 Nc6 {In these lines, Black is playing for a move repetition and due to the hidden static and dynamics of the position, White can do little to unbalance things. In fact, starting with a certain stage, this is the tendency in this system.}) (22... Rff7 $5) 23. b4 Bg6 {White has count with both ...e6-e5 and ...Bg4 now.} 24. Qe1 $5 Bf5 (24... Nxd4 $2 25. Nxd4 Bxd4 26. Rxf8+ Kxf8 27. Bxd4 Rxd4 28. Qf2+) (24... Bxd4 $5 25. Nxd4 Rxf1 26. Bxf1 Nxd4 27. c5 Nf5 28. Rxd7 Nxd7 29. Qxe6+ Kh7 30. Bf2 Nf6 {Black's harmonious regrouping compensates for White's bishops' pair.}) 25. Qf2 (25. g4 Bg6 $11 {mainly weakens White's kingside, without providing him with a constructive plan.}) (25. Qd1 $11) 25... g5 $5 26. Qe3 Bg7 $13 {Black's regrouping looks better than ever. He is ready to continue the positional fight and his chances are not worse. I would like to sum up things regarding the main tabiya after 12...Bxf6, examined in Lines 35 to 37. After both sides completed the development, White needs to play accurately in order to prevent Black from equalizing at once or getting immediate counterplay. In phase 2, it is Black who needs to keep his play fluent, based on tiny details. Phase 3 is characterized by "mutual watching" and equality depending on subtle issues. In the last position, things start to look a bit more lively, at least for Black, but equality is still there.} *

