1. e4 Nf6 2. e5 Nd5 3. d4 d6 4. c4 Nb6 5. f4 Bf5 {Since the Four Pawns Attack is a critical system, with many wrongly thinking that it refutes the Alekhine Defence, it makes sense to have a reserve weapon as an alternative to the main line examined above. The system offered below allows Black to at least avoid the dangerous lines with an early d4-d5, while against White's by far most popular move order, it introduces a whole new system. As mentioned earlier, the last move can lead to a transposition, but not necessarily. By refraining from the exchange on e5, Black keeps the possibility of breaking the centre with ...d6-d5, leading to completely different structures than above.. While working on this database, I examined again (for the nth time) all the games in which Fischer played the Alekhine Defence. My attention was caught by the relatively unknown draw with Ujtumen. Never before had I noticed that Fischer did not take on e5. True, after a few moves, Ujtumen released the tension himself, causing the game to lose part of its theoretical interest, but I was curious to guess which could have been Fischer's idea. The result of my research lies ahead.} 6. Nc3 e6 7. Be3 (7. Nf3 {is another move order.} Be7 8. Be2 {This is rarely played but induces Black to change his initial plans.} ({Most of the games continue with} 8. Be3 {, transposing.}) 8... dxe5 {With the white bishop on c1, Black does not have anything better than switching back to the main line, after having avoided the optically dangerous lines with an early d4-d5.} 9. fxe5 {The only move tried in practice.} (9. Nxe5 {Black has a choice now.} N8d7 (9... c5 $6 {may be premature.} 10. dxc5 (10. d5 exd5 11. cxd5 O-O 12. O-O Bd6 13. g4 Bc8 14. a4 a5 $13) 10... Qxd1+ 11. Bxd1 $1 (11. Kxd1 Bxc5 12. g4 Bg6 13. h4 {It may seem that the vulnerability of the bishop puts Black in some trouble, but he has enough resources.} Na6 14. h5 Rd8+ 15. Bd2 (15. Ke1 Bc2 $13) 15... Be3 16. Nf3 Bxd2 17. Nxd2 Bd3 $11) 11... Bxc5 12. g4 Bg6 13. h4 $14) 10. O-O (10. g4 Nxe5 11. gxf5 Bh4+ 12. Kf1 Nc6 $15) 10... O-O 11. Be3 (11. g4 Nxe5 12. fxe5 Bg6 13. Be3 c5 14. d5 Nd7 15. Bf4 Bg5 16. Qd2 Bxf4 17. Qxf4 exd5 18. cxd5 Qe7 $13) 11... h6 {Finally clearing the h7-square for the bishop.} 12. Qd2 c5 13. d5 exd5 14. cxd5 Nc8 15. g4 Bh7 16. Nxd7 Qxd7 17. f5 Nd6 {Such a blocking knight is likely to keep the position together, even though for the time being the bishop on h7 is passive. In the long run, it could return into play with ...Kh8, ...f7-f6 and ...Bg8, or maybe ...g7-g6.} 18. Bxh6 (18. Bxc5 Nxf5 $11) (18. Rad1 Rfc8 {taking measures against the sacrifice while defending c5.}) 18... gxh6 19. f6 Rfe8 20. fxe7 Rxe7 21. Qxh6 Rae8 22. Bf3 Re5 23. Rad1 b5 $44 {Black's optimally placed pieces fully compensate for the pawn.}) (9. dxe5 Qxd1+ 10. Kxd1 Nc6 11. Be3 O-O-O+ 12. Ke1 Nb4 $15) 9... Nc6 10. O-O (10. d5 {Â½-Â½ Krejcik, J (2155)-Herskovic, R (2165) CZE-chT2b 0506 Czech Republic 2005 (9.2) is ineffective now, for two main reasons. The check on b5 would suppose a loss of tempo, while the knight on d4 is not defended by the queen's bishop.} exd5 11. cxd5 Nb4 12. Nd4 Bc8 13. Bb5+ c6 14. dxc6 O-O 15. cxb7 Bxb7 16. O-O Bc5 17. Be3 Qc7 $11) 10... O-O 11. Be3 {There is not anything better now.} (11. Bf4 {apart from ...f7-f6, with an improved version of the main lines, since d4 is less well defended, Black could also try the violent} g5 12. Be3 g4 13. Ne1 Bg5 14. Bf2 h5 $132) 11... f6 {transposing to the previous main lines.}) 7... Be7 8. Nf3 O-O {After the exchange on e5, I have advocated the early queen's knight's development. This would be desirable here, too, in order to inhibit Bd3, but there is a concrete problem with that.} ({In the event of} 8... Nc6 $6 {the central break is stronger than after the previous exchange on e5.} 9. d5 (9. Bd3 {allows} dxe5 10. fxe5 Bg4 {transposing to a position examined before.}) ({Another possible problem with this move order is that after} 9. Be2 d5 10. c5 Nc4 11. Bxc4 dxc4 12. Qa4 Bd3 13. O-O-O {threatening Ne1, Black does not have the possibility of securing the pawn on c4 by offering the queen exchange with ...Qd7, as in Line 39 below.}) 9... exd5 10. cxd5 Nb4 11. Bxb6 $1 axb6 (11... Nc2+ 12. Kd2 axb6 13. Rc1 Nb4 14. a3 Na6 15. Nd4 $14) 12. Nd4 Bg6 (12... Bd7 13. e6 fxe6 14. dxe6 Bc6 15. Nxc6 Nxc6 16. Bc4 $14 {In the absence of the d6 and f4-pawns, the position is equal, but here White has a considerable space advantage and a relatively mobile kingside majority.}) 13. Bb5+ Kf8 {1-0 Hamalainen,S (2168)-Eskelinen,A (2212) FIN-chT 0203 Finland 2002 (6.7)} 14. e6 Bh4+ 15. g3 Bf6 16. O-O Bd3 (16... Bxd4+ 17. Qxd4 Nc2 18. Qd2 Nxa1 19. f5 Bh5 20. f6 $5 $18) 17. Nde2 $14) 9. exd6 {This was Ujtumen's choice.} (9. b3 {takes measures against ...d6-d5, but Black is not forced to stick to the initial plan. Instead, he can switch to the system examined in Lines 35 to 37, where such an early b2-b3 does not make sense.} dxe5 $1 10. fxe5 Nc6 (10... Bb4 11. Qd2 c5 $132) 11. Bd3 ({In the event of} 11. Be2 f6 12. exf6 Bxf6 13. O-O {Black can resort to the familiar} Qe8 $5 $11) 11... Bb4 12. Qd2 Nxd4 $1 13. Nxd4 Bxd3 14. Qxd3 c5 $11) (9. Be2 {is examined in Line 39.}) ({The critical} 9. Bd3 {is the subject of Lines 40 and 41.}) 9... cxd6 10. b3 {Ujtumen takes preventive measures against the knight's intrusion to c4.} (10. Bd3 {allows Black to carry out his main idea.} Bxd3 11. Qxd3 d5 12. c5 Nc4 13. Bc1 (13. Bf2 Nc6 14. b3 Na3 15. O-O Bf6 $11) 13... b6 14. b3 Na5 15. Be3 bxc5 16. dxc5 Nbc6 17. O-O d4 18. Nxd4 Bxc5 $11 {Â½-Â½ Bobis, L-Chessakov, Z Nathanya-11 Open 1973 (7)}) (10. Be2 {does not cross Black's intentions, either.} Nc6 {is not a bad alternative to the immediate break in the centre.} ({The immediate break with} 10... d5 {is entirely possible.} 11. c5 Nc4 12. Bxc4 dxc4 13. Qa4 Bd3 14. Ne5 {The bishop and the defending pawn seem to be in some danger, but Black's better development and control on light squares yield him excellent dynamic resources.} Nc6 15. Nxd3 {Accepting the pawn sacrifice on c6 would be too dangerous since the bishop would have a dominating position.} cxd3 16. O-O-O Rb8 $5 {Preparing the opening of the queenside. It appears that Rxd3 is no real threat in view of ...Bxc5.} 17. Qc4 b5 18. Nxb5 {Otherwise ...b5-b4 with promising initiative.} Qc8 {Threatening ...Qb7.} 19. Nc3 (19. Rxd3 Qb7 20. Rb3 Na5 $19) 19... Rd8 20. Kb1 {It is remarkable that six moves after Ne5, White can still not take the lonely pawn under favorable circumstances.} (20. Rxd3 Rb4 {traps the queen.}) (20. Qxd3 Bxc5 $15) 20... Bf6 $5 21. Qxd3 Bxd4 22. Bxd4 Rxd4 23. Qe2 Rdb4 24. Rd2 Nd4 25. Qe3 Qxc5 $36) 11. Qd2 (11. O-O d5 12. c5 Nc4 13. Bxc4 dxc4 14. Qa4 Bd3 15. Rfd1 Bf6 16. b3 Qa5 17. Qxa5 Nxa5 $11) (11. d5 exd5 12. Nxd5 Nxd5 13. Qxd5 Be6 14. Qd2 d5 $11) 11... d5 12. c5 Nd7 (12... Nc4 {is more natural.} 13. Bxc4 dxc4 14. O-O Qd7 15. Rfd1 Rfd8 16. b3 cxb3 17. axb3 Qe8 18. Qe2 Nb4 $15 {[%cal Gb7b6] followed by ...b7-b6.}) 13. O-O b6 14. cxb6 Nxb6 15. Rfc1 Na5 {All Black's minor pieces contribute to the queenside counterplay.} 16. Ne5 (16. b3 Ba3 $36) 16... f6 $15 17. Nb5 $5 a6 $1 (17... fxe5 18. Qxa5 Nc4 19. Qxd8 Raxd8 20. Bxc4 exf4 21. Bxf4 dxc4 22. Be5 $11 {0-1 Diaz Vega, P-Lopez ESP-ch sf corr Spain 1990}) 18. Nc7 (18. Na3 Na4 19. Nc6 Nxc6 20. Rxc6 Qd7 21. Rxa6 Rxa6 22. Bxa6 Rb8 23. b3 Bb4 24. Qc1 Qd6 $17) 18... fxe5 19. Qxa5 Nc4 20. Bxc4 dxc4 21. Rxc4 (21. Qxe5 Bd6 22. Nxe6 Qe7) (21. dxe5 Rb8 {[%cal Ge7b4,Gb8b2]} 22. Bb6 Bd3 $17) 21... exf4 22. Bxf4 Bd3 $17) (10. d5 $146 {White's delay in development and the weakness on e4 make such an early space gain at least ineffective if not risky.} exd5 11. Bxb6 (11. cxd5 Re8 12. Be2 Bf6 13. Bd4 N8d7 $11) (11. Nxd5 Re8 {[%cal Ge7h4]} 12. Kf2 Nxd5 13. Qxd5 Be4 14. Qd2 Nc6 15. Rd1 d5 16. cxd5 Bb4 17. Qc1 Ne7 18. d6 Nd5 $17) 11... axb6 12. Nxd5 Bf6 13. Qd2 (13. Nxf6+ Qxf6 14. Qd2 Nc6 15. Be2 Rfd8 16. O-O Be4 $11 17. Qe3 Qxb2 18. Qxe4 Re8 19. Rfb1 Qxa1 20. Qxe8+ Rxe8 21. Rxa1 Rxe2 22. Rb1 $44) 13... Be4 14. Be2 Bxd5 15. cxd5 Nd7 16. O-O b5 $11) 10... d5 11. c5 N6d7 {We notice a small deviation from the trajectories examined in the classical system, Lines 2 to 9.} ({With the bishop on e7 instead of g7,} 11... Nc8 {may be too slow.} 12. Bd3 Bxd3 13. Qxd3 Nc6 14. O-O Bf6 15. Rab1 N8e7 16. g4 $1 {Prventing ...Nf5.} g6 17. b4 a6 18. a4 Bg7 {The bishop has reached this square after wasting two tempi. White does not have to hurry with b4-b5, inviting the knight to a5-c4, but can first improve his position gradually with} 19. Kg2 $5 $14) 12. Bd3 Bxd3 13. Qxd3 b6 {Black has solved all the opening problems and can think of fighting for some minimal plus due to his compact structure.} 14. cxb6 (14. b4 a5 $15) 14... Qxb6 15. O-O Qa6 16. Qd1 (16. Qxa6 Nxa6 17. f5 Nb4 $11) 16... Nc6 17. Ne5 Ncxe5 {Keeping the d7-knight for the purpose of breaking in the centre.} (17... Ndxe5 18. fxe5 Rac8 {would have allowed Black to use more pieces for his queenside play. On the other hand, White could have got some chances on the kingside.}) 18. fxe5 Rac8 19. Rc1 f6 20. exf6 Nxf6 $11 {Â½-Â½ Ujtumen,T-Fischer,R Interzonal-08 Palma de Mallorca 1970 (16)} *

