{[%evp 0,38,25,25,37,37,37,35,34,21,21,20,31,34,26,26,26,29,31,2,6,-12,6,10,10,-3,-6,8,8,8,16,-35,0,-22,-11,-17,-2,-2,-35,-35,-78]} 1. e4 Nf6 2. e5 Nd5 3. d4 d6 4. c4 Nb6 5. f4 Bf5 {poate asa} 6. Nc3 e6 7. Be3 Be7 8. Nf3 O-O 9. Be2 {White develops in the same way as in Lines 35 to 37, but Black is not forced to transpose to that system. It is interesting that players like Kortschnoj and Larsen have used this move order in the '60s, without yielding it any independent value, since they soon took on e5.} d5 {Probably part of Fischer's preparation, but as we know he was not given the possibility to use it. In Palma de Mallorca 1970, it would have been a novelty. Black actually played it for the first time during the 1978 women Olympiad (see below).} 10. c5 {The obvious and most consistent move.} (10. cxd5 {is an obvious concession. This is the way how the first game ever with this line continued:} Nxd5 11. Nxd5 Qxd5 12. O-O Nc6 $1 ({Which does not mean that many decades later, such concessions were unthinkable:} 12... c5 13. Rc1 Nc6 14. dxc5 {1-0 Alexakis, D (2486)-Trybus, D (2258) EU-ch Blitz Katowice 2022 (8)} Qxa2 $11) 13. a3 (13. b3 $6 {0-1 Meglitsch, K (2052)-Rogulj, B (2397) Oberwart op-A 34th 2012 (1)} Nb4 {The possibility of this knight jump makes the move from the older game better.} 14. Bf2 Qe4 15. g3 Bg4 $15) 13... Rfd8 14. Qd2 Na5 15. Bd1 $2 (15. Rad1 Rac8 $11) 15... Nc4 16. Qc3 Nxe3 17. Qxe3 c5 $17 {0-1 Ferrari Frei,C-Shikova,V (2115) Olympiad Women-08 Preliminaries 4 Buenos Aires 1978 (4)}) (10. b3 {consolidates the center but is likely to lose material.} Bb4 11. Qd2 {0-1 (100) Vinas Racionero, J (2130)-Romeu de la Cruz, J (1895) Vilafranca del Penedes 2012} (11. Rc1 Ba3 {wins the exchange.}) (11. Bd2 dxc4 12. bxc4 Nc6 $15) 11... dxc4 $15 12. bxc4 Na4 13. Rc1 c5 $17) 10... Nc4 11. Bxc4 ({If White wishes to keep the light-squared bishop, the most desirable retreat is} 11. Bf2 {, keeping c5 over-defended in view of the typical break with ...b7-b6. However, with his bishop on f5, Black can bravely take the pawn on b2È˜} Nxb2 12. Qb3 Nd3+ 13. Bxd3 Bxd3 14. Nxd5 (14. Qxb7 Na6 {Threatening ...Nb4.} 15. a3 Rb8 16. Qc6 Rb2 $17) 14... Qxd5 15. Qxd3 Bxc5 $15) ({Therefore, the only way of keeping both bishops is} 11. Bc1 b6 12. b3 Na5 13. Be3 {Yhe bishop has to return to the initial diagonal.} (13. cxb6 axb6 {is an obvious concession.} 14. O-O c5 15. Nb5 Nbc6 $15 {for instance} 16. Bb2 Qd7 17. a4 Rfc8 $15) (13. Na4 bxc5 14. Nxc5 {Otherwise, ...f7-f6.} Nd7 15. Nxd7 Qxd7 16. Be3 Rfb8 17. O-O Nc6 18. h3 a5 19. a3 Rb6 20. Ra2 Rab8 21. Nd2 Na7 $11 {followed by ...Rc6 and ...Nb5.}) 13... bxc5 ({More active than} 13... Nd7 14. Na4 c6 15. Rc1 b5 16. Nb2 Nb7 17. O-O Qc7 18. Bd3 Bxd3 19. Nxd3 f5 20. Ng5 Bxg5 21. fxg5 g6 22. Nf4 Rfe8 23. h4 Nf8 {White's position looks by far more active, but breaking Black's fortress is not easy. The engines' evaluation "î€Š" may be exaggerated. But anyway, we do not need to head for such a position.} 24. Qc2 a5 25. a3 a4 26. b4 Nd8 {0-1 (45) Laurencena, A-Wright, J corr 1978}) 14. dxc5 Nbc6 15. O-O f6 16. exf6 (16. Nb5 fxe5 17. fxe5 Be4 $11) (16. Qd2 fxe5 17. fxe5 a6 {Preventing Nb5 and preparing the next manoeuvre.} 18. Rad1 Qe8 $11) 16... Bxf6 17. Nd4 Nxd4 18. Bxd4 Nc6 19. Bxf6 Qxf6 $11) 11... dxc4 {Is the pawn on c4 a weakness or strength?} 12. d5 (12. Qe2 {is just a waste of time.} Bd3 13. Qd2 Nc6 14. b3 b6 15. bxc4 Bxc4 16. cxb6 axb6 $19 {1-0 (25) Bhandarkar, D (1569)-Fioravanti, D (1569) FICGS email 2008}) (12. Qa4 Bd3 13. O-O-O {Threatening Nd1.} Qd7 {eliminating the danger looming around the c4-pawn.} 14. b3 Qxa4 15. Nxa4 b5 16. Nc3 c6 $1 (16... b4 17. Rxd3 $1 (17. Na4 Be2 18. Rde1 Bxf3 19. gxf3 c3 $19) 17... cxd3 18. Na4 f6 19. Kd2 Nc6 20. Kxd3 Rfd8 $13) 17. Ne1 Bg6 18. bxc4 bxc4 19. g4 Na6 20. Rf1 f6 $15 {Â½- (49) Â½ (49) Hebert, J-Wright, J corr 1977}) 12... exd5 13. Qxd5 Qxd5 14. Nxd5 Bd8 {White seems to have the initiative, but the weaknesses on light squares will stay.} 15. Nd4 (15. Nd2 {0-1 (16) Martinez Martin,D (2403)-Nogueiras Santiago,J (2501) Havana 2018} Be6 16. Nc3 f6 $15) 15... Be4 16. Nc3 Bd3 {Modest and good.} (16... Bxg2 17. Rg1 Bh3 $13 18. f5 $6 Nc6 $15 19. f6 Nxe5 20. Rxg7+ Kh8 21. Rg3 Bd7 22. Bh6 Nd3+ 23. Rxd3 (23. Kd2 Bxf6) 23... cxd3 24. Bg7+ (24. Bxf8 Bxf6) 24... Kg8 25. Kd2 Re8 26. Rg1 h6 $17) 17. O-O-O (17. b3 f6 $5 18. e6 (18. Ne6 Re8 19. Nxd8 fxe5 20. fxe5 Rxd8 $15) 18... Nc6 19. Nxc6 bxc6 20. g4 f5 21. g5 Re8 $11) 17... c6 (17... Be7 $5 18. Nd5 (18. Ndb5 Na6 $15) (18. c6 bxc6 $15) 18... Bxc5 19. Nxc7 Nc6 20. Nxa8 Nxd4 21. Rxd3 (21. Bxd4 Bxd4 22. Nc7 Be3+ 23. Rd2 Bxf4 $17) (21. Nc7 Ne2+ 22. Kd2 Bb4# {Such things happen in the endgame, too...}) 21... cxd3 22. Nc7 Nb3+ 23. Kd1 $1 {The only way of surviving.} (23. axb3 Bxe3+ 24. Kd1 Rc8 $19) 23... Bxe3 24. Nd5 Bxf4 25. Nxf4 Nc5 $15) 18. g4 (18. b3 $13) 18... Na6 19. Nf5 {Â½- (35) Â½ (35) Sukovic,A (2356)-Rogulj,B (2363) Bihac 2022} f6 $15 *

