{[%evp 0,46,25,8,37,37,37,35,35,21,21,31,26,26,29,29,29,31,9,10,26,23,51,29,48,48,50,19,43,62,85,80,88,79,80,70,89,77,81,80,93,81,77,41,56,62,69,61,49]} 1. e4 Nf6 2. e5 Nd5 3. d4 d6 4. c4 Nb6 5. f4 Bf5 {poate asa} 6. Nc3 e6 7. Be3 Be7 8. Nf3 O-O 9. Bd3 {[%cal Bb8c6,Bf5g4] We are aware of this way of developing in situations where Black does not play ...Nc6 early.} d5 {Switching to the main plan, as in the previous line.} (9... Bxd3 10. Qxd3 d5 {runs into} 11. b3 $14 {, when Black has no adequate ways of undermining White's space advantage.}) ({As we know, with the knight on b8 still,} 9... Bg4 {does not produce the desired effect.} 10. O-O $14) 10. b3 {This is less effective than with the queen on d3 already.} (10. c5 {is likely to transpose elsewhere, but can also have independent value.} Nc4 {[%csl Rd3][%cal Gc4b2]} 11. Bc1 (11. Bxf5 exf5 {transposes to Line 41 below.}) (11. Bxc4 dxc4 {transposes to Line 39 above.}) (11. Bf2 $2 Nxb2 {wins material.}) 11... Bxd3 12. Qxd3 b6 {AFter exchanging the light-squared bishops, this typical queenside counterplay yields Black comfortable play.} 13. b3 Na5 14. b4 {This is t only way of maintaining the structural integrity, but it concedes control over the c4-square.} Nc4 15. Rb1 a5 16. a3 axb4 17. axb4 bxc5 18. bxc5 f5 19. O-O Nc6 $11 {Â½-Â½ Sahin, D (1974)-Darban Vaighani, M (2321) Mersin op 2017 (3)}) (10. Bxf5 {is examined in Line 41.}) 10... dxc4 11. bxc4 Bb4 {This gains an important tempo with respect to the similar line with the intermediate ...Bxd3, since the knight on c3 is undefended.} 12. Rc1 {Absolutely forced.} (12. Qd2 $2 Na4 $17) (12. Qc2 $2 Nxc4 $1 13. Bxf5 Nxe3 14. Bxh7+ Kh8 $17) 12... c5 {The game move may lead to interesting play, but may not be objectively the best.} (12... Bxd3 $1 $146 13. Qxd3 c5 {is simpler.} 14. d5 ({Black might have feared} 14. Ng5 {, but White's attack is not dangerous.} g6 15. O-O cxd4 16. Nce4 dxe3 17. Nf6+ Kg7 18. Nh5+ $11 {with a draw by perpetual. Black should not try to avoid it:} Kh8 $2 19. Nxf7+ Rxf7 20. Qxd8+ Rf8 21. Qd3 gxh5 22. c5 Nd5 23. f5 $36) 14... exd5 15. Ng5 (15. cxd5 Nxd5 $1) 15... g6 16. O-O dxc4 17. Qe2 Bxc3 18. Rxc3 Nc6 19. Bxc5 Na4 20. Rxc4 Nxc5 21. Rxc5 Qd4+ 22. Qf2 Rfd8 $11) 13. Bxf5 {The critical continuation.} ({The game went} 13. O-O cxd4 14. Nxd4 Bxd3 15. Qxd3 {1-0 Dominguez Perez,L (2683)-Nogueiras Santiago,J (2549) Carlos Torre Wimbledon 20th Merida 2007 (1.3)} Nc6 $1 16. Ncb5 Na4 17. Nd6 Nxd4 18. Qxd4 Bc5 19. Qd2 f6 (19... b6 $11) 20. Bxc5 Nxc5 21. Qe3 b6 $11) 13... exf5 14. O-O (14. d5 Nxc4 15. Bd2 b5 $11 {yields Black good counterplay. Together with the extra pawn, it compensates for White's massive centre.}) 14... Nxc4 15. Bf2 {Black has won a pawn, but White's better development and central control should not be underestimated.} cxd4 16. Nxd4 Nc6 17. Nxc6 {Only this offers chances to maintain some initiative.} (17. Nxf5 {retrieves the pawn but yields Black enough counterplay, based on the hanging knight on c3.} Qxd1 18. Rfxd1 Nb2 19. Rd7 (19. Rd5 Rfd8 20. Nd6 Ne7 21. Rd4 Nc6 22. Rd5 Ne7 $11 23. Rb5 {does not offer any chances for an advantage, either.} Nd3 24. Rc2 Bxc3 25. Rxc3 Nxf4 $11) 19... Rfd8 20. Rxd8+ Rxd8 21. Ne4 Nd3 22. Rf1 {Indirectly defending f4.} Rd5 (22... Nxf4 $6 23. Bh4 Ne2+ 24. Kf2 $14) 23. Be3 f6 $11) 17... bxc6 18. Qb3 Bxc3 19. Rfd1 Qb8 20. Qxc3 Nb6 {WHite's advantage is merely symbolic. Retrieving the pawn on c6 would lead to immediate equality.} 21. Qh3 (21. Qxc6 Rc8 22. Qf3 Rxc1 23. Rxc1 Qe8 $11) 21... Rd8 22. Qxf5 Rxd1+ 23. Rxd1 Nd5 $11 {The knight is not weaker than the bishop and Black is ready for starting his counterplay.} *

