{[%evp 0,54,17,20,37,37,45,37,37,31,31,26,29,29,31,31,31,34,26,34,30,10,39,70,64,71,76,78,74,74,78,65,70,74,70,68,70,61,71,58,88,87,59,26,45,29,71,72,86,91,86,61,63,66,66,41,61]} 1. e4 Nf6 2. e5 Nd5 3. d4 d6 4. c4 Nb6 5. f4 Bf5 {poate asa} 6. Nc3 e6 7. Be3 Be7 8. Nf3 O-O 9. Bd3 d5 10. Bxf5 {The critical continuation, slightly weakening Black's control in the centre, but also helping him to organize a kingside blockade.} exf5 ({The intermediate} 10... Nxc4 $2 {runs into} 11. Bb1 $1 Nxe3 12. Qd3 Nxg2+ 13. Kf2 g6 14. Kxg2 $16) 11. c5 Nc4 12. Bf2 {As mentioned in a previous comment to a similar situation, the most desirable retreat. The bishop is ready to over-defend c5 after the expectable ...b7-b6.} (12. Bc1 {offers Black easier play.} b6 13. b3 Na5 14. Be3 Nbc6 15. Rc1 Qd7 16. O-O Nb7 {The knight initiates its maneuver towards the perfect blocking square on e6.} ({In the game, Black wasted two tempi before carrying out the maneuver, which did not change the evaluation of the position too much.} 16... Rad8 17. Ne2 Rb8 18. Qc2 g6 19. h3 h5 20. Rfd1 Nd8 21. Nc3 Nac6 $11 {1-0 Avila Pavas, S (2435)-Nogueiras Santiago, J (2473) Guillermo Garcia Memorial-A Santa Clara 2022 (1) Black does not have any reasons to worry.}) 17. Qd3 g6 18. Rfd1 Nbd8 19. a3 Ne6 20. b4 a6 {[%cal Gb6b5]} 21. h3 b5 $5 22. g4 Ng7 {Black maintains his stability on light squares all over the board.} 23. g5 a5 {... and can even start active operations.} 24. Rb1 axb4 25. axb4 Rfb8 26. Nxb5 Ra4 27. Bd2 Nxb4 $11) 12... Qd7 $1 $146 {One of the two constructive developing moves.} ({The oldest game in which Black adopted the whole plan based on refraining from ...dxe5 and carrying out ...d6-d5, ended in an opening catastrophe:} 12... Nxb2 $2 13. Qb1 Nc4 14. Qxb7 c6 15. Qxa8 Qc7 16. O-O Na6 17. Nxd5 $1 $18 {1-0 Stein, L-Mikenas, V URS-ch30 Final Yerevan 1962 (8) It is very probable that Fischer knew this game since he was assiduously reading the Soviet chess magazines. He might have drawn his own conclusions.}) (12... c6 $5 {is unnatural, since it deprives the knight on b8 of the c6-square, while also wasting developing time. However, Black's position is so flexible and solid, while his knights are so versatile, that even such a move is playable. I do not have a clear favorite among this and the two possible ways of getting to the main line, but Black should definitely play better than in the actual game.} 13. b3 Na3 $1 {The knight is routed on the shortest path to... e6!} ({The game continued} 13... Na5 $6 14. Qc2 g6 15. h3 b6 16. g4 $18 {1-0 Kotronias, V (2599)-Baburin, A (2527) Olympiad-36 Mallorca 2004 (6)}) 14. Qc1 (14. Qd3 {surprisingly helps Black to develop.} Na6 $1 {Based on} 15. Qxf5 $6 g6 16. Qd3 Nb4 $15 {winning the exchange.}) 14... Nb5 15. Ne2 (15. Nxb5 cxb5 {offers Black another blocking square on c6.} 16. Qc2 Qd7 17. O-O Nc6 $11) 15... b6 ({The knight's transfer to e6 makes part of Black's plan, but} 15... Nc7 {is a bit premature since the knight could have things to do on the queenside.}) 16. Qc2 (16. b4 a5 17. a3 axb4 18. axb4 Na6 $11) 16... Qd7 17. h3 {White's only active plan is based on g2-g4.} bxc5 18. dxc5 g6 19. Rd1 {Overdefending d3.} ({Here is what could happen if White started an attack without preparing it properly.} 19. Rg1 Na6 20. a3 d4 $1 21. Nexd4 Nxc5 22. Nxb5 Nd3+ $15) 19... a5 20. Rg1 (20. O-O Na6 $11) 20... a4 $5 (20... Na6 21. g4 fxg4 22. hxg4 f5 $11) 21. g4 axb3 22. axb3 fxg4 23. hxg4 f5 $11 {I may even prefer Black's position slightly.}) (12... Nc6 $1 $146 {is another way of reaching the main line setup.} 13. b3 N4a5 14. Qc2 Qd7 {transposing.}) 13. b3 Na5 (13... Na3 {is also possible. It would make less sense if Black had played ...Nc6 instead of ...Qd7. In the actual position, the knight can return into play with ...Nb5 followed by ...c7-c6 and ...Nc7-e6.} 14. Qe2 {Preventing ...Nb5.} (14. O-O Nb5 15. Ne2 c6 16. a4 Nc7 17. b4 b6 $11 {[%cal Gg7g6,Gc7e6,Gd7c7,Gb8d7]}) (14. Bh4 Nc6 15. O-O b5 16. Qd3 g6) (14. Qd3 Nc6 15. O-O a5 $11 {[%cal Gb7b6]}) (14. h4 h5 $11) 14... a6 15. h3 (15. O-O Nc6 $11) 15... Nc6 16. Rg1 {Preparing the kingside attack.} b6 17. g4 (17. cxb6 $2 Bb4 $19 18. Qd2 Nb5) 17... bxc5 18. dxc5 Nb5 (18... d4 $5 19. O-O-O Bxc5 20. gxf5 Nb5 21. Nxb5 axb5 $132) 19. Nxb5 axb5 20. Nd4 ({In the event of} 20. Qxb5 $2 {Black can take on e5, of course, but even stronger is} Rfb8 21. Qd3 {Preventing ...Rxb3.} Rb4 {With the strong initiative, for instance} 22. Qxf5 Re4+ 23. Kf1 Qe8 {Threatening to trap the queen with ...g6.} 24. g5 Nd8 25. Kg2 Ne6 26. Bg3 Bxc5 $17) 20... Nxd4 (20... Bxc5 {leads to a wilder structure.} 21. Nxc6 Qxc6 22. gxf5 d4 $13) 21. Bxd4 Ra6 22. O-O-O f6 $11) 14. Qc2 Nbc6 15. h3 g6 {[%cal Gb7b6]} 16. Rd1 {Consolidating the centre before starting the attack.} (16. g4 {runs into a typical blockading plan.} fxg4 17. hxg4 f5 (17... Qxg4 18. Ke2 $16 {followed by Rag1 is dangerous for Black.}) 18. g5 (18. gxf5 Nb4 19. Qb1 Rxf5 $11) 18... Nd8 $13 {[%cal Gd8e6,Gb7b6] followed by ...Ne6 and ...b7-b6, with a solid and flexible position.}) (16. O-O-O {offers Black a clear queenside target - the king.} b6 17. g4 Rab8 $13 18. gxf5 $6 Nb4 19. Qb1 bxc5 20. dxc5 Bxc5 $1 21. Bxc5 Nxa2+ 22. Qxa2 Nxb3+ 23. Kc2 Qxf5+ 24. Rd3 Nxc5 $17) (16. O-O {frees Black from worries connected with g2-g4.} Nd8 17. Be3 (17. Bh4 Bxh4 18. Nxh4 Nac6 19. Rad1 Ne6 20. Qf2 Kh8 {[%cal Gb7b6] Planning ...b7-b6.} 21. g4 fxg4 22. hxg4 f5 23. gxf5 gxf5 {[%cal Gc6e7,Gf8g8,Ga8f8] followed by ...Rg8 and ...Ne7, with good counterplay.}) 17... Ne6 18. Rad1 b6 19. g4 Ng7 $11 {Black's kingside is solid and he has some queenside play.}) 16... b6 17. Be3 {Still waiting for Black to define his plans while strengthening his position bit by bit.} Rad8 {Black follows the same policy. Before undertaking anything active, he prepares against the most dangerous plan, based on g2-g4.} 18. O-O {Switching to solid play.} (18. g4 {allows Black to reveal his idea:} bxc5 19. dxc5 d4 $1 20. Nxd4 Nxd4 21. Bxd4 Qc6 $132) (18. Qf2 {such a half-waiting move can be answered in a similar way, with, say} Rfe8 {With the queen on f2,} 19. g4 {does not threaten gxf5, allowing Black to choose between several good continuations, one of them being} bxc5 20. dxc5 d4 21. Nxd4 Nxd4 22. Rxd4 Qe6 23. Rxd8 Rxd8 {White is over-expanded and Black has good control on light squares, ensuring him excellent compensation for the pawn.}) (18. Kf2 Nb7 19. a3 a5 20. cxb6 cxb6 {Black will switch to playing on the queenside, starting with ...Rc8.}) ({Preparing g2-g4 with} 18. cxb6 {is best met with} cxb6 $11 {From a strategic point of view, the capture towards the centre is more desirable, but here Black opens the c-file in order to prepare a quick counterplay.} 19. g4 $6 {leads to slight problems for White.} Rc8 $1 20. O-O {Relatively best.} (20. Qb2 Nb4 $36) (20. gxf5 Nb4 21. Qb2 Rxc3 22. Qxc3 Rc8 23. Qb2 Rc2 24. Qb1 Qb5 25. Rd2 Nd3+ 26. Kf1 Rc1+ $17) 20... Nb4 21. Qb2 Rc6 $132 {Black has a strong queenside initiative. The point is that after} 22. a3 $2 Rfc8 $17 {White cannot defend both the c-file and the d3-square.}) 18... Rb8 {After having achieved his initial aim, namely preventing g2-g4, Black also switches back to positional play. The rook clears the d8-square for the knight and prepares a later ...b6-b5.} 19. Kh2 {Maintaining the possibility of advancing the pawns on either wing.} Nb7 20. a3 {Preparing b2=b4.} ({The straightforward} 20. Rg1 {is met in a familiar way:} Nbd8 21. g4 fxg4 22. hxg4 f5 $11) 20... Nba5 $5 {A well-timed adjustment of plans after White has weakened his queenside. The threat ...bxc5 followed by ...Rxb3 is not real yet, since d5 is also hanging, but in the long run, White needs to care about his b3-pawn. In the short term, Black is ready to meet b3-b4 with ...Nc4.} (20... Ncd8 $5) 21. Rg1 h5 22. Bf2 {Preparing b3-b4 without running into a double attack after ...Nc4.} (22. b4 Nc4 23. Bc1 b5 {followed by ...a7-a5.}) 22... b5 {As mentioned, one of the ideas behind ...Rb8. Black threatens to open the b-file with ...b5-b4.} (22... Qe6 {allows White to gain a lot of space.} 23. b4 Nc4 24. b5 N6a5 25. a4 $14) 23. Ne2 (23. g4 {is interesting, but not especially dangerous.} hxg4 24. hxg4 fxg4 25. Nh4 Bxh4 26. Bxh4 f5 $1 {Preventing the paralyzing Bf6.} 27. exf6 (27. Rxg4 fxg4 28. Qxg6+ Qg7 29. Qe6+ Kh8 30. Rh1 Rbe8 31. Qxd5 Qg6 32. Bf6+ Rxf6 33. exf6 Re3 34. Kg2+ Rh3 35. Rxh3+ gxh3+ 36. Kxh3 Qxf6 $11 {White has normal compensation for the piece, but with both kings exposed, the most probable result is a draw by perpetual.}) 27... Kf7 $13 {Because of his hanging queenside pawns, White cannot organize an effective attack against the g4-pawn.}) 23... Kg7 $1 {Black has to be careful when maneuvering with the knights. It is useful to defend the pawn on g6 first.} (23... Nb7 $2 {leaves the knight on c6 insufficiently well defended, running into} 24. g4 hxg4 25. hxg4 fxg4 26. Nh4 Bxh4 27. Bxh4 f5 28. Rxg4 $1 fxg4 29. Qxg6+ Qg7 30. Qxc6 $18) 24. Be1 {Inducing the knight on a5 to make up its mind.} ({In the event of} 24. Bh4 Bxh4 25. Nxh4 Rh8 $5 {it is hard to think of a way of opening the kingside with g2-g4.}) 24... Nb7 25. b4 Nbd8 26. Bd2 Ne6 27. Qd3 (27. g4 $2 hxg4 28. hxg4 fxg4 29. Rxg4 Nexd4 $19) 27... Rh8 $11 {The kingside is secure and on the queenside, Black is not worse.} *

