{[%evp 0,36,29,30,52,92,69,59,59,41,46,14,55,53,55,58,72,74,53,56,56,15,1,17,17,4,53,60,38,36,36,-12,-22,-22,-15,-47,-47,-47,36]} 1. e4 Nf6 2. e5 Nd5 3. d4 d6 4. c4 Nb6 5. exd6 {At this stage, this may look like a concession. We are used to the fact that White consolidates his most advanced pawn with either Nf3 or f2-f4. However, these moves imply some commitment somewhat restricting White's possibilities if he takes on d6 later. By doing it now, WHite is heading to some sort of classical system with a delayed Nf3, in order to prevent ...Bg4. True, play can transpose to Lines 2 to 9 any moment White plays Nf3.} cxd6 ({There have been a decade or two when theory strongly suggested} 5... exd6 6. Nc3 Be7 {, which is a solid alternative. It is refreshing, though, that over the past time, the non-symmetrical capture has restored its older reputation. How old? Hard to say, but in such situations, Fischer always answered exd6 with ...cxd6.}) 6. Nc3 {In principle, White cannot do without this move. The first moment when he will have a choice is on the next move.} (6. Be3 g6 7. d5 Bg7 8. Bd4 {is premature activity.} Bxd4 9. Qxd4 O-O 10. Nc3 e5 $1 {Black aims at opening the centre, in order to take advantage of the white king's presence in the centre.} 11. dxe6 (11. Qd2 f5 12. Nf3 N8d7 13. O-O-O Qf6 $36 {0-1 Suttles, D-Fischer, R Interzonal-08 Palma de Mallorca 1970 (20) yielded Black a fantastic position.}) 11... Nc6 $5 {Development above all.} 12. Qd2 (12. exf7+ {helps Black to activate his king's rook.} Rxf7 13. Qd2 Qe8+ 14. Nge2 Nxc4 $19) (12. Qf4 Bxe6 13. Nf3 Ne5 $15 14. Nxe5 dxe5 15. Qxe5 $2 Re8 $19) 12... Bxe6 13. b3 (13. O-O-O Nxc4 14. Bxc4 Bxc4 15. Nf3 Qa5 16. Qh6 f6 17. Rxd6 {1-0 Webb,S-Cafferty,B British CF-55 Championship Bristol 1968 (4)} Nb4 18. a3 Na2+ 19. Nxa2 Bxa2 $19) 13... d5 14. cxd5 Nxd5 15. Rd1 Qf6 16. Ne4 {0-1 Petermann,H (2180)-Polaczek,R (2420) Antwerp op 1996 (1)} (16. Nxd5 Bxd5 17. Qxd5 Rad8 18. Qc4 Rxd1+ 19. Kxd1 Rd8+ 20. Kc2 Qa1 $19) 16... Qe7 $19) 6... g6 7. a4 (7. Nf3 Bg7 8. Be2 O-O 9. O-O {transposes to the classical system examined in Lines 2 to 9.}) ({We deal with the aggressive} 7. h4 {in Line 43.}) (7. Bd3 {is examined in Lines 44 and 45.}) ({For} 7. h3 {see Lines 46 and 47.}) (7. Be3 {is the subject of Lines 48 to 52.}) 7... a5 {The natural answer, which offers White some tactical chances, though.} (7... Bg7 {is entirely playable, too.} 8. a5 N6d7 9. Nf3 O-O 10. Ra3 Nc6 11. d5 Nb4 12. Qa4 Na6 13. b4 b6 {Starting to challenge White's space advantage, partly based on his delay in development.} (13... e6 {0-1 Adocchio,G (2174)-Shabalov,A (2520) Reykjavik op 2016 (2)} 14. dxe6 $14) 14. axb6 (14. Be2 bxa5 15. Qxa5 Qxa5 16. bxa5 Nb4 $15) 14... Nxb6 15. Qb3 Nc7 16. Be2 e6 {Black has solved the opening problems.} 17. O-O exd5 18. Nxd5 Ncxd5 19. cxd5 Bb7 20. Rd1 Rc8 (20... Re8 $2 {unnecessarily exposes the rook.} 21. Bb5 Re4 {Â½-Â½ Genov, I (2156)-Mesheriakov, A Astrakhan op 2009 (3)} 22. Bc6 $16) 21. Ra5 (21. Rxa7 Bxd5 $1 $11) 21... Rc3 22. Qb1 (22. Qa2 Qc8 23. Bd2 Rc2 24. Qb3 Rb2 25. Qd3 Qb8 $11) 22... Qa8 $11) 8. c5 {Without this break, the insertion of the rook pawn moves would leave White with an unflexible queenside structure at no reward.} dxc5 9. Bb5+ N6d7 10. Bf4 Bg7 11. Nd5 {White's initiative looks threatening, but with his kingside underdeveloped, he cannot hope for much.} Na6 {My favorite move order.} (11... e5 {is also playable, though.} 12. Bxe5 (12. dxe5 O-O 13. Nf3 Nb6 14. Ne3 Qxd1+ 15. Rxd1 Nc6 $146 {with equal chances.}) 12... O-O 13. Bxg7 Kxg7 14. dxc5 Nc6 {Black has good compensation for the pawn, on account of his better development.} 15. Qd2 Nf6 16. Nxf6 Qxd2+ (16... Qxf6 17. Ne2 Bg4 18. f3 Rad8 19. Qc3 Qxc3+ 20. bxc3 Bc8 21. Rd1 Rxd1+ 22. Kxd1 Rd8+ $11 {followed by ...Rd5.} 23. Kc1 Rd5 24. Bxc6 bxc6 25. Nd4 Rxc5 $19 {0-1 Gurgenidze,B (2340)-Tabatadze,T (2450) GEO-ch Tbilisi 1996}) 17. Kxd2 Kxf6 18. Ne2 Rd8+ {WHite's king is insecure and the pawn on c5 is vulnerable.} 19. Ke3 Rd5 20. Nc3 (20. Rac1 Re5+ 21. Kd2 Be6 $11) 20... Re5+ 21. Ne4+ Kg7 22. f3 Bf5 23. Bxc6 bxc6 24. Kf4 Rd5 25. Nd6 Rb8 $44 {0-1 Todorov, T (2480)-Olivier, J (2417) FRA-chT2S 9900 France 1999 (7) With obvious compensation for the pawn.}) ({In a blitz game on Lichess, I fell for} 11... O-O $6 12. Bc7 Qe8 13. Nb6 Ra6 {This would have allowed me to stay alive and there have been games with this move, too.} ({I played} 13... Ra7 $2 14. Bxb8 {1-0}) 14. dxc5 (14. Bxa6 Nxa6 15. Nxc8 Nxc7 16. Na7 cxd4 $17) 14... Nc6 15. Bxa6 bxa6 16. Ne2 {Â½-Â½ Somlai,L (2340)-Varhegyi,M (2255) Mesterjelolt-ch 1990} Bxb2 17. Ra2 Bg7 $14) 12. Qe2 (12. Bxa6 {runs into} e5 $1 13. Bb5 exf4 14. Qe2+ Kf8 15. Nf3 Nf6 16. Nxf4 cxd4 17. O-O Bf5 18. Rfe1 Qd6 $13 {Â½-Â½ Savory, R (2101)-Carleton, J (2294) EU Union-ch Liverpool 2006 (6)}) 12... O-O $1 $146 13. Nxe7+ Kh8 {WHite cannot fully enjoy his extra pawn because he is underdeveloped and exposed along the e-file.} 14. Nf3 Nc7 15. d5 (15. dxc5 Ne6 16. Bg5 Nxg5 17. Nxg5 Nxc5 18. Rd1 Qb6 $11) 15... Nxb5 16. axb5 Nf6 17. d6 Nh5 18. Be5 Bg4 $11 *

