{[%evp 0,42,23,10,51,69,69,45,45,45,45,39,55,55,65,27,70,55,83,1,29,31,28,16,-2,-9,-9,-10,-6,-12,20,32,60,-26,-26,6,34,24,78,45,19,19,19,19,-12]} 1. e4 Nf6 2. e5 Nd5 3. d4 d6 4. c4 Nb6 5. exd6 cxd6 6. Nc3 g6 7. h4 {With the black king's knight away, this Sicilian Dragon type of attack comes into consideration.} h5 {The simplest way of stopping the attack. With the changed kingside structure, Black will enjoy stability for his bishop on either f5 or g4.} 8. Be3 (8. Bg5 Bg7 9. Rc1 Nc6 10. Nf3 Bg4 {Apparently, White has got a worse version of the classical system, but the pressure on e7 offers him some different kind of play.} 11. Be2 Bxf3 12. Bxf3 Nxc4 13. O-O Nb6 14. Re1 d5 15. b4 {The most obvious way of proving White's compensation for the pawn.} O-O $1 {A very accurate answer. Black is ready to sacrifice an exchange.} 16. b5 Nxd4 17. Bxe7 Qd7 18. Bxf8 Rxf8 19. a4 Nxf3+ 20. Qxf3 d4 {It is obvious that Black is not worse.} 21. Red1 Qg4 22. Qxg4 hxg4 23. Ne2 Nxa4 24. Nxd4 Nb2 25. Rd2 Bh6 $15 {Â½-Â½ Vocaturo, D (2615)-Spyropoulos, N (2409) Chania op 2019 (2)}) 8... Bg7 9. Rc1 (9. Qd2 Nc6 10. O-O-O Bf5 11. Nf3 Rc8 $15 {0-1 Kett,T (2178)-Crevatin,L (2171) Titled Tuesday intern op 20th Apr Chess.com INT blitz 2021 (10)}) 9... O-O 10. b3 {White develops in the same way as in Lines 48 to 52.} Nc6 {The typical Alekhine Defence way of developing.} ({With the g4-square inviting,} 10... N6d7 $5 $146 {is also possible.} 11. Nf3 Nf6 12. d5 e6 13. dxe6 Bxe6 14. Ng5 d5 15. Nxe6 fxe6 16. cxd5 exd5 17. Be2 Nc6 18. Bg5 d4 19. Nd5 Qd6 $11) ({With the actual kingside structure, the same reaction as in Lines 49 to 52 is less adequate.} 10... e5 $6 $146 11. dxe5 dxe5 12. Qxd8 Rxd8 13. c5 N6d7 (13... Nd5 $2 14. Rd1 Be6 15. Bc4 $18) 14. Nf3 Nc6 15. Ng5 $14 {This is the difference. White retains some pressure.}) 11. d5 Ne5 12. Be2 Bf5 {Black is better developed but the question remains whether he can create counterplay against White's solid structure.} (12... e6 13. Bg5 $146 f6 14. Be3 $14) (12... Ng4 13. Bd4 $14) 13. Nh3 {A flexible way of developing.} ({Exchanging one knight helps Black in principle, as he has less space.} 13. Nf3 Nxf3+ 14. Bxf3 Nd7 15. O-O a6 16. Be2 Rc8 {Threatening ...b7-b5 already.} 17. Bd4 (17. a4 Qa5 18. Bd3 (18. Bd2 Qb6 $15 {threatening ...Nc5 endangers the pawn on b3.}) (18. Bd4 {The bishops' exchange favors Black since White's queenside pawns are placed on light squares.} Bxd4 19. Qxd4 Nc5 20. Bd1 Rce8 21. Ne2 e5 22. dxe6 Rxe6 $11) 18... Bxd3 (18... Bxc3 {is possible, but yields White an optically dangerous attack.} 19. Bxf5 gxf5 20. Rxc3 Qxc3 21. Bd4 Qb4 22. Qxh5 f6 23. Qg6+ Kh8 24. f4 {Black needs to defend accurately now since White threatens Rf3-g3.} Qd2 25. Rf3 Qxd4+ 26. Kh2 Ne5 27. fxe5 {[%csl Gh2][%cal Gd4g4] With the white king on h1, Black could now play ...Qg4. However, having the king on h2 is not without drawbacks, either.} f4 28. Qh6+ Kg8 29. Rxf4 Qxe5 {[%cal Gf6f5] Pinning the rook and threatening to repel the attack with ...f6-f5..} 30. Qg6+ $11 {with a draw by perpetual.}) 19. Qxd3 Qb4 20. Ne2 b5 {Black has excellent counterplay.} 21. cxb5 axb5 22. Qxb5 Qxb5 23. axb5 Rb8 24. Nd4 Bxd4 25. Bxd4 Rxb5 26. Rc7 Rxd5 27. Rxd7 Rxd4 28. Rxe7 Rb8 29. Re3 Rxh4 $15 {A draw remains the most probable result, but just for the record, Black is a pawn up.}) 17... Ne5 $5 {The reserve knight lands on e5.} 18. Qd2 Kh7 19. f4 (19. Rce1 Bh6 20. Qd1 b5 21. cxb5 axb5 22. Nxb5 Rc1 23. Qxc1 Bxc1 24. Rxc1 Nd3 $15) 19... Bh6 20. Qe3 Ng4 21. Bxg4 Bxg4 22. g3 e5 (22... b5 $5 23. cxb5 axb5 24. Nxb5 Qd7 25. a4 Qb7 $44) 23. dxe6 fxe6 $11 {0-1 Caposciutti,M (2310)-Rudolph,J (2160) Portoroz op 1996}) 13... Nbd7 {One of the possible move orders.} (13... Ng4 {Â½-Â½ Aleksic, N (2347)-Rambaldi, F (2308) Milan Crespi op-A 33rd 2012 (5)} 14. Bd4 {does not look entirely satisfactory for Black.}) (13... a6 {is the other way of starting the regrouping. The move ...a7-a6 is part of Black's plan anyway.} 14. Ng5 (14. Nf4 Nbd7 15. O-O Nf6 16. f3 Rc8 17. Kh1 Re8) (14. f3 {Hoping for Nf2.} Bxh3 {Now that the rook does not have access to e3, this exchange is good.} 15. Rxh3 {[%cal Gh3e3]} f5 16. Qd2 (16. f4 Ng4 17. Bxg4 hxg4 18. Rh1 Nd7) 16... Nbd7 {followed by ...Qa5 and ..Rae8.} 17. Kf1 Qa5 18. Bd4 Rae8 19. Kg1 e6 20. Rc2 Nf6 $11) 14... Nbd7 15. Nge4 (15. O-O Nc5 16. Bd4 Qa5 $11 {[%cal Gb7b5] planning ...b7-b5.}) 15... b5 $1 16. Ng3 (16. cxb5 axb5 17. Bxb5 $2 Bxe4 18. Nxe4 Qa5+ 19. Nc3 Rfc8 $19) 16... bxc4 (16... e6 $5) 17. Nxf5 gxf5 18. bxc4 Rc8 19. O-O Nxc4 $11) 14. f3 (14. Nf4 {defends d3, but turns White's position a bit rigid.} a6 15. O-O Nf6 $11 {with a stable position for Black.}) (14. Ng5 Nc5 15. O-O Ned3 16. Bxd3 Nxd3 17. Rc2 Nb4 18. Rc1 b5 $5 19. cxb5 Nd3 20. Rc2 Qa5 $44) 14... Bxh3 {Same idea as above.} 15. Rxh3 Nf6 ({Without ...a7-a6,} 15... f5 {may run into} 16. Nb5 {followed by Nd4.}) 16. g4 {The only active plan.} (16. Kf1 a6 17. a4 Qd7 $11 {[%cal Ga8e8,Ge7e6] followed by ...Rae8 and ...e7-e6.}) 16... hxg4 17. fxg4 Qd7 (17... b5 $5 {is also possible, but more difficult to handle.} 18. g5 Nh5 19. Bxh5 gxh5 20. Nxb5 Ng4 21. Bd4 e5 22. dxe6 fxe6 23. Bxg7 Kxg7 $13) 18. Rg3 a6 19. a4 (19. g5 Nh5 20. Bxh5 gxh5 21. Qxh5 Qf5 (21... Nd3+ 22. Kd2 Nxc1 23. g6 $18) (21... b5) 22. Ke2 b5 $36 {with dangerous initiative for the pawn.}) 19... b5 $1 {Anyway!} 20. axb5 axb5 21. cxb5 (21. Nxb5 $2 Ne4 22. Rg1 Bf6 23. g5 Qh3 $19) 21... Rfc8 $44 {With great compensation for the pawn.} *

