1. e4 Nf6 2. e5 Nd5 3. d4 d6 4. c4 Nb6 5. exd6 cxd6 6. Nc3 g6 7. Bd3 Bg7 8. Nge2 O-O 9. O-O {The soundest continuation, even though Black's development remains a bit artificial.} Nc6 10. Be3 ({In the event of} 10. d5 {, my favourite is} Nb4 {, keeping the path clear for the e-pawn.} ({For some reasons,} 10... Ne5 {is by far more popular. It is not a bad move, of course.} 11. b3 Nxd3 12. Qxd3 e5 13. dxe6 Bxe6 14. Ba3 Re8 15. Rad1 d5 $11 {Due to the hanging knight on e2, Black has equalized.}) 11. b3 (11. Bb1 a5 12. a3 Na6 13. Ba2 {1-0 Johansen, D (2420)-Hornung, K Doeberl Cup Canberra 1990 (7)} e5 14. dxe6 Bxe6 $11) 11... e6 {With the knight on b4 instead of e5, Black does not have to hurry with capturing on d3.} (11... e5 {is also possible.}) 12. dxe6 (12. a3 {1-0 Speck,N-Wohl,A (2275) AUS-ch Melbourne 1991 (1)} Nxd3 13. Qxd3 exd5 14. cxd5 Bf5) (12. Be4 exd5 13. cxd5 Bg4 14. f3 Bd7 15. a3 f5 16. axb4 fxe4 17. fxe4 Rxf1+ 18. Qxf1 Bg4 19. Ra2 Qe7 $44) 12... Bxe6 13. Ba3 (13. Be3 d5 $15 14. Bc5 (14. c5 d4 $17) 14... Nxd3 15. Bxf8 (15. Qxd3 dxc4 $17) 15... Nxf2 $1 (15... Qxf8 16. Qxd3 dxc4 17. Qf3 cxb3 18. axb3 Qb4 19. Rab1 Rc8 20. Ne4 {Â½-Â½ Borgo,G (2345)-Zelcic,R (2500) Formia op 1995} Qe7 $44) 16. Rxf2 Qxf8 17. cxd5 Nxd5 18. Nxd5 (18. Rc1 Nxc3 19. Nxc3 Rd8 $17 {[%cal Gg7d4]} 20. Rd2 Rxd2 21. Qxd2 Bh6 $17) 18... Bxa1 $15) 13... a5 14. Rc1 d5 $11 15. c5 $6 {0-1 Vasiesiu, V (2254)-Bashirli, N (2381) World School-ch U17 12th Sochi 2016 (6)} Nd7 {[%csl Ga2,Gc5]} 16. Bxb4 axb4 17. Na4 Qh4 18. Qd2 Ne5 $15) 10... e5 {One of those cases in which I had to deviate from my favourite pawn break.} (10... d5 11. c5 Nc4 $6 (11... Nd7 {is better, even if White did not waste a tempo on b2-b3.}) 12. Bxc4 dxc4 13. Qa4 Nxd4 14. Nxd4 Bxd4 15. Rfd1 e5 16. Bxd4 exd4 17. Qxc4 $14) (10... Nb4 11. b3 $14) 11. d5 ({With the bishop on d3,} 11. dxe5 dxe5 12. c5 {does not bother Black any single bit.} Nd5 13. Nxd5 Qxd5 14. Nc3 Qd8 15. Be4 Nd4 16. b4 Kh8 17. Bxd4 exd4 18. Nb5 a5 {Â½-Â½ Buza,A-Ghinda,M ROM-ch35 Final Bucharest 1971 (3)} 19. a3 axb4 20. axb4 Rxa1 21. Qxa1 b6 $11 {[%csl Gd6]} 22. c6 d3 23. Qb1 d2 24. Rd1 Qg5 $17) 11... Nb4 12. b3 {Black has several ways of achieving a good position. Play remains sharp, though, due to the non-symmetrical structure.} Nxd3 {Not the only move.} (12... f5 13. f4 (13. Bb1 a5 14. f4 a4 15. fxe5 Bxe5 $36) 13... Nd7 14. Rc1 g5 $5 {The most ambitious.} (14... Nf6 15. h3 {0-1 Andersen,P-Ingerslev,A DEN-ch corr Denmark 1983} Nxd3 16. Qxd3 b6 $13) 15. g3 {0-1 Gagic, M (1880)-Pesotsky, V (2343) EU-ch 10th Budva 2009 (2)} (15. fxg5 Nxd3 16. Qxd3 f4 17. Bf2 Qxg5 18. Ne4 Qg6 $36 {with a promising position.}) 15... Nf6 16. h3 Nxd3 17. Qxd3 Ne4 {[%csl Gh3]} (17... g4 18. h4 b6 $13) 18. fxe5 Nxc3 19. Nxc3 dxe5 $132) 13. Qxd3 f5 14. f4 Nd7 15. Qd2 (15. Rad1 g5 $5 16. g3 gxf4 17. gxf4 Nf6 18. h3 (18. fxe5 dxe5 19. Bg5 Qe8 20. Bxf6 Rxf6 21. Kh1 Kh8 22. Rde1 Bd7 $15 {Â½-Â½ Weinstock,S-Wright,S NAmerica-ch8 corr9600 1996}) 18... Kh8 19. Kh2 Nh5 20. c5 dxc5 21. Bxc5 Rg8 22. Qf3 {0-1 Levy,L-Torre,E Reggio Emilia-15 1972/73} Qe8 23. Rg1 Bd7 $13 24. Rg5 Rc8 25. Bf2 (25. Bxa7 Nxf4 26. Nxf4 exf4 27. Rxg7 Kxg7 28. Bd4+ Kf8 29. Qxf4 Rg6 $13) 25... Bf6 26. Qxh5 (26. Rxh5 e4 $19) 26... Bxg5 27. Qxe8 Bxf4+ 28. Nxf4 Rgxe8 29. Nfe2 f4 $13) 15... b6 16. Rad1 Nf6 17. fxe5 dxe5 {The structure has turned even less symmetrical now.} 18. Bg5 Bd7 19. Kh1 Rf7 20. Ng1 Qf8 21. d6 Bc6 22. b4 Rc8 (22... h6 {wastes a tempo, but is playable anyway.} 23. Bxf6 Bxf6 24. c5 bxc5 25. bxc5 {1-0 Fischer, R-Berliner, H USA-ch New York 1962 (3)} Rc8 $1 $13 {putting c5 under observation. The only game in this database, in which Fischer played with the white pieces.}) 23. c5 bxc5 24. bxc5 Nd7 25. Be7 Rxe7 26. dxe7 Qxe7 $15 *

