{[%evp 0,34,19,19,62,62,62,50,50,50,51,23,55,55,55,59,59,30,20,41,41,7,-3,-32,-34,-44,-41,-39,-39,-70,-23,-59,-94,-65,-72,-71,-49]} 1. e4 Nf6 2. e5 Nd5 3. d4 d6 4. c4 Nb6 5. exd6 cxd6 6. Nc3 g6 7. h3 Bg7 8. Nf3 O-O 9. Be3 {White does not define his intentions regarding the light-squared bishops yet. He may transpose to the classical system with Be2, or he may look for different developing plans.} Nc6 10. d5 (10. Be2 {leads to similar play as in the classical system although a perfect transposition can be avoided.} d5 11. c5 Nc4 12. Bxc4 (12. Bc1 b6 13. b3 bxc5 14. bxc4 cxd4 15. Nxd5 d3 16. Rb1 dxe2 17. Qxe2 Ba6 $17 {Â½-Â½ Zill, C (2144)-Lautner, J (2185) Regionalliga SO 0809 Bayern 2008 (8.1)}) 12... dxc4 13. O-O (13. Qa4 {leads to a similar position to one we avoid in Line 45, with the difference that White has spent a tempo on h2-h3.} Nxd4 14. Nxd4 Bxd4 15. Rd1 e5 16. Qxc4 (16. Bxd4 exd4 17. Qxc4 Qe7+ 18. Ne2 Re8 19. Rxd4 Bf5 $17) 16... Be6 17. Qa4 Qe7 $15) 13... b6 $5 {Trying to keep the independent character of the game.} (13... Bf5 {transposes to Line 7.}) 14. cxb6 (14. d5 Nb4 15. Bd4 bxc5 16. Bxg7 Kxg7 17. Qe2 Ba6 $11) (14. Qa4 Nxd4 15. Nxd4 Bxd4 16. Rad1 bxc5 17. Qxc4 Be6 $15 {0-1 Rousseau,D (1782)-Desforges,J (1951) Montreal Hiver/Winter op 1982 (4)}) 14... axb6 15. Qe2 Ba6 $11 {[%cal Ge7e6]}) (10. Rc1 {is examined in Lines 48 to 52.}) 10... Na5 11. Bd4 {Indirectly defending the pawn on c4, but exposing the queen.} (11. Nd2 {1-0 Halt, D (2055)-Singh, M (1926) GER-ch Net blitz qual3 Playchess.com INT 2020 (6) is too passive.} Bf5 (11... e6 $11) 12. Rc1 (12. g4 Bd7 13. Bd3 (13. Bxb6 Qxb6 14. Qc2 Rac8 15. b3 Qb4 16. Rc1 b5 $19) 13... Rc8 14. Qe2 e6 $15) 12... Rc8 13. b3 (13. Bxb6 Qxb6 14. b3 Qb4) (13. Na4 Nxa4 14. Qxa4 Bxb2 15. Rd1 e6 $17 16. g4 exd5 17. gxf5 d4 18. Bh6 Re8+ 19. Be2 d3 $19) 13... Bxc3 14. Rxc3 Nxd5 $19 {Unlike in a previous variation, Black wins the pawn and exchanges the white dark-squared bishop.}) 11... Bxd4 12. Qxd4 e5 $1 {SImilar to a pawn break carried out by Fischer against Suttles.} 13. dxe6 Bxe6 14. Ne4 {White tries to maintain his activity by using the weakness of the f6-square. No matter what he does, it is not easy to catch up in development, though.} (14. b3 Nc6 15. Qf4 d5 16. O-O-O (16. c5 d4 17. Nb5 Nd5 18. Qd2 a6 19. Nbxd4 Nxd4 20. Nxd4 Qf6 21. Rd1 Rad8 $19) 16... Qe7 17. cxd5 Qa3+ 18. Kb1 Nb4 19. dxe6 Nxa2 $1 20. Nxa2 Qxb3+ 21. Ka1 Qxd1+ 22. Qc1 Qxc1+ 23. Nxc1 fxe6 24. Bd3 Nd5 25. Ne2 Rac8 26. Rb1 b6 $15 {0-1 Schweber,S (2395)-Piza Cortizo,D Buenos Aires BCA op 1988}) 14... Nc6 {Not fearing any ghosts. It is just a check!} 15. Nf6+ (15. Qxd6 Bf5 16. Qxd8 Raxd8 17. Ned2 Rfe8+ 18. Kd1 Na4 19. b3 Nc5 20. Kc1 Nb4 21. Kb2 a5 $17) 15... Kh8 16. Qf4 Nxc4 $1 {Just winning a pawn.} (16... Bf5 {is the second best.} 17. Ng4 Re8+ 18. Be2 Bd3 19. Ne3 Bxe2 20. Kxe2 d5 $36 {0-1 Aronian, L (2773)-Carlsen, M (2863) Clutch-ch June Lichess.org INT rapid 2020 (2.2)}) 17. Be2 (17. Bxc4 Bxc4 18. Qxc4 Qxf6 $15) (17. O-O-O Rc8 $17) 17... N4e5 $15 *

