{[%evp 0,70,25,31,37,37,43,31,61,31,31,30,55,53,53,40,40,15,22,34,42,17,10,47,46,60,58,56,64,58,68,61,42,63,52,46,89,80,66,59,46,35,57,40,67,43,43,47,51,51,83,56,102,64,101,32,50,32,32,26,54,54,61,51,52,52,45,53,63,38,65,72,53]} 1. e4 Nf6 2. e5 Nd5 3. d4 d6 4. c4 Nb6 5. exd6 cxd6 6. Nc3 g6 7. Be3 Bg7 8. Rc1 O-O 9. b3 e5 10. dxe5 dxe5 11. Qxd8 {By exchanging the queens, White weakens Black's defence on f7 and also makes c7 accessible to his knights.} Rxd8 12. c5 {The most consistent continuation, clearing the c4-square for the bishop and forcing Black to weaken his control over d5.} (12. Nb5 {wins a pawn but offers Black ample compensation for it.} Nc6 13. Nxa7 Nd4 14. Nxc8 Nxc8 15. Bxd4 {The only way of keeping the extra pawn.} exd4 16. a4 d3 17. Nf3 Ra6 {White has serious problems already.} 18. Kd1 {Â½-Â½ Le,N-Vu,P VIE-chT (Women) Can Tho 2006 (10)} (18. g3 $6 {0-1 Herndlbauer, M (2162)-Schroll, G (2381) AUT-chT2O 0203 Austria 2002 (11.5) wastes a tempo since Bg2 is hardly a threat since it would allow the black rook's intrusion to e2.} Re6+ 19. Kd1 Bb2 20. Rb1 Bc3 $17 21. Rc1 Bb4 $19 {White is completely paralyzed.} 22. c5 $6 d2 23. Rc4 Re1+ {wins at once.}) 18... Nd6 $5 $146 (18... Bb2 19. Rb1 Bc3 {Â½-Â½ Le, N-Vu, P VIE-chT (Women) Can Tho 2006 (10)} 20. Rc1 Bb4 21. c5 $132 {planning Rc4, offers White some freedom.}) 19. Bxd3 Ne4 20. Kc2 Nxf2 21. Rhd1 Rad6 22. Be2 Nxd1 23. Rxd1 {White is forced to exchange one rook, which is generally undesirable when an exchange down.} (23. Bxd1 Rd3 $19) 23... Rxd1 24. Bxd1 Re8 $15) (12. Nf3 Nc6 {transposes to Line 51.}) 12... N6d7 ({With the knight on b8 still,} 12... Nd5 $2 {loses material to} 13. Rd1 Be6 14. Bc4 $18) 13. Bc4 Nc6 14. Ne4 {The most direct approach.} (14. Nf3 {is best met with} h6 {preventing Ng5.} 15. Ne4 (15. O-O Nf8 16. Nb5 Be6 17. Nd6 Bxc4 18. Rxc4 Rd7 $11 {The next phase is a good illustration of the long-term tendency in this structure.} 19. b4 Ne6 20. b5 Ncd4 $15 21. Nxd4 $6 exd4 22. Bc1 b6 $17 {0-1 Miesbauer,J (2217)-Liska,J (2087) CZE-ch U18/U20 sf Kovarska 2016 (9)}) 15... Na5 {Now is a good moment for starting to fight against the active bishop.} (15... Nf8 {is a popular alternative, but I am slightly put off by the following game, in which White retained some minimal advantage.} 16. Nd6 Rd7 17. Nd2 Re7 18. Nxc8 Rxc8 19. Ne4 Ne6 20. h4 $14 {1-0 Zaitsev, M (2508)-Essing, A (2233) NRW Class1 1617 Germany 2016 (7.1)}) 16. Bd5 (16. Be2 {allows} f5 17. Nd6 Nc6 18. Bc4+ Kh7 19. h4 Nf6 20. h5 Nxh5 21. Nh4 {1-0 Kroneberger, W (1720)-Nonnenmacher, T (1776) GER HS-014 email GER email 2006} Nf6 22. Bf7 Ne7) (16. Nd6 Nxc4 17. Rxc4 f5 $11) 16... Nf6 17. Nxf6+ Bxf6 18. Rd1 (18. Be4 Bg7 19. b4 Nc6 20. b5 Nb4 21. c6 bxc6 22. bxc6 Ba6 23. c7 Nd3+ 24. Bxd3 Rxd3 25. O-O Rc8 26. Rc2 Rxe3 27. fxe3 Bxf1 28. Kxf1 e4 29. Nd2 Be5 $11) 18... Kg7 19. O-O Bd7 20. b4 Bc6 21. Bxf7 (21. Bxc6 Nxc6 $11 22. b5 $6 Nd4 $15) 21... Kxf7 22. bxa5 g5 23. Nd2 Ke6 24. f3 Rd3 25. Nc4 Rad8 26. Rc1 Be7 $11 {0-1 Silva, A (2173)-Rain, R (2372) SLO-ch15 sf05 email ICCF email 2010 WHite's extra pawn is meaningless.}) 14... Nf8 (14... Na5 {is also playable, but under the given circumstances, the knight maneuver runs into} 15. Bg5 Rf8 16. Bd5 {with light initiative.}) 15. Nd6 (15. Ng5 {allows Black to regroup in time.} Rd7 16. Ne2 h6 17. Ne4 Re7 18. N2c3 Be6 19. Bxe6 Rxe6 20. Nd5 Rd8 21. Nd6 Nd4 $11 {[%cal Gb7b6]} 22. Bxd4 $6 exd4+ 23. Kd2 Be5 24. Nc7 Rf6 25. Nxb7 Rd7 26. Ne8 Rxf2+ 27. Ke1 Rxa2 $19 {0-1 Vajda,S (2364)-Polyik,P (2264) HUN-chT 1718 Hungary 2017 (2.11)}) 15... Be6 {This pawn sacrifice has been tried in a few correspondence games. Black has full compensation.} 16. Nxb7 (16. Bxe6 $6 Nxe6 17. Nxb7 Rdb8 18. Nd6 Nb4 $15 {Black retrieves the pawn, retaining the better chances.}) 16... Rdb8 17. Nd6 Bxc4 18. Rxc4 a5 {Black's play is logical. He is well-regrouped for the queenside break. White's extra pawn is safely blocked by the knight on c6.} 19. Ne2 (19. Bd2 {Â½-Â½ Laffont, J (1863)-Ilyin, I (1967) RC-2019-0-00235 LSS email prevents the pawn break but weakens the defence on c5.} f5 (19... a4 $2 20. b4 $18) 20. Ne2 Ne6 21. O-O Bf8 22. Bc3 Rd8 23. Rd1 Ra6 24. g3 Nxc5 25. Rxc5 Rxd6 26. Rxd6 Bxd6 27. Rd5 Nb4 $11) 19... a4 20. Rxa4 (20. bxa4 Rb2 21. Nc3 Ne6 22. O-O f5 23. Rb1 Rc2 24. Rc1 Rb2 25. Rb1 Rc2 26. Nd5 Rxc4 27. Nxc4 Rxa4 28. Rb6 Rxc4 29. Rxc6 Kf7 30. Kf1 f4 31. Bd2 Rc2 32. Be1 Rxa2 $11) (20. Nc1 {Â½-Â½ Ovcharenko, L (2294)-Malchev, E (2343) GER CM01-E email GER email 2014} axb3 21. axb3 f5 22. O-O Ne6 $44 {White is too passive for claiming an advantage.}) 20... Rxa4 21. bxa4 Rb1+ 22. Nc1 Rb4 {Black's active rook and White numerous weaknesses make the position roughly equal.} 23. a5 Ra4 24. O-O f5 (24... Rxa5 $44) 25. Rd1 Ne6 26. Nb7 Bf8 27. f3 Rb4 28. Nd6 Ra4 29. Rd5 Nc7 (29... Rxa5 30. Nc4) 30. Rd2 Nxa5 31. Kf1 Ne6 32. Re2 Nc6 33. h3 Kg7 34. Rb2 Be7 35. Bf2 Kf6 $44 {Â½-Â½ Cloes, D (2247)-Hablizel, F (2338) WS TT/4/15/fin email ICCF email 2017} *

