{[%evp 0,46,25,31,37,37,61,61,61,31,31,22,46,53,40,37,37,34,36,34,36,33,27,-9,3,-2,12,-12,-13,-13,-13,-38,-23,-3,140,-31,-38,-23,-29,-41,-44,-46,-54,-51,-47,-47,-39,-35,-39]} 1. e4 Nf6 2. e5 Nd5 3. d4 d6 4. c4 Nb6 5. exd6 cxd6 6. Nc3 g6 7. Be3 Bg7 8. Rc1 O-O 9. b3 e5 10. Nf3 {Maintaining the tension is a principled decision.} Nc6 11. dxe5 {The same type of plan as in the previous line.} (11. d5 Ne7 {is promising for Black.} 12. Be2 Nf5 13. Bg5 {1-0 Leopold,C (1966)-Nuesslein,C (1535) Nuremberg Zabo op 20th 2018 (1)} f6 14. Bd2 Re8 {[%cal Be5e4]} 15. Ne4 (15. Qc2 Nd4 $15 16. Nxd4 exd4 17. Ne4 Bf5 18. f3 Bxe4 19. fxe4 f5 20. exf5 Nd7 $17 21. fxg6 $2 Nc5 22. gxh7+ Kh8 23. Kd1 Rxe2 24. Kxe2 d3+ $19) 15... Nd4 16. Bb4 (16. O-O Nxe2+ 17. Qxe2 f5 18. Bg5 fxe4 $5 {Black could allow Nf6+ without any problems, but the last move is more entertaining.} 19. Bxd8 exf3 20. Qxf3 Rxd8 $44) 16... a5 {Black starts active operations on the other wing, too.} 17. Ba3 (17. Bxd6 f5 $17) 17... a4 18. Bb4 axb3 19. axb3 Ra2 20. Nc3 (20. Bd3 Bg4 21. Nxd6 Bf8 $19) 20... Nxe2 21. Nxa2 Nxc1 22. Nxc1 Nd7 $15 23. Bxd6 $2 Qb6 24. c5 (24. Ba3 Qa5+) 24... Nxc5 25. Bxc5 Qxc5 $19 {followed by ...Rd8, winning the central pawn.}) (11. Be2 {is examined in Line 52.}) 11... dxe5 12. c5 (12. Qxd8 Rxd8 13. c5 {offers Black a choice.} Nd5 {With the rook defended by the knight on c6, this is possible.} (13... Nd7 14. Bc4 h6 {transposes to the previous line.}) 14. Nxd5 Rxd5 15. Bc4 Rd7 16. O-O Re7 17. Rfd1 (17. Bg5 Re8 18. Rfd1 e4 $11) (17. Ng5 {0-1 Zelbel,P (2123)-Kotainy,J (2032) GER-ch internet U14 final Playchess.com INT blitz 2007 (4)} e4 $11) 17... e4 (17... Be6 18. Bxe6 Rxe6 19. Rd7 Re7 20. Rxe7 Nxe7 21. Rd1 Nc6 22. Rd7 Rd8 $11) 18. Nd4 (18. Nd2 Bg4 19. Re1 Nb4 $5 $11) 18... Bxd4 19. Bxd4 Bg4 20. Rd2 Rd8 21. Bc3 Rxd2 22. Bxd2 Ne5 23. Bf1 Be6 24. Re1 f5 $11 {In view of the possible ...Nd3, White's bishops' pair does not have much meaning.}) 12... Nd7 13. Bc4 {The most active.} (13. Bb5 e4 $5 14. Bxc6 (14. Nxe4 Qa5+) 14... bxc6 15. Nxe4 Ba6 {Black has obvious compensation for the pawn since White cannot get castled.} 16. Nd6 Qe7 17. b4 (17. Qd2 Nxc5 18. Rxc5 Rfd8 19. Rxc6 Bb7 $17) 17... Bb2 18. Rc2 Ba3 19. b5 Bxb5 20. Nxb5 cxb5 21. O-O Nxc5 $13 {Â½-Â½ Schmidt, A-Chovanec, M (2371) Champion's League 02/Q14-1 email ICCF email 2002}) (13. Qd2 {allows} f5 14. Bg5 Qa5 (14... Nf6 $11) 15. Nb5 e4 16. Qxa5 Nxa5 17. Nfd4 Ne5 18. Nc7 Rb8 $11 {Â½-Â½ Benedetto, D (2228)-Sciallero, V (2273) ITA-ch68 final email ICCF email 2018}) 13... Qa5 {In the previous line, the absence of queens deprived Black of such counterplay.} 14. O-O (14. Ng5 Nxc5 15. Qd5 Ne6 $5 $146 16. Qxa5 Nxa5 17. Nxe6 Bxe6 18. Bxe6 fxe6 19. Ne4 Nc6 $11) 14... Nxc5 15. b4 {Play becomes entertaining now.} (15. Ng5 Ne6 16. Nxe6 Bxe6 17. Bxe6 fxe6 18. Qd7 Nd4 19. Qxb7 Rac8 20. Bxd4 exd4 21. Ne4 Rxc1 22. Rxc1 Qd5 (22... d3 23. h4 Qxa2 $11) 23. Rc7 {1-0 Cioara,A (2417)-Seretakis,N (2181) Kavala op 24th 2015 (8)} Be5 24. Rd7 (24. Rxh7 d3 25. Rd7 Qxb7 26. Rxb7 Rd8) 24... Qa5 25. g3 Qe1+ 26. Kg2 Qe2 27. h4 g5 28. hxg5 Qf3+ {with a draw by perpetual.}) 15... Nxb4 (15... Qxb4 {is also possible.} 16. Nd5 Qa5 17. Bxc5 Qxc5 18. Nc7 Qe7 19. Nxa8 Bf5 {Black will have enough compensation for the exchange.} 20. Bd5 (20. Nb6 {throws away a tempo.} axb6 21. Re1 {0-1 Batsanin, D (2245)-Siegel, N (2240) Wch U14 Menorca 1996 (10)} Bh6 22. Rc3 e4 $17) 20... Rxa8 21. Bxc6 bxc6 22. Rxc6 Rd8 23. Qc1 {Black's bishops are strong in an open position. Here are some possible continuations.} e4 (23... h6 $5 24. Rc7 Qf6 25. Rxa7 e4 26. Ne1 Qb6 27. Qc7 Qxc7 28. Rxc7 Ra8 29. Nc2 Rxa2 30. Ne3 Be6 31. Rd1 Bf6 $5 $11) 24. Rc7 Qf6 25. Ng5 {The knight embarks on a dangerous adventure, but other squares are more passive.} h6 26. Nxf7 Rd7 27. Rxd7 Bxd7 28. Nxh6+ Kh7 29. Qc7 Be6 30. Qxa7 Qg5 31. Nf7 Qd5 {The knight remains trapped.} 32. a4 Bxf7 33. a5 Bd4 34. Qc7 Kg7 35. a6 Qc4 36. Qxc4 Bxc4 37. Rd1 Bd3 $11 {White cannot sustain his a-pawn and Black threatens to simplify completely with ...e4-e3.} 38. h4 (38. Rd2 $2 e3 39. Rxd3 e2 $19) 38... e3 $5 39. fxe3 (39. Rxd3 e2 $19) 39... Bxe3+ 40. Kh2 Bxa6 $11) 16. Nd5 Nxd5 17. Qxd5 b6 {Another interesting moment.} 18. Qxa8 (18. Ng5 Bb7 $11) (18. Bxc5 Be6 19. Qd2 Qxd2 20. Nxd2 bxc5 21. Bxe6 fxe6 22. Rxc5 Rfc8 23. Ra5 e4 24. Nxe4 Bd4 $11) 18... Bb7 19. Bxf7+ $5 (19. Qxf8+ Kxf8 20. Ng5 Ba6 21. Bxc5+ bxc5 22. Bxa6 Qxa6 23. Rxc5 {Â½-Â½ Bokros,A (2477)-Grunberg,F (2267) Szombathely Savaria op 3rd 2003 (7)} h6 24. Ne4 Kg8 $13) 19... Kxf7 20. Rxc5 Rxa8 21. Rxa5 bxa5 22. Ng5+ Kg8 23. Rd1 Bc6 $11 {0-1 Morano,A (2350)-Poleschi,R (2322) Master Chess Tourn 1st email Eclipse email 2000 (5)} *

