1. e4 Nf6 2. e5 Nd5 3. d4 d6 4. c4 Nb6 5. exd6 cxd6 6. Nc3 g6 7. Be3 Bg7 8. Rc1 O-O 9. b3 e5 10. Nf3 Nc6 11. Be2 {Maintaining the tension for as long as possible is the most principled policy, but from a practical point of view, the previous lines were also full of content, as we know already.} Bg4 {A simple way of forcing White to release the tension anyway. True, the bishop move is a small commitment, but on the other hand, after the exchange on e5 and d8, Black has ...Rad8, maintaining f7 well-defended.} 12. dxe5 (12. O-O {is not especially promising.} Bxf3 13. Bxf3 exd4 14. Bxc6 dxe3 15. Bxb7 exf2+ 16. Kh1 (16. Rxf2 Rb8 17. Bf3 Bh6 18. Rcc2 Be3 $15 {0-1 Chojnowski,M (2147)-Wojcieszyn,Z (2171) POL-ch blind 36th Poznan 2007 (2)}) (16. Kxf2 Nxc4 17. Nd5 Rb8 $15) 16... Rb8 17. Bf3 Be5 18. g3 h5 19. Rxf2 h4 20. g4 {0-1 Schoenreich,M-Kuhne,D (2205) Oberliga Nord O 9697 Germany 1996} Qg5 $11) (12. d5 {allows} Bxf3 13. Bxf3 Nd4 14. Bxd4 (14. O-O Nd7 15. g3 Nxf3+ $146 16. Qxf3 f5 $11) 14... exd4 15. Ne2 Qf6 16. O-O Nd7 17. Qd2 {Black has more than one way of achieving a good game.} Rfe8 $5 {may be the most flexible and promising..} (17... Nc5 18. Rcd1 (18. b4 Na4 19. c5 a5 20. a3 Nc3 $11) 18... d3 19. Nc1 a5 20. Nxd3 b6 $44 {1-0 Bakiev, D (2074)-Aleksanyan, D (1795) EU-ch Hybrid U14 Tornelo INT 2021 (3)}) 18. Rfe1 (18. Rcd1 d3 $1 19. Qxd3 Ne5 20. Qc2 Nxf3+ 21. gxf3 Qxf3 $15) 18... Qh4 19. Rcd1 Ne5 20. Qf4 (20. Nxd4 $2 Qxd4 $1 21. Qxd4 Nxf3+ 22. gxf3 Rxe1+ $19) 20... Qxf4 21. Nxf4 Bh6 22. Ne2 d3 $15) 12... dxe5 13. O-O ({Alternatively,} 13. c5 {With queens on board, Black has fewer problems containing White's light initiative.} Nd7 (13... Nc8 14. O-O N8e7 15. h3 Bxf3 16. Bxf3 Nf5 $13 {1-0 Szostko,J (2217)-Flak,P (2180) Bialystok Zamenhof Memorial 38th 2019 (6)}) 14. O-O Nf6 15. h3 Be6 16. Ng5 {Â½-Â½ Mitusov,S (2332)-Abdrlauf,E (2455) Kvisla 2022 (8)} Bf5 17. g4 (17. Bc4 h6 18. Nf3 Ne4 $11) 17... Bd7 18. Bc4 h6 19. Nge4 Nd4 20. f4 Nxe4 21. Nxe4 Bc6 22. Nd6 Qh4 23. Kh2 exf4 24. Bxf4 (24. Bxd4 $2 Qg3#) (24. Rxf4 Ne6 $17) 24... b5 $5 $13) (13. Qxd8 Raxd8 {helps Black complete his development.} 14. h3 (14. Bxb6 axb6 15. Nd5 e4 $1 $146 16. Nd2 Bxe2 17. Kxe2 Nd4+ 18. Kf1 f5 19. Nb1 b5 $15) 14... Bf5 15. g4 Bc8 (15... Bd7 16. Nb5 Nc8 $11 17. Bc5 Rfe8 18. Nc7 e4 $1 19. Nxe8 {Otherwise ...Re5.} exf3 20. Nxg7 fxe2 21. Kxe2 Kxg7 $11) 16. Nb5 Nd7 17. O-O {0-1 Kiolbasa, O (2255)-Osmak, I (2428) Cappelle Online (Women) op Europe Echecs INT blitz 2021 (6)} (17. Nxa7 Nxa7 18. Bxa7 b6 19. O-O e4 20. Nh4 Bd4 21. Rfd1 Ne5 $44) 17... e4 $11) 13... h6 {Preparing a safe retreat of the bishop to e6.} 14. c5 (14. h3 Be6 15. Qxd8 Raxd8 16. Nb5 Nc8 17. Rfd1 f5 $13 {1-0 Cano Egea,J (1574)-Diaz Comas,J (1921) Girona op-A 4th 2013 (8)}) 14... Nd7 (14... Nc8 15. b4 Qxd1 16. Rfxd1 Nxb4 17. Rb1 Nc6 18. Rxb7 N8e7 $11) 15. h3 (15. Ne4 f5 16. Nd6 {1-0 Fernandez, D (2458)-Coca Cubillos, J (2055) Titled Arena May 8th Lichess.org INT blitz 2021} Kh7 17. Nxb7 Qc7 18. Nd6 f4 19. Bd2 Nxc5 20. Qc2 Qxd6 21. Qxc5 Rf6 22. h3 Bf5 $11) 15... Be6 16. Nb5 {1-0 Von Beers,R (1995)-Wassermann,F Herne Laufer op 2003 (4.10)} f5 {The most ambitious.} (16... Nf6 17. Nd6 Qe7 $11 {is also fine.}) 17. Nd6 Qe7 $1 {The queen needs to defend the kingside.} (17... Qc7 $6 {allows} 18. b4 $1 $14 Nxb4 $6 19. Bc4 Bxc4 20. Rxc4 Nc6 21. Qd5+ Kh7 22. Rh4 $18) 18. b4 (18. Nxb7 $6 f4 19. Bb5 (19. Bd2 e4 $15) 19... Ndb8 $15 20. Nd6 fxe3 21. fxe3 e4 22. Nxe4 a6 $15) 18... Nxb4 19. Bc4 Bxc4 (19... Kh7 $5 20. Bxe6 Qxe6 21. Rc4 $13) 20. Rxc4 Nc6 21. Qd5+ Kh7 22. Rh4 f4 {Parrying the check on g5 and leaving the rook isolated on the kingside.} 23. Bc1 (23. Bd2 $2 {leaves the bishop exposed on d2.} Rad8 24. Nxb7 Nd4 25. Nxd8 Rxd8 $15 26. Nxd4 $2 Nxc5 27. Nc6 Rxd5 28. Nxe7 Rxd2 $17) 23... Rad8 24. Nxb7 Nd4 25. Nxd8 Nxf3+ (25... Rxd8 {does not work with the bishop elsewhere than on d2.} 26. Nxd4 Nxc5 27. Nc6 Rxd5 28. Nxe7 Rd7 29. Ba3 $16) 26. gxf3 Rxd8 27. Rd1 $1 {The only chance.} (27. Rg4 Nxc5 $15) 27... Qxh4 28. c6 Qxh3 29. c7 (29. cxd7 e4 $1 30. Qxe4 (30. fxe4 f3 $19) 30... Rxd7 $11) 29... Rf8 30. Qxd7 Rf5 31. Bxf4 $1 {The only clear way to equality.} (31. c8=Q $2 Rg5+ 32. Qg4 Qxf3 33. Qxg5 Qxd1+ 34. Kg2 hxg5 $19) (31. Qxf5 $6 Qxf5 32. Rd8 e4 $3 {This is why White had to eliminate one of the pawns!} 33. c8=Q (33. fxe4 Qg4+ 34. Kf1 f3 35. c8=Q Qg2+ 36. Ke1 Qg1+ 37. Kd2 Qxf2+ 38. Kd3 Qe2#) 33... Qg5+ 34. Qg4 (34. Kf1 exf3 35. Re8 Qg2+ 36. Ke1 Qg1+ 37. Kd2 Qxf2+ 38. Kd1 Qd4+ 39. Bd2 f2 40. Ke2 Qxd2+ 41. Kxd2 f1=Q $19) 34... Qxd8 $15) 31... exf4 32. Qxf5 Qxf5 33. Rd8 Qg5+ 34. Kf1 Qb5+ $11 {with a perpetual.} *

