{[%evp 0,48,16,38,40,38,59,55,29,43,63,-28,-30,-32,-18,-32,-15,-52,-35,-26,-36,-46,-38,-90,-81,-73,-30,-29,-9,-38,6,6,8,-63,-35,-45,183,185,-54,-53,-79,-67,-72,-92,-71,-81,-81,-51,-42,-69,-62]} 1. e4 Nf6 2. e5 Nd5 3. c4 {The same comment as in the introduction to Line 33 applies here. The last move is natural, forcing Black to spend even more time jumping around with the daring knight. It was played for the first time by Rubinstein in 1921, a few months after Alekhine officially introduced his opening. True, Rubinstein played d2-d4 next, transposing elsewhere.} Nb6 4. a4 {We are familiar with the fact that Black has to be constantly aware of the advance of White's a-pawn.} (4. Nc3 d6 5. exd6 cxd6 6. d4 {and}) (4. d4 d6 {transpose to any of the Lines 28 to 52.}) ({The main continuation with independent value is} 4. c5 {. We will examine it in Lines 54 to 62.}) 4... a5 {The natural reaction.} ({The same as in Line 42, Black can also ignore the threat and keep developing.} 4... d6 5. a5 N6d7 6. exd6 (6. e6 {is a sound pawn sacrifice, which should not bother Black too much, though.} fxe6 7. d4 e5 8. Bd3 g6 9. d5 Nc5 $146 10. Bc2 Bg7 11. b4 e4 12. Ra3 Nd3+ 13. Bxd3 exd3 14. Rxd3 c5 $5 15. bxc5 Bf5 16. Re3 O-O 17. Bd2 Bd4 $13) 6... exd6 $5 ({Deviating from} 6... cxd6 7. d4 g6 {with a transposition to Line 42.}) 7. d4 c5 {With the white pawn exposed on a5 and the square on b4 weak, this way of attacking the centre is possible.} 8. Nc3 (8. d5 Na6 9. Nf3 Be7 10. Nc3 O-O 11. Bd3 Bf6 12. O-O {Â½-Â½ Jorge,C (2177)-Bulcourf,C (2018) ARG-ch sf Vicente Lopez 2016 (9)} Ne5 13. Nxe5 Bxe5 $11) 8... Be7 9. Nf3 O-O 10. Bd3 Nc6 11. O-O (11. dxc5 Nxc5 12. Bb1 Bf6 13. O-O Bxc3 $5 14. Qc2 $5 Bf5 15. Qxf5 {taking on c3 would allow the exchange of the light-squared bishops.} g6 16. Qg4 Bg7 17. Ra3 Rc8 $5 $13) 11... cxd4 (11... Nxa5 12. Nd5 Nc6 13. Re1 Re8 $6 {0-1 Grabinsky, J (2251)-Ramasindraibe, G (2146) Titled Tuesday intern op 6th June Chess.com INT blitz 2020 (8)} 14. Ng5 Bxg5 15. Rxe8+ Qxe8 16. Bxg5 $16) 12. Nd5 Nde5 $13) 5. Ra3 {This is the main idea behind the very early a2-a4. With the knight on b1 still, White can transfer his rook to the kingside.} (5. c5 {makes less sense after a2-a4.} Nd5 6. Nc3 Nb4 7. d4 d6 {and the knight has a wonderful square on b4.}) (5. d4 d6 6. exd6 cxd6 7. Nc3 g6 {transposes to Line 42. .}) 5... d5 $5 {The most resolute way of continuing the development. Since White is a bit underdeveloped, he needs to treat the central tension with care.} 6. exd6 {Reducing Black's dynamic potential.} (6. c5 $6 Nc4 7. Bxc4 dxc4 8. d4 Bf5 9. Be3 {1-0 Seiler,A (2170)-Reinemer,F (2265) Cologne op 47th 1998 (5)} Na6 10. Nf3 (10. Nd2 Nb4 $15) 10... Nxc5 $1 11. dxc5 Qxd1+ 12. Kxd1 Bxb1 13. Nd2 Bd3 14. Rc3 O-O-O 15. Kc1 Rd5 16. f4 f6 $15) 6... cxd6 7. Rg3 g6 8. h4 h5 9. Nc3 Nc6 10. d4 Bg7 11. Be3 Bf5 {Black has achieved a normal development and the rook appears to be less threatening on g3 than intended.} 12. Bd3 (12. Nb5 {Â½-Â½ Kurayan, R (2357)-Nestorovic, L (2397) EU-ch U18 Albena 2011 (5)} Nb4 {[%cal Gf5c2,Gc2a4] with the strong threat ...Bc2 followed by ...Bxa4.}) (12. Rg5 {with the idea of sacrificing on f5 is not too effective.} Nb4 (12... e6 $5 13. Nf3 Nb4 $15) (12... d5 13. c5 Nc4 14. Bxc4 dxc4 $15) 13. Rxf5 gxf5 14. Nf3 Rc8 15. b3 d5 16. c5 Nd7 17. Bb5 Kf8 $15) 12... Bxd3 13. Qxd3 Rc8 14. b3 {1-0 Christiansen, J (2609)-Manafov, V (2236) Titled Tuesday intern op 3rd March Chess.com INT blitz 2020 (7)} d5 $1 $146 {AFter the bishops' exchange, this is the logical way of attacking the centre, of course.} 15. c5 Nb4 {The queenside structure does not help White too much.} 16. Qd2 Nd7 17. Nge2 Nxc5 (17... b6 $15) 18. dxc5 d4 19. Nxd4 Bxd4 20. Bxd4 Qxd4 21. Qxd4 Nc2+ 22. Kd2 Nxd4 23. Rb1 Nf5 24. Rh3 Rxc5 $15 *

