{[%evp 0,38,16,38,62,55,45,29,29,29,29,11,6,7,5,5,5,21,27,7,12,9,9,-4,-20,12,11,-1,-5,-6,3,-4,-4,-4,5,4,11,-19,-20,-22,-26]} 1. e4 Nf6 2. e5 Nd5 3. c4 Nb6 4. c5 {White continues gaining space, obviously irritated by the black knight, which will have to move for the first time in a row, at a stage when Black did not touch any of his other pieces yet. The move was introduced by Gruber in his game against Gruenfeld in 1923 and next used by Lasker in a simul game in 1927. In other words, the players with white were not always ready to advance their pawns so resolutely in the early years of the official existence of the Alekhine Defence.} Nd5 {The knight has finally reached relative stability in the centre, but Black still did not develop any other piece. The latter also applies for White, who hopes to use his huge space advantage in order to get attacking chances. At the same time, the white centre is exposed to ...d7-d6 and ...b7-b6. The next phase is characterized by a mutual fight for rapid development. Against all White's plans, Black has more than one adequate reaction. I have aimed at yielding certain logical coherence to our repertoire, by choosing principled answers. Black will try to maintain the tension whenever possible and sacrifice small amounts of material for the initiative, instead of grabbing the offered pawns, which would yield White some attacking possibilities.} 5. Nc3 (5. Bc4 {is examined in Line 56.}) ({For} 5. d4 {, see Lines 57 to 62.}) 5... e6 {Following the principle exposed above.} ({There is nothing wrong with} 5... Nxc3 {, but I discarded it because} 6. dxc3 {frees White's development.}) 6. d4 (6. Nxd5 exd5 {is examined in Line 55.}) 6... d6 7. cxd6 {The most common reaction.} ({The attempt to maintain the tension with} 7. Nxd5 exd5 8. Be3 {yields Black a comfortable structure.} dxe5 9. dxe5 c6 10. Rc1 Nd7 11. f4 b6 12. cxb6 (12. Qa4 {Â½-Â½ Dutschak,H-Migl,D (2235) BL2-Sued 9091 Germany 1990 [3]} Bxc5 13. Bxc5 bxc5 14. Qxc6 Qa5+ 15. Kf2 Rb8 $15) 12... axb6 13. Rxc6 Rxa2 $11 {Black's minor pieces will soon be very active.}) 7... cxd6 8. Nf3 (8. Nxd5 exd5 {transposes to Line 55.}) 8... Nc6 9. Be2 {A flexible move, allowing the queen to maintain some control along the d-file.} (9. Bd3 {exposes the bishop.} Ndb4 10. Be4 dxe5 11. dxe5 Qxd1+ 12. Nxd1 Bd7 13. Nc3 (13. a3 Nd5 14. Ne3 {0-1 Orozbaev, E (1973)-Quintiliano Pinto, R (2469) Titled Tuesday intern op 20th Oct Chess.com INT blitz 2020 (5)} Nb6 {The white knight is misplaced on e3, so there is no need to exchange it.} 15. Bd2 Be7 16. O-O O-O 17. Rac1 Rfd8 18. Rfd1 Be8 $11) 13... Na6 14. O-O Nc5 15. Bb1 O-O-O 16. Be3 Be7 17. Rc1 Kb8 18. Ne4 Nxe4 19. Bxe4 Nb4 20. a3 Nd5 21. Bxd5 exd5 22. Nd4 Rc8 23. f4 g6 24. Kf2 Rc4 25. b3 Rxc1 26. Bxc1 Rc8 27. b4 Rc4 28. Bb2 Bf5 29. Rc1 Rxc1 30. Bxc1 Be4 31. g4 f6 $11 {1-0 Hajek,R-Vachtfeidl,P (2016) Zdar nad Sazavou Vysocina op-B 2007 (3)}) (9. exd6 Bxd6 {helps Black's development.} 10. Bd3 Ncb4 $5 ({The more restraint development is good, too.} 10... Bd7 11. O-O O-O 12. Re1 Rc8 13. a3 Qb6 $11 {as tried in several correspondence games.}) 11. Bb1 Nxc3 12. bxc3 Nd5 13. Bd2 Qc7 14. Qb3 b6 15. Be4 (15. c4 Nf6 16. O-O O-O 17. Re1 Bb7 18. Ne5 Nd7 $11) 15... Bb7 16. c4 Ne7 17. Bxb7 Qxb7 18. O-O O-O 19. Rfe1 {Â½-Â½ Maze,S (2554)-Thorfinnsson,B (2398) Reykjavik op 2010 (9)} Rac8 $11) (9. Bb5 {exposes the bishop slightly.} Nxc3 (9... dxe5 10. Nxe5 Bd7 11. Nxd7 Qxd7 12. O-O Be7 {is also safe for Black, as proven in many games.}) 10. bxc3 Bd7 11. O-O (11. Rb1 dxe5 12. dxe5 Qc7 13. O-O {1-0 Comp The King I-De Waard, J The Hague AEGON 1993 (4)} Rd8 {In this phase, it is important to make all the useful moves before castling, in order to prevent an early white attack against the king.} 14. Qe2 Bc5 15. Bd3 Ne7 {Planning ...Bc6.} 16. Nd4 Bc6 17. Nxc6 Nxc6 18. Bf4 Rd7 19. h4 O-O 20. h5 Rfd8 21. Bc2 a6 {Anticipating Ba4.} 22. Qe4 g6 $11 {followed by ...Bf8 and ...Ne7 if needed.}) 11... Nxe5 12. Nxe5 dxe5 (12... Bxb5 $6 13. Nxf7 $1 Kxf7 14. Qh5+ $14) 13. Bxd7+ Qxd7 14. dxe5 Qxd1 15. Rxd1 Bc5 $11) 9... Nxc3 10. bxc3 dxe5 11. Nxe5 (11. dxe5 Qxd1+ 12. Bxd1 b6 $11 13. O-O (13. Ba4 Bd7 14. Bc2 Rc8 $15) 13... Bb7 14. Be2 (14. Be3 Ba3 $15) 14... Bc5 $15) 11... Nxe5 12. dxe5 Qxd1+ 13. Bxd1 Bd7 {Â½-Â½ Falk, T-Siegler, W Hessenliga Germany 1995 Black does not have any problems, of course.} 14. Bf3 Rc8 15. Bxb7 Rxc3 16. O-O Rc7 17. Bf3 Bc5 18. Bb2 O-O 19. Rfc1 Rfc8 $11 {0-1 Haack,S (1926)-Hein,S (2027) Hamburger Liga Aufstieg 2009 (5.9)} *

