{[%evp 0,38,30,23,62,53,43,23,34,12,9,-7,12,-41,-32,-24,-18,-41,-9,-15,-9,-41,-45,-19,-9,10,-11,-5,45,33,15,32,9,-26,1,-32,-42,-85,-85,-108,-125]} 1. e4 Nf6 2. e5 Nd5 3. c4 Nb6 4. c5 Nd5 5. d4 {A flexible move, not defining White's intentions yet. Its main drawback is giving Black a tempo for free.} d6 {The logical way of undermining White's centre.} 6. cxd6 (6. Bc4 {fails to transpose to Lines 57 to 62, since Black can play} dxe5 7. dxe5 e6 {, when c5 is in danger.} 8. Bxd5 (8. Qg4 Nd7 9. Nf3 h5 10. Qg3 Nxc5 11. Nbd2 Nb6 12. O-O Nxc4 13. Nxc4 {1-0 Faraoni,E (2190)-Palma Espinoza,H (2140) SEMI A001 corr SEMI email 1999} Qd3 14. Qf4 b6 $17) 8... Qxd5 9. Qxd5 exd5 10. Be3 Nd7 11. Nc3 c6 12. Nf3 Nxc5 $17 {0-1 Hernandez, R-Alayola Montanez, J (2212) Estatal Chic op 2000 (3)}) (6. exd6 exd6 7. cxd6 Bxd6 $11 {yields Black a comfortable position against the Isolani.}) 6... exd6 7. Nf3 dxe5 8. dxe5 Bb4+ {Black displays early activity, making White's space advantage irrelevant.} 9. Bd2 O-O 10. Bc4 Nc6 11. O-O Bg4 {Black has some lead in development and the pawn on e5 is in danger. White needs to be careful.} 12. h3 (12. Re1 Re8 13. Bxb4 Ndxb4 $11 14. Qb3 $6 (14. Nbd2 Nd3 $11) 14... Bxf3 15. Bxf7+ Kh8 16. Qxf3 (16. Bxe8 Bd5 17. Qg3 Qxe8 $15) (16. gxf3 Rxe5 17. Nc3 Nd3 18. Rxe5 Ncxe5 19. Ne4 Qh4 20. Qe6 Nxf3+ 21. Kf1 Nxh2+ {0-1 Jerez Perez,A (2350)-Westerinen,H (2405) Zaragoza op-A 1995 (5)}) 16... Nxe5 17. Qc3 {[%csl Ge1]} Nf3+ 18. gxf3 Rxe1+ 19. Qxe1 Qg5+ 20. Kh1 Nc2 21. Qd1 Nxa1 22. Nc3 b5 $15) 12... Bxf3 {The simplest. Black maintains the rhythm of his initiative.} (12... Bh5 13. g4 Nb6 (13... Bg6 14. Bg5 Be7 15. Bxd5 Bxg5 16. Nc3 $14) 14. Bb5 Bxd2 15. Nbxd2 Bg6 16. Bxc6 bxc6 {In principle, Black is OK here, too, as his queenside weaknesses are balanced by White's relatively vulnerable kingside. In practical play, though, White's position may be easier to handle.} 17. Rc1 Nd5 (17... h5 18. Re1 hxg4 19. hxg4 {1-0 Mammadov,Z (2446)-Mamedov,R (2662) Nakhchivan op 2013 (2)} Qd5 $5 $11) 18. Qa4 (18. Rxc6 Qd7 19. Rc1 h5 $132) 18... Rb8 19. b3 h5 $13) 13. Qxf3 Nb6 (13... Bxd2 14. Nxd2 Nxe5 {is likely to lead to a better ending for White.} 15. Qxd5 Qxd5 16. Bxd5 Rad8 17. Bxb7 Rxd2 18. Rfc1 Rxb2 19. Rxc7 g5 20. Bd5 Rd8 21. Bb3 Rd7 22. Rxd7 Nxd7 23. Rc1 $14) 14. Bxb4 Nxb4 15. Bb3 a5 (15... c5 $5 16. Qxb7 (16. Na3 Qe7 17. Rae1 Nc6 $11) (16. e6 c4 17. Bxc4 Nxc4 18. Qb3 Nxb2 19. exf7+ Rxf7 20. Qxb4 Nd3 21. Qb3 Nf4 $44) 16... c4 17. Qe4 (17. Bd1 Nd3 18. Bc2 Qd4 $11) 17... Qd3 18. Qe1 (18. Qxd3 Nxd3 19. Bc2 Nxb2 $11) 18... N6d5 19. Ba4 Qd4 20. Nc3 Nd3 21. Rd1 N5f4 $44) 16. e6 fxe6 17. Qxb7 (17. Bxe6+ Kh8 18. Qb3 (18. Qxb7 Nc2 $17) 18... Qd6 $11) 17... N6d5 $13 {Black has a lot of pawn weaknesses, but his knights are very active and White is underdeveloped.} 18. Nc3 $2 {Overlooking that the white queen is in danger.} (18. Qb5 c6 19. Qe2 Nf4 20. Qe4 Qg5 21. Kh2 a4 22. Bxe6+ (22. Bd1 Rad8 23. Nc3 Rd4 24. Qf3 a3 25. bxa3 Rd3 26. Qg4 Qe5 27. Kg1 h5 $19 {trapping the queen.}) 22... Kh8 $15 {White has serious problems since his queenside pieces are not playing yet.}) 18... c6 $1 {Threatening ...Rf7.} 19. Bxd5 exd5 $17 {0-1 Atabayev, Y (2455)-Lalith, B (2529) Asian Continental op 16th Chengdu 2017 (7)} *

