{[%evp 0,52,18,13,52,51,51,33,35,17,20,12,25,12,9,-6,15,31,30,-23,75,81,73,70,70,63,70,58,58,55,57,61,61,61,74,29,56,33,33,37,111,-7,1,1,-5,-50,-7,-7,-14,-14,-14,-7,-23,-21,-24]} 1. e4 Nf6 2. e5 Nd5 3. c4 Nb6 4. c5 Nd5 5. Bc4 {Before establishing the knight contact or advancing the d-pawn, White induces the next move.} e6 6. Nc3 {The most popular move, implying a pawn sacrifice.} (6. Bxd5 exd5 {is likely to transpose to some lines below.}) (6. d4 {is examined in Lines 58 to 62.}) 6... Bxc5 {I was attracted by this pawn grabbing only because, in the later phase, I spotted an interesting exchange sacrifice.} (6... Nxc3 7. dxc3 Bxc5 {is less principled because it grabs a pawn AND clears the c1-h6 diagonal.} 8. Qg4 {This causes Black certain queenside problems.} g6 (8... O-O $2 9. Bh6 g6 10. h4 $5 {White does not have to hurry with taking the exchange.} d5 {1-0 Vermeulen, F (1930)-Bettman, J (1858) Groningen Atlantis op-B 2013 (5)} 11. Bd3 Nd7 12. Nf3 $18) (8... Kf8 $13) (8... Bf8 9. Bg5 $36) 9. Bh6 $44 {With one exception, all these lines are playable for Black, but White would have the initiative, which contradicts the principle mentioned in the introduction to Line 54.}) ({The adventurous} 6... d6 {corresponds the spirit of our repertoire and is examined in Line 58.}) 7. d4 (7. Qg4 {is premature.} O-O 8. d4 (8. Nf3 f5 9. Qg3 Nb4 10. O-O d5 (10... Nc2 11. Rb1 Nc6 12. d3 N2d4 13. Nxd4 Bxd4 14. Bf4 a6 15. a3 b5 16. Bb3 Bb7 $15 {0-1 Augustin,J-Popov,L WchT Students 07th Leningrad 1960 (2)}) 11. Bb3 (11. Be2 d4 12. Na4 Be7 $17 {0-1 Kende,G (2227)-Sondermann,J (2164) Budapest FS08 IM-B 2005 (5)}) 11... Nd3 12. Bc2 Nxc1 13. Raxc1 Be7 $15) 8... f5 $1 {This intermediate move reveals why the queen incursion to g4 is premature.} 9. exf6 (9. Qg3 {0-1 Florian, J-Ratolistka, J CSR-ch30 Kosice 1961 (5)} Nxc3 10. bxc3 d5 11. Bd3 Be7 $15) 9... Nxf6 10. Qh4 Bb6 11. Nf3 {0-1 Dias,S (2032)-Assumpcao,R (2285) Sao Paulo Braga op 2011 (8)} Nc6 12. a4 (12. O-O Ne7 $15) 12... d5 13. Bd3 Qe8 14. O-O Qh5 $15) (7. Bxd5 exd5 8. Nxd5 (8. d4 Bb4 $11) 8... d6 9. d4 Bb6 10. Nxb6 axb6 11. exd6 Qxd6 12. Ne2 O-O 13. Bf4 $11 {Â½-Â½ Keber,E-Manarin,F (2500) EM/O/006 corr ICCF email 1999}) (7. Nxd5 exd5 8. Bxd5 d6 9. d4 Bb4+ 10. Bd2 dxe5 (10... Bxd2+ 11. Qxd2 c6 12. Bb3 dxe5 13. dxe5 Qxd2+ 14. Kxd2 Na6 15. f4 Nc5 16. Bc2 Be6 17. Nf3 O-O-O+ 18. Ke3 Bd5 $11 {Â½-Â½ Roose,J-Honfi,K olm11 qual GP2 B2 corr ICCF corr 1987}) 11. Qa4+ c6 12. Bxf7+ Kxf7 13. Qxb4 exd4 14. Nf3 Re8+ 15. Kf1 b6 $15) 7... Bb4 (7... Nxc3 8. bxc3 d5 9. Bd3 Bf8 10. Nh3 c5 11. O-O Nc6 12. Ng5 $44 {alows White to create certain kingside threats.}) 8. Bxd5 ({Even though rarely played,} 8. Qg4 {deserves mentioning.} Nxc3 9. a3 $1 $146 (9. bxc3 $2 Bxc3+ 10. Kf1 Qe7 11. Rb1 (11. Qxg7 Qf8) 11... f5 12. Qh5+ g6 13. Qd1 Nc6 14. Nf3 Bxd4 15. Nxd4 Qc5 16. Nb5 Qxc4+ 17. Qe2 Qxe2+ 18. Kxe2 Kf7 19. Nxc7 Rb8 $15 {0-1 Sveshnikov,E (2515)-Khmelnitsky,I Sibenik op 1990}) 9... Ne4+ (9... Qe7 10. axb4 Ne4 {transposes.}) 10. axb4 (10. Kf1 Be7 11. Qxe4 d5 12. exd6 cxd6 $17) 10... Qe7 $1 11. Qxg7 (11. Ra4 f5 12. Qh5+ (12. exf6 Nxf6 13. Qh4 b6 $15) 12... g6 13. Qd1 (13. Qh6 Nc6 14. f3 Nxd4 15. fxe4 b5 $15) 13... d5 14. Be2 {The central knight is in a certain danger, but f2-f3 is not a threat yet, due to ...Qh4, and if g2-g3, then ...Nxg3. Besides, Black can fight for clearing the path for the knight's retreat.} Bd7 15. b5 c6 16. bxc6 bxc6 17. Nh3 c5 $13) 11... Qxb4+ 12. Kf1 $1 {Paradoxically, the only good square. White allows his opponent to take the bishop with a check.} (12. Kd1 Rf8 13. Bh6 Nxf2+ 14. Ke2 Nxh1 15. Ra4 Qe7 16. Nf3 f5 17. exf6 Qxf6 $17) 12... Rf8 $1 (12... Qxc4+ $2 13. Ne2 Rf8 14. Bh6 Qb4 15. f3 Nd2+ 16. Kf2 Nb3 17. Ra4 Qe7 18. Ra3 $18 {The knight is trapped.}) 13. Bh6 (13. Ne2 d5 $132) 13... Nd2+ 14. Ke2 Nxc4 15. Ra4 Qxb2+ {The probability of a draw by perpetual is very high now.} 16. Kf3 (16. Kd3 Qb1+ 17. Kxc4 Qc2+ 18. Kb4 Qb2+ 19. Kc4 d5+ $19 {[%cal Gb8d7] followed by ...Nd7.}) 16... Nxe5+ $1 (16... Qc3+ 17. Kg4 Qxd4+ 18. Kh3 Qc5 19. Rxc4 Qe7 20. Nf3 f5 21. Qxe7+ Kxe7 22. Bxf8+ Kxf8 23. g4 b5 24. Rf4 Nc6 25. gxf5 exf5 26. Rxf5+ Ke7 27. Rh5 $14) 17. dxe5 Qb3+ 18. Ke2 Qc2+ 19. Ke1 Qb1+ {with a draw.}) 8... exd5 9. Qg4 O-O $5 $146 {This is the novelty that tempted me to investigate this variation.} (9... Kf8 {is playable, but White's compensation is beyond doubt.}) 10. Bh6 g6 11. Bxf8 (11. Nf3 d6 {does not change much.}) 11... Qxf8 {Black has a pawn for the exchange, a compact structure, and two potentially strong bishops. The main idea is to break with ...d7-d6.} 12. Nf3 (12. a3 d6 13. Qf4 dxe5 14. dxe5 Bxc3+ 15. bxc3 Nd7 16. Nf3 Nc5 $44) (12. h4 {In the absence of the light-squared bishop, which could carry out a sacrifice on g6, this is not dangerous.} d6 13. Qf4 dxe5 14. dxe5 Nd7 15. h5 c6 {It is useful to consolidate d5 and leave the a3-f8 diagonal open for a short while.} (15... Nc5 16. Qh4 $5 Bf5 17. hxg6 Bxg6 {is interesting, too.}) 16. Nf3 (16. hxg6 fxg6 $1 17. Qxf8+ Bxf8 18. f4 Nc5 19. Rd1 Bg4 $15) (16. Qh4 Be7 17. Qh2 g5 $44) 16... Nc5 (16... Be7 17. hxg6 fxg6 18. Qxf8+ Nxf8 19. Nd4 h5 $13 {Black has a safe blockade on light squares.}) 17. Qh4 Nd3+ 18. Ke2 Be7 19. Qh2 Bf5 {The position remains very complicated.} 20. g4 $5 Bxg4 21. Kxd3 Bxf3 22. hxg6 h5 $1 23. Rhg1 fxg6 24. Rxg6+ Kh7 25. Rag1 Qf5+ 26. Kd2 d4 $13 {It is not entirely clear which king is more exposed.}) 12... d6 13. Qf4 c6 14. O-O dxe5 15. Nxe5 Bd6 16. Qh4 Na6 17. f4 {White's only active plan.} Nc7 18. Rae1 f6 19. Kh1 (19. Re3 $2 fxe5 20. fxe5 Qe7 21. Rf6 Ne8 $17 {In this line, there is a pin along the e-file.}) 19... Ne6 (19... fxe5 $2 20. fxe5 Qe7 21. Rf6 Ne8 22. exd6 $18) (19... Ne8 $5 {Heading for f5.} 20. Ng4 Bxg4 21. Qxg4 f5 22. Qf3 Nf6 $11) 20. f5 g5 21. Qg4 (21. Qf2 Nf4 22. Qg3 Qg7 23. Nd3 Bxf5 24. Nxf4 gxf4 25. Qxg7+ Kxg7 26. Ne2 Bd3 27. Rf3 Be4 28. Rf2 Re8 29. Rc1 f3 30. gxf3 Bg6 $5 $11) 21... Ng7 {[%cal Gc8f5,Gf6e5] White has to count with ...Bxf5 followed by ...fxe5.} 22. Qf3 (22. Nd3 h5 23. Qh3 Bd7 $15 {Black is very compact and the pawn on f5 is in danger.}) 22... Bxf5 (22... fxe5 $5 23. dxe5 Bc5 24. g4 $13) 23. Ng4 Bxg4 24. Qxg4 Qf7 25. Na4 h5 26. Qd1 f5 $44 *

