{[%evp 0,52,18,13,52,51,51,33,35,17,20,12,25,12,9,-6,15,31,30,-23,75,81,73,70,70,63,70,58,58,55,57,61,61,61,74,29,56,33,33,37,111,-7,1,1,-5,-50,-7,-7,-14,-14,-14,-7,-23,-21,-24]} 1. e4 Nf6 2. e5 Nd5 3. c4 Nb6 4. c5 Nd5 5. Bc4 e6 6. Nc3 d6 $5 {After analyzing Line 57, I still had the feeling that I had deviated a bit from our main principle in this line. Looking through Bagirov's book on the Alekhine, published in Russian in 1987, I discovered this interesting move, entirely corresponding to the spirit of our repertoire. Bagirov calls it "The Mikenas line" since Vladas Mikenas had tried it in a couple of games in the '40s. A few moves later, we will deviate from Mikenas' games, though.} 7. Nxd5 {There is not anything better.} (7. d4 dxe5 8. dxe5 Nxc3 9. Qxd8+ Kxd8 10. bxc3 Bxc5 $17 {1-0 Polyansky, V (1985)-Leun, V (1849) Voronezh Rating op 06 2014 (7)}) 7... exd5 8. Bxd5 dxe5 $1 {Bagirov considers this move insufficient.} ({The genuine Mikenas line goes} 8... c6 $5 9. Bxf7+ $1 (9. Bb3 dxe5 10. Qh5 Qe7 $15) 9... Kxf7 10. cxd6 {with obvious compensation for the piece. Bagirov considers this one of the most complicated lines in the Alekhine Defence. Mikenas tried two moves here:} Qe8 {This was the other move tried between the same players.} (10... Be6 11. Nf3 $1 {Mentioned by Bagirov as an improvement over the initial game.} (11. f4 $6 {delayed the king's evacuation from the center, allowing} Bxd6 $1 12. exd6 Re8 13. Kf2 Qxd6 $44 {0-1 Nezhmetdinov, R-Mikenas, V Match Nezhmetdinov-Mikenas Kazan 1948 (3)}) (11. Nh3 {is the other move mentioned by Bagirov but never tested yet. Engines consider it the strongest. Bagirov writes that White has such ideas as Ng5, Nf4, and d2-d4. The point is that the sacrifice on d6 is not entirely satisfactory now, meaning that Black is under strong pressure.} Bxd6 12. Qf3+ Kg8 13. exd6 Qxd6 14. O-O $14) 11... Nd7 {This has been played a few times, but I will quote here the game mentioned by Bagirov, not available in the database.} 12. O-O g6 13. d3 h6 14. Nd4 Qe8 15. f4 Kg8 16. Bd2 Rh7 17. Bc3 Rf7 18. Qe2 Nb6 19. Rae1 Qd7 20. Nxe6 Qxe6 21. g4 $40 {Petriaev-Sholokhov, Novosibirsk 1955. It is interesting that during the whole sequence, White has almost always played the first or the second engine's suggestion. We should be careful when calling a move typical for the computer since anonymous players could play like machines more than half a century ago.}) 11. Qe2 {is the move played by "Nezh".} (11. Qf3+ {This is Bagirov's recommendation.} Kg8 12. Qe3 {White has transferred his queen to the optimal square with a gain of time. The sacrifice on d6 is bad now.} Be6 (12... Bxd6 $2 13. exd6 Qxe3+ 14. dxe3 $16) 13. Ne2 Nd7 14. f4 (14. d4 g6 15. O-O Bg7 16. f4 {transposes.}) ({Another classical game went} 14. O-O $6 Nxe5 $1 15. Qxe5 Bc4 16. Qxe8 Rxe8 17. d3 Bxd3 18. Rd1 Bxe2 19. d7 Rd8 20. Bg5 Bxd1 21. Rxd1 Be7 22. Bxe7 Kf7 23. Bxd8 Rxd8 24. f4 Ke7 25. Kf2 Rxd7 26. Rxd7+ Kxd7 27. Ke3 Ke6 28. Ke4 g6 $11 {Â½-Â½ Vasiukov,E-Spassky,B URS-ch26 Final Tbilisi 1959 (3)}) 14... g6 15. O-O Bg7 16. d4 Nb6 $13 {Black is better prepared against White's attack than in Petriaev-Sholokhov.}) 11... c5 {taking measures against d2-d4.} 12. Nf3 ({Even without gaining a tempo,} 12. Qe3 {is the best.} Bxd6 13. exd6 Qxe3+ 14. dxe3 Rd8 $14 {Black has some compensation for the pawn, but White is better of course.}) 12... Bxd6 $1 13. Ng5+ Kg6 14. Qd3+ Kxg5 {An exotic position.} 15. Qxd6 Qd8 (15... Qc6 $17 16. d4+ Kh5) (15... Nc6 16. d4+ Kh5 17. Qxc5 Qe7 $15 {Bagirov.}) 16. d4+ Kf5 $2 ({Bagirov does not notice that} 16... Kh5 $1 $13 {, keeping g4 defended by the bishop, would have maintained the game unclear.}) 17. g4+ $1 Ke4 18. Qxc5 Rf8 19. O-O Kf3 20. h3 b6 21. Qc3+ Ke4 22. Qc4 {1-0 Nezhmetdinov, R-Mikenas, V Match Nezhmetdinov-Mikenas Kazan 1948 A beautiful game, is it not?}) 9. Qb3 ({Bagirov considers that} 9. Qf3 {causes Black big problems, but this is not true.} f6 (9... Qe7 10. Bxb7 e4 11. Qb3 $18 {1-0 Nguyen, P-Vo, T VIE-chT Thua Thien Hue 2001 (8) was given by Bagirov and... happened in a much later game!}) 10. Bxb7 ({Curiously, Bagirov considers the line unplayable because of} 10. Bb3 $2 Bxc5 11. Qg3 {. After} Qe7 12. Ne2 Nc6 $17 {Black is a pawn up, has the better structure and is better developed.}) 10... Bxb7 11. Qxb7 Nd7 {Bagirov is right when considering this unclear.} 12. b4 a5 13. d4 axb4 $13) 9... Bxc5 $1 {Black needs resolute action, of course.} 10. Bxf7+ (10. Bxb7 Bxb7 11. Qxb7 Nd7 $15) 10... Kf8 11. Bd5 (11. Qf3 Qf6 12. Bd5 Nd7 13. Ne2 c6 14. Be4 Qxf3 15. Bxf3 Nf6 16. Nc3 Bf5 $15 {0-1 Goldt, R-Schreck, R corr 1998}) 11... c6 (11... Qh4 $5 {0-1 Klementev, O (2141)-Bykovskiy, O (2251) Olkhovskiy Memorial rapid Vinnytsia 2016 (3)} 12. d4 Bxd4 13. g3 Qf6 14. Nf3 $36) 12. Bc4 Qd4 (12... b5 $5 13. Be2 Qf6 14. d4 exd4 15. Nf3 Be6 16. Qc2 Nd7 17. O-O h6 $13) 13. Qf3+ Ke8 14. Qf7+ Kd8 15. Ne2 Qd7 $11 *

