{[%evp 0,32,28,23,45,45,24,40,27,12,12,9,17,33,33,38,36,-5,-20,16,7,-4,-8,-58,11,2,-22,-22,-31,-31,-31,-51,-51,-36,2]} 1. e4 Nf6 2. e5 Nd5 3. c4 Nb6 4. c5 Nd5 5. Bc4 e6 6. d4 {A flexible move, which, however, allows Black to choose his favorite way of breaking the white centre.} b6 {A principled move, aimed at exchanging a wing pawn for a central one.} (6... d6 {is entirely playable, too.}) 7. Bxd5 (7. Nf3 bxc5 8. dxc5 Bb7 {leaves White exposed in the centre.} 9. Qb3 (9. Bxd5 Bxd5 10. b4 a5 11. b5 (11. Bd2 axb4 12. Bxb4 Nc6 13. Qd2 Ra4 $19 {0-1 Ualpaev,S (623)-Lenz,J (1053) RN-2016-0-01234 LSS email}) 11... Bxc5 12. O-O c6 (12... Bc4 13. Qc2 Bxf1 14. Qxc5 $36) 13. a4 Bb4 $15) 9... Qc8 10. O-O Bxc5 11. Ng5 Nb6 12. Be3 {1-0 Pias,L-Pomar Salamanca,A Estoril IT 1950} Bxe3 $1 13. fxe3 h6 $1 14. Rxf7 (14. Nxf7 O-O $19) 14... hxg5 15. Rxg7 Kf8 16. Rxg5 Qd8 17. Rg4 Qe7 18. Nd2 Ke8 19. Rf1 Nc6 $17 {[%cal Ge8d8] followed by the king's march to the queenside.}) (7. Nc3 {is examined in Line 60.}) ({For} 7. cxb6 {, see Lines 61 and 62.}) 7... exd5 8. b4 {Trying to consolidate the centre. It is curious that all the white and black pieces are undeveloped and both sides are concerned about the pawn fight.} (8. Nc3 bxc5 9. Nxd5 (9. dxc5 c6 10. Be3 Na6 11. Qg4 Rb8 12. Nge2 Rxb2 13. O-O Rb4 14. Qg3 h5 $17 {1-0 Ptacnik,S (2037)-Vieira,A (1835) Wch Seniors 50 26th Marianske Lazne 2016 (9)}) 9... Nc6 $5 {The most ambitious continuation, maintaining Black's structural flexibility.} (9... c6 10. Nc3 d5 11. exd6 Bxd6 12. dxc5 Qe7+ 13. Qe2 Bxc5 14. Qxe7+ Bxe7 15. Nf3 O-O 16. O-O Na6 $11) 10. dxc5 Bxc5 11. Nf3 Bb7 12. O-O (12. Bg5 Ne7 $11) 12... Ne7 13. Nf4 O-O $13) (8. cxb6 axb6 {transposes to Line 2.}) 8... a5 9. b5 bxc5 10. dxc5 Bxc5 {Finally a piece move. Black's two bishops and the extra pawn allow him to fight against White's space advantage.} 11. Nf3 (11. a4 $6 {0-1 Ualpaev, S (766)-Lenz, J (1156) RN-2015-0-00997 LSS email wastes a tempo and weakens a square.} Bb4+ 12. Bd2 d6 13. Bxb4 axb4 14. Qxd5 c6 15. bxc6 Be6 $17 16. Qxd6 Qxd6 17. exd6 Nxc6 18. Nd2 Kd7 19. Ne2 Rhb8 $17) (11. Qxd5 {also offers Black an important tempo, followed by others soon.} Bb4+ 12. Bd2 c6 13. Qf3 Qb6 14. Nc3 Bb7 15. Qg3 O-O $15) 11... d6 12. Qxd5 c6 13. bxc6 Be6 14. Qe4 d5 15. Qc2 Qb6 16. O-O Nxc6 $11 *

