{[%evp 0,52,17,39,58,64,64,66,66,61,61,15,15,2,31,31,23,17,23,23,41,41,41,-3,5,5,1,7,7,-7,25,25,22,47,45,70,56,66,62,62,53,53,74,59,122,93,89,63,48,46,45,32,44,34,34]} 1. e4 Nf6 2. e5 Nd5 3. c4 Nb6 4. c5 Nd5 5. Bc4 e6 6. d4 b6 7. Nc3 {An ambitious move, preparing an interesting pawn sacrifice.} Nxc3 8. bxc3 bxc5 {This allows WHite to carry out the planned sacrifice.} (8... Nc6 {corresponds better to our main principle, but there is not enough practical material on it. I have organized Line 60 in such a way that the tree does not grow chaotically, but it is possible that in my first game with this line I would choose precisely this move.} 9. Nf3 (9. cxb6 axb6 10. Nf3 Ba6 $11 {With the more flexible structure for Black, compensating for White's space advantage.}) (9. Qg4 {1-0 Matous, M-Tichy, V CSR-ch41 Semifinal C Havirov 1971 (11)} bxc5 $13) 9... Bb7 {Still preparing the capture on c5.} (9... bxc5 10. d5 $14) 10. cxb6 (10. O-O bxc5 11. d5 Na5 $15) 10... axb6 11. O-O Be7 (11... Ba6 $5) 12. Re1 Na5 13. Bd3 O-O 14. Nd2 f5 15. exf6 Bxf6 16. Qh5 g6 17. Qg4 {White has more space, but also some pawn weaknesses.} c5 18. Re3 cxd4 19. cxd4 Rf7 20. Bb2 Rc8 21. Rg3 Qe7 22. Ne4 Bxe4 23. Qxe4 {1-0 Kordonowski,F-Koch,K Ruhrgebiet VK2 9697 1996} Bh4 24. d5 (24. Rf3 Rxf3 25. gxf3 Nc4 $15) 24... Bxg3 25. hxg3 e5 26. Re1 Re8 $13) 9. d5 {White's main idea.} (9. Nf3 {is less challenging.} cxd4 10. Nxd4 (10. Qxd4 d5 11. Bb3 Ba6 $15 {0-1 Rahls,P (2338)-Keller,M (2179) Bad Woerishofen op 23th 2007 (9)}) 10... Bb7 (10... Ba6 $5) 11. O-O Nc6 12. Rb1 Rb8 13. Rxb7 Rxb7 14. Nxc6 dxc6 15. Qa4 Rb6 16. Be3 Qa8 17. Bxb6 cxb6 {Â½-Â½ Bauer,R (1363)-Loktayev,V (1337) RE-2012-0-00089 LSS email} 18. Bb5 $1 {Leading to a perpetual in avoidance of the worse.} cxb5 19. Qxb5+ Ke7 20. Rd1 Qc8 21. Qb4+ Qc5 22. Qe4 Qc7 23. Qb4+ Ke8 24. Qb5+ Ke7 $11) 9... Qh4 10. Qd3 Bb7 (10... Qg4 $6 {is premature.} 11. Nh3 $1 Ba6 (11... Qxg2 12. Rg1 Qxh2 13. Bf4 $18) 12. Bxa6 Nxa6 13. Nf4 (13. Qxa6 Qxg2 14. Qf1 Qxd5 15. Bf4 Qe4+ 16. Kd2 c4 $44) 13... c4 14. Qxc4 Nc5 15. O-O $14 {1-0 Midonet, M (2169)-Marceline, P (1904) Martinique-ch 31th Madiana 2015 (1) Black has serious problems with his development.}) 11. Nh3 $5 $146 (11. Nf3 {is less effective.} Qg4 12. O-O exd5 13. Bxd5 Bxd5 14. Qxd5 Nc6 15. Ng5 Qf5 16. Re1 Be7 $13 17. Nxf7 $2 Rf8 18. Nd6+ cxd6 19. Bf4 Qe6 $19 {0-1 Midonet,M (2180)-Marceline,P (1945) Martinique-ch Schoelcher 2014 (10)}) 11... exd5 12. Bxd5 c4 $1 {Fighting for space.} (12... Bxd5 13. Qxd5 Nc6 14. Ng5 $14) 13. Qf3 Bxd5 14. Qxd5 Nc6 (14... c6 {is also worth mentioning.} 15. Qf3 {[%csl Ge4] Defending e4.} Qe7 (15... Be7 $6 16. O-O h5 {Hoping for ...Qg4.} 17. Qf5 {[%cal Gf5b1] Threatening Qb1 +-.} Na6 18. e6 $1 dxe6 19. Qa5 Nc5 20. Bg5 $1 Bxg5 21. Qxc5 $14 {with dangerous initiative.}) 16. O-O Na6 17. Be3 Nc5 18. Qf4 h6 19. Qd4 Qe6 20. Nf4 Qf5 21. Qxc4 Qe4 22. Qe2 Be7 $13 {Black has been balancing over the precipice, but now seems to have a viable position.}) 15. Ng5 Qh5 16. O-O Be7 17. e6 $1 {The only way to make something out of White's activity.} fxe6 18. Nxe6 $1 Qxd5 19. Nxc7+ Kf7 20. Nxd5 {White's knight looks impressive, but the pawn on c3 is a liability. Besides, the square on d3 is weak.} Rab8 (20... Rhd8 21. Bf4 Bc5 22. Rab1 Ne7 23. Rfd1 Nxd5 24. Rxd5 d6 25. Rb7+ Kg8 26. g3 (26. h4 Rab8 27. Rxb8 Rxb8 28. Bxd6 Rb1+ 29. Kh2 Bxf2 $11) 26... Rab8 27. Rxb8 Rxb8 28. Bxd6 Bxd6 29. Rxd6 Rb2 30. Kg2 Rc2 31. Ra6 Rxc3 {with a probable draw with three white pawns versus two black ones.}) 21. Bf4 (21. Ne3 Bf6 $11) 21... Rb5 22. Rfd1 Rd8 {Preparing to meet Ne3 with ...d7-d5.} 23. Rd2 Bc5 24. Rad1 d6 25. Ne3 (25. h3 Ra5 $5) 25... Bxe3 26. Bxe3 d5 $11 *

