{[%evp 0,32,35,22,33,33,24,22,22,22,22,15,15,8,8,-9,-9,-13,-13,-11,-11,-10,-10,-10,-14,-10,-10,-23,-22,-14,-31,-30,-20,-20,-20]} 1. e4 Nf6 2. e5 Nd5 3. c4 Nb6 4. c5 Nd5 5. Bc4 e6 6. d4 b6 7. cxb6 {Even though it looks like a positional concession, this is the most popular move.} axb6 {Capturing towards the centre is the principled decision of course. Black also opens the a-file for his rook.} 8. Nf3 (8. Ne2 {induces some small differences with respect to the main line.} Ba6 (8... Bb4+ $5 $146 9. Bd2 Bxd2+ 10. Qxd2 Bb7 11. Nbc3 Nxc3 12. Nxc3 O-O 13. O-O d6 $11) 9. Bxd5 (9. Bxa6 Nxa6 10. O-O Be7 11. Nbc3 Nab4 $1 $146 {The best way of maintaining the stability in the centre.} 12. a3 O-O 13. Bd2 Nxc3 14. Nxc3 Nc6 15. Bf4 d5 $11) 9... exd5 10. Nbc3 d6 11. O-O (11. e6 $5 fxe6 12. O-O Qf6 13. Re1 Bxe2 14. Nxe2 g5 {Preventing Nf4.} 15. f4 h6 16. Qc2 Kd7 17. Rf1 Nc6 $1 18. fxg5 Nxd4 $1 19. Qd3 Nxe2+ 20. Qxe2 Qe5 21. Rf7+ Kc8 22. Qf2 Bg7 23. gxh6 Bxh6 24. Bxh6 Rxh6 25. Rxc7+ $5 Kxc7 26. Qf7+ Kc6 27. Rc1+ Kb5 28. Qf1+ Kb4 29. a3+ Rxa3 30. bxa3+ Ka5 $15) 11... dxe5 12. Re1 Be7 (12... Nc6 $5 13. dxe5 Qd7 14. Nf4 O-O-O 15. Nfxd5 Nb4 16. Nxb4 Qxd1 17. Rxd1 Bxb4 18. Bg5 Rxd1+ 19. Rxd1 Bxc3 20. bxc3 Bc4 21. a3 h6 {with a probable draw.}) (12... e4 13. Nf4 c6 14. f3 Be7 15. fxe4 dxe4 16. Nxe4 O-O $11) 13. dxe5 Bxe2 14. Nxe2 O-O 15. Nf4 c6 16. Qg4 Qd7 17. e6 fxe6 18. Nxe6 Bc5 19. Re2 Na6 $13 {Â½-Â½ Looshnikov,N (2512)-Schuh,D (2364) Pardubice Czech op 22nd 2011 (4)}) (8. Nc3 {is examined in Line 62.}) 8... Ba6 9. Bxa6 (9. b3 {maintains the control over the light squares, but prevents White of the idea Nbc3 followed by bxc3.} Be7 10. O-O Bb7 $5 $146 11. Bb2 O-O 12. Nc3 Nxc3 13. Bxc3 d5 $11) (9. Nbd2 Be7 10. O-O O-O 11. Re1 d6 12. Bb3 Nd7 13. Nc4 dxe5 14. Nfxe5 Bb7 $11 {Black is doing fine and White's attacking attempts will lead to disaster.} 15. Qg4 $6 N5f6 16. Qg3 Ne4 17. Qd3 b5 18. Ne3 Nxe5 19. Qxb5 Bh4 20. Nd1 Nxf2 $19 {0-1 Kuksov, V-Baburin, A URS Soviet Union 1986}) 9... Nxa6 10. O-O (10. Nc3 Nab4 $11) 10... Be7 11. Nc3 Nab4 12. a3 O-O 13. Bd2 Nxc3 14. Bxc3 (14. bxc3 Nc6 15. a4 d6 $15) 14... Nd5 15. Qc2 b5 (15... Nxc3 {This is not wrong, but I do not see reasons to part with the central knight.} 16. Qxc3 c6 17. Rad1 b5 18. b4 f6 $11 {Â½-Â½ Groeber, E-Kalsch, H corr 1989}) 16. Bd2 c6 $11 *

