{[%evp 0,30,23,10,37,-41,-33,-26,-26,-44,-50,-77,-12,6,18,24,18,25,17,-11,1,50,49,29,30,27,25,1,17,0,25,10,21]} 1. e4 Nf6 {In this section, we will examine few rare ways of defending the pawn on e4, instead of the principled 2.e5. The main philosophy behind all these moves is that 1...Nf6 is a bit committal, possibly facing Black with problems maintaining his play coherent. I will only give some guidelines since these moves are neither dangerous nor popular.} 2. d3 (2. Bc4 {leads to a few exchanges favouring Black.} Nxe4 3. Bxf7+ Kxf7 4. Qh5+ Kg8 5. Qd5+ e6 6. Qxe4 d5 7. Qe3 {The white queen is exposed and Black has better control in the centre.} e5 {The most ambitious continuation.} (7... c5 $15 {followed by ...Nc6 is also good.}) 8. Qxe5 {Otherwise, White would be simply worse.} Nc6 9. Qe3 Qf6 (9... d4 $4 10. Qb3+ {1-0 Magana, B (2091)-Joseph, M (1731) Nairobi op 57th 2015 (1)}) 10. Ne2 Bd7 $15 {with a huge advance in development and excellent attacking chances.}) (2. Bd3 {is rather clumsy, since it blocks the path of the d-pawn.} e5 {Now is a good moment for transposing to the open games.} 3. Nf3 Nc6 4. O-O Bc5 5. c3 O-O 6. Bc2 d5 7. exd5 Qxd5 8. d3 Bf5 $11) (2. Qe2 e5 {leads to a curious situation. In the French Defence, there is such a variation: 1.e4 e6 2.Qe2 e5!? which is held as playable for Black. Here, we have an extra tempo, namely ...Nf6.} 3. Nf3 Nc6 4. c3 d5 5. d3 (5. exd5 Qxd5 6. d4 Bg4 7. dxe5 Nd7 $15) 5... Bc5 6. b4 Bb6 7. a4 a6 $11) ({The slightly more consistent} 2. Nc3 {is examined in Lines 64 and 65.}) 2... e5 {Once again, this is the most reliable way of obtaining a good position. The open games with an early d2-d3 are anything but challenging.} (2... d5 {is a good move, but after} 3. e5 Nfd7 4. f4 e6 5. Nf3 {Black cannot do without} c5 {, when after, say,} 6. g3 Nc6 7. Bg2 {we reach a Sicilian setup. It is not especially threatening for Black, but it is reasonably consistent for White, too. When playing the Alekhine Defence, we usually do not wish to transpose to other openings, unless White has made some important concession. We can say that after 1.e4 e5, 2.d3 is a concession, while after 1.e4 c5 less so.}) (2... c5 {also invites a transposition to the Sicilian, with the slight problem that Black has defined his intentions with respect to his king's knight a bit earlier than he might have wished to.}) ({As a curiosity, Napoleon played} 2... Nc6 {in the first recorded Alekhine Defence game ever. The game transposes below and will be shown just for fun in the respective place.}) 3. f4 {To my understanding, the only principled move. White fights for the centre in the spirit of the King's Gambit, with the important differences, that occupying the centre with d3-d4 would imply a loss of tempo and that his king's bishop cannot emerge on c4 quickly. On the other hand, the last move does not imply a pawn sacrifice as in the King's Gambit. Keeping the position static offers White just a solid position, sometimes some sort of Philidor Defence with an extra tempo. By the way, Philidor (and later Morphy) used to treat "his" opening completely differently from our modern perception. He used to play 3...f5, which in the concrete analysis is not really adequate.} (3. Nf3 Nc6 4. g3 {is an invitation to the Gleck variation. It is not a dangerous opening for Black, of course, but he can think of ways of sidestepping it.} (4. Be2 {is more passive and offers Black a choice between 4...Bc5 followed by ...d7-d6, with an active version of the Italian, or else transposing to a reversed Phillidor with an irrelevant tempo less:} d5 5. Nbd2 Bc5 6. O-O O-O 7. c3 a5 $11 {The Phillidor Defence is a solid, but not especially active opening, explaining why I called White's extra tempo "irrelevant". If anything, Black can play an early ...dxe5, leading to clear equality.}) (4. Nc3 {fails to transpose to the Glek system, since with the pawn on d3 already, Black can play} Bb4 {for instance} 5. Bd2 O-O 6. g3 d5 7. exd5 Nd4 $5 {Taking on d5 is very much OK, too, of course.} 8. Bg2 Bg4 $11) 4... d5 (4... Bc5 5. Bg2 d6 6. O-O O-O 7. Nc3 {would transpose to the Glek variation.}) 5. exd5 (5. Nbd2 {leads to a reve4rsed classical Pirc, where Black could get his tempo back with} dxe4 6. dxe4 Bc5 {, since in similar positions White usually plays Bf1-e2-c4.} 7. Bg2 O-O 8. O-O a5 {[%cal Gb7b6] Black has very comfortable play.} 9. c3 (9. Qe2 b6 $15 {followed by ...Ba6.}) 9... Qd3 $5 $15 {A typical move in the Pirc, causing WHite some developing problems.}) 5... Nxd5 6. Bg2 Bc5 7. O-O O-O 8. Re1 Re8 {This looks like some sort of reversed Pirc, or a relatively active reversed Phillidor. However, Black does not have problems, since he can keep his space advantage.} 9. Nbd2 Bg4 10. h3 Bh5 11. c3 (11. Nc4 f6 $11) 11... a5 (11... a6 $5) 12. Nc4 (12. a4 f6 $5 $11) (12. g4 Bg6 13. Ne4 Bb6 $11) 12... Nb6 13. Nxb6 Bxb6 $11 {1-0 Pedersen, D (2268)-Van Dael, S (2006) Hilversum op 2016 (4)}) (3. Nc3 Bb4 {is likely to transpose above.}) 3... Nc6 {This developing move appeals to me most. It is also in the style of the French emperor, who scared the whole continent (not with his chess games, though).} ({There is nothing wrong with} 3... exf4) 4. Nf3 (4. fxe5 Nxe5 {leads to some sort of mirrored Alekhine, with the queen's knight exposed in the centre, instead of its colleague.} 5. Nc3 (5. d4 Ng6 6. e5 Nd5 7. Nf3 d6 8. c4 {1-0 Shevchenko, K (2599)-Polivanov, A (2454) Bogdanovich Memorial Final Lichess.org INT blitz 2021 (4)} Ndf4 $11) 5... Bb4 {With the pawn on d3, always an active idea.} ({Napoleon played the adventurous} 5... Nfg4 $2 6. d4 Qh4+ 7. g3 Qf6 {AFter 8.Bf4, Black is just lost, but instead the countess allowed him to win quickly.} 8. Nh3 $4 Nf3+ 9. Ke2 Nxd4+ 10. Kd3 Ne5+ 11. Kxd4 Bc5+ 12. Kxc5 Qb6+ 13. Kd5 Qd6# {0-1 Madame de Remusat-Napoleon I Napoleon Bonaparte Paris 1802}) (5... d5 {is entirely playable.} 6. d4 Ng6 7. e5 Ne4 8. Nxe4 dxe4 9. Bc4 c5 10. c3 Be7 11. Ne2 {1-0 Blackburne, J-Fenton, R Blackburne GBR tour sim Great Britain 1873} O-O 12. O-O cxd4 13. cxd4 b5 $5 14. Bxb5 Qb6 15. Bc4 Nxe5 16. Bd5 Rb8 17. Bf4 Bd6 18. Bxe4 Ba6 19. Re1 Ng4 20. Bxd6 Bxe2 21. Rxe2 Qxd6 22. g3 Rb4 $11) 6. Nf3 Nxf3+ 7. Qxf3 d5 8. e5 Qe7 9. d4 Ne4 10. a3 Bxc3+ (10... Ba5 $5 11. b4 Nxc3 12. Qxc3 Bb6 $11 {[%cal Gf7f6]}) 11. bxc3 O-O 12. c4 Qh4+ (12... c6 {looks more natural and if} 13. Bd3 Qh4+ 14. g3 {î€£then already} Qh3 $11) 13. g3 {1-0 Van Wieringen,C (2253)-Jans,A (1844) VW-Cup3 Gr28 email ICCF email 2010} Qd8 14. Bd3 c6 15. Bxe4 dxe4 16. Qxe4 Bh3 $44 {Black has good compensation for the pawn. WHite's light squares are weak and his king is insecure. Using the compact centre is not a good idea:} 17. d5 cxd5 18. cxd5 Rc8 $15) (4. Nc3 exf4 5. Bxf4 Bb4 6. Nf3 d5 {leads to familiar counterplay.} 7. exd5 (7. e5 d4 $1 $146 8. a3 Bxc3+ 9. bxc3 Nd5 $17) 7... Nxd5 8. Bd2 O-O 9. Nxd5 Qxd5 $11 {0-1 Ratolistka, J-Sikora Lerch, J (2365) CZE-ch 18th Karvina 1987 (1)}) 4... d5 {A principled move, increasing the central tension instead of releasing it.} ({The simpler} 4... exf4 5. Bxf4 d5 {is not a bit worse.} 6. e5 Nh5 7. Bg5 (7. Be3 d4 8. Bf2 Nf4 9. c3 dxc3 10. bxc3 Bg4 11. h3 Bh5 12. d4 Be7 $13 {0-1 Juhar,R (2168)-Kantorik,M (2345) SVK-chT1E 0708 Slovakia 2007 (10.6)}) 7... Be7 8. Bxe7 Qxe7 9. d4 Bg4 10. Bb5 Qb4+ 11. Nc3 Qxb2 12. Kd2 (12. Nxd5 Bxf3 13. gxf3 O-O 14. Bxc6 bxc6 15. Ne7+ Kh8 16. Nf5 $17 {1-0 Kocur, L (1578)-Pruimboom, J (1596) NED-SVK email ICCF email 2017 [51] Black probably lost interest for the game or fell asleep for several days.}) 12... O-O 13. Rb1 $44 {with reasonable compensation for the pawn.}) 5. Nxe5 (5. fxe5 {runs into} dxe4 $1 6. exf6 exf3 7. Qxf3 Nd4 8. Qe4+ Be6 9. Kd1 (9. fxg7 {offers Black a free developing tempo.} Bxg7 10. Kd1 O-O $17 {0-1 Llanos, G (2437)-Reides, M (2354) Najdorf Memorial op Buenos Aires 1999 (1)}) 9... Qxf6 10. c3 Nc6 11. Be2 O-O-O 12. Rf1 {0-1 Kraszewski,D-Johnson,M GBR-ch cand02 corr England 1989} Qe7 $17 {[%cal Gg7g6]}) 5... Nxe5 $5 ({More ambitious than} 5... dxe4 6. Nxc6 bxc6 7. dxe4 (7. Nc3 Bb4) 7... Qxd1+ 8. Kxd1 Nxe4 $11 {Black's better development and the weakness on e4 compensate for the spoiled queenside structure.}) 6. fxe5 Nxe4 $1 {The point behind the previous move.} 7. g3 (7. dxe4 $146 Qh4+ {is likely to lead to a draw by perpetual.} 8. Kd2 Qh6+ 9. Ke2 Qh5+ 10. Kd2 Qh6+ 11. Kc3 Qc6+ $11 {AVoiding a draw is not recommendable for White.} 12. Kd3 $2 dxe4+ 13. Kd2 h5 14. Ke1 Bg4 15. Be2 Rd8 16. Bxg4 (16. Nd2 e3 $19) (16. Bd2 e3 $19) 16... Rxd1+ 17. Bxd1 Bc5 $17) 7... Ng5 8. Bg2 Be7 9. O-O O-O 10. Nc3 c6 11. d4 Nh3+ $5 {The knight could well occupy the perfect blockading square on e6, but this move is good, too.} 12. Kh1 Be6 13. Ne2 Bg4 14. Qd3 Qd7 15. c3 f6 $11 {Â½-Â½ Reinhart,E (2141)-Leutwyler,M (2166) Oberliga Baden 0203 Germany 2002 (5.7)} *

