{[%evp 0,40,26,10,37,10,32,7,9,1,1,-12,-18,-20,3,3,4,4,4,-6,34,31,23,17,56,47,72,30,52,33,51,36,62,40,25,30,38,40,30,10,21,36,31]} 1. e4 Nf6 2. Nc3 {This developing move is the most consistent way of refraining from 2.e5. As far as I know, Black has only one good way of avoiding a transposition to other openings.} d5 (2... e5 {is very good, of course, but transposes to the open games.} 3. Nf3 (3. f4 d5 {is another possibility. Black is doing fine, but there is some theory here.}) 3... Nc6 4. d4 (4. Bb5 {leads to the Four Knights Game.}) (4. g3 {is the Glek system.}) 4... exd4 5. Nxd4 {reaching a Four Knights Scotch tabyia, which is not completely unpopular.}) 3. e5 {The most ambitious answer.} ({I remember that as a teenager I had the following variation in my repertoire with white:} 3. exd5 Nxd5 4. Bc4 Nxc3 (4... Nb6 {also looks normal.}) 5. Qf3 (5. bxc3 {Strengthens White's centre, but spoils the overall structural flexibility.} e6 6. Nf3 Be7 7. O-O O-O 8. d4 Nd7 9. Re1 b6 10. Qe2 (10. Bd3 Bb7 11. c4 Bf6 12. c3 c5 13. Rb1 Rc8 14. Be3 Qc7 {This move is good, but Black could avoid the weakening of his kingside with, say, 14...Re8 followed by ...Nf8-g6.} 15. Ng5 g6 16. Qg4 Bg7 17. Bf4 {1-0 Kortschnoj,V (2617)-Sieglen,J (2288) Berlin Casino Prominenten sim 2001} Nf6 $1 18. Qh4 Qd8 19. Be5 h6 {White has strongly committed himself and if the knight retreats, he will be a bit worse.} 20. Nxf7 $5 {This or the sacrifice on e6 do not yield enough compensation.} Kxf7 21. Qh3 Qd7 $15) 10... Bb7 11. Bf4 Bd6 $5 12. Bg3 (12. Bg5 $2 {runs into} Bxf3 $1 {0-1 Golub, S-Bacetic, N (2345) YUG-chT Cetinje 1992} 13. Qe3 {The only try.} f6 $1 14. Bxe6+ Kh8 15. Qxf3 fxg5 $19) 12... Bxg3 13. hxg3 c5 14. Rad1 Qc7 $11 {Black has a comfortable position.}) 5... e6 6. Qxc3 {This is the position shown to me by an experienced trainer, with the evaluation that Black has problems completing his kingside development. Things are not that bad for Black, though.} Nc6 7. Nf3 Rg8 {Defending g7.} (7... Qf6 {is also playable, but I would prefer to do without weakening the kingside structure.} 8. Qxf6 gxf6 9. d4 Bd7 10. Bf4 O-O-O $11) 8. h4 (8. O-O g5 $5 {reveals another idea behind ...Rg8.} 9. Ne5 Nxe5 10. Qxe5 Bd6 11. Qe4 f5 12. Qf3 Qf6 $11 {with kingside counterplay.}) (8. a3 {1-0 Szabo, G (2355)-Claviere, R Wch U10 Bratislava 1993 (7) preparing d2-d4 without fearing ...Bb4 is passive.} g5 $132 {the same idea as in the main line.}) (8. d4 $4 Bb4 $19 {This is some limitation induced by the queen's presence on c3.}) 8... Be7 9. h5 Bf6 10. Qe3 b6 11. c3 Bb7 12. d4 Qe7 13. Bd2 O-O-O 14. O-O-O Kb8 $5 $11) 3... d4 (3... Nfd7 {most likely transposes to one of the French Defence main lines.} 4. d4 c5 5. f4 e6 6. Nf3) (3... Ne4 4. Nce2 {causes Black some problems with his daring knight.}) 4. exf6 {This leads to simplifications and approximate equality.} (4. Nce2 {is examined in Line 65.}) 4... dxc3 5. fxg7 (5. dxc3 Qxd1+ 6. Kxd1 exf6 {Aiming for rapid development.} (6... gxf6 $11 {turns the position non-symmetrical, yielding Black a mobile majority, but delays the development.}) 7. Bf4 Bc5 $5 $146 (7... c6 8. Nf3 Bc5 $11) 8. Bxc7 (8. Ke1 Bb6 $15) 8... Bxf2 9. Nf3 O-O $11) (5. bxc3 {Black has the same kind of choice like above.} exf6 $5 {It is interesting to compare this position with the one arising in an already fashionable Caro Kann system: 1.e4 c6 2.d4 d5 3.Nc3 dxe4 4.Nxe4 Nf6 5.Nxf6+ exf6. In our position, White's centre is less flexible, ensuring Black comfortable play.} (5... gxf6 6. d4 e5 $11 {looks OK for Black, but instinctively I prefer to avoid such weaknesses.}) 6. d4 Bd6 7. Bd3 O-O 8. Ne2 c5 9. O-O Nc6 10. Be3 Qc7 11. Ng3 Ne7 {defends both f5 and c5, but is not the most active continuation.} (11... cxd4 12. cxd4 Nb4 {is more resolute, but not necessarily better objectively.} 13. Be4 Re8 14. Qf3 Bxg3 15. hxg3 f5 {The double pawns on the f-file show their strength. Black can attack the bishop without weakening his kingside since the reserve pawn on f7 defends e6.} 16. Bxf5 Bxf5 17. Qxf5 Nxc2 18. Rac1 Nxe3 19. fxe3 Qe7 $11 {0-1 Cernik,L-Hallerova,E (2153) CZE-ch op Plzen 1999}) 12. Qh5 (12. dxc5 Bxc5 13. Bxh7+ Kxh7 14. Qh5+ Kg8 15. Qxc5 Qxc5 16. Bxc5 Re8 $11 {White's extra pawn is irrelevant.}) 12... f5 $1 $11 {The pawn on f5 is taboo due to the possible fork with ...g7g6.} (12... g6 $6 {1-0 Cernik, L (1965)-Marous, R (1660) CZE-ch U18 Czech Republic 1998} 13. Qh6 $14) 13. c4 (13. Nxf5 Bxf5 14. Bxf5 g6 $19) (13. Bxf5 g6 $19) 13... cxd4 14. Bxd4 f6 15. Rfe1 Nc6 16. Bc3 g6 17. Qh4 Be5 $11 {Once again we notice the implicit strength of the double pawns.}) (5. fxe7 Qxe7+ {leads to plain equality.} 6. Be2 cxb2 7. Bxb2 Bg4 $11 {0-1 Rozlapa, V-Alexandria, N (2340) URS-chT Cup 09th Tbilisi 1976 (3)}) 5... cxd2+ 6. Qxd2 {SInce Black's queen has better possibilities of becoming active, WHite's best try is exchanging it.} (6. Bxd2 Bxg7 7. c3 Nc6 8. Nf3 Qd5 9. Be2 Be6 $5 $146 10. O-O O-O-O $11) 6... Qxd2+ 7. Bxd2 Bxg7 8. O-O-O Nc6 $11 {White's structure is more compact, but Black is well developed and has a central majority.} 9. Bb5 (9. Nf3 Bd7 10. Bc4 e6 11. Rhe1 h6 $5 {Preventing Ng5 followed by f2-f4.} 12. Bf4 O-O-O 13. Ne5 Nxe5 14. Bxe5 Bxe5 15. Rxe5 {Â½-Â½ Zaitsev,M (2507)-Nalbandian,T (2453) Dortmund Sparkassen op-A 2010 (5)} Bc6 $11 16. Rxd8+ Kxd8 17. g3 Ke7 18. Kd2 b6 $11) 9... Bd7 10. Nf3 (10. Ne2 O-O-O 11. Bc3 {is another possible plan. White invests a few tempi in exchanging the active black bishop but helps Black get some counterplay along the g-file.} Bxc3 12. Nxc3 a6 13. Ba4 b5 14. Bb3 e6 15. Ne4 Na5 16. Nc5 (16. g3 Bc6 17. Rhe1 Rxd1+ 18. Kxd1 Nb7 19. c3 Kd8 20. Bc2 Ke7 $11 {0-1 Radovic,M (1601)-Radovic,L (1970) Jagodina op 2012 (4)}) 16... Bc6 17. Rhg1 Rxd1+ 18. Kxd1 Rg8 19. g3 Rg5 $11 20. Nxa6 $2 Bf3+ 21. Kc1 c5 $17) 10... a6 (10... O-O-O 11. Rhe1 e6 {allows} 12. Ng5 Rdf8 13. f4 h6 14. Nf3 a6 15. Bc4 {Â½-Â½ Arakeljan, A (2311)-Moiseev, V (2425) Bogoroditsk 07 2013 (10) with some symbolical white advantage.}) 11. Ba4 (11. Bc4 e6 12. Rhe1 h6 {Preventing Ng5, as in a previous line.} 13. Bf4 O-O-O 14. Ne5 Nxe5 15. Bxe5 Bxe5 16. Rxe5 Bc6 17. f3 Rxd1+ 18. Kxd1 Rg8 19. Re2 Rg5 20. Ke1 Bb5 $11 {1-0 Eigemann,J (1954)-Schueller,T (1852) Cologne Longerich op 8th 2011 (2)}) 11... b5 12. Bb3 e6 {This is not the first time in this database when the white bishop is immobile on b3. It happens in some main lines, too.} 13. Bf4 O-O-O 14. c3 Na5 15. Bc2 f6 16. b3 Nb7 17. Rhe1 e5 18. Be3 Nd6 {Very coherent regrouping. The centre has advanced and the knight defends the relative weakness on f5.} 19. Nh4 Be6 20. Kb2 f5 $11 {1-0 Drabke,L (2035)-Ubezio,M (2071) Corsico Magistrale op 19th 1999 (5)} *

