1. e4 Nf6 2. Nc3 d5 3. e5 d4 4. Nce2 {By avoiding the exchanges, White hopes to cause Black some problems with relocating his king's knight.} Ng4 {Inducing the next (slightly weakening) move and maintaining the possibility of transferring the knight to f5.} 5. f4 (5. Nf3 {is inoffensive.} Nc6 6. d3 Ngxe5 7. Nexd4 Nxd4 8. Nxe5 Qd5 9. Nc4 e5 10. c3 Nc6 11. f4 {Â½-Â½ Schleich, T-Ruecker, B (2178) Bad Zwesten op 8th 2004 (2)} Be7 $11) 5... Nc6 {At this stage, development is the highest priority.} ({Gaining kingside space with the typical} 5... h5 {wastes a developing tempo.} 6. Nf3 Nc6 7. c3 d3 8. Ned4 $14) 6. h3 (6. Nf3 {allows} d3 7. cxd3 Nh6 $5 $146 {Preparing to activate the knight. White's extra pawn is not too relevant and his development will be delayed a bit, precisely because of the double pawns.} 8. d4 (8. h3 Be6 9. g4 Bd5 10. Bg2 Ng8 {[%cal Gh7h5] planning ...h7-h5.} 11. Ng3 e6 12. O-O Qd7 $44) 8... Bg4 9. Qb3 e6 10. Qxb7 Nb4 11. Kf2 c6 $5 12. a3 Rb8 13. Qxa7 Ra8 $11) 6... Nh6 7. Nf3 (7. g4 f6 $132 {clears the f7-square for the knight and undermines White's space advantage.}) (7. d3 e6 8. Nf3 Nf5 9. g4 (9. g3 b6 $5 $146) 9... Nh4 $11) 7... e6 8. g4 (8. d3 Nf5 {transposes above.}) 8... d3 $5 $146 {A familiar idea.} 9. cxd3 Nb4 10. Kf2 (10. Nc3 Nxd3+ 11. Bxd3 Qxd3 $15) 10... Bd7 {Just developing.} (10... Nxd3+ {offers White some time for getting coordinated.} 11. Kg3 c5 12. Nc3) 11. Nc3 Bc6 12. Kg3 {The same maneuver as above.} g5 $5 13. fxg5 Bxf3 14. Qxf3 Qxg5 15. Qxb7 Qxe5+ 16. Kf3 Rd8 $44 *

